<HEADLINE>
FORWARD-LOOKING PIAZZA TAKES A GLANCE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Piazza didn't play Thursday, but the crush for
post-game interviews around his locker had a World Series feel to
it.
</P>
<P>
   That much hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has his old team 3,000 miles away, still bloated, still
sloshing around .500, still telling anyone who will listen that
there is a half-season left to play.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza used to take the heat for the Dodgers' indifference, the
one thing the .338 lifetime hitter had to answer for over and over
again. Now he's gone and that indifference continues to rage.
</P>
<P>
   But Piazza takes no joy in knowing the problem stayed after he
left. Thirteen months after joining the New York Mets, he still
knows he was the best player on a team expected to do much more.
All Piazza can do is move on and hope people understand that it
takes 25 guys to make a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about playing in New York is that it lets you turn
the page on everything,'' he said after missing the first of two
games with a slight concussion. ``Maybe if I was somewhere else,
somewhere smaller, I'd wonder. It's clear you can't just throw
money at a problem. You have to get the right players who will play
as a unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what has happened here. For me, there is not much
looking back.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean others haven't looked back for him.
</P>
<P>
   Mets manager Bobby Valentine, who nearly lost his job two weeks
ago when a player mutiny led to an eight-game losing streak, knows
what Piazza means to his team. Since the failed coup, the Mets have
won 13 of 17, including Friday's 10-2 rout of Atlanta that moved
them within two games of the Braves in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who turns 31 in September, was in the midst of a 24-game
hitting streak during that span, although Valentine said, ``he
wasn't that ferocious, dominant hitter he was with the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He got his hits, but you didn't see that terror everyone came
to expect in L.A.,'' Valentine said of Piazza, who batted .211 with
runners in scoring position during the streak. ``But that was
almost a good thing because others stepped up. That's what winning
is all about. It's not one guy carrying the load.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine admitted that Piazza's quiet nature was puzzling to
his new team after the trade and into this year. He said that
changed when Piazza hit a ninth-inning, game-winning home run April
28 off San Diego closer Trevor Hoffman. Piazza pumped his fist
circling the bases and later in the clubhouse. His rare display of
emotion bubbled over to teammates who realized he could be one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike opened up that day,'' Valentine said. ``He laughed a lot
and suddenly became more approachable. Guys felt they could kid
with him and I don't think that had happened anywhere before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he feel vindicated about the situation (in L.A.)? I think
it is too soon to tell. Maybe a little, but that is something you
think about after a career, when you wonder about the decisions you
made in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser, a Dodger early in Piazza's career, says the
catcher is far different than L.A. fans remember. Although Piazza
signed a seven-year, $91 million contract last winter, he appears
more relaxed than ever. Hershiser says the presence of solid
veterans like Robin Ventura, Rickey Henderson and John Franco have
removed the pressure from Piazza of setting the team's tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always seemed like out there he was searching for who he
was,'' Hershiser said. ``That's pretty common for a young player.
But now he knows who he is. A Hall of Fame catcher who can carry a
team with his bat, who doesn't always let a lot of people in. It's
hard to be one of the guys when you're that great, but he has fit
in here.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the guys, Bobby Bonilla, was part of the seven-player
trade that sent Piazza from the Dodgers to Florida last May. They
never played together, but he says it's easy to understand the
change in Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might sound like a baseball thing, but when you're a
catcher in L.A. the travel absolutely kills you,'' he said. ``Last
year I remember (Charles Johnson) saying how the travel made him
wonder if he could play here. Except for the West, every flight is
four hours. Here, everybody is close, Philadelphia, Montreal,
Pittsburgh. That's doable. For a guy catching 140 games a year and
asked to carry the team, that was not possible. Not even for Mike
Piazza.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
