<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0942 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASVEGAS-AZR &LR;      06-27 2359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-MOB LAWYER RIDES TO POWER ON NEIGBORHOOD-FOCUSED CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
 VEGAS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAUN MCKINNON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The Bagel Cafe sits in a small office park miles
from the slot machines and gaming tables of the famous Strip, on
the edge of a sprawling master-planned community so full of stucco,
tile roofs and cul-de-sacs it can barely contain its typical
suburbanness.
</P>
<P>
   This is the new Las Vegas. Sin City gone legit. Not a showgirl
or a buffet line in sight. Except for a couple of video poker
machines in the corner 7-Eleven, it could be Mesa. And it is to
this Chamber of Commerce postcard one recent Sun day morning that
defense attorney Oscar Goodman, a man who built his career
representing the accused murderers, money launderers and organized
crime bosses of Old Vegas, came to buy bagels.
</P>
<P>
   He was spotted at once and within moments, he was, pardon the
terminology, mobbed by diners who wanted to shake the hand of this
improbable new civic hero, this throwback to a nearly buried past
who defied the city's political ma chine earlier this month and got
himself elected mayor in a land slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Mr. Goodman,'' one woman said, waving from a table
by the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give 'em hell, Oscar!'' yelled a man from across the room.
Good man grinned, reveling in the atten tion.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone outside Nevada, the idea that a millionaire lawyer who
works for reputed mobsters could be elected mayor of Las Vegas
isn't so far out, probably even makes sense. But to image-conscious
business and tourism leaders who want desperately to reinvent this
desert gambling town as a sophisticated international resort
destination, Goodman was poison, a source of potentially disastrous
publicity they wanted to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't count on was a candidate adept at reinventing
him self and an electorate willing to give him a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman drilled to the core with issues that hit closer to home
than attracting new visitors to fill the ever-expanding number of
Strip hotel rooms. His campaign focused on rebuilding
neighborhoods, fixing clogged roads and freeways, and forcing
developers to pay a bigger share for the infrastructure needs
created by more than a decade of phenomenal growth _ issues that
could have been lifted from a mayoral race in Phoenix or Glen dale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked about quality of life and standard of living when
most of the time politicians talk about gam ing, hotels and
tourism,'' said Rob ert Parker, a professor of sociology at the
University of Nevada at Las Vegas. ``People have become much more
sensitive to the underside of growth the past few years. He has an
opportunity to do some good for the city.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Goodman wants to hear, what he needs to hear. He
entered the race for mayor, he said, because he wanted to give some
thing back to a city he loves.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly didn't do it for the money. He's a millionaire many
times over and will earn $48,000 a year as mayor. His power will be
limited. Las Vegas operates under a city manager form of
government, and the mayor is just one of five votes on the City
Council. For ego? Hardly. Around Las Vegas, Good man is better
known in most circles than the governor, and he definitely has a
better chance of getting a good table than the state's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a true believer,'' fellow attorney and former City
Council man Matthew Callister said. ``He's a look-you-in-the-eye
kind of guy who says, `The community's been good to me, now here's
what I want to do for the community.' I think he'll have a lot of
frustrations early on, but I think he really intends to make it a
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the pundits held sway, Oscar Goodman would not be taking the
oath of office Monday morning. He was dismissed from the start as
unelectable because of his political inexperience, because of a
strong slate of other candidates, but mostly because of his past,
his tendency to represent, in his own words, tough guys whose names
end in vowels.
</P>
<P>
   Days after he declared his candi dacy, the state's largest daily
news paper, the Las Vegas Review-Journal, ran an editorial early in
the race with the headline, ``Anybody but Oscar,'' branding him a
``barrister to butchers.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that the newspaper, or anyone else for that matter,
worried that Goodman's election would usher in a new day for the
mob, whose influence along the Strip was pushed aside during the
1990s by the arrival of huge, publicly traded gaming corporations.
</P>
<P>
   No, it was mostly the image thing _ ``Oscar Goodman carries so
much baggage he could be Sky Cap of the Century at McCarran Interna
tional Airport,'' the newspaper wrote, ``and as the most visible
personification of the `new' Las Vegas, he'd be a PR catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried about his populist cam paign, some business and gaming
leaders began to beat the drum on the image issue, first
whispering, then going on record in national newsmagazines and on
television that electing a former mob mouth piece mayor would be
bad for Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there he is, ``Oscar Mayor Winner,'' as one newspaper trum
peted the morning after a victory so convincing _ Goodman garnered
64 percent of the vote _ some observers now say it may have been
backlash against such a well-organ ized attempt by the
establishment to discredit the so-called mob lawyer and avoid the
embarrassment of a mob mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is very excited about Oscar Goodman being mayor,''
the 59-year-old Goodman said in an interview last week. ``The
planes haven't stopped flying in and the cars aren't stopping at
the border. The media stories are turn ing around; and now, instead
of the past, they're talking about the fu ture. And that's what my
tenure is going to be about.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman has lived at the top of the world since June 8.
President Clinton called to congratulate him. Al Gore called to
wish him the best. Everywhere he goes, people wave and want to
shake his hand. He laughs, remembering the little old ladies who
raced after him one morning as he walked down Fre mont Street, in
the city's downtown casino district. He can't go any where, he
said, without drawing crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place like Las Vegas,'' he said. ``Las Vegas is
special. There's an electricity here you don't find anywhere else.
And I think I bring a little mystique because of my background.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, his background. A brief synopsis, then: Born and reared
in Philadelphia, Goodman with his wife, Carolyn, trekked west 35
years ago and settled in Las Vegas, where he almost stumbled into
his first job representing a person accused of being a mob figure.
</P>
<P>
   He won the case and many more after that, and he soon found
himself in courtrooms side by side with ``bad guys'' like Meyer Lan
sky, the mob's money man; Joey Cusumano; Charlie ``The Moose''
Panarella; Frank ``Lefty'' Rosen thal; and Tony ``The Ant''
Spilotro, the Chicago mob's Las Vegas en forcer during the 1970s
and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman apologizes for nothing in his past, resents even any
ques tions about it. People accused of crimes deserve a good
attorney, he said, and by standing up for the constitutional rights
of these tough guys, he's standing up for the Constitution itself.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed in business and out of prison by knowing what he
needed to. He would never acknowledge his clients' alleged mob
ties, even proclaimed straight-faced for years that he knew of no
Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Spilotro, whose life was fictional ized in the Martin Scorsese
film Casino, was accused once of stick ing a man's head in a vise
and twisting so hard the man's skull cracked and his eyes popped
out. Did it happen? Spilotro was acquit ted, said Goodman, who
played himself opposite Joe Pesci in the movie. That's what was
important.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Goodman landed in the newspapers and on
television frequently, aghast each time a client was indicted anew,
ready to chase away government prosecutors. Spi lotro was suspected
in 22 killings and charged with a laundry list of other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed out of prison thanks to Goodman, until 1986, when he
and his brother were found beaten to death in an Indiana cornfield,
appar ent victims of a mob hit.
</P>
<P>
   All of that was common knowl edge in Las Vegas. But for the
thousands of newcomers, Good man's opponents dredged much of it up
for a series of TV advertise ments. Still, voters looked the other
way, telling one pollster Goodman's past didn't make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Callister, the former councilman, offers several theories. For
one thing, Goodman brings to the job a certain brashness and
ability to deliver a message that Las Vegas voters became
accustomed to under two-term Mayor Jan Laverty Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was elected in 1991 with no political experience but with
the notoriety of her appearances in TV spots for her family's car
dealer ships. In one ad the people of Las Vegas still talk about,
Jones ca vorted with female impersonator Kenny Kerr, a Strip
regular who played the future mayor's evil sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural for people to want some glitz in their
politicians, some glamour, some flash,'' Callister said. ``This is
Vegas, after all. I used to tell people to celebrate their
Vegas-ness. This isn't like any other town.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, the UNLV sociologist, buys into that, in part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some people are very happy and proud to live here,''
he said. ``They relish the imagery, and Oscar looks like Las Vegas,
he acts like Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many residents also may be worried about the
negative effects not only of growth _ the traffic, the polluted air
_ but of the city's rise to international prominence, appealing to
the elite travelers with five-star restaurants and exclusive
boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming almost unafford able for locals,'' Parker said.
``There's a growing division be tween the haves and have-nots.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, Parker theorizes, seems to recognize that and offers
himself as an advocate for the people, another odd contrast consid
ering his wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who was one of the region's first elected officials to
advocate growth management, said no one should overlook the impor
tance of neighborhood issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone gets caught up in Las Vegas as being part of
the Number One resort destination in the country,'' she said.
``That doesn't mean people who live here don't have concerns about
their neighborhoods. If Las Vegas is going to continue to grow, it
has to put all of its energy into city issues, in building a real
city that puts the quality of life of its residents as its
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much Goodman can accomplish remains part of the debate,
as does much of his specific list of ideas. He promised to work for
impact fees, something that developers have successfully avoided
for years and that would require action by the state Legisla ture.
He has pledged to bring new housing and businesses to older
neighborhoods, proposing that de velopers who want to build in the
city's growing outer edges first commit to in-fill projects.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he saw no reason Las Vegas, which barely supports a
Triple-A baseball team, shouldn't get an NFL franchise. He wants
more high-tech jobs and promised to get Microsoft chief Bill Gates
on the phone his first week or two in office to try to strike a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a passion for the community,'' said Kara Kelley, sen
ior vice president of the Las Vegas Chamber of Commerce. ``He's en
gaging and, hopefully, he will be able to help people appreciate
what a wonderful place this is. But in the business community, we
have a lot of bigger issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``For any company seriously con sidering relocating here, the
mayor isn't going to be a factor in the decision. We have life
beyond the Strip. I think there's a tendency to underestimate the
quality of life here.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, there's only so much Las Vegas can do to overcome its
deeper image problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never going to be a cultural mecca for a Bostonian,''
Kelley said. ``But we're living in a major metropolitan area, and
we've created a community. People who call this home love it for
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman's greatest reality check may come when he tries to push
one of his grander ideas and needs the help of other government
entities _ and he will. Of the 1.3 million people who live in Clark
County, barely one-third live in the city of Las Vegas and the
revenue-generat ing Strip resorts all lie in the unincorporated
county.
</P>
<P>
   The county and the neighboring Henderson, with nearly 200,000
residents _ the fastest-growing city in the valley _ have proved
far less amiable to growth-control measures and far more likely to
encourage new development as long as the demand continues.
</P>
<P>
   In a crunch, the true depth of Goodman's support may become a
factor as well. Although he was elected by a huge margin, turnout
overall was miserably low and Goodman took home fewer than 37,000
votes in a city of more than 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman is undeterred. He will begin, he said, by revitalizing
down town, which now is a sometimes uncomfortable grouping of older
casinos, government buildings and rows of aging motels and wedding
chapels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make downtown the same kind of glittering beacon as
we have on the Strip,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get private enter prise involved. We're going to
bring in bookstores and coffeehouses and movie theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman plans to devote himself full time to the job, leaving
his law practice behind, a painful, he said, but necessary step if
he is to accomplish his goals. He attended his first-ever City
Council meeting a week after he was elected and has stayed up
nights studying Robert's Rules of Order.
</P>
<P>
   And for good measure, just in case anyone thinks he's forgotten
how to celebrate his Vegas-ness, Goodman attended a party last
weekend with an old pal and Casino co-star, actor Robert De Niro,
who is opening a restaurant in town.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman chuckles at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a colorful life and I've met a lot of colorful
people,'' he said. ``And if I had to do it all over again, I
wouldn't change a day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
