<HEADLINE>
COYOTES DEAL TVERDOVSKY TO GET MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ About 15 minutes before the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim
were scheduled to make their first-round selection in Saturday's
NHL entry draft with the 15th overall pick, General Manager Pierre
Gauthier received a call from his counterpart from Phoenix, Bobby
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   What would it take, the Coyotes GM asked, for the Ducks to part
with the pick?
</P>
<P>
   Smith and the Coyotes desperately wanted to grab Seattle
Thunderbirds center Scott Kelman but weren't sure they'd be able to
nab him at No. 19. Gauthier thought about it, and said he would
send the 15th choice, along with 28-year-old center Travis Green,
if the Coyotes were willing to part with talented defenseman Oleg
Tverdovsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was about a 12-second pause,'' Gauthier said, ``and then
Bobby said, `It's a deal' and hung up the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, the Coyotes made some noise of their own on an
eventful NHL draft day at the FleetCenter that produced plenty of
surprises and more than enough trades.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to trading Tverdovsky, the Coyotes also sent veteran
enforcer Jim Cummins to Montreal for a sixth-round pick,
jettisoning the $666,000 it would have cost to re-sign him. And,
they nearly pulled off a deal with the Atlanta Thrashers for
defenseman Jamie Pushor, acquired a day earlier in the NHL
expansion draft from Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   That deal, for a second- or third-round pick next year, could
still be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rumors of a possible trade involving center Jeremy
Roenick going to Detroit for left wing Brendan Shanahan were
quickly shot down by Smith, although where there is smoke, there
usually is fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not once mentioned Roenick's name to (Red Wings General
Manager ) Ken Holland,'' Smith said flatly.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes got their man in Kelman, 6-foot-2, 185 pounds, who
entered the draft as the sixth highest-rated North American
prospect, according to final rankings released by the Central
Scouting Bureau. The 18-year-old from Winnipeg scored only 19 goals
last season in the Western Hockey League, but scouts like his
play-making abilities, as his 54 assists would attest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the teams I could have gone to, Phoenix is the one I
really hoped would draft me,'' said Kelman, who grew up an avid
fans of the franchise when it was known as the Winnipeg Jets. ``I
know they traded a great young player in Oleg to get me, and I
guess that means they wanted me as much as I wanted them to pick
me.''
</P>
<P>
   With their original first-round pick, No. 19, the Coyotes went
with Russian defenseman Kiril Safronov, 6-foot-2, 196 pounds, who
was the sixth-highest rated European in the draft but is seen by
many scouts as perhaps the best overall defenseman of the entire
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision (trading Tverdovsky), but we feel like
Kelman's going to be a guy who's going to be with us for a long
time at center and there's a premium on centers right now,'' Smith
said. ``To get a guy like Travis Green, who's 215 pounds and can
play the position, is really going to help our team. He's a guy who
can play in the No. 2 spot behind Roenick, if we decide to put him
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky, meanwhile, returns to his former team, which made
him the second overall selection in the 1994 draft. An All-Star
three seasons ago during his first year in Phoenix when he scored
55 points, Tverdovsky has suffered back-to-back disappointing
seasons. A contract dispute limited him to just 46 games in
1997-98, when he scored 7 goals and 19 points, and last season,
despite appearing in all 82 games, he finished with just seven
goals and 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oleg's last couple years have not been great, but he's still a
player with a world of potential,'' Smith said. ``They don't come
along every day, but we feel like we got good value for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow-born Tverdovsky was in Russia and could not
immediately be reached to be informed of his trade back to the
Ducks. He initially was dealt, along with center Chad Kilger, as
the two key components of the Teemu Selanne trade on Feb. 7, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's probably beneficial for everyone concerned,''
said Meehan, who ironically, represents all three players involved
in the deal. ``Phoenix ended up getting some help where they think
they need some help and given what transpired last year, some of
the factors which led to this trade, I know Oleg will look forward
to this as being a positive step.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, a seven-year pro who spent his first six years in the NHL
with the New York Islanders, was caught off guard by the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds exciting. I know they've got some skilled, gritty
forwards and good people and I'm looking forward to going there,''
said Green, who twice scored 20 or more goals in New York, but was
limited to 13 goals and 30 points last season with the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Green has one more year left on his contract at $1.8 million.
Tverdovsky, a restricted free agent, earned $1.7 last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
