<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0954 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-TEEN-AGERS-     06-27 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-TEEN-AGERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA'S TEENAGE WASTELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When Rhode Island's Lamar Odom missed a couple of
workouts, fired his agent and found himself torn between remaining
in the NBA draft or trying to return to college, the red flags
began popping up.
</P>
<P>
   Does Odom have something to hide? Is he stable? Did he get bad
advice?
</P>
<P>
   Or is he just a confused 19-year-old kid unsure about making
decisions that are going to have an impact on the rest of his life
and career?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question the NBA has to answer for Odom and hundreds of
players like him, who are pushed by street agents, coerced by club
coaches and prodded by hangers-on to go on to the professional
level before finishing college _ or even starting it.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the faces get younger. Odom is 19. Jonathan Bender, a
talented 18-year-old from Picayune High in New Orleans also is
expected to be taken high in Wednesday's NBA draft. Of the top
picks, only a few have played four years of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressures that surround these kids, the temptations
they're faced with _ it's a horror story, and everyone knows it,''
said Dick Percudani, the Suns' director of college scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Some, such as Kevin Garnett and Kobe Bryant in recent years or
Moses Malone 25 years ago, can make the leap and succeed. Others,
such as Magic Johnson, Isiah Thomas and Michael Jordan, have made
the transition smoothly with one or two years of collegiate
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can count those on one hand,'' said agent Bill Duffy, who,
as a member of the agents' advisory board to the NBA Players
Association, thinks it's time for reform. ``You could use all your
fingers and all your toes and not come close to counting all those
who have failed.''
</P>
<P>
   A minimum age requirement
</P>
<P>
   During his annual ``State of the Game'' address at the start of
the NBA Finals, Commissioner David Stern said the league and
players association were contemplating a minimum age limit for
players entering the league, probably 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Such a limit would probably have to be made in conjunction with
an arrangement with the Continental Basketball Association or
another developmental league to give young players not academically
qualified for college a place to play.
</P>
<P>
   And Stern said the NBA was awaiting word from the NCAA
concerning a league proposal, at the suggestion of the players
association, to provide potential NBA prospects with loans or
subsidies in college. The hope is that providing financial help to
college players might reduce the temptation to leave early for pro
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different components to this issue,'' Stern
said. ``One being the notion that so many kids are drawn . . . to
believe they will play (in the NBA), but so few actually do that.
It is a dream that is not fair, almost, and perhaps we could slow
that down a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many businesses have certain minimum-age requirements,
and we are sort of pushed in that direction now by a variety of
different concerns that have been expressed to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns include what has happened with Odom, who clearly
was not sure about the decisions he made. The NCAA has ruled that
he would not be eligible, so Odom is in Wednesday's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a classic example of what's happening to the modern
athlete,'' Percudani said. ``He went to three different high
schools, can't get into college, street agents all around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He becomes indebted to people and beholden to people who are
taking him for a ride because of what he could eventually be. These
kids live in a virtual-reality world. Then every once in a while,
they wake up and ask themselves, `Am I moving too fast? Am I good
enough for this?' And he panics.''
</P>
<P>
   A rookie salary scale
</P>
<P>
   The NBA often is criticized for throwing money at young
athletes, tempting them out of the college programs before they're
ready. It's an image the league is fighting, and one with which
Suns General Manager Brya Colangelo takes exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wholeheartedly disagree with the people who say it's the
NBA's fault,'' Colangelo said. ``There are a lot of hurdles to
clear, but we've tried to slow down the process by implementing the
rookie salary scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially a three-year scale, the latest collective bargaining
agreement puts rookies under a four-year scale with the club having
first-right-of-refusal for another three years _ keeping players
from being full free agents for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Many argue the rookie scale has had an opposite effect on young
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a player's standpoint, he sees that if he comes out at
18, then he's in his peak years when that seven years is up,''
Duffy said. ``From their vantage point, the sooner the clock starts
ticking, the sooner they get to free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   A breakthrough may be coming.
</P>
<P>
   The players association has long resisted a developmental
arrangement between the NBA and CBA or other such league. But
Thomas, a former president of the union and a former president of
the Toronto Raptors, is negotiating for the purchase of the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has the influence to bring all the parties together. With
the CBA acting as an official minor league, young players who don't
qualify for college or who want to leave early but aren't old
enough to meet the NBA's minimum age, could be sent to a CBA
affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   There, the player would be in a system that mirrors that of the
major league baseball club. Instead of sitting on the end of a
bench or being hidden on an injured list, a player would be getting
valuable time in a quality professional league.
</P>
<P>
   Linking the leagues
</P>
<P>
   CBA Commissioner Gary Hunter refused to comment on the
negotiations with Thomas, but he said his league had strived for
years to accomplish a direct link with the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us in the CBA are very much pro-education,'' Hunter
said. ``Nothing would please us more than to see these young men
stay in college for four years, mature physically, mentally and
emotionally and develop their basketball skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we also can see a trend that's not going to go away. We're
going to have to deal with it. We think we play the second-best
basketball played in the entire world in the CBA. Our league is
very, very competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't realize the average age is between 23 and 24
years old. It's very difficult for players to come directly out of
high school and compete at the level of this league.''
</P>
<P>
   An example is Stephen Jackson, a second-round draft pick of the
Suns in 1997. Jackson was an Arizona recruit who did not qualify
academically. He enrolled at a junior college but never played
there. The Suns waived Jackson in the preseason, and he was later
cut by a CBA club.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter says the CBA could be fashioned to work with young
players such as Jackson and teach them more than just basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some ideas,'' he said. ``We could modify our
schedule, put in a life-skills program and work with the NBA and
the NBA Players Association to come up with a true affiliation. Let
players come to our league for a few games, a few weeks or a few
months and work on their games or mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players association's feeling, frankly, is that if NBA
teams expand their rosters and assign players to the CBA, that's a
reduction in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to persuade them that it's more job opportunities. A
young player may not be in Salt Lake City playing for the Jazz, but
he could be in their organization assigned to the Idaho Stampede.
He would still be monitored closely and tutored by the home team,
within their system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of rehabing on the injured list, he could be getting
some very valuable, precious game time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the viewpoint of the players association could change. Billy
Hunter, the executive director of the union, did not return phone
calls from ``The Arizona Republic.'' But Duffy said he and other
agents have made their feelings known. They support Thomas' ideas
for the CBA, which are endorsed by Gary Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much better would (Portland's) Jermaine O'Neal be right
now if he had been playing 40 minutes a game the last three
years?'' Duffy said. ``Maybe we have to put a limit on it. After a
certain number of years, a player can't be sent down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think Isiah's vision makes a lot of sense because we're
not developing young players. It's time for some alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   On that much, everyone seems to agree. And Stern said he thought
the place to start was with the age restriction.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It) might encourage certain kids, whose lives are literally
ruined because they get and follow bad advice, from making those
bad decisions,'' he said. ``It is really an interesting subject
that we are wrestling with. . . . It is one of the most difficult
things we have had to deal with.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
