u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-STEVENS     06-27 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-STEVENSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENSON WELL-EDUCATED BY MOM'S HOME SCHOOLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Martina Navratilova has just won her ninth Wimbledon.
It is 1990, and she is telling a TV reporter, ``Somewhere out there
is a 9-year-old working on her game, who'll be standing here as
champion some day.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Stevenson, watching in an out-there called San Diego,
shouts toward the kitchen, ``Mom . . . mom . . . that's me
Martina's talking about!''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Stevenson made up her mind then: ``I would win
Wimbledon when I was 19. I don't know why 19, but I figured it
would take about 10 years. So if I cheat by a year, that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years pass. With them countless lessons from illustrious
pros, the usual growing pains, and a date for the recent senior
prom, an event unknown to most tennis prodigies. Even _ no kidding
_ a high school diploma, a document that undereducated girls on the
circuit, a majority, might equate with a Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Now Alexandra is here as she always believed she'd be. She
hasn't won yet, understand. Her 6-3, 6-3, stunning of 11th-seeded
Julie Halard-Decugis Saturday was a third-rounder. But after
curtsying all around to an admiring gathering way out at Court 13,
the tall, tawny kid out of LaJolla Country Day School is one of the
unlikelys to scuffle and sneak through the first week at the Big W
and find herself among 16 survivors. She is No. 86 in a universe
she intends to conquer.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra finished the afternoon job with a flourish, a
sprinting forehand along the line that eluded the Frenchwoman's
racket. With this victory she joyously proclaimed, ``I'm free!''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: She will not sign the letter of intent binding her
to UCLA. With that non-stroke she turned her strong back on
amateurism and declared herself a pro.
</P>
<P>
   Instead she will cart around a stack of books from a carton
given her as a graduation present by a San Diego poet, Susan
Pollis. ``I think there are about 100, and Susan says reading them
all will be a great education. I'm reading Sinclair Lewis's ``Main
Street'' right now, with John Steinbeck's ``The Grapes of Wrath''
next.''
</P>
<P>
   One more win, over another American, Lisa Raymond, Monday would
put Stevenson on main street all right, the quarters of her initial
major.
</P>
<P>
   The book box did not include Bill Tilden, one of the game's
foremost champs and authors, who wrote: ``Great champions are not
born. They're made on their own _ and their coaches' _ efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra has that in her head via a triple play: Tilden to
Vines to Stevenson. ``I've been very lucky with the people who've
helped me one way or another, coaching and advice,'' says
Alexandra. ``I met Ellsworth Vines (US and Wimbledon champ in 1932)
before he died, and he passed that along to me from Tilden
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   So another ``Me and Mom Show'' is unfolding at Wimbledon where a
more celebrated one closed early (presumably temporarily) as
Martina Hingis was beaten in the first round. That left Martina and
parent Melanie Molitor with nothing much to do for a while and the
Stevensons _ Alexandra and Samantha _ ready and willing to stand
in, even upstage the Swiss pair.
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference in styles even though this mother, Samantha
Stevenson, is no less ambitious or determined on behalf of the
child she has raised alone. While Melanie is the coach with an
aversion to speaking English, or anything, to reporters, Samantha,
a journalist by trade, maybe the game's first press agent parent.
She is comfortable mixing with scribblers and babblers, obviously a
facilitator in obtaining the best in tutelage. Craig Kardon,
veteran of several years as Navratilova's coach, is the latest.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter at Boston's Ch. 7 in 1974, and a sportswriter in
various ports of call including the New York Times, Samantha is a
savvy lady who has schooled her daughter well in dealing with the
press and public. Alexandra comes across as a delightful, polite,
and outgoing kid with big brown eyes, and, at 6 feet 1 inch, a big
serve, too. She takes to the local lawns with adroit volleying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to play an attacking game, but it wasn't always that
way.'' Two of her earlier coaches had clashing ideas. Robert
Lansdorp, launcher of US champs Tracy Austin and Lindsay Davenport,
teaches both-handed backhands and baselining. Dr. Pete Fisher,
developer of Pete Sampras, insisted that Sampras and Stevenson use
one hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was traumatic for a while,'' recounts mom. ``Playing a
16-and-under final when she was 11, Alexandra was instructed by
Fisher never to use two hands again. But she was losing. She felt
she could win if she went back to the two-handed, and did. Fisher
was furious, and threatened to drop her. She cried. But we worked
it out.'' Today only the right hand is involved with the racket.
</P>
<P>
   She's a wage-earner now, and the $100 bills that the old
hustler, Bobby Riggs, held out for her don't seem so big now.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom took me to hit with Bobby. You remember when he played
Billie Jean King at the Astrodome, don't you? Anyway, he would put
$100 bills under cones on the court. `You hit the cone and you get
the money,' he told me. But you know how tricky Bobby was. He hit
the balls at me in a way I could never hit the cones.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be more tricky times and opponents, but I'm sure
there's a book in that gift carton of classics whose title covers
her dreams: Charles Dickens's ``Great Expectations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
