<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-EXPANSION?-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION MOLD BROKEN BY D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -The Arizona Diamondbacks, should they still be
considered an expansion club?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question many folks in baseball are posing as the
Diamondbacks spend their 31st consecutive day atop the National
League West standings today.
</P>
<P>
   The problem some in the game have with the Diamondbacks'
meteoric rise is that they have ignored traditional avenues in
building a contender. Basically, they've circumvented the way
things have been done by expansion clubs since the Los Angeles
Angels and Washington Senators first were added to the league in
1961.
</P>
<P>
   They have built through free agency, much like every other
big-market team in recent years. Yet they aren't the typical
expansion team lagging at the bottom of the standings, building a
farm system and waiting for the young talent to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the true sense of the word, they are an expansion team,''
said Toronto General Manager Gord Ash, who has been with the Blue
Jays since their inception in 1977. ``The term expansion has always
been used in a negative aspect in our game. It's always meant less
than stellar performance. Clearly, the Diamondbacks are changing
that thought, much like Colorado and Florida each did in making the
playoffs in their first five years. I think it's a wise trend. It
doesn't suit anybody to sit there and lose for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Because baseball is the tradition-packed game it is, some would
have preferred that the Diamondbacks take a more conservative
approach and follow the time-consuming route of building through
the farm system, a process that left the Toronto Blue Jays,
considered the model expansion franchise, waiting nine seasons
before making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the protest over the Diamondbacks' philosophy has come
from the NL West, where several front-office members seem to spend
their days grinding their teeth as they scan the NL West standings
and have to look ``up'' to the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The definition of expansion has changed dramatically over the
years,'' Diamondbacks Managing General Partner Jerry Colangelo
said. ``The price of admission has changed, as have values and
salaries. So has competition for the sports dollar, in terms of fan
support. There's much more pressure today than there was 20 years
ago or even 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The loudest opposing voice to the Diamondbacks plan resides in
San Francisco, where Giants managing general partner Peter Magowan
has spent months lashing out against Colangelo and the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Magowan railed against Arizona in a recent magazine article,
citing what he called the out-of-control spending habits of the
Diamondbacks and Los Angeles Dodgers. He also said that Colangelo
and the Dodgers broke promises they gave when they entered the
inner-circle of Major League Baseball owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Colangelo) departed from his announced strategy,'' Magowan
told the ``Sports Business Journal.'' ``The group that bought the
Dodgers did the same thing. . . . I'm used to doing business with
people you can trust and they tell you what they're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Magowan is the same owner who was taken to task by
fellow owners in December 1992 when he signed then-free agent Barry
Bonds to a six-year $42 million contract, by far the largest ever
given at that time.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, of course, are the Diamondbacks' closest competitors
in the NL West. At least one other club's management in the NL
West, that of the San Diego Padres, has also openly criticized the
Diamondbacks' spending. Padres owner John Moores voiced his
displeasure with the $118.9 million the Diamondbacks spent on free
agents over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the NL West is busy sniping at the Diamondbacks.
Colorado General Manager Bob Gebhard, who oversaw the Rockies'
quick rise as they made the playoffs faster than any previous
expansion club in 1995, is sympathetic to the Diamondbacks plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what it is, a franchise in its second year of
operations,'' Gebhard said. ``They've made great strides and been
very active in the free-agent market. I give them a lot of credit
for the changes they've made. They made a stand. Colangelo wanted
to improve that ballclub and Joe (Garagiola Jr.) and Buck
(Showalter) have made a great job in selecting players.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Rockies' playoff season in 1995, just their third
year of existence, Colorado's payroll was $30.5 million. The top
payroll that season belonged to the Showalter-managed New York
Yankees, who were paying $46.3 million in salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks current payroll stands around $65 million. The
top figure in the game once again belongs to the Yankees, who have
an $85-million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other expansion clubs, the Diamondbacks have one very big
factor working in their favor: Bank One Ballpark. The stadium,
regarded as one of the top five in baseball, is a virtual cash cow.
In terms of in-house advertising and sponsorships, BOB brought in
more money than any other stadium last season. In turn, it allows
the Diamondbacks to be active on the free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new ballpark can do a lot for a club,'' said Texas General
Manager Doug Melvin, who has seen the Rangers' revenues jump since
they moved into the Ballpark in Arlington in 1994. ``From a
financial standpoint, that can do wonders.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo insists there will be no gloating from his end, that
he and the organization are in this for the long haul. Nor, he
added, should anyone take exception to how they are going about
their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expected ``modus operandi'' for an expansion team today is
different, just by the nature of how the system has changed,''
Colangelo said. ``The old prototype doesn't exist anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Colorado experience and the Florida experience _
although two different paths were selected, one had a game plan and
got to playoffs in a record three years; the other changed their
game plan after four years and were able to gain a championship
when all the stars aligned _ there's no question times have
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to adjust in midstream. In our case, our
basis was much higher coming in.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
