<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIPS HOPES TO TEST NFL WATERS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Every time he goes to the beach, Lawrence
Phillips knows how far he's slipped.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, the first-round draft
choice-turned-Barcelona Dragon has walked to the shores of the
Mediterranean Sea to soak his battered ankle in the soothing water
instead of dunking it in a whirlpool bath _ because the only
whirlpool bath where he is comes attached to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   When he finishes his self-directed medical treatment, Phillips
limps off for another practice session and once a week he goes out
and tears apart the untutored defenses of NFL Europe, the minor
league that has become his refuge and his last chance. Phillips has
done this well enough to become the first player in league history
to rush for 1,000 yards, piling up 1,021, scoring 14 touchdowns and
averaging 5.5 yards a carry against the likes of the Scottish
Claymores and Frankfurt Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers are the kind people in the NFL notice, which is why
scouts from several teams will be in Dusseldorf, Germany, to watch
Phillips in the World Bowl championship game Sunday while many
personnel people around the NFL continue to gaze at tape of his
performances and wonder what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, Phillips was a troubled All-American on two
Nebraska national championship teams before becoming the sixth
player taken in the 1996 NFL draft. He was the kind of back you
could build a future with, the St. Louis Rams hoped, despite
personal demons that threatened him almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips spent his formative years in a juvenile home for
troubled kids in California and in college he was charged with
assaulting an ex-girlfriend, dragging her half-naked by her hair
down three flights of stairs. This was not the only problem he had
at Nebraska, only the most publicized one.
</P>
<P>
   He was suspended from the team but allowed back in time to star
in the Fiesta Bowl, a controversial move that former coach Tom
Osborne now admits may have been a mistake. Phillips then settled a
civil suit the ex-girlfriend filed against him and claimed to be
working on anger management.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips moved on to the NFL, and the Rams paid him millions.
But soon he was arrested and later convicted for drunk driving,
allegedly for going nearly 80 miles an hour through a neighborhood
posted at 35.
</P>
<P>
   In his second year, Phillips was charged with disorderly conduct
in an Omaha hotel and spent 23 days in jail for a probation
violation. Upon his release, his coach, Dick Vermeil, took him out
the jail's back door to avoid the media.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil also fined Phillips more than 50 times, mostly for being
late to meetings and practices. This went on until Phillips finally
stormed out once too often and was released 10 games into the 1997
season. He was leading the team in rushing at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But players like Phillips are seldom out of second chances, and
he got one when the Dolphins signed him several weeks later. He
lasted two games before being released basically for being a pain
in the buttocks _ which is what leads him to be soaking his ankle
in the Mediterranean before the World Bowl, with at least four NFL
teams apparently ready to give him his latest last chance.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't seem to come as much of a surprise to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, there weren't really any targets,'' Phillips
said during a press conference at which he was named World League
Offensive MVP. ``I just wanted to come over here and play like I
knew I could. There were no specific stats that I wanted to reach,
just come out here and help us win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The reason) why the players are all coming over here is to
impress the NFL scouts. When they notice and come over, it makes
everybody feel like we've gotten the job done. I owe Coach (Jack
Bicknell) a great debt. I was very happy to find out they drafted
me and were going to give me a chance to play. Coach called but
there was no big speech or anything. He just said, `You know what
you have to do. Come over and play.' And that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is no longer quite enough. Although Green Bay, Oakland,
Kansas City, and Washington are considering signing Phillips if the
price is right, many other teams believe that, as well as he's
played, it's not worth taking the risk on him yet.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens coach Brian Billick said as much last week when he told
the Baltimore Sun that he'd been looking at Phillips on tape but
added, ``I would need to know more about him. I would need a
face-to-face with him . . . If we signed him, we wouldn't be doing
it as some benevolent gesture. The parameters we'd set would be
very narrow and definable. If you're late for one meeting, you're
gone. We're not experienced enough to absorb a problem . . . but he
may not be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he may be, because he has been one everywhere he's
been except Barcelona, which is a problem in itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are so desperate for a big-time NFL back that
they've worked out broken-down veterans such as Harold Green, Terry
Allen, Raymont Harris, and James Stewart (the one who used to be
with the Vikings, not the one with the Jaguars), but vice president
of player personnel Bobby Grier said Phillips is not on his list.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody else on the horizon,'' Grier said of the backs
he's considering signing when salary cap money finally appears. ``I
hear Baltimore, Kansas City, Oakland, and Green Bay are interested
in him but I don't know if you can ever know if the guy will revert
to what he's done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a model citizen over there so far but I just wonder
how many people change their stripes once they get back to the
States and have some money again. It's a question I have, but he'll
surface somewhere in the NFL and play because there are enough
people willing to take a chance on a big, strong, fast guy like
Lawrence.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, indeed, but not as many as there were in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Even Phillips seemed to understand the changed nature of things.
Running with a football hasn't changed much, even in Dusseldorf,
but the rest of his life has, and he need only walk down to the sea
to understand the breadth of those changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough on a running back because it's one of the toughest
positions as far as trying to recover from game to game,'' Phillips
said. ``But you have to make it work. I get out in the sea and let
that be a whirlpool for me. That's the best you can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a little bit like high school in that we had to make
do with what we had. You don't have every resource that you have in
the States but we've made it work.''
</P>
<P>
   So far he has, but how much farther it will go, nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Chiefs end up winning the Lawrence Phillips Sweepstakes,
they'll qualify to open a branch of Boys Town in their backfield.
Kansas City already has Bam Morris, who is working on his fourth
team because of off-field drug problems and Phillips would be
working on his third in four years. Morris is considered the
Chiefs' best back, and they intend to use him or whomever they end
up with to get back to playing power football. Morris admits that
he weighed 300 pounds when he got out of a Texas jail last year but
is working to get down to his old playing weight of 248. Morris
sounded the same tone in Kansas City that Phillips did in
Barcelona, with one eerie exception. ``People around here seem to
realize that everyone will have problems in life,'' Morris said.
``But the big thing is, where do you go after that? Do you go down
the same path that got you in trouble or do you make a complete 360
and do the right thing?'' Unfortunately, if you make a complete
360, you're right back where you started from . . . Phillips
dropped his weight from 240 to 215 and may go down to 210 to
prepare for his return to the NFL. ``When I was in college, I put
on about 10 pounds and it didn't hurt me,'' Phillips said. ``I went
from about 200 to 210-215 and I got better. I kept putting on
weight and I didn't think it would hurt me. I got up to 235-240 and
it kind of slowed me down. Gradually, I started to notice it and I
dropped the weight and feel a lot better. I'm definitely a better
player than I was in St. Louis and Miami.'' . . . While the warring
factions in Los Angeles continue to flail away at each other rather
than reach a compromise that would allow the Coliseum to be
repaired in timely fashion or construction to begin on a new
stadium, the clock keeps ticking on their efforts to convince the
NFL to give them an expansion team. It is ticking also on Houston
businessman Robert McNair, who is all set to bring expansion to
that city but will lose his financing for a stadium in January if a
deal with the league isn't done by then. That's why some insiders
among ownership say they will enforce the Sept. 15 deadline on Los
Angeles for significant progress to be made on the stadium
problems. Some owners and NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue wanted
Gov. Gray Davis of California to get involved, and last week he
did. If something doesn't break over the summer, McNair may get the
team he deserves . . . If the LA efforts at expansion fail, don't
be surprised to see Oakland Raiders owner Al Davis join forces with
movie and oil mogul Marvin Davis to reenergize plans for a new
stadium at Hollywood Park. Marvin Davis recently bought land and
the rights to build a new stadium there, and Al Davis has always
insisted he never gave up his rights to the LA market when he took
the Raiders back to Oakland. Count on two things: If Davis builds
it, Davis will come, and if Davis builds it and Davis comes, the
NFL won't be able to do a thing about it . . . The financial
problems of Ravens owner Art Modell are forcing him to sell a
minority share of his team with a likely option for the new partner
to buy the club in the event Modell decides to sell, and this has a
number of owners upset with him. Modell claimed financial problems
in Cleveland forced him to move the Browns despite strong fan
support, and he landed a sweetheart deal in Baltimore. Now he
claims he can't make a $29 million relocation payment he owes the
other owners and is trying to get them to waive it or float him a
loan. There is little sympathy for Modell because many owners
believe he has self-inflicted problems resulting from a profligate
lifestyle. Patriots owner Robert Kraft will be a powerful figure in
this situation from his perch as chairman of the league's Finance
Committee, which would oversee any such assistance. Kraft has been
mum on the subject, but Modell has already taken public hits from
Bills owner Ralph Wilson and Giants owner Robert Tisch . . . The
NFL has decided to allow line judge Byron Boston to work the
Arizona-Denver exhibition game Aug. 14 in which his son David is
likely to be playing for the Cardinals. That would not be allowed
in the regular season or playoffs, but head of officials Jerry
Seeman decided it would not be a problem in the preseason and would
be a nice thing for both father and son. It is believed to be the
first father-son/official-player coincidence in league history . .
. Here's how things can take on a life of their own. John Thompson,
the portly Browns fan made famous by the huge dog bone he used to
wear in the end zone seats known as the Dawg Pound at the old
Stadium, has so many offers to make appearances that he's hired an
attorney to represent him . . . If you've got an extra prayer, say
it for longtime 49ers offensive line coach Bobb McKittrick, whose
battle with cancer is not going well. McKittrick recently learned
the liver transplant he needs cannot be done until the cancer,
which has spread from his bile duct, is contained. McKittrick, one
of the NFL's best assistant coaches and a gentleman, is facing an
uphill battle, but the old Marine fights on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
