<HEADLINE>
JIMENEZ: `I'M STILL VERY EXCITED, VERY HAPPY' 
 NO-HITTER SINKS IN SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Jose Jimenez jogged along the dirt warning track on
the edge of the field at Bank One Ballpark on Saturday, looking up
at the rows of empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours before, on Friday night, they were filled
with screaming fans as the St. Louis Cardinals' rookie right-hander
threw the first no-hitter of his career and the first no-hitter in
the major leagues this season.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out eight and allowed only three runners (two walks
and a hit batter) in the 1-0 victory over Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Beads of sweat rolled down Jimenez's face and neck after the
run. Someone mentioned he hardly broke a sweat Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jimenez's infectious smile returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know . . . I was working pretty hard out there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Was it still a bit hard to believe, despite all the
chest-bumping (watch out for Mr. McGwire) and revelry afterward in
the clubhouse?
</P>
<P>
   ``A little,'' Jimenez said. ``I'm still very excited, very
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old said he didn't really celebrate. Oh, there may
have been a few thoughts of a Presidente, perhaps the most popular
beer in his native Dominican Republic, crossing his lips, but it
isn't available in many places in the United States. He said he
wanted to concentrate on telling his family back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all happy for me. It was a big moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Big Unit, left-hander Randy Johnson, recognized the
big moment. Johnson, who struck out 14 and gave up the Cardinals'
run on five hits, called Jimenez at his hotel room to congratulate
him.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez (4-7, 6.02 ERA) threw a no-hitter while with the
Cardinals' Double-A Arkansas affiliate last season, but claimed he
wasn't sure he had a no-hitter going this time until about the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alberto (Castillo) wouldn't let me look at the scoreboard. He
just encouraged me the whole time, kept me going, you know, `Come
on, let's go!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Said Castillo: ``You don't want them to look at the scoreboard
in a situation like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals catcher Joe Garagiola was broadcasting Friday
night's game for the Diamondbacks' radio network. It was the fourth
no-hitter he has seen: The others were thrown by Cleveland's Dick
Bosman, Houston's Nolan Ryan and Minnesota's Jack Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola said Castillo's work behind the plate was key, keeping
Jimenez's mind in the game, providing a wide target and making a
crucial catch of a third strike against Andy Fox in the ninth. The
pitch was borderline low, and Garagiola said the fact that Castillo
caught it with the mitt facing down rather than up perhaps provided
the illusion that the pitch was higher.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Manager Tony La Russa said the most important aspect
of the effort ``was that it came in a clutch situation with the
game so close and the fact we had lost a heartbreaking game the
night before (Arizona won, 8-7), it came against a quality-hitting
team in their own park. All his pitches were working to all parts
of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be no disagreement from Arizona third baseman Matt
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sinker,'' Williams said, shaking his head at the thought.
``It was hard to square up on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Cardinals rookie, second baseman Joe McEwing, made the
game's final play on a ground ball by Tony Womack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a part of anything like that. You sort of want
the ball to be hit to you (for the last out), but you have to
concentrate on the hitter and see what happens. It's something I'll
always remember,'' said McEwing.
</P>
<P>
   So will Arizona Manager Buck Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we lost, it's a part of baseball history and you
have to take that moment in,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
