<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-EXPAND-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION TWINS DEVELOP DIFFERENTLY  
 D-BACKS DEAL, DEVIL RAYS STAND PAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just 19 months after Arizona and Tampa Bay participated in the
expansion draft, one thing has become abundantly clear: These two
franchises are taking opposite paths as they build.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, these two organizations will be linked for years
to come. It's just the way it is with expansion clubs. Toronto and
Seattle, which both joined the American League in 1977, are still
compared with one another, as are Colorado and Florida, the 1993
expansion club class.
</P>
<P>
   Of the original 35 expansion picks each club made on Nov. 17,
1997, the Diamondbacks have just 10 remaining in their
organization. At the other end of the spectrum, Tampa Bay still has
26 in its system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advice we got _ independently from people with the Marlins
and Rockies _ was that after you've scouted as long as you scouted
and they're finally your players, not to really get too attached to
them,'' said Diamondbacks General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never lose sight of the fact that you have to
immediately look and ask, `How do we get better?' After all, these
are not the players we're going to win a championship with. You
have to sort through them and see who can be part of your long-term
process.''
</P>
<P>
   In sifting through their draft picks, the Diamondbacks
discovered they may very well have some pieces to their puzzle in
players such as pitcher Omar Daal and outfielder David Dellucci, to
name two.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 25 players on the active big-league roster, the Devil
Rays have eight expansion picks. The Diamondbacks have six.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep a guy simply because he was one of your
originals,'' said Baltimore General Manager Frank Wren, who was an
assistant GM with the Florida Marlins during their expansion year.
``If you find a diamond in the rough, like we did with Jeff Conine
or Colorado did with a Vinny Castilla, or if you have a guy you
feel is a long-range fit, you keep him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I don't think it is a bad thing to turn over the
expansion picks; I think it's a healthy thing. A lot of times when
you're making trades, you might get two-for-one. If the deal is
good enough, you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has been much more aggressive when it's come to trading
than Tampa Bay. Since the handful of deals made the night of the
expansion draft, the Diamondbacks have not been afraid to delve
into the trade market. The acquisition of reliever Dan Plesac from
Toronto two weeks ago was the 15th for Arizona since the expansion
draft. They're looking to make No. 16, a move to further help the
sagging bullpen, in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Tampa Bay has made one trade in the 19 months
since the draft, sending pitcher Jason Johnson to Baltimore for
outfielder Danny Clyburn.
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness, the Diamondbacks have much more money to play
with than their expansion counterparts on the central Florida
coast, where attendance is dropping quicker than any projections.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of equal revenue streams for Tampa Bay may be keeping
it from making glitzy free-agent acquisitions which, in turn, keeps
the Devil Rays from turning over their expansion draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay has also been hit hard by injuries to their draft
picks. The Devil Rays currently have eight of their original 35 on
the disabled list, six of those on the major league DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have to remember that when you're drafting an
organization's players who are unprotected, at best, you're getting
their 16th best player,'' Florida GM Dave Dombrowski said. ``Lot's
of times it's further down the list than that. You have to be
careful because if you're looking to win championships, you'd be be
fortunate to have even one of those draft picks around.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
