u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-27 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANTA'S HIGHLIGHT SHOW GETS REEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Where to start? Well, let's see, he beat . . . no,
that's not right. But how about that match in . . . oops, cancel
that. And then there was the time he . . . uh, no, he didn't, did
he?
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, this achievement will occupy a cherished place in
Lorenzo Manta's memory bank basically because until Saturday, the
vault was empty.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Swiss tennis nonentity has found it almost
impossible to get into Wimbledon, let alone into its second week.
When the tournament began, he ranked a lofty 196th in the world,
owing to his gilded record in Grand Slam, ATP Tour, and Davis Cup
matches _ 0-11. That's for his seven-year career, if you can call
it that.
</P>
<P>
   But, implausibly, he took out the No. 5 men's seed and 1996
champion Richard Krajicek, 6-3, 7-6 (7-5), 4-6, 4-6, 6-4, in a
2-hour 47-minute third-round exercise in shock therapy on the All
England Club's dreaded Court 2.
</P>
<P>
   The color theme here is green, and tradition is sacrosanct, but
they really ought to make an exception for No. 2. Drape it in black
crepe and resod it with 6 feet of dirt. Krajicek would gladly
oversee the remodeling, perhaps Sunday on the traditional
mid-tournament hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's far less a court than Centre or No. 1,'' he said.
``There's a lot of worse bounces. For me, the reason why it's
called graveyard is because they've been digging it or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite, Richard. It's the results, not the conditions, that
cause Court 2 to live in infamy as ``The Graveyard of Champions.''
Krajicek became the latest name on a gold-embossed tombstone that
already included Ilie Nastase, Jimmy Connors, John McEnroe, Arthur
Ashe, Boris Becker, and, just two days ago, Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Sanchez Vicario's funeral, Krajicek, the man from
the Netherlands, had emerged from that netherworld by disposing of
Todd Woodbridge. But the All England folks must have a grudge
against Krajicek; they put him on 2 again. Still, he had every
right to beat Manta, because just about everybody has _ including
Krajicek four years ago in a Davis Cup singles match he considers
so noteworthy that he couldn't remember a thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shame in that; Manta is hard-pressed to come up with
personal highlights himself. Asked what had been his peak
accomplishment, he paused for the longest time, tugged on his
baseball cap, and said, somewhat sheepishly, ``I don't know. Not
too much, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is life for a 6-foot-3-inch, 180-pounder who roams the
shadow world of tennis, primarily playing the satellite and
challenger circuits when he's not trying _ and failing _ to qualify
for the majors. It's basically a blur of ineptitude to him. He
knows he's tried to make the French and US Opens, but he can't
specify how many times. The number of successes is easier to
compute: zero.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, Wimbledon has been a garden spot for Manta. It's
the only Grand Slam event in which he's made the main draw _ in
1996, when he advanced all the way to the first round before losing
to Alexander Volkov in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, freed from the litany of shoulder, elbow, and
hand injuries that, along with consistent failure, prompted him to
consider retirement a couple of years ago, Manta has made a
breakthrough. He beat Tom Spinks in the first round, then knocked
off 49th-ranked Jan-Michael Gambill. And he didn't consider his
task against Krajicek hopeless. ``I felt I had a chance,'' he said.
``A small one.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he was a preying Manta right from the start, stunning
Krajicek by capturing the first two sets, the second in a 7-5
tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was serving pretty well in the first two sets,'' said Manta,
``and you have to keep focusing against him because you don't get
many chances to break him, and I got the first break right at the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   The natural order seemed about to prevail when Krajicek took the
next two sets. But Manta pounced again, breaking his opponent in
the first game of the fifth set and shaking off thoughts of the
inevitable when Krajicek erased that advantage by breaking back to
3-4. Manta then became a bulldog on his returns, and when he broke
Krajicek on match point with a slice down the line, Court 2 had
struck again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let a few important points go,'' said Krajicek, ``but in the
end, I was surprised how well he played because I expected him
actually to get a little nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Manta let him in on a little secret: ``I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait until he sees his paycheck. Having piled up $151,305 in
lifetime earnings before landing in London, he's guaranteed $50,960
for reaching the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Manta set off the lone tremor as Wimbledon's weeklong
sorting-out process concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Second seed Patrick Rafter avenged his Australian Open loss to
Thomas Enqvist, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2, 6-2; No. 4 Andre Agassi, the French
champ, lost his first set of the week but still dispatched Alberto
Martin, 6-2, 6-0, 2-6, 6-3; No. 8 Todd Martin withstood Jens
Knippschild, 6-7 (5-7), 6-1, 7-6 (8-6), 7-5; No. 10 Goran
Ivanisevic swept Paul Haarhuis, 7-6 (7-2), 6-4, 7-6 (7-3); and
three-time winner Becker extended his second Wimbledon farewell in
three years by ousting Lleyton Hewitt, 6-1, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
   There were no surprises among the top 10 women as No. 3 Lindsay
Davenport whipped Laura Golarsa, 6-3, 6-2; defender and fifth seed
Jana Novotna paid back Maria Antonia Sanchez Lorenzo for her
Australian Open defeat, 6-4, 6-3; and No. 9 Mary Pierce subdued
Elena Wagner, 6-3, 6-0. Meanwhile, qualifier Jelena Dokic, Martina
Hingis's conqueror, remained a fairy princess at least until next
week, beating Anne Kremer, 6-7 (7-9), 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
