<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOCCER STAR OFTEN RUNS ON EMPTY  
 AKERS SUFFERS CHRONIC FATIGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Michelle Akers seemed to struggle to force out the
words. It was difficult for her to admit that, perhaps, a day off
might be a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Akers doesn't want to sit out any match, or even a part of a
match, especially not during this premier international soccer
event, the Women's World Cup. But with the U.S. national team all
be assured of advancing to the quarterfinals, U.S. Coach Tony
DiCicco will likely rest Akers and a few other starters tonight
against North Korea in the Group A finale at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After a practice session on Saturday at Babson College, neither
DiCicco nor Akers would tip their hands as to who would be the
starters. DiCicco said he had his lineup fairly well set in his
mind, but would not release it to the public. Akers laughingly said
she couldn't ``give away our top-secret plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Akers knows better than any other player the value of a day
off. The veteran midfielder suffers from chronic fatigue syndrome,
a disease that saps her strength and forces wholesale changes in
her lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone would notice when she is on the field. Akers,
33, has been with the national program since its inception in 1985.
She is one of only four players in the world to score more than 100
goals. At 5 feet 10, she is intimidating on defense and an imposing
and dangerous figure in front of the opposition's net.
</P>
<P>
   But Akers knows she must pace herself throughout the grueling
World Cup schedule. She was replaced before the second half of
Thursday's 7-1 victory over Nigeria in Chicago, and insists she
won't complain should DiCicco opt to rest her again tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating and at times I get really ticked off,'' Akers
said of needing to take an occasional break because of her disease.
``Seeing the team do well and get excited while I'm sitting on the
bench is tough to deal with. But if Tony decides to give me a rest,
I won't, as my dad says, puff out my chest, curl my lower lip and
pout. I know this World Cup is a sprint, it's not a marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   In order for Akers to reach the finish line, of even a single
match, she must make concessions to her disease. She doesn't
participate in all the team drills during practice. She adheres to
a stringent diet. She receives intravenous fluids after playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into a game with only half a tank and you expend
that in the first half, you use up the tank too quickly,'' she
said. ``So I have to take measures to keep going as long as I can.
I evaluate what I eat, I stay hydrated and I do like I did today,
just stay off to the side and work on my own. If I can be mature
about it, stay disciplined and keep doing all the things I've been
doing, then I will be rewarded in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   While Akers' teammates are reaping the rewards now during a
World Cup that has received tremendous receptions across the United
States, Akers stays pretty much in the shadows. She doesn't attend
all the team functions and she doesn't do commercials or chat with
talk-show hosts.
</P>
<P>
   But ask any member of the team who is the most respected,
admired and inspirational player, and the majority will say
Michelle Akers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's done more for women's soccer than anyone else,''
megastar Mia Hamm said. ``From Day One, she set the standards. She
showed us the proper mentality for the game and how to work hard,
all the while being very professional about it. She's really helped
take this team and the sport of women's soccer to a higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is very much responsible for all I've learned and
accomplished in this game,'' defender Brandi Chastain said. ``I've
relied on her as a resource for many things, as a person and a
player.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
