<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVELRY SPURRED ON AND ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The small room is humid on this early Saturday
morning. The smells of cigar smoke and sweat, champagne and beer
clog the air. This tiny visitors locker room at Madison Square
Garden is where the San Antonio Spurs are celebrating their first
NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   An hour earlier, these men had defeated the New York Knicks,
78-77, to win the best-of-seven Finals, four games to one. The game
ended late Friday night. Now it is after midnight, and you hear and
see things that you usually don't experience in NBA locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Jaren Jackson is standing in a corner, talking to a television
reporter. The reporter asks him what message he has for fans in San
Antonio, fans who might take to the streets to celebrate the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' Jackson answers. ``You all stay away from my car! My
car is out on those streets! Don't be tearing up my car, you hear
me?''
</P>
<P>
   He cracks up laughing. He is smoking a cigar. Earlier, he played
24 minutes, made three 3-pointers, and scored 11 points. He still
is wearing his sweaty No. 2 uniform, with a ``Spurs _ NBA Champs''
T-shirt pulled over the jersey. It is covered with sweat and
champagne. He spots teammate Will Perdue, once a member of three
Chicago Bulls championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Will,'' says Jackson. ``When you were with the Bulls and
y'all won the title, did you take a shower?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell no,'' Perdue answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' Jackson says. ``I ain't taking a shower. I'm
going out just like this.''
</P>
<P>
   No one even tries to persuade Jackson to take five minutes and
head to a nearby shower. Maybe next time. This is a group that
seems to believe there could be many more titles in its future. The
Spurs' best player, 7-footer Tim Duncan, is 23 years old. His first
year in the league, he was the league's Rookie of the Year as well
as a first-team All-NBA forward. In his second season, he finished
third in the MVP voting, won the NBA championship, and was voted
MVP of the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is a true original. Not simply because he averaged 23
points and 12 rebounds in the NBA Finals. It's the way he did it.
He has been playing basketball for less than 10 years, but you get
the feeling he could teach it. His go-to shot is an old one, the
bank shot. But if you start to get too comfortable around him,
thinking that he is a landlocked type, he can dunk on you as well.
</P>
<P>
   In this fifth and final game, he and New York's Latrell Sprewell
engaged in a classic sword fight (remember, Duncan collects knives
and swords). Sprewell had 35 points and Duncan 31. But Sprewell
went to a quiet locker room after the game, while Duncan showed
he's not completely old-fashioned: He immediately got hold of a
home video camera to catch the reaction of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just making some records for myself,'' he says. ``Just keeping
it on tape. I don't know, it's a blessing to get to where I am now,
it's a blessing to do what we did this year. There's no guarantees
I'll ever get back. So I'm enjoying this team, documenting this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   It is truly a strange Saturday morning for the NBA. Usually, it
is coaches and scouts who make tapes of players. But there is
Duncan, videotaping his teammates. Just over two years ago, two
representatives from the Celtics _ Jan Volk and M.L. Carr _ sat in
a room as tiny as this one watching tapes of Duncan. He was in
college then, and the Celtics thought they were going to get him.
He made a move in that college game, and Carr looked at Volk and
smiled. He'll be doing that in Boston one day, they thought. Not
quite. He was doing that 200 miles away in New York, doing it for
the Spurs, the NBA champions.
</P>
<P>
   In a less smoky room, David Robinson is sitting with his son.
His son is asking a lot of questions. There are cameras everywhere.
Robinson, 33, is finally a champion. Echoes of Avery Johnson and
Mario Elie are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Elie: ``I said, `Dave, shut everybody up. They can leave you
alone now. You've accomplished everything in your career. This was
the final chapter.' I told him when he wrote his autobiography, he
better have a paragraph in there about me, or at least a chapter.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson: ``He knows I'm one of his greatest critics, behind him
and to his face. Sometimes we have a love-hate relationship. That's
a guy I really love, and I'm so pumped for him right now. What else
can he do? What else can he do? He's done everything.''
</P>
<P>
   All of these Spurs have interesting stories. Take Johnson. The
Spurs once cut him on Christmas Eve. Another time, he had just
finished being a groomsman in Robinson's wedding when he found that
the Spurs had cut him again. But on Friday against the Knicks, he
hit the winning shot. He got himself open in a corner, 18 feet from
the hoop, and made a jumper with 47 seconds left. That made the
score 78-77. The smallest and most rejected Spur hit the winning
shot in the biggest game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, understand why this small room is now so smoky and
joyous and loud. The Iceman, George Gervin, is in one corner
smiling. Security is lax, so people without the proper credentials
are now entering the room. Jackson stands up and looks at Jerome
Kersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, chief,'' he says to the veteran forward. ``We got a ring,
chief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for this for 15 years,'' Kersey says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chief,'' Jackson repeats, ``we've got ourselves a ring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
