<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTAW ANSWERED CALL FOR LPGA 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ The phone call came in January, on a
Thursday. From Orlando, LPGA commissioner Jim Ritts phoned deputy
commissioner Ty Votaw, who was in Waco, Texas, for the induction of
Judy Rankin into the Texas Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was planing to resign,'' said Votaw, ``and he said
he had spoken to a number of our board members telling them of his
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritts had asked the board members to talk to Votaw about his
interest in the job. Votaw, who has been with the LPGA since 1991,
flew to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went home Sunday, talked it over with my wife, and I told
them, `If offered, I would accept it,' '' said Votaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the next thee days talking to various board members,
mostly players. They had a board meeting on Wednesday, and on
Friday I was offered the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of it happened within a span of eight days.''
</P>
<P>
   Votaw, who studied journalism at Ohio University and received a
law degree from Ohio State, became the sixth commissioner of the
largest women's sports organization in the United States, one that
celebrates its 50th anniversary next year.
</P>
<P>
   Votaw originally was hired as general counsel by former
commissioner Charles Mechem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd worked for the LPGA for eight years, so I've learned at
the feet of two pretty good commissioners,'' he said. ``They
brought a lot to the table, so that will enable me to go into the
job with my eyes open and know what the challenges and
opportunities are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest adjustment has been to get to work with the media.
I tell people I'm a recovering lawyer. One step in the recovery of
a lawyer is to talk to the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Votaw, who is here for the LPGA Championship at DuPont CC, has
been involved heavily with the growth of an organization that has
passed some troubled times but still suffers in comparison with the
PGA Tour and PGA Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past 10 years have seen the biggest growth, and it's
important to continue to grow in a competitive marketplace,'' he
said. ``We've increased our purses over the past 10 years. We've
increased them by 75 percent over the past five years. The number
of television events has gone from 14 in 1991 to 34 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our biggest challenge is going to be continuing to do
a good job with help from our tournament sponsors. I want to focus
on the positive realities rather than the negative perceptions that
might be out there. We're very successful. We're the most
successful women's organization I think in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take joy in other people's downfalls or lack of
success, but we feel very good about where we are in the sports
marketplace. We're celebrating our 50th anniversary next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `How do you feel about the disparity between you
and the PGA Tour?' Just because we're not as successful as some
other organizations does not mean, in fact, we're not successful.
We push the number of TV hours, the quality of play, the
international expansion we've been able to do. There's a lot of
depth in the foreign players. We have a world tour. I think our
players are going to focus on that. Can we get better? Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   There are lucrative contracts in Korea in large part because of
Se Ri Pak, in Australia because of Karrie Webb, and in Sweden
because of Annika Sorenstam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The percentage of our TV revenues had been basically 75
percent domestic and 25 percent foreign,'' said Votaw. ``Today it's
55 percent domestic and 45 percent international.''
</P>
<P>
   The only regret the new commissioner has is that he can't attend
a Bruce Springsteen concert this summer because of an LPGA board
meeting that conflicts with the schedule. The Boss has to attend to
business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Webb left the farm town of Ayr near the Queensland
coast of Australia to join the LPGA Tour in 1996, she has been a
force. She won rookie of the year honors and hasn't finished out of
the top five in earnings. She entered the LPGA Championship with
five victories this year, 14 in her brief career, and the No. 1
spot on the money list with $941,1984. ``I have always focused,
from a young age, on what I wanted to do,'' said Webb on the eve of
the tournament. ``I dreamed about being out here. I still enjoyed
my teenage years and school years, but I wanted to play golf and to
be in the position I am now.'' She had 13 starts entering the LPGA
Championship _ and 13 finishes in the top 10. ``That's sort of a
goal I set for myself every week,'' said Webb, ``and you always
wonder when the week is going to come and you don't finish in the
top 10. It's not going to last forever.'' Indeed it didn't, as Webb
missed the cut here with 72-72_144 . . . Pat Bradley, who played in
the LPGA Championship at Pleasant Valley CC in Sutton, Mass., in
her rookie season of 1974, is looking forward to returning to the
venue for the LPGA Boston Classic Aug. 5-8. It was the late Cuz
Mingolla who brought the LPGA and PGA to Sutton, and he passed the
baton to his son, Ted, who will preside over this year's event. ``I
am really looking forward to going home,'' said Bradley, a native
of Westford, Mass. ``The players are absolutely going to love it. I
think Junior (Ted) is going to love having us there. Junior's a
smart guy. He knows the right thing to do, and that is bringing us
back.'' . . . Nancy Lopez, who withdrew from the LPGA Championship
to undergo arthroscopic surgery on her right knee, should be able
to return to the golf course in four weeks. Dr. Craig Morgan, who
performed the surgery, told the News Journal of Wilmington, ``The
procedure went well and there were no surprises. She will probably
be able to pick up her clubs in two weeks and be back playing in
about four weeks. She couldn't even walk. It was not like she was
limping around a little bit. She couldn't walk.'' The doctor said
she will eventually need a knee replacement . . . Rosie Jones has
knocked on the door in each of the LPGA's four majors but never won
one. She was locked in a duel to the finish with Hollis Stacy in
the 1984 US Women's Open at Salem (Mass.) CC. But Jones faltered,
bogeying the final hole, and Stacy won the championship for the
second time. She is not convinced that a win at Salem would have
paved the way to more victories. ``I was pretty young,'' said
Jones. ``I was only 24, on the tour two years, and actually the
next week I tied in Rochester and got beat in a playoff. I think
those types of outcomes were the best for me, because I needed to
grow a little bit and become a better golfer and get ready. But
coming down that stretch in the Open at Salem, I was right there
leading or tied for the lead. I got a little too aggressive on the
last hole, got above the hole and pretty much had an impossible
chip. I was young, and probably a little dumb. I have kind of paid
all my dues, sowed all my oats, and made all those beds. I'm ready
to play better golf right now. I'm better prepared for the
challenge.'' She opened with a 64, missing the course record by one
. . . There is little question that the men's US Open will return
to Pinehurst No. 2. David Fay, executive director of the US Golf
Association, said as much last Sunday in published interviews.
``You'd be hard pressed to find any reason to not believe the US
Open will return to Pinehurst No. 2,'' Fay told the News and
Observer in Raleigh, N.C. ``It has been an unqualified success''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
