<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ROAD-RACES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE BEATEN TRACK  
 MOST AGREE ROAD COURSES ARE GOOD _ IN MODERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. - It is pretty here. The scenic Pacific coast is
nearby, and Napa Valley is just up the road.
</P>
<P>
   The weather? Gorgeous. The high around the Bay area today is
supposed to be about 72 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it nearly July?
</P>
<P>
   And who can argue the importance of the San Francisco market?
</P>
<P>
   But with so many emerging racetracks seeking NASCAR Winston Cup
races, not to mention established facilities such as Texas Motor
Speedway and Phoenix International Raceway beating the drum for
profitable second-race dates, should NASCAR think twice about being
here?
</P>
<P>
   Sears Point Raceway, the site of today's 112-lap race over a
twisting 10-turn, 1.949-mile layout, and Watkins Glen (N.Y.)
International are the only road courses on NASCAR's crowded
schedule, taking up two spots on a crowded 34-race circuit.
</P>
<P>
   As such, they represent odd configurations in a series defined
by banked ovals and left-hand turns.
</P>
<P>
   Odd enough to remove them from the schedule to make room for
more traditional ovals?
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect if you polled the garage, it would be 50-50 on
whether we should be road racing or not,'' NASCAR executive Mike
Helton said. ``But the same would happen if you polled them about
short tracks or 2{-mile superspeedways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the end of it all is Sears Point and Watkins Glen
offer a style of racing that complements the championship. When a
driver today can win the NASCAR title with all the variables we
throw at them, their credibility as champion is much more
apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Sears Point and Watkins Glen likely aren't going to
disappear from the NASCAR schedule anytime soon, which won't upset
drivers such as Jeremy Mayfield and Sterling Marlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need the road courses,'' Mayfield said. ``I don't
want to run them 36 times a year, but twice, or even three or four
times, wouldn't be that bad of a deal at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that makes Winston Cup racing so cool, I think, and
makes the championship so important, is the fact we run on every
kind of track there is. If you win the championship or if you
finish high in the points, you've proven you're one of the best
teams in all of racing, not just stock-car racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Marlin has been labeled as someone with a distaste for
road racing, the opposite is true.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fun to race,'' Marlin said. ``It's not the most
competitive stuff we do and you don't see a lot of passing, but if
you're sitting in the driver's seat of one of these things, it's
pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Sears Point has only been on NASCAR's schedule since 1989, when
it was added to fill a void following the West Coast departure of
Riverside (Calif.) International Raceway (1958-1988), also a
road-racing venue.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins Glen was home to NASCAR races in 1957, 1964 and 1965,
then disappeared until returning in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1965 race, retired driver Buddy Baker, now a television
commentator at several NASCAR races, finished third.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a Winston Cup champion, you should be able to adapt to
short tracks, big tracks and road courses,'' Baker said. ``Dropping
Sears Point would be like dropping Martinsville or Bristol. I
really think road courses are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it when I did it. You get tired of the clones, the
tracks that are exactly alike. You need diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time driving champion Ned Jarrett, also a television
commentator, finished one position ahead of Baker in the '65 race.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some sense, road races were a necessary evil, but in
another sense, it was a special challenge _ and that's what drivers
look forward to,'' Jarrett said. ``I think part of the appeal of
Winston Cup racing is the fact that they run on so many different
types of racetracks. It further tests the skills of a driver and a
team setting up a race car.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other side of the coin, most of the time fans can't see
all the way around the racetrack. But they still come out in big
numbers, so I guess they're willing to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although road racing adds a hefty price tag to the yearly
budget, car owner/driver Ricky Rudd said he thought removing Sears
Point or Watkins Glen would be detrimental to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a car for the road courses that you don't race
anywhere else, and we're talking $100,000 a car,'' Rudd said. ``But
I would enjoy even more road courses. The feedback I get from fans
is they really like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Car owner Travis Carter, whose driver Jimmy Spencer never has
posted a top-10 finish at Sears Point, also sees the merits of road
courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a business perspective, California is a big state and it
has a lot of people,'' Carter said. ``It's a big market for these
companies that sponsor NASCAR racing. How can you say no to that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, for us, (Sears Point) is a little bit of a
refreshing venue.''
</P>
<P>
   So refreshing NASCAR doesn't seem intent on turning its back on
the pretzel-shaped courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only run on two each year, so it's not a major-type issue
with us,'' said Helton, who in February was tabbed by NASCAR
President Bill France Jr. to take over the organization's
day-to-day operations. ``It's fun and it's different, but we're not
going to be out there looking for a lot more road courses to run
when at the same time you have all the oval opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two a year works well.''
</P>
<P>
   It works well for John Andretti, who finished third in last
year's Sears Point race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans enjoy it, and I think everybody likes
something different every once in a while,'' Andretti said. ``I
don't know if everyone would like it if, say, half the races were
on road corses. They're not always everybody's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these guys are awfully good racers, period. And the road
courses give you another chance to show what you can do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
