r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-CENTERS-AZR     06-27 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-CENTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIAN IS THE CENTER OF ATTENTION  
 BUT RADOJEVIC LACKS EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are no secrets in the NBA draft. Every team may hope to
find that player everybody else missed, but it rarely happens.
</P>
<P>
   Even Aleksandar Radojevic, who slipped out of the Yugoslavian
army's grasp by playing basketball at Barton County Community
College in Kansas, couldn't escape the long reach of the NBA's
talent spies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make this massive drive to see him play in Great
Bend, Kansas,'' said Dave Babcock, scouting director of the
Milwaukee Bucks and a former coach at Arizona Western junior
college. ``It was classic JUCO. They introduced the players, and
then they introduced the coach (Ryan Cross).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of a big guy. His shirt tail wasn't quite tucked in.
And when he came out on the floor, he was carrying one of those Big
Gulp sodas.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was worth the trip. There were a few big gulps in store
for Babcock as he watched Barton County's star player, the 7-foot-3
Radojevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played the point of their press, had great footwork, ran
well and had a nice shooting touch,'' Babcock said. ``It's amazing
the stuff he can do facing the basket for a guy who's 7-2 or
whatever he is. The big question is his lack of strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Radojevic's sleight build _ he weighs about 245
pounds _ and style, he could play forward at the start of his pro
career, despite his height.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Babcock figured he was watching a player who wouldn't
be in the NBA for at least another year anyway. Radojevic signed a
letter of intent to play for Ohio State. But the NCAA ruled the
22-year-old former water polo player from Montenegro ineligible
because he had played a total of 19 minutes in four games for
Papagou, a professional club in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He found out about a week before players had to declare
themselves for the draft,'' said Marc Cornstein, who represents
Radojevic and other European players. ``He's the biggest enigma,
both literally and figuratively, in the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Radojevic set out on a cross-country tour of NBA teams for
individual workouts, including one for the Suns on June 17. In all,
he worked out for 16 teams, including the Chicago Bulls, who have
the No. 1 overall pick but might trade down in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, I saw a mock draft on the Internet that had him
going 36th,'' Cornstein said. ``We saved that just to remind
ourselves where he started on this journey. I'm an optimist. I
thought that when word got out, his stock would rise. I didn't
expect it to rise as much as it has.''
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic is likely to go somewhere near the middle of the first
round after some impressive workouts.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a leap, considering he only began playing basketball
when he was 16. He grew to 7-feet by the time he was 19 and was
measured at 7-2} recently. The plan was to spend two years at
Barton County, then develop further at a major university before
embarking on an NBA career.
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic said that was his preference, but his timetable had to
change because of the NCAA's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a huge step,'' Radojevic said in a telephone
conversation from Salt Lake City, where he worked out for the Jazz
Wednesday. ``I planned to go to Ohio State. The experience in
junior college was good, but there was no competition. What I did
in junior college, it doesn't matter because I didn't play anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm somebody nobody in the NBA knows. I didn't play in any big
league so I'm new to all these people. I have to prove myself.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Radojevic figures he'll be playing in the NBA. If not
for the game, he might have wound up in the war in Kosovo. A
Serbian, he grew up on the Montenegro coast and worried that he
would be drafted into the army.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't come here and pick me up,'' he said, laughing.
``If I had been in Yugoslavia at the time, I would have been
drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   A thought which horrifies Cornstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 7-foot-3 guy makes a pretty good target,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic, whose father died a few years ago, said he plans to
bring his mother and the rest of his family to the United States
once he's established. He makes no secret of his disgust for what
happened in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation bad for all people,'' he said. ``It doesn't
matter if they were Albanian or Serbian, it was bad for all of
them. Everybody suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are idiot politicians in every country, and people are
suffering because of them. It's wrong. A lot of people died for
nothing. I'm sad for the people, but not the politicians. They're
all idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   One Yugoslavian, and fellow Serbian, whom Radojevic admires
greatly is Sacramento Kings center Vlade Divac.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to work hard to break his records,'' Radojevic said.
``A lot of kids can learn from his example, especially off the
court. He's a great person.''
</P>
<P>
   But not necessarily Radojevic's role mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to be like Hakeem Olajuwon,'' he said. ``And to
pass like Arvydas Sabonis. That would be a great combination, eh?''
</P>
<P>
   One worth the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Booth, 6-11, Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic, but only 220 pounds. But he's ``long'' as the scouts
like to say for players with long arms and legs, who can get off
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's left-handed, and a good shot blocker,'' said Suns Player
Personnel Director Dick Van Arsdale. ``He has a pretty decent
shooting touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan Eschmeyer, 7-2, Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   Overachiever and a hard worker. Not very athletic. Thus, typical
of this year's centers.
</P>
<P>
   Others to watch: Tim Young, 7-1, Stanford; Todd McCulloch, 7-0,
Washington. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
