<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MERCURY-SHOCK-AZR     06-27 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-SHOCK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEPRINT FOR MERCURY SUCCESS  
 PLAYERS CITE TEAM EFFORT IN WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ There was something foundational about the
Mercury's 66-60 win over the Detroit Shock on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its previous victories, over struggling Cleveland and
inexperienced Washington, this was more controlled and repeatable.
In leading from 14:24 of the first half on, Phoenix (3-4) looked
like a team that found a clue amidst the ashes of an 88-72 loss to
Charlotte on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we see how we're capable of playing,'' said Lisa Harrison,
who steadied a lineup without Clarissa Davis-Wrightsil for almost
all of the second half. ``We were really embarrassed last game. It
helps our confidence to come out and show what we can do and to
play together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Mercury played with patience for the first time
all season, shooting 51.6 percent in the first half when it led
35-22 before dropping back to 37-32 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the Shock (4-4) found a higher defensive gear in the
second half and Phoenix went just 6-for-27 (22.2 percent) from the
field, the Mercury kept grinding on both ends of the court and
converted 11-of-14 free throws in the final 1:43.
</P>
<P>
   In losing before 7,651 at The Palace and a national television
audience, Detroit falls to 0-4 all-time vs. Phoenix, a sore point
with the Shock staff of former Mercury Nancy Lieberman-Cline and
former Mercury assistant Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like the Wizard of Oz,'' said Lieberman-Cline, in her
second season as Detroit coach/general manager. ``We don't have
courage, we don't have heart and sometimes we don't have a brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix was lacking all those qualities against Charlotte, which
lost to Detroit, 75-69, Tuesday, but finally appears to have bought
into the four-pass offense that ``lets us see what the weak side
looks like,'' Coach Cheryl Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we played like a team, and when we play like a team we
look great,'' said point guard Michele Timms, who held her
Australian mate Sandy Brondello three below her 16.6 scoring
average. ``We know that it's just a matter of us putting our
individual needs aside and deciding that we're going to do this as
a team. Team overrides the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller credited Timms with her best game of the season. She and
the other Australian Mercury point, Kristi Harrower, had 5 assists
apiece as Phoenix had a 17-9 lead in that category. And just as
significantly, a 35-25 rebounding edge including a game-high 13 by
Jennifer Gillom, who with 17 points posted her third double-double.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury was outscored in the paint, 30-24, for the seventh
straight time but by taking better shots stymied Detroit in
transition and for the first time this season had an advantage,
7-5, in fast-break points.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we need to focus on our defense, and that's
going to help our offense,'' Harrison said. ``And being more
patient in our offense and not thinking one person has to get the
ball and go 1-on-1. That's not going to work for us, for us to
solely focus on Jen and for her to carry us through the season. We
need to get help from everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the 6-foot Harrison, who played 20 of her 28 minutes in the
second half after Davis-Wrightsil, with 14 first-half points,
cracked her right knee on the floor. She finished with 9 points, 3
rebounds, 2 assists and a steal and made three of the stretch free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   And 6-8 Maria Stepanova, playing 19 minutes because Marlies
Askamp was in foul trouble, who had 6 blocks to go with 6 rebounds
and 3 points. The Russian is up to 14 blocks (2.00 average) and
pressing Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith and Charlotte's Vicky
Bullett for the league lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Dominique Canty, with a team-high 16 points off the
bench, kept Detroit within three, 55-52, with 3:33 remaining. But
Astou Ndiaye missed an open layup off a feed from Canty, then the
Mercury refused to crack in its parade to the line, going 19-for-23
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit guard Jennifer Azzi sat out a second consecutive game
due to a left hamstring injury. Starting forward Cindy Brown
suffered a possible fractured tailbone with 5:13 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury is more than halfway through its seven-game road
trip with a 2-2 record and plays Monday at Cleveland. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
