<HEADLINE>
LEAGUE LOSING GROUND IN FINANCIAL DRAG RACE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The world's latest batch of teenage millionaires took
the giant step into the deep green sea with Saturday's amateur
draft inside the Vault. For those new to National Hockey League
economics, the collective bargaining agreement between owners and
labor ``limits'' this year's first-round picks to a maximum annual
salary of $1.025 million.
</P>
<P>
   These golden-bladed wannabes _ we can't even call them rookies
yet _ have played a key role in the high spike in league salaries
ever since the CBA took hold in January 1995. The owners wanted a
salary ``drag,'' part of the reason they locked out the players in
the fall of '94, and were convinced that the rookie cap would bring
the desired slowdown. It hasn't happened. The drag has turned into
a cash cudgel for the players.
</P>
<P>
   Primo draft picks aren't the entire reason for runaway pay, but
they unquestionably have driven up the price of lower-end talent.
When the 18-year-old first-rounder with 0-0_0 next to his name
pockets a guarantee of $3 million-plus over three years, every guy
with a year or two in the league, even if his career totals read
0-0_1, looks at the entry-level cash grab for some leverage.
</P>
<P>
   For example, what do you expect Hal Gill will want from the
Bruins? The towering defenseman made $410,000 last season as Ray
Bourque's blue line partner. The 207th pick in the '93 draft, Gill
in two seasons has shaped into a respectable, reliable presence.
His pride and his pay expanded considerably when the great Jaromir
Jagr identified him as the toughest guy to go around in the league.
He'll take that endorsement to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Gill undoubtedly will look at the pay for this year's
first-round picks as a payroll template. The Bruins won't like
hearing that, and will dismiss it by pointing to the ``207'' next
to Gill's name. But rest assured any club picking in the first
round Saturday _ especially those selecting after, say, No. 12 _
would have been glad to leave FleetStreet knowing it got another
Gill.
</P>
<P>
   The CBA doesn't expire until the spring of 2004. Until then,
owners will have to live with the deal they cut in '94 and then
quickly extended to its current termination date. The desired drag
hasn't materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've gotten it, but it hasn't been enough,'' said NHL
commissioner Gary Bettman. ``The first two years of the CBA, it was
working fine _ revenues were increasing faster than salaries. The
last two years it has been the the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   So where does it go from here?
</P>
<P>
   ``Either teams will adjust, which they have the ability to do,
at least theoretically under the CBA,'' said Bettman, ``or when we
get to the next round of bargaining, we will fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a certain emphasis and conviction in Bettman's voice
when he said, ``We will fix it.'' It wasn't quite Nikita Khruschev
declaring, ``We will bury you,'' but it had weight. It sounded as
if another lockout loomed on the horizon. Is that what he meant?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Bettman. ``We will fix it. Whatever it takes to fix
it. The league from a revenue standpoint has never been stronger.
Our revenues the last five years have grown a half-billion dollars
a year. We're not having a revenue problem. We're having an
expense-side problem. And any well-run business has to address that
when the appropriate time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, the NHL decided last Monday to adopt
four-on-four play as a five-minute tie-breaker next season. When
the game is tied after 60 minutes, both clubs will receive a point
in the standings. A third point will be awarded to a club that
scores when the two sides are skating one man down during overtime.
Sorry, but I can't get too excited. It's a gimmick. It only
encourages clubs to play it safe, put 1 point in the bank, and then
let it all hang out for the five minutes. How about no points for a
tie? Let's see how they play when they both teams know they'll walk
with nothing at the end of the night . . . Outgoing Tampa owner Art
Williams, the same guy who last year told us No. 1 draft pick
Vincent LeCavalier would be ``the Michael Jordan of hockey,''
torched a deal last week that had top Czech goalie prospect Roman
Turek joining the Bolts from Dallas. New Lightning boss Rick Dudley
cut the deal, but Williams kiboshed it, pointing to the fact that
he technically still owned the club and didn't want to be on the
hook for Turek's salary if the sale wasn't finalized. What's going
on here? Williams has agreed to sell to Bill Davidson. The right
thing to do would have been for Williams to ask Davidson to
guarantee Turek's pay. Instead, he voided it and the Stars then
flipped Turek to the Blues for a third-round pick (something
Williams could have done, if his doomsday scenario came true). It's
time for this deal to get done before the ongoing joke that is
Tampa becomes the next club headed to the courtroom . . . Larry
Kelly, ex- of North Quincy and now the Stars' fine public relations
director, took one for the team Saturday night when the Stars
clinched the Cup. He cut his hand while lugging the Conn Smythe
Trophy (playoff MVP) with recipient Joe Nieuwendyk. Dallas doctors
reportedly have suggested a well-deserved month-long soaking in
Cape Cod Bay as the cure . . . You can look it up: Phil Housley
received one vote in the Norris Trophy balloting as the league's
top defenseman . . . The Flyers left Luke Richardson available in
Friday's exansion draft, but the Thrashers weren't biting. Philly
GM Bob Clarke says he'll renew attempts to trade the former Oiler
blue liner, whom he brought to Broad Street for a five-year deal
worth $12.5 million. ``For whatever reason,'' said Clarke,
``(coach) Roger (Neilson) doesn't like the way he plays _ it's not
the player's fault.'' Richardson isn't the fastest skater out
there, but he can play the position. Philly's best chance to move
him will be to work out a pay split with the club that acquires
him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every coach's dream: When Ivan Novoseltsev recently came to
contract terms with the Panthers, he phoned Mark Hunter, his coach
last season at Sarnia, and told him that he would send him and his
wife anywhere in the world on vacation _ a thank you for the help .
. . The Thrashers finally put some names to their roster Friday,
but they still don't have a coach. General manager Don Waddell has
a candidate or two to interview _ Buffalo assistant Don Lever
possibly among them _ before making his decision . . . Speculation
grows that the Canadiens will make a serious pitch to Bob Gainey,
hoping that he'll return to Montreal to fill the presidency vacated
by Ron Corey. Now that the Stars have won, he'll never be able to
accomplish more in Dallas. And the shattered Habs couldn't be much
worse than they are today . . . Now that Mario Lemieux is the new
owner of the Pittsburgh Penguins _ effective July 16, with a key
assist from the US Bankruptcy Court on Thursday _ how long before
he begins to bellyache about the runaway salaries? Team Lemieux and
SMG hammered out a new lease at the Igloo late Friday night. Under
the new deal, the Penguins will pay some $1.9 million in rent per
season, a reduction of better than two-thirds from the $6
million-$7 million they were paying before the former ownership
went bust. The deal runs out in 2004, by which time Lemieux and
crew hope to have a new building . . . The NHL Award ceremonies
televised on ESPN Thursday night hit a new low for poor taste. What
an unmitigated disgrace. Comedienne Cathy Jones played a '90s
version of Mae West, packing her painful, embarrassing set with a
boatload of sexual innuendo (not the least of which was a cheap,
prurient play on Michael Peca's last name). Hey, soft porn has its
place, I guess, but Jones should work somewhere she can charge 25
cents a peep. Someone in the league should have had the decency to
pull the plug, followed by an immediate offer of resignation . . .
If I'm a Sabres fan, sure, I'm upset that Brett Hull's goal was
allowed to stand as the Cup winner. But I'm equally upset that the
Sabres' two best defensemen, Alexei Zhitnik and Richard Smehlik,
were on the ice and did absolutely nothing to prevent the goal . .
. It's a technical point, but one worth making: Mike Smith wasn't
fired in Toronto _ his contract was up and he couldn't see eye to
eye with Leafs boss Ken Dryden about the job definition of GM. ``He
pretends to listen, but he doesn't,'' said Smith. ``He just looks
like he's listening.'' . . . Colorado's Chris Drury picked up
$100,000 along with that Calder Trophy as the NHL's rookie of the
year. The former Boston University center, who made $735,000 this
past season, was drained after his first day in the Avalanche camp
last September. Coach Bob Hartley called him into his office and
told him that things would have to change the next day or he'd be
assigned to Hershey. ``That kind of woke me up,'' said Drury . . .
Former Bruins coach Brian Sutter will be back behind the Calgary
bench next season after getting his salary bumped to about
$325,000. He also will have the one-year agreement extended if his
hard-working Flames clinch a playoff berth . . . Peca on Dallas
forward Jere Lehtinen, who was named the Selke winner Thursday
night as the league's best checking forward: ``The Modanos,
Nieuwendyks, and Hulls get the publicity, but Lehtinen makes that
team go. He contributes to a lot of wins, often more than the other
guys do.'' . . . Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock is convinced the league
is on the brink of a new era, with a true emphasis on offense.
``Everything's going to be over the top, long bombs,'' said
Hitchcock, predicting the end of the dreaded trap. Here's hoping
his clairvoyance turns out to be the equal of his coaching.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Equally amazing as Ray Bourque's tenure with the Bruins _
celebrated at the draft Saturday _ is the 19-year relationship he
has maintained with his agent, Steve Freyer. In an age when
high-profile players change agents virtually between shifts _ which
could be a reflection of both sides of the equation _ Bourque has
had Freyer at his side from almost day one. He's been as religious
about his representation as he has been about his conditioning.
``What you find out about Ray early on is that's he's all about
loyalty and dedication,'' said Freyer. ``He's loyal to his friends,
his family, me. That's his view of the world. He talks about his
genes being part of the player he is. I think loyalty for him is
genetic, too.'' . . . One last Bourque note: His dad, Ray Sr.,
still has the rocking chair that his now-famous son built for him
in high school. ``Yeah,'' said Ray Sr., reached at his home last
week in Moncton, New Brunswick. ``We even went out and got a new
cover put on it recently, so it'll be nice when Ray comes to
visit.'' Twenty years ago, the elder Bourque was shocked when he
heard the Bruins selected his son in the amateur draft. ``I said,
`Ray, why didn't you tell me?' '' said Ray Sr., who learned the
news the next day on the radio. ``He told me he couldn't tell me,
because I asked him not to tell me. I guess I did. I'd been getting
so many calls, and whenever a reporter would call, I'd go on and on
about whatever he'd told me. He got mad. I guess it embarrassed
him. Finally I told him, `OK, don't tell me anything.' So he
didn't.'' . . . Bettman, when asked about the high cost of
attending an NHL games, makes note of the high cost of seeing a
Broadway show, a movie, an NFL game, a baseball game, or an NBA
game. ``The fact is,'' he said, ``it's something that all of us in
entertainment need to be focused on.'' . . . Had the Thrashers not
hired Les Jackson away from Dallas as their assistant GM, he would
be in line for a Cup ring now that the Stars are the champs. Noting
that, Dr. Harvey Schiller, the Thrasher president, ordered Jackson
a Rolex watch to commemorate the win.
</P>
</TEXT>
