<HEADLINE>
OLD TRIESTE CAN'T GO FOR GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The recent retirement of Silver Charm leaves the
handicap division up for grabs. The presumptive nominee coming into
the season, Silver Charm was sent to stud following a string of
dull races. Left standing are Victory Gallop, Behrens, and Real
Quiet, any one of which could win the Eclipse Award. Unfortunately,
Old Trieste, arguably the most brilliant of the group, will not get
a chance to show his stuff in Sunday's $1 million Hollywood Gold
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-year-old son of former Horse of the Year A.P. Indy, Old
Trieste has been plagued by bad feet, and an abcess turned up
Tuesday, causing trainer Mike Puype to scratch him from the Gold
Cup, in which he would have been favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was facing backwards in his stall, and I knew something was
wrong,'' said Puype, who trains Old Trieste for owner Gary Bisantz.
``We took his temperature, and it was 103 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   The same problem kept Old Trieste out of the Strub Stakes over
the winter, and his only start this year was a dominating 7-length
tally under regular rider Chris McCarron in the Californian at
Hollywood May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Old Trieste has a career record of 11-6-1-1, and he has won four
straight stakes since stopping after setting the pace in the 1998
Kentucky Derby. A noted front-runner, he appears to have a rare
combination of speed and stamina, but he is going to have to run
more often to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a temporary setback,'' said Bisantz, who now will point
Old Trieste toward the Pacific Classic at Del Mar in August and the
Breeders' Cup Classic at Gulfstream Park in November.
</P>
<P>
   The scratch leaves Real Quiet, trained by Bob Baffert, the
Richard Mandella-trained pair of Puerto Madero and Malek, and
Budroyale, to contest the Gold Cup. The four-horse field is so
competitive that the odds range merely from 7-5 to 7-2, with Real
Quiet 7-5, Puerto Madero 2-1, Budroyale 5-2, and Malek 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   Like the race itself, the division is wide open. At least, that
is, until Old Trieste's feet heal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Great Barrington Fair, which originally applied for 10
thoroughbred racing dates from Sept. 10-19, will not race this
year, and owner Henry Vara has put the 56-acre property up for
sale. Great Barrington ran 20 dates last year but suffered because
some of the programs conflicted with racing at Saratoga. Vara
estimates that he lost $1.15 million on racing, and the final straw
came in May when local residents rejected a referendum to allow
Great Barrington to bring in simulcasting. ``It's a sad day,'' Vara
told The Berkshire Eagle. ``I'm unhappy to do it. But, financially,
I just can't carry on.'' In 1995, a tornado destroyed the
grandstand, but the facility was rebuilt, and racing was conducted
there the past two years. Vara is reportedly seeking $3 million for
the grounds . . . For the first time, Baffert will campaign at a
New York meeting. He has asked for six stalls at Saratoga, which
opens July 27, and will stable Real Quiet there. Baffert, the king
of the Midwest and West Coast, is 0 for 9 in New York and 0 for 1
in Boston, as Real Quiet finished third to Behrens in the MassCap
at Suffolk . . . Sunday, Churchill Downs will honor Silver Charm,
who won the 1997 Kentucky Derby. The 5-year-old will parade before
the grandstand and gallop past the Twin Spires. He will then go to
the winner's circle, where he will be presented with a silver
basket of carrots, apples, and mints.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harry Mangurian, who owned the Celtics in the early '80s and was
a noted thoroughbred owner, is retiring from racing at the age of
75. Mangurian intends to disperse his stock, including 275 in-foal
mares, and sell Mockingbird Farm, which sits on 1,100 acres in
Ocala, Fla. ``Mr. Mangurian has always been a hands-on type owner,
but it was getting to where he was spending less and less time in
Ocala,'' said Mark Casse, director of operations at Mockingbird.
``That was one thing he got out of his involvement in this
industry, the enjoyment. But he is going to be spending all of his
time in Fort Lauderdale now, and he decided it was time to
disperse.'' The mares will be sold Oct. 10, with the yearlings and
2-year-olds sold subsequently, at the Ocala sales. The stallions
will be sold privately . . . A reminder that Suffolk Downs is open
every day during the summer for simulcasting, with admission and
preferred parking free. ``Trackside at Suffolk Downs,'' hosted by
publicist T.D. Thornton, also continues Saturdays at 11 a.m. on
WESX (1230). Live racing resumes Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yagli, winner of the Manhattan Handicap at Belmont June 5 and
currently the top turf horse in the US, will race in the King
George VI and Queen Elizabeth Diamond Stakes at Ascot July 24. The
King George is the first race in the nine-race Emirates World
Series Racing Championship, which also includes the Breeders' Cup
Turf and offers a $1 million bonus. ``We're going in that
direction; we want to give it a try,'' said Bill Mott, who trains
Yagli, a son of Jade Hunter, for Allen Paulson. ``Of course, he
still has to be coming up to the race well. But if he trains on
schedule, it's our decision to go. It would be a real feather in
our cap to win it. There's not much in the US this summer that we'd
be missing, and we'd be going for a purse that's nearly $1 million.
It's a very prestigious race, and we should be meeting the best
turf horses in the world.'' . . . Charismatic, who fractured his
left front leg while trying to win the Triple Crown in the Belmont
and was subsequently retired, is recovering nicely two weeks after
surgery. ``He's a very good patient,'' said trainer D. Wayne Lukas.
``He's doing better than we could have hoped. He's bearing weight
on that leg very well. He's not showing stress at all from the
whole deal. He's stabilized well. The most critical part is behind
us.'' Charismatic no longer needs medication, and he will remain in
his Belmont stall for 60 days . . . Baffert has a top 2-year-old
filly named Chilukki, who broke the 4 1/2-furlong track record at
Churchill Downs by running :51 April 28. The daughter of Cherokee
Run, who is now 2 for 2, is working sensationally for the Debutante
Stakes at Churchill June 27. Chilukki recently zipped 5 furlongs in
:59 4/5, which caused Baffert's jaw to drop. ``I've never had a
2-year-old quite like her,'' he said. ``Both Chilukki and
Silverbulletday are in a league of their own. They've just come
from another planet or something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
