<SLUG> BC-SPT-XGAMES-MARKETING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X GAMES SPONSORS COVET GEN-YERS  
 NEW STRATEGIES HOPE TO REACH SAVVY YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG MORGAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Maybe the Marines should update their slogan to
reflect their current recruiting base: ``The Few, The Body-Pierced,
The Marines.'' Sure it's a radical departure from the past, but so
is the entire approach today's marketers are taking toward a
previously overlooked demographic _ youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old advertising belief was that youths were not very savvy
consumers and couldn't be reached,'' said Howard McNally, president
of transaction services for AT&AMP;T. ``But what we've realized is that
they're extremely savvy and astute. Whether that's something new or
we just figured it out I can't tell you, but we're trying things we
never would have tried in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those is sponsoring the X Games, ESPN's 5-year-old
``olympics of alternative sports,'' currently running in San
Francisco. The X Games are a montage of individual-based sports
such as skysurfing, street luging, in-line skating and stunt
bicycling. ESPN's target audience is 12- to 24-year-old males, but
two-thirds of the attendees (233,000 last year in San Diego) are 21
or younger and 70 percent are male, according to Performance
Research of Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really after the athletes at the X Games because
they have their own sponsors and are making a lot of money,'' said
Lt. Col. Jeffrey Sammons, a public information officer with the
Marine Corps Recruiting Command. ``We're after the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, the Marines and 13 other sponsors paid ESPN a total of $22
million for multimedia ad packages that include commercials, online
advertising, signage at the games and a booth in the X Games
interactive village where corporations are free to hawk their
wares. Six primary sponsors paid $2 million each while the rest
paid about $1 million each.
</P>
<P>
   So while X Games athletes compete for a share of the
comparatively low $1 million in total prize money, sponsors are
after a much larger pot of gold _ the estimated $100 billion spent
by U.S. teens each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a huge amount of disposable income,'' McNally said.
``Each kid spends more than $100 a month. It's just a matter of
maturity and good sense on our part that we're finally trying to
tap this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapping it is easier said than done, however. According to most
companies, the youth market is both wary and cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're tired of being talked down to and overcommercialized.
They want to be treated with respect,'' said John Harris, a
spokesman for X Games sponsor Mountain Dew, which uses skysurfing
and other extreme sports in its commercials. ``Our ad campaign has
been very successful with this group because we've never tried to
be something we're not, but it's a real challenge to stay relevant
with these consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Current advertising no-nos include commercials that depict
Generation Y as outlandish or brash. Research has found kids are
tired of that notion. Companies are also in constant fear of
appearing too corporate, a faux pas that could induce negative
responses to their `exploitative' products.
</P>
<P>
   Adidas, which only became a sponsor when Nike dropped out two
years ago, has used only about half its signage at the X Games, an
ESPN spokesman said. Since the company was not part of the original
Games, it doesn't want to be seen as taking advantage of the X
Games' financial possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But savvy or not, the nose-pierced, sideburn-sporting, knit cap
and baggy shorts-wearing set is being watched very closely. And
since a Nielsen Media Research study has found that kids watch less
television than adults, the X Games give advertisers a variety of
ways to reach a concentrated group of young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a direct bull's eye for a demographic these companies
are dying to reach,'' said Chris Stiepock, ESPN's X Games director
of marketing and communications.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive village is a prime example with its rows of
booths.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is promoting its new 20-something series ``Wasteland'' by
having 30-something adults dressed in `grunged-out' garb giving
away bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   VISA is giving away free gifts with X Games VISA card
applications, conveniently located at the front of the booth, at
the low introductory interest rate of 3.9.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines have a chin-up challenge and information packets
about the corps.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy is giving away trucks, Mountain Dew is pouring free
samples and AT&AMP;T is pushing its collect number, 1-800-CALL-ATT,
which is used mostly by young people.
</P>
<P>
   As for pitchmen, milk has skateboarding legend Tony Hawks,
Mountain Dew has those rad skysurfers, and AT&AMP;T is running
television ads with actor David Arquette and radio ads with rap
music.
</P>
<P>
   McNally said research has shown that previous X Games
sponsorship increased awareness of 1-800-CALL-ATT. A 1996
Performance Research Survey also revealed that 92 percent of game
attendees remembered Mountain Dew was a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   But the real goal, McNally said, is for companies to develop
product loyalty with consumers _ in AT&AMP;T's case, those who will
soon be paying the phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to tell this story because it epitomizes the way we've
had to change our thinking,'' McNally said. ``We were discussing
what kinds of ads we wanted to run, and the head of our advertising
says to me, `Mr. McNally, if you want to reach the urban youth,
your advertising has to be cool and you, Mr. McNally, are not
cool.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Before when ads came up, a bunch of old execs would gather
round and give their impressions _ but his point was, who are we to
decide what's cool? We have no idea what's cool. Now I show the ads
to my daughter before they ever see the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   The research gets far more complex than that, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of youth attitude-tracking surveys . . .'' Sammons
said. ``What we've found in the overwhelming majority is they want
to belong to something larger than themselves, they want to be held
to higher standards, they want an opportunity to lead and they want
something challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I just told you are things the Marine Corps
promises. The X Games just give us a chance to reach young men and
women with that message.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
