<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG PLANS FOR LITTLE E 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ When it was decided that Dale Earnhardt Jr. would
enter five Winston Cup races this year to prepare for his official
rookie campaign next season, New Hampshire International Speedway
was selected as one of the venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those flat tracks,'' the 24-year-old driver said
Wednesday, ``where it's really difficult to make the cars turn in
the corners.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Earnhardt figured it, it was better to learn something
new at an unfamiliar setting than to learn nothing at all by
turning laps at a familiar track.
</P>
<P>
   That explained why Earnhardt was on the 1-mile NHIS oval for a
test session in his No. 8 Budweiser Chevrolet Monte Carlo. He came
to gain some local knowledge of NHIS in preparation for his second
Winston Cup race, the Jiffy Lube 300 July 11. He will attempt to
qualify also for Winston Cup events in Michigan, Richmond, and
Atlanta before turning his attention to the series full time next
season as primary driver for his father, seven-time champion Dale
Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really adapted well to most of the tracks we've tested
at,'' crew chief Tony Eury Sr. said. ``He was pretty fast here,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Since capturing the 1998 championship of the NASCAR Busch
Series, ``Little E'' as he's been nicknamed, has been on a fast
track to Winston Cup stardom. That was evident in May when he made
his Winston Cup debut in Charlotte by qualifying eighth-fastest and
finishing 16th in the Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy,'' said Earnhardt, referring to the fans' wild
reaction after he qualified faster than his father. ``I was
surprised at how the race fans were as happy and as excited.
Everybody was pumped.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, by all accounts, a successful debut. And while Earnhardt
has focused much of his attention on the buildup for next season,
he hasn't lost sight of defending his Busch Series title this
season. After 16 races, Earnhardt holds a 64-point lead over Matt
Kenseth, 2,264-2,200, entering Sunday's Lysol 200 at Watkins Glen,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   How has he managed to juggle the circuits?
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been that difficult,'' he said. ``The team's been
adapting well and they don't mind the extra load or the hard work,
but that's been cool. I was worried about that, because I was
thinking, `Man, we might get behind on the (Busch) car.' But
they've stuck with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can handle driving and driving and driving, or flying here
and there, meeting this guy or that, shaking these hands, or
signing this and that; I can handle all that, man. If the cars look
good and everybody's pumped about going racing, that excites me.
And I can go handle everything else. I was just worried maybe some
other areas would suffer and fall apart from it and then
everybody's morale would fall, but that hasn't been the case.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, winner of last week's NASCAR Winston Cup race at
Pocono, Pa., will go for his second victory in a row (and third in
four races) in Sunday's Save Mart-Kragen 350 at Sears Point Raceway
in Sonoma, Calif. Labonte trails Dale Jarrett by 89 points in the
Winston Cup standings and will need another strong performance from
his No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac to continue his hot streak,
this time on the winding road course at Sears Point, one of two
venues on the Winston Cup schedule where drivers are required to
execute left- and right-hand turns. ``We've been creeping up on
this thing over the past couple years, finishing seventh in points,
sixth in points, just getting closer and closer,'' Labonte said.
``It just seems like things are clicking a little bit better right
now. It's team chemistry and teamwork.'' . . . To prepare for the
challenges of road racing, Winston Cup rookie Tony Stewart took a
few crash courses at the Bob Bondurant School in Phoenix prior to
the Winston Cup event at Talladega, Ala., then took another
intensive one-day Skip Barber road racing course at Sonoma before
the California 500 at Fontana and returned for two more days of
study following the race. ``My first road course race is going to
be an interesting experience,'' said Stewart, who crammed his road
course work in the month before he pulled double duty by running
both the Indianapolis 500 and Coca-Cola 600 in Charlotte on the
same day, May 30. ``There's definitely an art to driving these big
cars on a road course,'' Stewart said. ``The last time I raced on a
course like this was in a go-kart, which doesn't have much in
common with my Home Depot Pontiac.'' . . . With 5 points separating
Juan Pablo Montoya from Dario Franchitti (90-85) in the CART FedEx
Championship Series points race, watch out for some wild action in
Sunday's Medic Drug Grand Prix of Cleveland on the wide-open runway
and tarmac of Burke Lakefront Airport, which should provide ample
room for three- and four-wide racing. ``There are a lot of
opportunities to pass on this circuit,'' said Franchitti. ``There's
so much room in Turn 1 that you can have four or five cars
side-by-side when the green flag drops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
