<HEADLINE>
COYOTES, HLINKA TALK ABOUT JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Coyotes General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith confirmed Saturday
that the team has heavy interest in famed Czech Republic Coach
 &UR; Ivan
 &UR; Hlinka joining the club as an assistant on new Coach  &UR; Bobby
Francis' staff.
</P>
<P>
   Hlinka, who has guided the Czechs to three world championships
and the Olympic gold medal last year in Nagano, Japan, met with
Smith and Francis last week in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He could be hired as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy I approached, and he's shown some willingness to
come over here,'' Smith said. ``It's very interesting to talk
hockey with him for quite a few hours. Like I said, he's willing to
come (to the NHL), and I think he's looking for a new challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes also have interviewed former Boston Bruins and New
York Islanders Coach  &UR; Rick Bowness for an assistant's role. After
being replaced in New York early last season, Bowness has worked
for the Nashville Predators as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked with Rick,'' Smith said. ``He's a veteran coach
who's been around. Obviously, with a rookie NHL coach, you'd like
to add some experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Hlinka will become the first European to become a
head coach in the NHL. Smith doesn't discount that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to happen at some point, I think,'' he said. ``I
don't know when and I don't know who, but it's going to happen, and
he's certainly a likely candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the possible hiring of Hlinka shouldn't be construed
as a way to help the Coyotes re-sign Czech center  &UR; Robert
 &UR; Reichel, who has had a standing offer from Hlinka to become a
full-time player/coach for the national team. Reichel, who becomes
a Group II restricted free agent on July 1, may not return to the
NHL unless he is offered a contract worth more than $3 million a
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the issues separately,'' Smith said. ``We're
not going to get a guy who's not going to add value to our coaching
staff to appease Robert Reichel. And we're not going to leave a guy
(Hlinka) back if (Reichel isn't re-signed). We could get Reichel
and not get Hlinka.'' &QL; 
Remembering Oleg &QL; 
When  &UR; Oleg Tverdovsky discovers he has been traded back to the
Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, he might gets the shakes. Ever since the
Russian defenseman made some flippant remarks about his former team
before a playoff series three seasons ago, he has been booed
unmercifully in Anaheim every time he touches the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be interesting,'' said Washington Capitals Coach
 &UR; Ron Wilson, the former Ducks coach. ``He's a pretty sensitive kid.
I haven't talked to him in two or three years and I don't know if
he's matured as an individual. Oleg's got a big heart and
everything, but he made some comments that you could classify as
immature, and it's haunted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But fans are pretty forgiving. If he goes in there and
performs, he'll be fine. He's going to play with some great players
and he needs to take advantage of that. It's a fresh start for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky was vacationing in Russia when the Coyotes dealt him
Saturday in exchange for center  &UR; Travis Green and a first-round
pick, which Phoenix used to select Seattle Thunderbirds center
 &UR; Scott
 &UR; Kelman. It is believed he has no knowledge of the trade. &QL; 
Deal off, for now &QL; 
The Coyotes apparently thought they had a deal reached with the
Atlanta Thrashers late Friday night to acquire defenseman
 &UR; Jamie &UR; Pushor, obtained earlier in the day from Anaheim in the
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a second-round pick by Detroit in 1991, the 6-foot-3
Pushor didn't know how to react when reporters told him it looked
as though he was about to change teams again.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, though, fell through after Atlanta apparently wanted
the offer to be sweetened. The Coyotes are believed to have offered
a second- or third-round pick in next year's draft for the
fourth-year pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some negotiations,'' Thrashers General Manager  &UR; Don
 &UR; Waddell said. ``But right now, we're happy to have Jamie Pushor.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
