<HEADLINE>
COYOTES STICK TO PLAN IN DRAFT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Coyotes addressed their primary needs in Saturday's
NHL entry draft, scouring the 1999 class for quality forwards.
</P>
<P>
   They got one of the highest-rated ones they wanted, too, by
making a trade with Anaheim to grab the 15th overall choice and
selecting 18-year-old center Scott Kelman of the Western Hockey
League's Seattle Thunderbirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I rated out in that area and I was kind of hoping
that's where I'd go,'' said Kelman, a Winnipeg native who scored 63
goals and 168 points the past three seasons for his junior team.
``They gave up a pretty good player (Oleg Tverdovsky) to get me, so
it's nice to come to an organization that really wants you. I'm
going to try and prove to them that they made the right decision
and go out and do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   He underwent minor shoulder surgery last month, but it isn't
expected to slow him down. He also plays baseball, where he is a
pitcher and first baseman for an All-Star team from Winnipeg that
will play in an international tournament next month in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the shoulder, I've been playing mostly first
base,'' said Kelman, whose fastball has been clocked at nearly 90
mph. ``But I'm getting ready to throw the ball sometime next week
and we'll see how it goes. . . . I've definitely picked hockey as
my Number 1 sport, though.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of major league clubs, including the Los Angeles
Dodgers and Atlanta Braves, have scouted him.
</P>
<P>
   Kelman, who scored 19 goals and 73 points last season, was the
first of five forwards picked by Phoenix with the club's six draft
choices through the first four rounds. Four of them were centers.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes used their other first-rounder on Russian defenseman
Kiril Safronov, who like Kelman, was rated near the top of the pack
at his position. Safronov, 18, is a solid, responsible blueliner
who most scouts agree could be ready to crack a top-four role in
the NHL within a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Safronov, who speaks excellent English _ he was tutored by his
grandmother, a St. Petersburg schoolteacher _ likens his style of
play to that of Buffalo's Alexei Szhitnik and Dallas' Sergei Zubov.
</P>
<P>
   Although modest, it's apparent Safronov doesn't lack
self-confidence. Asked whether he agrees with most scouts'
appraisal that he might be the best defensemen in this year' draft,
he replied: ``Yes. I think I probably am the best.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't shown much offensively, scoring only one goal and
adding one assist for St. Petersburg. But he made a huge jump while
playing for Team Russia in the World Junior Championships in
Winnipeg, further impressing scouts and raising his stock for
Saturday's showcase at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that tournament helped me a lot,'' he said. ``It opened
some eyes. It was very important that I played well there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes selected Brad Ralph, a quality scoring left wing
from the Oshawa Generals, with their second-round pick, the 53rd
choice overall. He netted 31 goals and 75 points last season and
was the Ontario Hockey League's Rookie of the Year the previous
season, when he scored 20 goals and 37 points.
</P>
<P>
   With the third-round pick they swapped with the New York
Islanders as part of the Robert Reichel-Brad Isbister trade, the
Coyotes took Jason Jaspers, a 5-foot-11{, 185-pound center from OHL
Sudbury who scored 28 goals and 61 points for the Wolves. They then
grabbed two more centers with two picks in the fourth round, Ryan
Lauzon, who scored 21 goals and 47 points for the Hull Olympiques
of the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League, and Preston Mizzi, who
scored 29 goals and 58 points for Peterborogh of the OHL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
