<SLUG> BC-BB-BASEBALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO DEMOTE JIMENEZ? AN EMPHATIC NO-NO 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was not a night for modest pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal,'' Cardinals pitcher Jose Jimenez said after throwing
the first no-hitter of the season Friday night, ``is to be a
superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old righthander took a giant step in that direction
with his no-no, which came in a 1-0 win over the Arizona
Diamondbacks and ace Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez, a Dominican who comes from Sammy Sosa's neighborhood in
San Pedro de Macoris, was an unlikely candidate to author a
no-hitter, despite his status as one of the team's best pitching
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez threw a no-hitter for Double A Arkansas last season, and
led the Southern League in wins (15) and earned run average (3.11).
Called up in September by the Cardinals, he won all three of his
starts, then won his first two this season.
</P>
<P>
   The game, he said, was coming too easily.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in a hurry, however, as Jimenez lost seven
decisions in a row and gave up 55 earned runs in 57 1/3 innings.
Despite an outstanding sinker and an improving changeup and slider,
Jimenez was another start or two away from being demoted to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday night, that is, when he was bigger than the Big
Unit, although aided by two sliding catches by outfielder Eric
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   One of those catches came with one out in the ninth, when Davis
grabbed a liner by pinch hitter David Dellucci off his shoetops
with a tumbling catch. Davis came up with the ball in his glove,
then dropped it as he waved his arm, signalling a catch. Umpires
Jeff Nelson at first and Mark Wegner at second both ruled that
Davis had caught the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez's no-hitter was the Cardinals' first since Bob Forsch's
on Sept. 26, 1983. He became the second Cardinal rookie to throw a
no-hitter; Paul Dean, Dizzy's brother, threw one in 1934. And he
also joined Juan Marichal and Ramon Martinez as Dominican pitchers
who have thrown no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lose too much sleep,'' said losing pitcher
Johnson, beaten by a run in the ninth. ``I pitched a pretty good
ballgame, and we got no-hit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, after winning their seventh straight Friday night,
including three against Los Angeles, were just a half-game behind
the fourth-place Dodgers, and are doing their best to make a
prophet of GM Kevin Towers, who heard Dodgers GM Kevin Malone
predict a World Series and countered by saying the La-La's would
finish no higher than third.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made their bed, and they have to sleep in it,'' Towers
said. ``We still have to chase them. We'll take a lot more delight
as a group, not just me, in catching and passing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers third baseman Todd Zeile, who realized his dream of
playing for his hometown Dodgers in 1997 only to be traded a year
later, said he's as mystified as anyone as to why the team is
falling short of expectations. ``The Dodgers had that solid
foundation with the O'Malley family,'' Zeile said last week. ``They
understood baseball and understood there's more to it than putting
good names on paper. There has to be cohesiveness, and I don't see
that there yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the old question of which comes first, winning or
chemistry?''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago last Monday, the Fox Group fired Dodgers GM Fred
Claire and manager Bill Russell. Three days later, coaches Reggie
Smith, Mark Cresse, and Glenn Gregson also were dismissed. Claire
is now teaching a sports business and media course at Southern Cal,
though he's also looking for work as a baseball consultant. Russell
is managing Orlando, the Double A affiliate of the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays. Gregson is the Phillies' pitching coach at Triple A Scranton,
while Smith and Cresse are running baseball camps near their homes
in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, meanwhile, are hardly better off than they were a
year ago, when they also were hovering a couple of games under
.500.
</P>
<P>
   One Dodger told Chris Jenkins of the San Diego Union-Tribune:
``I've never been in a clubhouse where so many guys show up late to
the park and leave right after the game. And I've never seen so
many cell phones in one place before.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reported $400 million price Cablevision would pay for the
Mets is the highest ever for a baseball team, eclipsing the $311
million Fox mogul Rupert Murdoch paid for the Dodgers. Cablevision,
the sixth-largest cable company in the country, already owns a
majority stake in Madison Square Garden, the Knicks, and the
Rangers, and has shown interest in buying the Jets. The Mets, flush
with Cablevision cash, presumably would be better positioned to
pursue building a new ballpark in Queens. How did the Mets' players
react to the impending sale of the club? ``I was going to make a
bid,'' Mike Piazza said. ``See if some of the other guys would chip
in their meal money.'' . . . Sometimes, Mohammed goes to the
mountain: Texas manager Johnny Oates took the unusual step of
kneeling alongside slumping slugger Juan Gonzalez for a 15-minute
chat at the player's locker, rather than calling him into his
office. Gonzalez, frustrated by his recent lack of production,
caused some eyes to roll when he flung his helmet in disgust after
doubling off the left-center-field wall at the Ballpark in
Arlington. Gonzalez, who has said he thinks the power alleys are
too deep there, apparently was upset that the drive fell short of
being a home run . . . The Reds weren't amused by the politicking
the Mets did on behalf of shortstop Rey Ordonez, who trailed
Cincinnati mainstay Barry Larkin, a nine-time All-Star, by fewer
than 8,000 votes with a week of balloting left. Sniffed Reds GM Jim
Bowden, ``We don't have to encourage people to vote for Barry. They
know that Barry's the best all-around shortstop in the league.
Ordonez may be one of the best defensive shortstops, but Barry's
the complete package.'' Meanwhile, the close race between
shortstops Nomar Garciaparra and Derek Jeter in the American League
is reminiscent of the razor-edge margin by which another Sox
shortstop, Rick Burleson, edged his Yankee counterpart, Bucky Dent,
for the starting spot in 1977. Dent more than made up for that, of
course, a year later . . . Holyoke's Mark Wohlers, who had been
making encouraging progress in his comeback, ran into a bit of a
setback Thursday night while pitching for the Reds' Single A team
in Chattanooga. In a steady rain, Wohlers gave up three runs on a
hit, two walks, and three wild pitches. Only 13 of his 29 pitches
went for strikes . . . With their biggest crowd of the season,
40,553, showing up Friday for the opener of a series with the
Phillies, the Cubs went over the 1 million mark in attendance on
just their 29th home date, and they are a quarter of a million
ahead of last season's pace . . . The Mariners face the Rangers six
times in the next 10 days in a belated attempt to rejoin the race
in the AL West. Biggest difference between the clubs? The Rangers'
bullpen began this weekend's series with a 17-2 record, 28 saves in
34 chances, and an AL-low ERA of 3.46. The Mariners' pen,
meanwhile, was 9-15 with 17 saves in 28 chances and an AL-worst ERA
of 6.48 . . . Five weeks after undergoing surgery to repair a
partial tear in his rotator cuff, Arizona pitcher Todd Stottlemyre
was playing catch, which places him far ahead of projections. He
was scheduled to be reevaluated at the start of this week . . . The
D-Backs, who need a closer in the wake of the Gregg Olson meltdown,
have shown some interest in Montreal's Ugueth Urbina. The Expos
reportedly were asking for one of Arizona's three top starters at
Double A El Paso: Nick Bierbrodt, Brad Penny, or John Patterson.
The D-Backs also inquired about Reds reliever Danny Graves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies have scored 10 or more runs 16 times this season.
Six times they've scored 12 or more _ and have a 3-3 record to show
for those games. They blew a 9-1 lead in a loss to the Cubs last
week. ``I think,'' Larry Walker said, ``you'll find most of the
time it has happened at home. In this ballpark you know there are
going to be those nights where you get hammered. You can't hang
your head. You can't give up. You just come back the next game
knowing that you could do the hammering, and go about your job.'' .
. . The King, Jim Leyritz, went on the disabled list for the first
time in his career after his left hand was fractured by a pitch
from Chan Ho Park of the Dodgers. Leyritz probably will come off
the DL just in time to be traded from San Diego to a contender.
Wherever he goes, he won't be coveted for his ability to throw out
base-stealers. He caught just 3 of 29 runners for the Padres this
season . . . Promoted to take Leyritz's place on the Padres roster
is Ben Davis, their much-heralded catcher of the future. Davis, who
was the second pick in the 1995 draft, has unlimited potential. ``I
would like to have his future,'' said Don Logan, the general
manager of the Triple A Las Vegas Stars. ``He's got it going on.
He's solid, man. Church every Sunday, too.'' . . . The Philadelphia
police department reportedly is continuing an investigation of the
June 11 hotel bar scuffle in which Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi
was struck in the left eye and pitching coach Mel Queen was hit in
the side of the head with a beer bottle . . . Twelve of the 25
players on Tampa Bay's Opening Day roster have been on the disabled
list. Four of the original five starters in the rotation have been
on the DL. Where does it hurt? Everywhere. Lefthanded pitcher Tony
Saunders fractured his arm and went on the DL. Dave Eiland was
called up from Triple A to replace him and had to come out of his
second start with back spasms. He went on the DL. Mickey Callaway
was called up from Triple A to replace him and in his second start
pulled a hamstring and went on the DL. Callaway threw just 10
pitches before he had to come out. Pitcher Rick White was in the
clubhouse when a batboy ran back to tell him he was going into the
game. White thought it was a prank and ignored the kid. Only after
he saw on TV that Callaway was walking off the mound did he sprint
out of the clubhouse. ``I get there and (umpire) Rocky (Roe) says,
`By the way, there are two men on and a 3-0 count on the hitter,'
'' White said. ``I'm thinking, `That's nice.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Bill Haselman, who shared Sox catching duties two
years ago with Scott Hatteberg, has asked to be traded. Haselman
signed as a free agent and thought he'd be playing regularly, but
the Tigers traded a month later for Brad Ausmus . . . The Tigers
are very protective of pitching prodigy Jeff Weaver. They won't
allow him to throw more than 110 pitches in a start. ``You can't
sacrifice the future for right now,'' manager Larry Parrish said,
citing broken-down Cubs star Kerry Wood as a case in point. Wood
exceeded 110 pitches 13 times as a rookie last season, including a
span in which he threw at least 121 pitches four times in five
starts, and another span in which he threw at least 119 in four
straight starts. Wood is missing all of this season because of
elbow surgery. ``Some people are thinking I don't want to win,''
Parrish said of his pitch-count removals of Weaver. ``I feel like I
want to win more than anybody. I'm the guy that it affects the
most.'' . . . Overlooked on the Indians' All-Star-laden roster is
reliever Steve Karsay, who came into the season with seven wins, a
total he's already matched. In 32 appearances, Karsay is 7-1 with a
2.20 ERA. Batters are hitting .224 against him. The Indians' record
for most wins by a reliever is 12, by Sid Monge in 1979 and Dan
Spillner in 1982 . . . Joe Torre's lineup reshuffling, putting
Bernie Williams in the second spot ahead of Derek Jeter, has had
dramatic results. They reached base in the same inning seven times
in the first five games since the switch. ``A lot of guys are
seeing the ball well, and it's great to see them get their
confidence going,'' said Roger Clemens. ``We've got a lot of guys
who are tough on themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
