<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-OUTDOORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIAL CONFIRMS WOLF ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The inevitable happened.
</P>
<P>
   A pack of Mexican gray wolves, an endangered species
reintroduced into Arizona, attacked a domestic cattle calf on a
ranch north of Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   An interagency team of biologists now is monitoring the Pipestem
Pack's movements in the Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest on a
24-hour basis.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, the injured calf was discovered on the T-Link
Ranch by the ranch manager.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alan Armistead, a biologist for the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's Wildlife Services and the wolf team's depredation
specialist, concluded after examining the calf that its wounds
include bites and scrapes that were consistent with a wolf attack.
</P>
<P>
   The calf is expected to recover from the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The attack occurred in the same area, where in the middle of
June, biologists discovered the mostly consumed remains of two
calves and a partially consumed adult cow. The cow died after its
hind leg became tangled in the strands of a barbed-wire fence.
</P>
<P>
   The livestock manager was contacted after the find and
participated in investigating it.
</P>
<P>
   Cause of the three animals' death couldn't be determined. Both
coyotes and wolves were found in the area, and one or both had fed
on the carcasses. The wolf pack was in the area at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Another calf was found dead last Thursday in the Pipestem Pack's
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring of that pack has been intensified through radio
collars. The wolves' location will be determined every four hours,
day and night. If the wolves move to the location of livestock,
they will be run off. Supplemental food is being provided near the
pack's den site.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists determined the pups were born to the Pipestem Pack
this spring. The number hasn't been determined. This is the second
litter produced by the pack.
</P>
<P>
   The only surviving pup for a year ago disappeared after its
mother was illegally shot last August.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch's livestock manager plans to move the cows and calves
to another place, far away from the wolf activity.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists expressed their appreciation for the cooperation of
the livestock manager. This is an attempt to discourage the wolves
from preying on livestock.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of Wildlife, a non-profit conservation organization,
will offer compensation to the livestock owner, as is its policy
when the loss or injury of domestic livestock occurs and is caused
by wolves.
</P>
<P>
   More than 24 wolves now range the Apache-Sitgreaves. That's
nearly triple the number of last year at this time.
</P>
<P>
   The first confirmed attack on domestic animals occurred in May
of 1998. A member of the Campbell Blue pack attacked a miniature
horse colt. The owner was compensated by Defenders of Wildlife for
the veterinarian expenses, and the colt survived.
</P>
<P>
   The organization also compensated owners in the wolf-recovery
unit for the death of a ranch dog and injury of another dog,
following a fight with a wolf. &QL; 
Fire restrictions &QL; 
Last Wednesday, fire restrictions were changed on Bureau of Land
Management lands.
</P>
<P>
   Fire restrictions were placed on the Hualapai and Cerbat
mountains in northwestern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Open campfires are allowed only in developed campgrounds or
where specifically posted. Propane gas stoves, lanterns and heaters
are allowed in all areas. Smoking is allowed only in developed
campgrounds and recreation sites, including buildings or vehicles
or in an area that has been cleared of flammable material.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache-Sitgreaves National Forest has lifted fire
restrictions on the Apache part of the forest. That includes the
Clifton, Alpine and Springerville ranger districts.
</P>
<P>
   The area has received enough moisture to allow campfires in
dispersed areas. &QL; 
Mammal tracking &QL; 
Glendale Community College will offer a class on tracking mammals
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The class is designed for hunters, naturalists, photographers,
scouts and others who wish to follows the tracks and signs of wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
   The class will include distinguishing common tracks, reading
subtle signs such as gnawing, droppings and claw marks plus other
information.
</P>
<P>
   Course registration is $14 plus $10 for the instructor. For more
information, call (623) 845-3333. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
