<HEADLINE>
COLLINS IN CHARGE  
 NEW CONTRACT EMPOWERS ANGELS MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major league kudos go out to Anaheim General Manager  &UR; Bill
Bavasi, who did not cave in to the wishes of 10 of his players who
had voiced displeasure with Manager  &UR; Terry Collins' game management
and sometimes abrasive manner.
</P>
<P>
   When asked on a conference call with reporters if he had
concerns over how the extension might be received within the
clubhouse, Bavasi, who grew up in a baseball family, answered
directly and bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares?'' said Bavasi, the son of longtime Dodgers, Angels
and Padres GM  &UR; Buzzie Bavasi. ``As Buzzie always said, we need good
players, not happy ones. I'm more concerned with how our on-field
performance is going over in the clubhouse. I know it's not going
over too well in the offices of the general manager and the field
manager.''
</P>
<P>
   So now what? For one, Collins, whose five big-league clubs
(three in Houston and two in Anaheim) have all finished in second
place, is free to do as he pleases with these Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any way Terry handles players is up to him,'' Bavasi said.
``I'm not looking for him to change. . . . It's the players'
responsibility to react to what he wants done, not his
responsibility to react to what they want done.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who received a two-year extension that includes a club
option for 2002, can't be blamed for the injuries that have ravaged
the Angels this season. It started in spring training when
shortstop
 &UR; Gary DiSarcina, the heart and soul of this club, was sidelined
until last week after he suffered a broken bone in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   It continued when center fielder  &UR; Jim Edmonds was lost for at
least four months after surgery and right fielder  &UR; Tim Salmon went
down also. That's a lot of sock the offense has been missing.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the players seemed indifferent to Collins
extension. One veteran who remains one of the best baseball players
in the game and probably was not part of the veteran revolt, is &UR; 
 &UR; DiSarcina, who, as usual, summed up what needs to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do a better job of focusing on the game,'' he said.
``It's been a blurred vision around here. Maybe this is a signal.
This is the way it's going to be. Terry's here to stay. Deal with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi's signal can only be viewed as a boon for major league
managers everywhere. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's  &UR; Tony Fernandez, who is flirting with a .400 average,
is attempting to become the oldest player in major league history
to win a batting crown for the first time in his career. Fernandez
will turn 37 on Wednesday. Who is the oldest player to win a
batting championship without ever winning one before and how old
was he? &QL; 
Tinkering in the Bronx &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yankees Manager  &UR; Joe Torre did a bit of lineup juggling last
week and the results have been impressive, even if a three-game
sweep over the lowly Tampa Bay Devil Rays is thrown into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who has never been a great fan of batting  &UR; Bernie
Williams in the cleanup spot, shifted the center fielder into the
second spot. Williams entered the weekend series batting .556 (15
for 27) since the move. In turn, the Yankees have been helped. They
rose to 14 games over .500 Thursday, their best mark of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The other shuffling included moving  &UR; Derek Jeter from second to
third,  &UR; Paul O'Neill from third to fifth and  &UR; Tino Martinez from
fifth to fourth. Moving Williams, who is now followed by Jeter,
Martinez and O'Neill, basically forces opposing pitchers to throw
better pitches to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take the credit, sure,'' Torre joked. ``But I don't think
changing spots means a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kile pile &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest name free-agent pitcher after the 1997 season has
not done so well since signing a three-year $24 million contract.
But  &UR; Darryl Kile, who spurned the Diamondbacks' equal offer to take
Colorado's that winter, insists he has no regrets with his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one bit,'' said Kile, who watched a 9-1 lead evaporate at
Coors Field Tuesday in what turned out to be a 12-11 loss to
Chicago. ``I came here to do a job, and I am going to try to do the
best I can. The only thing I try to do is go out and pitch when
they tell me to pitch and help this team win.''
</P>
<P>
   There is growing concern within the Rockies organization that
Kile's game is simply not suited for the high altitude at Coors
Field, that his curveball, considered the best in the game two
years ago, has no chance of snapping the same way in the high and
dry air in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers back up that claim. Since he signed with the
Rockies, Kile is 6-10 with a 6.64 ERA at Coors Field. On the road
he is 11-11 with a 4.19 ERA. The year before he came to Colorado,
when he finished fifth in the Cy Young Award voting, he posted a
19-7 record with a 2.57 ERA for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Kile was 10-3 with a 2.59 ERA when pitching at the Astrodome
that season and 9-4 with a 2.55 ERA on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is now running around that Colorado may have no
choice but to trade Kile, who is trying to discourage such talk but
probably realizes there may be some truth to the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a commitment to come here and do the best I can for as
long as I am here, whether it's longer (than three years), shorter
or a full (three-year) term,'' said Kile, who is scheduled to start
today in San Diego. ``I do the best I can every time I pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   You still have to wonder how many free agent pitchers will even
consider going to Colorado. After all, if Kile couldn't handle it,
who could?
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't pay me enough money to play here,'' said Chicago
Cubs pitcher  &UR; Steve Trachsel, who will be a free agent after this
season. ``It ruins the back of your baseball card.'' &QL; 
Could he have helped? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota reliever  &UR; Hector Carrasco, released by the
Diamondbacks during spring training last year, is back with the
Twins after coming very close to dying earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Carrasco, who was diagnosed with blood clots in his pitching
shoulder and eventually needed surgery to repair a damaged artery,
was activated by the Twins this weekend. During Carrasco's final
tuneups he pitched 1 scoreless innings Tuesday and followed it up
with another scoreless inning Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The former Cincinnati set-up pitcher, had a lively fastball and
is actually throwing his change-up with confidence, something the
Diamondbacks tried in vain to instill in the right-hander last
spring. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Montreal's  &UR; Al Oliver led the National League with a
.331 average. At age 35, Oliver became the oldest player ever to
win a batting title without ever having done so before. Four other
players accomplished the feat at age 34 _  &UR; Billy Williams of the
Cubs in 1972, Brooklyn's  &UR; Dixie Walker in 1944, Detroit's  &UR; Charlie
Gehringer in 1937 and Cincinnati's  &UR; Bubbles Hargrave in 1926. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; They always said this guy could drive in runs in his sleep:
 &UR; Hack Wilson, the single-season record holder for RBI with 190, had
that total increased to 191 after extensive research proved he was
short-changed during a doubleheader in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Say Bud, can we still change our mind?: The one-year
anniversary of the Dodgers' sale from the  &UR; O'Malley Family to the
Fox Corporation passed last Tuesday. As they close in on their
first 162 games as owners, the Dodgers were 79-79 entering the
weekend series at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Dave Cash.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An indication that MLB is making the right decisions
 &UR; or just dumb luck?: It's looking like a done deal that the Dodgers
will be the first opponent at San Francisco's new Pac Bell Park
next spring. Dodgers-Giants, now that's the way it ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; It's your feet we need, not your arm: Detroit Manager  &UR; Larry
Parrish summoned  &UR; Gregg Jefferies to pinch-run last weekend.
Jefferies had spent some time in the trainer's room for his tender
elbow and probably didn't expect to play. At least we hope so since
he ran in tennis shoes. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
The June 19 game between Florida and Colorado marked the first time
in 345 major league games played in Denver that neither club issued
a walk. That includes the two years the Rockies played at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched  &UR; Kent Bottenfield and  &UR; Dustin
 &UR; Hermanson's careers take off after moving from the bullpen to the
rotation, San Diego is primed to see if it will see similar results
from  &UR; Brian Boehringer, who was placed into the rotation Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's  &UR; Ben Grieve, who grew up a few miles from the Ballpark
at Arlington, is now batting .348 in 66 career at-bats at Texas'
home ballpark. He has five home runs at Arlington, including a pair
of multi-homer games.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers entered their weekend series in San Francisco with
an unsightly 4.40 team ERA. The worst mark since the club moved
from Brooklyn occurred in 1958 when Dodger pitchers accrued a 4.47
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs fans can stop fantasizing about pitcher  &UR; Jeremi
 &UR; Gonzalez returning for the stretch run this season. Gonzalez, who
has not pitched since last July because of elbow problems, is due
to undergo `` &UR; Tommy John'' surgery in the coming weeks. He is not
expected to return before 2001.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ben McDonald, the No. 1 overall pick in the 1989 draft, will
not be able to pitch this season. Now with Tampa Bay, McDonald will
have arthroscopic surgery on his shoulder, the same one that had
full-blown rotator cuff surgery last year, soon. If the shoulder
does not respond, McDonald expects his career to be over. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
One outfielder who is definitely on the market these days is
Detroit's  &UR; Bobby Higginson, whom the Diamondbacks tried to pry away
from the Tigers during the winter before winding up with
 &UR; Luis &UR; Gonzalez. The Yankees, in need of a left-fielder, may be
interested.
</P>
<P>
   Freaked out reliever  &UR; Mark Wohlers has apparently done a
180-degree turn in Cincinnati's system. Wohlers had a 1-2-3 inning
at Triple A in which nine of his 14 pitches were strikes last week.
It's at the point where Wohlers could be called up to the Reds
later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Chuck Finley, the all-time leader in service time with
the Angels, is contemplating the idea of requesting a trade away
from the only organization he has known. Finley is in the final
year of a contract. Cleveland and the Yankees might be interested
and, who knows, Finley might just wind up right back with the
Angels as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Count Cleveland out of the market if Toronto decides to trade
starter  &UR; David Wells. ``For me, he's out of the picture,'' Indians
GM  &UR; John Hart said. The Blue Jays, however, will continue to listen
to offers for Wells, who may be more attractive to other clubs now
that he is signed through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh left-hander  &UR; Pete Schourek, who has pitched 7 innings
since being removed from the rotation on May 27, has asked Pirates
GM  &UR; Cam Bonifay to trade him. Schourek is guaranteed $2 million
next season. Philadelphia and the Yankees showed some interest but
have since changed their minds. &QL; 
nTHE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandJust started a 13-game stretch against Kansas City and
Minnesota.  &QL; 
2. NY YankeesThe high-octane machine is revving up in the south
Bronx.  &QL; 
3. AtlantaTeam average ranks 14th in the NL, making their record
more incredible.  &QL; 
4. Houston &UR; Larry Dierker was itching to get back into his Hawaiian
shirt collection.  &QL; 
5. BostonTake away Pedro Martinez's record and the Sox are a .500
club.  &QL; 
6. NY MetsThe Asylum in Queens is once again on the rise in a big
way.  &QL; 
7. CincinnatiThey may not be pretty, but they play the game right.
 &QL; 
8. ArizonaTo quote former Manager  &UR; Kevin Kennedy: ``No bullpen, no
championship.''  &QL; 
9. San FranciscoGiants'main goal is to be in first place at the
All-Star break. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. FloridaJust slightly ahead of last year's 108-loss pace.  &QL; 
29. MinnesotaIn an unusual turn, Twins management splurges with
drafted players.  &QL; 
28. Tampa Bay12 of the 25 players on the opening-day roster have
been on the DL.  &QL; 
27. DetroitHow many different ways can we say, underachieving?  &QL; 
26. MontrealAnother week, another battle over a new stadium.  &QL; 
25. AnaheimGM  &UR; Bill Bavasi shows who's boss, extends Manager &UR; Terry
Collins' contract.  &QL; 
24. Los AngelesAt $80 million, easily the most expensive hunk of
junk in the majors.  &QL; 
23. San DiegoA serious two-team battle with the Dodgers to escape
the NL West cellar  &QL; 
22. MilwaukeeThe Brew Crew is getting blue playing at home, where
they can't win. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Toronto Blue Jays: Even with slugging first baseman  &UR; Carlos
 &UR; Delgado struggling (he went through an 0-for-25 slump that ended
Wednesday, the Blue Jays have been making a move in the AL East
standings. They remained eight games behind first-place New York
entering the weekend series, but the progress has been noticeable
on the field. Even pitcher  &UR; Joey Hamilton registered his first
victory of the season. The obvious story in Toronto belongs to
 &UR; Tony Fernandez, who was still hitting over .400 entering the
weekend. But  &UR; Shawn Green appears to have emerged as a star and new
closer  &UR; Billy Koch (eight saves) looks like the real thing. This is
a club with a lot of attractive pieces. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Texas Rangers: Playing in what has to be considered the worst
division in baseball definitely has its upside, just ask the
Rangers. Even though they have been scuffling the last two weeks,
losing eight of 13 games actually translated into gaining one-half
game in the AL West standings. But problems are rising. Two-time
MVP  &UR; Juan Gonzalez entered the weekend series with just eight RBIs
in his previous 18 games, going 1 for 18 with runners in scoring
position during that span. Now there may even be added pressure to
do well this season since the Dallas Stars are coming off the
Stanley Cup championship.
 &UR; Tom Hicks owns both the Stars and Rangers and wants the Rangers to
rise to the same level as his hockey club. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Embattled Kansas City closer  &UR; Jeff Montgomery, who has struggled
mightly this season, on an off-season promise he made to himself
concerning his future in the game after this season: ``I've kind of
made a deal with myself that I would retire when either my wife
told me to or the hitters told me to. Right now, the hitters are
screaming that message, I know.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
Bank One Ballpark fans were treated to a fabulous three-game series
from Cincinnati second baseman  &UR; Pokey Reese, who appears to be
emerging as a potential star. Statistics aside, Reese showed a
tremendous ability to recognize the game from a team standpoint,
rather than the often selfish position some players tend to take
these days. With a single, double and triple already in the books
for him Tuesday night and Reese up with two outs in the ninth, he
was very aware of what was at stake if he hit a home run. The first
pitch he saw was a chest-high fastball, the kind that could easily
be driven. Instead, Reese passed and let it sail by so the Reds
pitcher, who had just run around the bases, could take a breather.
``What he did, take that fastball to help the pitcher, shows how
unselfish he is, thinking about what's best for the club,'' Reds
Manager  &UR; Jack McKeon said. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
