<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0977 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-DRAFT-LBPT     06-27 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-DRAFT-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEFAN GOES NO. 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For one day, anyway, a Long Beach Ice Dog made a bigger impact
than the big-league Kings and Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Czech center Patrik Stefan, who played the last two seasons in
Long Beach, was chosen first in the NHL draft Saturday after a
series of trades left the expansion Atlanta Thrashers with the
opening selection in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, meanwhile, sat idle until the 43rd selection, when
they chose 17-year-old Russian winger Andrei Shefer. Earlier, the
Ducks had dealt center Travis Green and their first-round
selection, No.15, to Phoenix for offensive defenseman Oleg
Tverdovsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Shefer) is a pretty good all-around player, good skater and
good on the defensive side,'' Kings general manager Dave Taylor
said. ``He has no real weaknesses. We expect he'll play another two
years (in Russia).''
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Tverdovsky, the Ducks' first selection in 1994,
has been with Phoenix since Feb. 7, 1996, when he was dealt to the
Coyotes in the deal that brought Teemu Selanne to Anaheim. Last
season with Phoenix, Tverdovsky played in all 82 games, collecting
seven goals and 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks didn't make a selection until immediately after the
Kings selected Shefer. At No.44, the Ducks chose 18-year-old
University of Minnesota defenseman Jordan Leopold.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had three selections in the third round and used them
on Swedish defenseman Frantisek Kaberle, Ohio State defenseman
Jason Crain and Canadian junior goalie Cory Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant of the three is the 6-foot-1, 185-pound
Kaberle, who is 25 and was named the most valuable defenseman in
Sweden last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a player who we anticipate can step in and play right
away,'' Taylor said. ``He's a very good skater and moves the puck
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an eventful day in the draft, with a series of trades
announced even before selections began.
</P>
<P>
   Once the trades were completed, Tampa Bay's first pick belonged
to Atlanta, Vancouver had the second and third selections and the
New York Rangers had the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The result of this action was that Stefan, the only player in
this draft expected to make an impact in the NHL next season, ended
up in Atlanta, and Swedish twins Daniel and Henrik Sedin wound up
together with the Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, youth conscious after the retirement of Wayne
Gretzky and their failure to acquire star forward Ziggy Palffy from
the New York Islanders, chose Czech winger Pavel Brendl, perhaps
the best goal scorer available. The Islanders traded Palffy to the
Kings a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also had the ninth selection, using it on Canadian
center Jamie Lundmark, and the Islanders had three picks in the top
10, giving the New York metropolitan area half of the first 10
selections. The Islanders used their picks on American defenseman
Tim Connolly at No.5, Canadian winger Taylor Pyatt at No.8 (this
was originally the Kings' selection) and Slovakian defenseman
Branislav Mezei at No.10. The Islanders also had a fourth
first-round selection, the 28th and final pick in the opening
round, and used it on Slovakian defenseman Kristian Kudroc.
</P>
<P>
   Of note for the Kings was that forward Matt Zultek, whom they
drafted in the first round two years ago but never signed, was not
selected until Boston picked him 56th. Two years ago, Zultek was
the 15th player chosen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
