<HEADER>
A0978 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     06-27 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS TRADE FOR TVERDOVSKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mighty Ducks general manager Pierre Gauthier was waiting
patiently to make the No. 15 pick in the 1999 NHL Entry Draft on
Saturday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve teams had already made their selections when the phone
rang and Phoenix GM Bobby Smith was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes Gauthier made Ducks history of sorts. He traded
away Anaheim's first-round pick for the first time in the club's
existence, packaging it with center Travis Green to acquire
former-Duck Oleg Tverdovsky from the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never say never,'' said Gauthier, who like former GM Jack
Ferreira, had long expressed a reluctance to trade draft picks,
especially first-rounders.
</P>
<P>
   But Gauthier all but admitted Saturday's deal was a no-brainer,
especially for a team that struggled to score in even strength
situations last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filled our No. 1 need,'' he said. ``There wasn't a fan or
media member that couldn't answer what our No. 1 need was.''
</P>
<P>
   The smooth-skating Tverdovsky, who was the No. 2 overall pick by
the Ducks in the 1994 draft, was a part of the blockbuster trade
that brought Teemu Selanne to Anaheim in 1996. But the Ducks have
since struggled to find a presence on the blue line that could
compliment the skills of Selanne and Paul Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a offensive element,'' said Gauthier. ``And I don't
think a team can win (a Stanley Cup) without that type of player.''
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky's defense is not considered his strength, but even
defensive-minded Craig Hartsburg is excited about the prospect of
adding a defenseman who can carry the puck out of his own zone and
jump into the play when the opportunity presents itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a world class player,'' said the Mighty Ducks
coach, who hopes to play Tverdovsky with Kariya and Selanne as much
as possible in 5-on-5 situations. ``He makes us better, faster and
more exciting for our fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a chance to add a player like that you have to
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier inquired about Tverdovsky's availability last month,
only to have Smith say it would ``take an unbelievable deal'' to
pry him away from the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith, who displayed interest in Green over the past month,
finally called Gauthier on Saturday and asked what it would acquire
the center, who had 13 goals and 30 points last season.
</P>
<P>
   When Gauthier said ``Oleg,'' Smith replied ``Oleg Tverdovsky?''
</P>
<P>
   After a pause, Gauthier said Smith said ``it's a deal and he
hung up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier, surprised and delighted, admitted when he went to
finalize the deal with Smith he still thought ``maybe I
misunderstood.''
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky was an all-star for the Coyotes in '97 when he scored
10 goals and 55 points. But he had his share of troubles in Phoenix
as well. He was a holdout at the beginning of the '97-98 season and
was involved in a well-publicized fight with Jeremy Roenick. The
low point for Tverdovsky came during the recent playoffs when he
was a healthy scratch in the seventh game of the Coyotes-St. Louis
Blues first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   The defenseman becomes a restricted free agent on July 1, but
Gauthier said he has already talked with Tverdovsky's agent and
does not expect problems signing him to a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky has been a favorite target of angry Ducks fans since
comments he made about the Anaheim franchise were taken out of
context before the Ducks-Phoenix playoff series in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the 23-year old should certainly be a favorite of Anaheim
forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense did what they did best last year and that was
defend,'' said Hartsburg. ``But we felt we had to upgrade our
transition game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier added two more defensemen to the system in the second
and third round when he selected Jordan Leopold with the No. 44
pick and Niklas Havelid with the No. 83.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim hopes those two players will be contributors 2-3 years
down the line, but there's little doubt the Gauthier was thinking
about Tverdovsky's immediate impact when he said ``it's a great day
for the Mighty Ducks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 0150EDT &QL; 
