<HEADER>
A0979 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-WBA-AYALA-WINS-TE     06-27 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-WBA-AYALA-WINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA STUNS TAPIA TO WIN WBA BANTAMWEIGHT TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Paulie Ayala believed all along that Johnny Tapia
did not respect his punching power. And ultimately that punching
power cost Tapia his World Boxing Association bantamweight
championship last night.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's Ayala lured Tapia into the ultimate street fight at
the Mandalay Bay Events Center to register a stunning, unanimous
12-round decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Johnny Tapia. I've said he may have been the best
junior bantamweight in the world,'' Ayala said moments after
handing Tapia his first professional defeat. ``But I'm the best
bantamweight \R118-pounder\S in the world. I knew he has never
faced an opponent like me. I was fighting my fight. I did a little
boxing, a little slugging. I knew they underestimated my punching
power.''
</P>
<P>
   In a fight that featured no knockdowns, Ayala won by scores of
116-113 on the cards of judges Duane Ford of Las Vegas and Fernando
Viso of Valencia, Venezuela. He prevailed on the card of Guy Jutras
of Montreal, 115-114. The ``Star-Telegram'' had it for Ayala,
115-113.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, a left-hander ranked No. 2 by the WBA, improved to 28-1
with 12 KOs. Tapia dropped to 46-1-2 with 25 knockouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was stronger than him. I was hurting him a lot,''
said Tapia, of Albuquerque, N.M.. ``Everybody knows what happened.
But I'm not a poor loser. I give all respect to Mr. Ayala, and the
better man won. There are bigger and better things on the table for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad blood between the fighters had begun to boil as early as
the introductions, when Tapia marched over to Ayala and thrust his
gloves into Ayala's neck. That drew a stern warning from referee
Joe Cortez, who was working his 116th title fight, to knock off the
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Cortez stopped the fight momentarily at the start of the 10th to
have a cut on Tapia's head examined. Tapia answered by pressing the
action and throwing both hands. Ayala held his ground and
retaliated with a series of left uppercuts. Tapia landed a huge
straight right with 18 seconds left, but Ayala weathered that shot.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia got his punches off first in the ninth, and a left caused
Ayala to stumble forward for a second. Tapia came right back and
threw a right and slipped but got up immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia concentrated on staying inside at the outset of the
eighth, throwing more punches. The champion landed a combination to
the head with 1:30 to go, but Ayala landed a left-right just when
it looked he was tiring. Tapia then began to exhort the crowd to
turn it up.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh round was heading into its final minute when Ayala
threw a four-punch flurry to the head that got Tapia on his
bicycle. The challenger closed with another series of shots off the
shoulders and head, and then snapped off a right to the head just
before the bell.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia did throw more rights in the sixth, and briefly switched
to a southpaw stance. The champion closed with a flurry and
straight right that likely stole him the round.
</P>
<P>
   Between rounds, trainer Freddie Roach implored Tapia to throw
the right lead and double left hook.
</P>
<P>
   The slugging got toe-to-toe in the fifth, each fighter landing
body shots off hooks with their respective power hands. In the
final minute, Ayala began loading up shots to the head to finish
strong.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia began using his jab to distance himself from Ayala in the
fourth, but Ayala continued to press forward. Tapia landed a
straight right, a shot that was met by a flurry of body shots from
Ayala. The fighters bumped heads with about 1:30 remaining, but
continued without a stoppage. With the round drawing to a close,
the pair bumped heads again.
</P>
<P>
   An Ayala right to the head spun Tapia early in the third round.
The pair then settled into the middle of the ring, and Tapia lost
his balance and nearly fell down after a right hook to the head.
The right hook continued to drive Tapia back with a minute left.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia came back with a combination to the face, but Ayala's left
hook continued to score up to the bell. Ayala raised his hands as
he headed back to his corner to signify he had won the round.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala pushed Tapia back at the outset of the second round, and
then landed a series of body shots to the body and head. Tapia
stopped one flurry with a hold, and then responded with a pair of
double left hooks. Ayala answered that salvo with a straight left
hook.
</P>
<P>
   In the night's first title fight, Stevie Johnston of Denver
retained his World Boxing Council lightweight (135-pound) title
with a lackluster, but unanimous, 12-round decision against Aldo
Rios of Argentina. In a fight that began drawing boos from the
crowd for lack of action by the sixth round, Johnston (27-1, 14
knockouts) prevailed by totals of 116-112, 117-112 and 118-110.
</P>
<P>
   Rios, the WBC's No. 6-ranked contender, suffered his first
defeat and is 20-1 with 4 KOs.
</P>
<P>
   In the lead-in to the main event, Eric ``Butterbean'' Esch
defended his International Boxing Association super heavyweight
title with a first-round technical knockout against Peter McNeeley.
Esch, the former Toughman Champion, ended the bout with a flurry of
right uppercuts and left hooks to the head that backed McNeeley
into the ropes. Referee Jay Nady stopped it at 2:59 in the round,
one second from the bell.
</P>
<P>
   Esch, the self-proclaimed ``King of the Four-Rounders,'' went
that distance two weeks ago in Fort Worth. Esch decisioned Russell
Chasteen on a Top Rank card at The Speedway Club at Texas Motor
Speedway. Esch now is 45-1-1 with 34 KOs.
</P>
<P>
   McNeeley, who at 212 pounds weighed 99 pounds less than Esch,
was making his first appearance in Las Vegas since suffering an
embarrassing 89-second, first-round disqualification loss against
former heavyweight champion Mike Tyson on Aug. 19, 1995. The fight
was Tyson's first after serving a prison term after being convicted
of rape in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   McNeeley now is 45-5 with 34 KOs.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala earned a career-best $60,000 last night, barely one-fourth
of Tapia's $250,000 payday. But Ayala downplayed the importance of
his purse before the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have fought Johnny Tapia for a trophy. Or the belt,''
Ayala said. ``I'll be more than happy to brag about my purses after
this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Ayala's second world-title fight in 10 months. Ayala
was unbeaten and the WBC's No. 1-ranked contender when he dropped a
sixth-round technical decision against then-champion Joichiro
Tatsuyoshi in Yokohama, Japan, on Aug. 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
