<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FB-AGENTS-MASTERP-HNS     06-27 1788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FB-AGENTS-MASTER </SLUG>
 P-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Like it or not, Master P and Co. about to get `rowdy, rowdy'
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IS the sports world ready for this?
</P>
<P>
   There is a recurring theme in the music Master P has produced.
With hard, repetitive beats and profanity-laced lyrics, Master P
makes sure his fans know he and his No Limit Soldiers are ``'bout
it, 'bout it.'' And if you don't like it, they get ``rowdy,
rowdy.''
</P>
<P>
   What are they 'bout?
</P>
<P>
   They are 'bout ``makin' it happen,'' or so the songs say.
</P>
<P>
   Percy Miller is a little different. But like his alter ego
Master P, there is no question he is ``'bout it, 'bout it,'' as
well.
</P>
<P>
   What is he 'bout?
</P>
<P>
   He's 'bout, as he says, ``takin' care of bidness.''
</P>
<P>
   While many young black men have made money in rap music in the
last 15 years, few have shown the vision and business acumen of
Miller, a 28-year-old New Orleans native.
</P>
<P>
   No Limit Inc., the company Miller started as a retail record
store with his $10,000 share of an inheritance, is estimated to
have grossed more than $56 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Turning $10,000 into $56 million in six years is impressive in
any industry.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall Forbes magazine listed Miller as the 10th-highest-paid
entertainer in 1998, behind the likes of Jerry Seinfeld, Oprah
Winfrey and the Rolling Stones, but well ahead of notables like the
Spice Girls, Celine Dion and Garth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Miller is a true American success story.
</P>
<P>
   Forget what the New York Knicks' Latrell Sprewell says in his
controversial television commercial. Many think Master P, not
Sprewell, is an American nightmare. But reality says Percy Miller
is the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's business savvy has led to the formation of No Limit
Sports, which could put him in a brighter national spotlight than
any crossover hit ever could for Master P.
</P>
<P>
   With No Limit Sports, Miller dreams of turning the sports world
upside down, and not with spectacular touchdown runs, towering home
runs or highlight-reel slam dunks.
</P>
<P>
   His clients will do that, or so he hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Tevester Scott, No Limit Sports' chief operating officer, has no
trouble defining the company's objective: ``The ultimate goal of No
Limit is to take over the whole entertainment and sports marketing
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   By landing Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams as its first
high-profile client, No Limit Sports showed it was serious about
accomplishing its goals.
</P>
<P>
   If that didn't prove the point, Miller is building a $21 million
training complex in Baton Rouge for his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, agents can compete with that.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't matter to No Limit. Like the chorus of Master P's
signature hit, No Limit plans to simply, ``Make 'Em Say Ugh!''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Though some agents refuse to even offer an opinion of Miller and
No Limit Sports, there is no shortage of those willing to criticize
anonymously. Some, though, believe the criticism is premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people have jumped up and decided they don't
have a place (in the business) before looking at their
performance,'' said Randy Bowman of Strategic Sports Ventures in
Dallas. ``I don't have any negative opinion of those guys because I
think there is room for anybody who can do a good job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the question is going to be whether or not they can do
a good job. So, I think their performance ought to speak to whether
or not they have a place.''
</P>
<P>
   No Limit believes its place in the business soon will be at the
top, and that is why others have been quick to criticize its early
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the agent community is deathly afraid of us,'' Leland
Hardy, the managing director and chief investment officer at No
Limit Sports, said in an interview for an ESPN Outside the Lines
special. ``I think the football community is eager to have us. We
bring new, fresh enthusiasm to the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that finally the agent community at large realizes
that we have arrived. `We' I mean from two perspectives _ `we,' No
Limit the company, but also the larger `we,' being those from the
community of hip hop. I've longed for almost a decade and talked
about what I call 'the messiah factor.' That eventually one from
among us, a messiah of hip hop, someone who could easily galvanize
the attention of all the young audience of prospective professional
basketball players and others, would realize their ability to
harness the power of their celebrity towards attracting prospective
athlete clients.
</P>
<P>
   `` I'm talking about a cultural kinship and a cultural
sensitivity that transcends race.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy does not hesitate to make such bold statements because he
believes in the coming years the sports world will find that many
athletes will relate better to No Limit Sports because of its
connection to hip hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every high school kid who we might want _ black, white, Asian,
otherwise _ is listening to No Limit music in their cars on the way
to school,'' he said. ``We don't have to make a sales pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a kinship of sports and entertainment that few agents can
offer. Solely owned by Miller, No Limit Inc. has under its umbrella
the nation's No. 1 independent record label, a movie and television
production company, an educational program and a line of toys.
</P>
<P>
   Miller also has a shoe deal with Converse, and earlier this
month he and a few cronies took to the lucrative world of
professional wrestling with an appearance at a World Championship
Wrestling event.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of hip hop, No Limit Soldiers are making money
everywhere (in one song he calls himself the ghetto Bill Gates);
only recently has the sports world been invaded.
</P>
<P>
   No Limit Sports, which signed its first clients last fall, has
four registered agents on staff, including Hardy. The company
represents a half dozen NBA players, among them Cleveland's Derek
Anderson and Boston's Ron Mercer, another half-dozen NFL draftees
and several WNBA players.
</P>
<P>
   But its biggest coup was reeling in Williams, the former
University of Texas star, who soon will become just the third
athlete in school history to have his jersey number retired.
</P>
<P>
   Having Williams, a first-round pick of the New Orleans Saints
(fifth overall) in the 1999 NFL draft, as a client gives No Limit
Sports instant credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people say a I took a big chance in going with No
Limit, but it was the best decision for me,'' Williams said.
``There is a family atmosphere there that I don't think I would get
anywhere else, and that's what helped sway me in their direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as all the negative talk I've never been concerned too
much with what other people think.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good thing, especially since Williams' incentive-laden,
eight-year, $16.2 million contract has been widely criticized by
other agents.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes a hefty $8.84 million signing bonus, but then
calls for Williams to be paid the league minimum salary throughout
the length of the agreement. However, incentives within the deal
could increase its value to more than $68 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also, bucking a now common trend, the contract has no buyout
clause that would allow Williams to renegotiate with the Saints or
become a free agent after a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Steinberg, who is one of the country's top sports agents,
thought that deal might not be the best one Williams could have
gotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leery of second-guessing a contract,'' Steinberg said in
an ESPN.com article. ``But the goal with a running back, who had
considerable leverage _ his team had traded their future picks
away; he was their only pick _ is to secure the largest up-front
signing bonus possible and then create a voidable year structure
that allows that player to come back within four years and
negotiate as a veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``To accept a contract with minimum base salaries is extremely
unusual. To sign away seven years plus an option year essentially
commits the entire career of a running back to his rookie contract.
That is not the goal with high-round picks.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is not concerned about his deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my decision,'' Williams said at a Saints minicamp
earlier this month. ``Whether it's good or bad, I'm the one that
has to deal with it. So it doesn't bother me. If I had held out for
a buyout, I wouldn't be in camp right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said a buyout clause was not necessary because he wants
to be a member of the Saints for his entire career and if he earns
his keep, as he expects, money will not be a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a respect between us,'' Williams said of his
relationship with Saints management. ``They're not going to (take
advantage of) me. I think they're honorable people. If I rush for
1,500 yards in my first three or four years, they're going to want
to redo the contract. I treated them fairly, and I think they'll
treat me fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents say Hardy, a rookie to deal-making with NFL teams, may
have been taken advantage of in an attempt to sign his client
quickly to let the league's powers-that-be know that No Limit would
be easy to deal with in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``With as much leverage as they had, it is hard to believe he
accepted that deal,'' said an agent who did not want to be
identified. ``The negative press they got when they got into the
business must have played a role in that. That was probably the
worst deal they could have agreed to. I would still be laughing had
the Saints come to me with that one, and I know people are laughing
at No Limit for agreeing to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they will learn that most of the time image is not as
important as doing the best you can for your client, even if it
takes a long, drawn-out negotiating process to get it done. Most of
the time, fast, quick and easy is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman said the flak No Limit is getting might be much ado about
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's room for more than a little bit of professional envy
when it comes down to those guys,'' he said. ``Who cares what a
bunch of stinking agents think about if No Limit ought to be
around; there a few players who think they ought to be around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't do a good job for their players, they will come
into the sports rep industry and they will leave, much like Hammer
did a few years ago. If they can deliver quality and provide a good
service for their clients, and they have expertise, they'll be
around. If they can't I won't have to worry about 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Miller and his agents at No Limit may have hit
the scene thinking they will continue to be ``bout it, bout it.''
But if they can't get the job done they will be out it, out it,
whether the sports world is ready for them or not. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
