<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FB-AGENTS-MINORITIES-     06-27 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FB-AGENTS-MINORITIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Despite barriers, blacks making inroads into sports industry
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IT is such a common occurrence that many among them are not even
fazed by it. It comes with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Black sports agents are no more monolithic than black people in
general are, but they all know that at some point they will share
in a common experience and be rejected by a client not because of
knowledge, expertise or ability, but because of race.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all have, as described by one black agent, a
``But-for-all-that-melanin-I'd-hire-you'' story.
</P>
<P>
   Though surely less damaging than the violence often associated
with overt racism and less meaningful to the world than the subtle
racism African-Americans contend with on a daily basis, what black
agents encounter in their world is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that black agents are subjected to
discrimination from black athletes as much as from white ones.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago Larry Reynolds represented a talented minor-league
ballplayer at the Class AAA level who told him he needed to change
agents because he felt it would be easier to get to the big leagues
if he had a white agent. That player now makes more than $6 million
a year. That player is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how he had been conditioned to think,'' said Reynolds,
who heads Reynolds Sports Management. ``Fortunately for me, a lot
of those issues have subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are people out there who view my race as a
problem, but I think it was more so a problem 10-15 years ago than
now because I have been in the business quite some time and have
built a solid reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to say `Look at character before color,' and if I can
get somebody to do that, then I'll be fine. And that goes for all
prospective clients, black or white.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who counts among his clients Astros outfielder Carl
Everett and shortstop Ricky Gutierrez, is one of an estimated 400
African-Americans who are registered as sports agents with the NFL,
NBA and Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the players unions of those three professional leagues
have registered roughly 1,600 agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles-based Black Sports Agents Association says that
though blacks make up 70 percent of NBA players, 67 percent of NFL
players and 17 percent of Major League Baseball players, only 11
percent of black athletes have black agents.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL Players Association, the only players union that would
venture a guess at the racial breakdown of its registered agents,
said roughly 30 percent of its 956 agents are blacks but estimates
that only 10 percent of its 1,600 players are represented by
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball is believed to be slightly behind that figure and
baseball well off that mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really shouldn't matter what race an agent is,'' said
Rockets forward Scottie Pippen, whose agent, Jimmy Sexton, is
black. ``In this day, that should not be a factor. With the kind of
money that is out there, you really need somebody that you can put
your confidence in to get you the best deals and give you the best
service. If you overlook somebody because they are black, you might
miss out on a person that could do the best job for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Francis, the NFLPA director of communication, said the
number of people registering as agents, including blacks, has been
growing rapidly the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a rocket scientist to know it has changed
dramatically the last five years,'' Francis said. ``I don't know if
it's (the movie) Jerry Maguire or what, but the business has
increased its numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also the money. You have to understand, agents took some
$60 million out of the (NFL) free agency system last year.''
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of money available in an already near-cutthroat
arena, the competition for clients is stiff. When race is a part of
the equation, as it so often is, the battle intensifies.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that regardless of qualifications, black agents point
to having to convince athletes they can get the job done as a
hurdle they must negotiate before they can negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   C. Lamont Smith, president and CEO of All Pro Sports and
Entertainment Inc., is the first African-American to represent two
Heisman Trophy winners (Barry Sanders and Eddie George), and he
lists NFL stars Jerome Bettis (Pittsburgh), Willie Roaf (New
Orleans), Steve Atwater (New York Jets) and Chad Brown (Seattle)
among his clients.
</P>
<P>
   On his website, he cites as his biggest obstacle ``getting over
the mental hurdle with players that, as a black man, I am just as
competent, if not more, than my non-black competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters, and further intensifying the battle for
clients, are white agents who players have said court them by
saying they need a white person on their side at the negotiating
table with white team owners and almost all-white general managers
in professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is a lucrative one, and some people _ a lot of
people _ will do whatever it takes to get a client,'' Reynolds
said. ``That shouldn't be an issue with me, because if I continue
to do things decently and in order, and work hard, opportunities
will continue to present themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Bowman of Strategic Sports Ventures in Dallas said that
while using race as a recruiting tool may present an obstacle, it
shouldn't prevent him or other blacks from attracting clients.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the University of Texas and Whittier College
School of Law, Bowman said he gained invaluable knowledge on how
deals were done when he began his law career working for firms that
represented sports teams, and he will put his expertise to the test
against anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem, but the bottom line is, if I trot out my track
record, I think I make it pretty obvious that the quality of the
deals I do for my clients are superior to and certainly no less
than the quality of the deals that other agents are able to deliver
for their clients, be those agents black or white,'' Bowman said.
``So, track record helps. The problem is getting a kid to keep an
open mind until he's had a chance to observe track records and the
other things that ought to be important in making this kind of
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   That decision is made more difficult by black agents who use an
``us-against-them'' tactic to win over players. Despite numbers
that point to the contrary, many think of color as an advantage
black agents have in relating to young athletes, especially the
large percentage that come from the inner city. That is part of the
fear generated by rapper Master P's recent foray into the business
with the formation of No Limit Sports.
</P>
<P>
   But Bowman said that while being black should not cost an agent
clients, it should not be enough to woo them, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have to be able to do something other than be black
and relate,'' Bowman said. ``If I'm an athlete and an agent comes
to me with a sales pitch composed primarily of, `I'm black, I can
relate to you better than the white agents, here are the guys that
I represent and I can get your deal done,' my response is probably
going to be, `OK, what else you got?' Because that's probably not
going to get it for me. The fact that you're black and you think
that you relate to me better (than a white agent) is just not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (players) are looking for that sales pitch, I won't get
them. I talk about expertise and experience and being able to
deliver results. Plus I can relate, because I relate well with all
my clients due to some shared experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you show up just black and relating, you ought to lose to
me every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Relating to prospective clients and/or their parents is often
overrated. Bowman said he has had players and parents relate to him
well enough to think of him as a friend, but they still wouldn't
hire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain comfort level with some players, but it's
offset by the fact that some guys still feel they need somebody
white to represent them,'' Reynolds said. ``Many players don't take
a mature approach in selecting an agent. The criteria by which they
select an agent are very poor in general. That's why you have so
many players that, after a number of years, switch and go from the
next guy to the next guy.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing frequent changes in representation, combined with
regular renegotiations and yearly influx of a new client base, does
is guarantee continued opportunities in the business. Opportunities
black agents hope that more blacks will take advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future is very bright to the extent that we, as black
agents, don't go out and undermine ourselves,'' Smith said. ``I've
observed a destructive trend that some of us attack each other
because we think that's competition, and it's not. That could dim
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not compete unfairly. We do not have to fight over
crumbs among us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
