<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FB-AGENTS-BASEBALL-HN     06-27 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FB-AGENTS-BASEBALL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Most black agents shy away from America's pastime
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There may not be any more exciting time to be involved in the
business of sport than now.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: There is a lot of money to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Television networks are offering billions of dollars for
broadcasting rights, conglomerates are paying hundreds of millions
of dollars to buy franchises, municipalities are fronting hundreds
of millions of dollars to build stadiums, and owners are shelling
out $100 million contracts to players to perform.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of money to go around. Black sports agents are
not getting much of it, but in recent years they have started
getting more of it than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to football and basketball, that is.
</P>
<P>
   In America's pastime, black agents remain far behind the curve.
</P>
<P>
   There are many black agents who have done limited work in
baseball, handling a client or two, but few make baseball a
priority.
</P>
<P>
   There are many theories as to why that is, but most believe it
is simply the nature of the business and the sport.
</P>
<P>
   For one, baseball is just not as popular among blacks as
football and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Sports Agents Association says blacks make up 70
percent of players in the NBA, 67 percent of players in the NFL and
only 17 percent of players in Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like when you're growing up,'' Larry Reynolds of
Reynolds Sports Management said. ``There are a lot of blacks that
love football and basketball, and those are the sports many black
youth grow up dreaming about becoming stars in.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small percentage of baseball players are black. You can
watch the college baseball world series and count on one hand the
number of black kids on those eight clubs there. Baseball is just
not as popular, and I think that translates into blacks wanting to
become football and basketball agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Things were different for Reynolds, who is from a baseball
family. He played baseball at Stanford and was in the St. Louis
Cardinals' farm system before a knee injury shortened his career.
His brother Harold spent 11 seasons in the big leagues, was a
two-time All-Star and now is an analyst with ESPN, and his brother
Don was also a player and is now a minor-league manager.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Reynolds also coached a year at the Class AA level before
deciding to become an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Now he represents major-leaguers Carl Everett and Ricky
Gutierrez of the Astros; former Astro James Mouton (Montreal);
Kenny Hill (Anaheim), who was one of his first clients; Brian L.
Hunter (Seattle); LaTroy Hawkins (Minnesota); and Torri Hunter
(Minnesota).
</P>
<P>
   He also recently signed Ryan Christianson, who was chosen by
Seattle with the 11th pick in the first round of the amateur draft
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds has been in baseball longer than any other black agent
and may be the lone black agent who has a mostly baseball
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in baseball since my brother Don was drafted in
1975,'' Reynolds said. ``I love the sport, and it is definitely
where my expertise is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew a lot of players and had a good relationship with a lot
of guys. Plus, my family was known in baseball. It was a
combination of all those things that made it an easier introduction
into the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few guys trying to get into the industry, but to
get a significant number of clients in the business you have to put
your time in. You may luck up and get one or two players every now
and then, but to really do this thing right, build any kind of
client list, you have to be around, go through a couple of labor
disputes and still be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds was joking about staying power through labor disputes,
but it is a valid concern for some agents looking at taking on
baseball clients.
</P>
<P>
   Agents are not nearly as anxious to do baseball thanks to the
impending labor war that is expected to come when the collective
bargaining agreement ends in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   And that opens the door to another major influence on blacks not
entering the business en masse _ money. The money is there, just as
it is in professional basketball and football, but it takes longer
to get to it.
</P>
<P>
   While lucrative contracts for star players are comparable to
those of other sports, second- and third-year players who show
potential don't hit the jackpot like they do in the NBA and NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Houstonian Alan Hendricks, one of baseball's power agents whose
lengthy client list includes Roger Clemens, Chuck Knoblauch, Andy
Pettitte, Jose Cruz Jr., Kerry Woods and Davis' Carl Crawford, said
he advises young attorneys interested in becoming agents _
regardless of their race _ to look to football and basketball if
they want to pay the bills in a timely manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lead time in baseball _ before a player reaches star
status or signs that first big contract _ that's why young agents
tend to gravitate toward the money sports,'' said Hendricks, a
white agent who heads Hendricks Sports Management. ``The bonuses
and big contracts are in the NBA and the NFL _ that's the deal,
that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks notes that all agents are not out to make a fast buck
but adds that time is money and the amount of time it takes to
build a reputation as a good baseball agent with a strong stable of
clients might not be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is I'm not going to spend an inordinate amount
of time sitting in the stands at a high school baseball game,
because that's not the best use of my time, nor is it a good way to
represent the clients that I currently represent,'' said Randy
Bowman, a Dallas-based attorney whose client list is composed
almost exclusively of basketball players and coaches. ``I take care
of the guys that I currently have instead of spending all of my
time, as some agents do, trying to find the next crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawyer in me says that if a high school player needs
representation in an area where I have expertise, like sports, then
I am the best person for the job, so I don't have anything against
representing them. But the process by which you come to represent
them, having to sink all that time into recruiting them and wooing
them, I'm not going to do that. My relationships have to form a
little more naturally than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman has represented a baseball player in the past, but that
was by referral. That is the story with most of the black agents
who handle football or basketball players _ they only dabble in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds hopes to see more blacks join him in the business,
though more young whites ask him about entering the business than
young blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it trailblazing, but I hope I can be helpful
in encouraging more black agents into coming into baseball,'' he
said. ``I'd just like to see (players) have a wider range of
choices in agents. I think black agents could do well in the sport,
and not because of race, but because there are a lot of talented
young people out there who could get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the type of job that you can go to school and say,
`I want to learn how to be a sports agent.' It takes time to build
up reputation. Guys build up reputations, some positive, some
negative, but you learn along the way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LADN     06-27 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SEASON IS SHORT AND SWEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You came back. Admit it now. You feigned indignation, played
cool with indifference, gave lip service to actual anger.
</P>
<P>
   Then the NBA started its season and you came running back.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's work stoppage in 1994 brought it to its sporting
knees. Fans cursed, cried heresy, filled newspapers and the airways
with rage, and then when baseball returned, stayed away in huge
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has a lockout that postpones the season's start three
months, sees the greatest star in its history retire, and its
faithful act like it almost never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fans made like the scorned lover, basketball's the
wide-eyed school boy given another chance by his true love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we're very lucky that our fans are as forgiving
as they have turned out to be,'' said NBA commissioner David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   After the league and players reached a collective bargaining
agreement, the NBA braced for the worst. Naysayers pointed to a
truncated, hastily designed 50-game season without Michael Jordan
and predicted Armageddon.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the regular season, both attendance and
television ratings were down only marginally.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA averaged 16,738 fans per game this season, down just
percentage points from last season's 17,135 per game. The regular
season NBC ratings only dropped from 4.6 last season to 4.3 this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball, meanwhile, is still trying to fully
recover from its 1994 troubles. Baseball was averaging 31,612 fans
per game when its season came to an abrupt halt five years ago. The
next year, its average fell to 25,260 per game. It has grown slowly
each season since, but even in last year's supposed home-run
inspired season of rebirth, attendance was up to only 29,285.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of reasons are promoted for why the NBA enjoyed an almost
seamless return: The NBA utilized a smart public relations
campaign; its sophisticated fans recognized a workable agreement;
new stars ignited interest; and if losing Jordan was an historic
blow, it did leave a more open playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the biggest reason may simply be in the very nature of the
NBA. Its regular season is a prolonged prelude to the playoffs. If
the NBA lost some prelude, baseball lost its grand finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky in two respects,'' Stern said. ``Number one, our
work stoppage cost us the beginning of the season and not the end.
That's important. And number two, our work stoppage resulted in an
agreement that the fans recognized was really a good-faith attempt
by both sides to deal with seemingly retractable problems. I think
that was not the perception coming out of the baseball strike.''
</P>
<P>
   After the agreement was reached, the NBA went into PR mode.
Teams were required to open a scrimmage to fans and have a free
exhibition game. Players and coaches were encouraged to become more
involved in the community. Every regular-season game had $10
tickets available.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there had never been a work stoppage in the NBA before,
and there could be no certainty as to how the fans would react. The
fans, too, seemed unsure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was angry at the start because they were out so long,'' said
Ryan Davidson, 22, a student and linebacker at Pierce College,
while watching a playoff game at B.J.'s Chicago Pizzeria in
Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost forgot basketball was around. When it came back
without Jordan, it was like a whole, strange season. Then I started
liking some of the young players coming up. The new faces kind of
brought basketball back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Locally, the Lakers made it difficult for the old followers to
turn away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a Laker fan, it was hard not to get sucked back into
it,'' Keith Dardic, 41, a TV commercial producer, said at Yankee
Doodles. ``The whole season played out like a Greek tragedy or an
opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a certain alienation during the lockout. But the bad
feelings go away once the season starts up again.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the short regular season cost the NBA financially, it
wasn't necessarily a problem for fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little more interesting with less games,''
college student Nima Ourmazdi, 23, said at the TGIFriday's in
Woodland Hills. ``It's always more interesting during the playoffs
anyway. It's not any fun for players on teams 15 games out by
midseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Michael Factor. Jordan had dominated the NBA
like no player before him, transcending the sport to become one of
the most recognized personalities in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone realized he would be missed, it was only the severity
and ultimate impact on the game that was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some practice,'' Stern said. ``We had two years without
him before, so we definitely knew the world as we knew it would not
end. It would be somewhat diminished, but in an interesting kind of
way, we expected it to be far better than the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time the focus was sort of on existing stars. This
time, the focus was on existing stars and a new generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, Allen Iverson, Jason Williams, Tim Duncan, Kevin
Garnett, Vince Carter, Stephon Marbury _ suddenly the NBA seemed
awash in bright young talent that before may have been diminished
in Jordan's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a special group of young players this season, that
everyone had every reason to dislike, that ultimately made you
watch them and respect them,'' Wise said. ``Whether it was Jason
Williams freezing people in mid air, or Vince Carter just throwing
down the most vicious dunk known to mankind _ a group of young
players really set the tone for an evolving NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA this season to me has been about almost the birth, or
the acceptance of the counter-culture hero. You might not like some
of the things that have happened in Latrell Sprewell's and Allen
Iverson's lives, but if you can't enjoy what they can do on the
floor, then you're not a basketball fan.''
</P>
<P>
   This evolving NBA continued to receive good ratings in the
playoffs, despite several sweeps. Leading into the prime time
telecasts, the playoffs received a 5.8 rating to last year's 6.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into this season with our eyes wide open and realistic
about what to expect,'' said Ed Markey, an NBC spokesman. ``But it
turned out our ratings were close in the regular season, and even
in the playoffs. Considering everything, we feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger test of life without Jordan came as the playoffs
moved into prime time, particularly with the Finals. Jordan could
draw the casual fan. Last year, it what was anticipated to be his
last season, the Finals drew a record 18.7 rating. Although the
overall ratings for this year's Finals won't be out until early
next week, the first four games were down about 35 percent from
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, significant numbers tuned in with great
intensity to see what we would call Michael's last dance,'' Stern
said. ``Here you have the player perhaps of the century, certainly
of our sport and maybe all sports, taking one last turn around the
track. That was an enormous magnet to attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you put this season in context of the last 10 years,
this season is going to turn out to be just fine, thank you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
