<HEADLINE>
JACOBS WILL GO FOR DOUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Regina Jacobs is still unsure whether the 1,500
or 5,000 meters is her best event. So the three-time Olympian opted
for a simple yet grueling solution in the USA Track &AMP; Field
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   She has decided to run in both events.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old completed the first half of the double Saturday,
clocking a world-leading and meet record 4 minutes, 2.41 seconds to
win her eighth national metric mile title before a Hayward Field
crowd of 9,149.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, a 1981 graduate of Argyll Academy now known as Campbell
Hall, will run in the 5,000-meter final today. In last year's
championships, Jacobs opted for the 5,000 and won her first
national title at the 3.1-mile distance. Jacobs later went on to
set the American record of 14:52.49.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't chosen (the 1,500 or the 5,000), that's why I am
running tomorrow,'' said Jacobs, rolling her eyes upward.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, who now lives in Oakland, will be favored in today's
5,000 final. The race will include Amy Skieresz of Agoura, a
seven-time NCAA champion in cross country and track at Arizona.
Skieresz missed the collegiate track season after she was diagnosed
with a benign tumor in her femur.
</P>
<P>
   Deena Drossin, a 1991 Agoura graduate and two-time defending
national cross country champion, was third in the 10,000 in a
career-best 32:00.72. Libbie Hickman won in a meet-record 31:43.33
and Anne-Marie Lauck was second in 31:43.50.
</P>
<P>
   The men's and women's 200 with Maurice Greene and Marion Jones
will culminate the final day of the four-day meet that serves as a
qualifier for the World Championships. The top three finishers in
each event advance to the competition in Seville, Spain in August.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who set the world 100-meter record of 9.79 two weeks
ago, and Jones, the 1998 world leader in the 100, 200 and long
jump, were semifinal heat winners in wind-aided 20.11 and 22.31.
</P>
<P>
   A showdown between Greene and world 200 record holder Michael
Johnson, however, was short-circuited when Johnson pulled out of
the competition on Friday after straining his quadriceps in
training. Rohsaan Griffin, the 1999 indoor champion, won the other
semifinal in a wind-aided 19.96.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, competing for the first time since injuring her right
knee in the Pontiac Grand Prix on June 12, is hoping to rebound in
the 200 after suffering her first loss to an American since 1987 in
finishing second in the long jump on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the best time in the world, but I made it through,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Young defended his 400-meter title in 44.24 to defeat
1991 world champion Antonio Pettigrew with the second fastest-time
in the world. Pettigrew was second in 44.59 and Jerome Davis of
USC, the 1999 Pac-10 Track Athlete of the Year, was third in 44.91.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's hurdles, Joanna Hayes of UCLA finished third in
the 400 hurdles in 55.76 after world-record holder Kim Batten fell
after hitting the eighth hurdle. Sandra Glover and Michelle Johnson
were second and third in 54.95 and 55.53.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little drama in the women's 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs strung out the field with a 60.9 opening quarter and
stretched her lead to 15 meters by 800 meters passed in 2:07.1 on
her way to dipping under Mary Slaney's 1983 meet record of 4:03.37
set in 1981. Stephanie Best finished more than six seconds back at
4:08.53 and Shayne Culpepper was third in 4:08.69.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what my plan was at the beginning of the race, and
based on that plan, I knew I wouldn't have company,'' Jacobs said.
``I knew I could use the crowd's energy to push me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
