<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY FIREWORKS FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox had their fun at Pedro Martinez's expense
the night before, taping him to a dugout post.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, they continued their hijinks, only this time
no one benefitted more than the Red Sox ace. Martinez's 14th win of
the season was assured in the first inning, when the Sox scored 11
times en route to a 17-1 drilling of the Chicago White Sox before a
sun-splashed crowd of 32,758 in Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a day for showing up late, though even the tardy
arrivals could have shown up a half-hour into the game and still
caught the bottom of the first. First pitch of the game: 4:08 p.m.
Last out of the first: 4:44.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just playing for one run at first,'' said rookie Brian
Daubach, who hit a three-run home run off White Sox starter James
Baldwin to start the score-o-rama, then singled in another run on
his next turn, setting a personal best for RBIs in a game before
the Sox had made three outs. ``When we got three, with Pedro
pitching, you kind of figure you've got a good lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it kept going and going. It was unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, in tying a club record for runs in their first at-bat
set 66 years before, paraded 14 batters to the plate in the first
inning, when they hit two home runs, four doubles, and three
singles and also had two walks. The first three batters in the
order _ Jose Offerman, Lou Merloni, and Daubach _ all reached
safely twice in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman doubled and walked, Merloni singled and hit a three-run
double that missed being a grand slam by a couple of feet, and
Daubach had his ninth home run, his second in two games, and an RBI
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that doesn't happen very often,'' said Mike
Stanley, who doubled and homered. ``So people just keep shaking
their heads and want to get back up there and hit again.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, who made the only out among the
first seven Sox batters when he struck out, hit a two-run home run
on his second go-round in the inning to cap the 11-run outburst,
then hit a three-run home run in the third inning on his next
at-bat. He didn't need a note from his doctor to convince anyone
he's fine after missing two games with a strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   In the day's most astonishing show of chutzpah, Baldwin actually
appeared to throw a fit when fetched by White Sox manager Jerry
Manuel after walking No. 9 hitter Trot Nixon with six runs already
in, flinging his chew and stalking off to the back of the mound
before handing the ball to his manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, winning for the 10th time in their last 13 games, hit
five home runs in all in erupting for their biggest offensive
showing since Aug. 5, 1997, when they beat the Rangers in Texas,
17-1.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, in his easiest tuneup yet for his all-but-official
All-Star start here on July 13, was dismissed after five easy
innings, giving way to John Wasdin, who breezed through four
hitless innings against the Chicagoans resigned to their fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely the Pedro express,'' said Chicago strongman
Frank Thomas, who struck out in both of his appearances against
Martinez. ``He's not overrated at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a special, special pitcher. He threw me nine pitches and
they were all unhittable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he has a special edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who struck out four, walked one, and gave up three
hits, including a home run by rookie Chris Singleton in the second,
now has won his last three starts to go to 14-2, with two starts
left before the break. The last two pitchers to have had 15 wins
before the break both had Red Sox ties, Roger Clemens and Bret
Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of who the starter was that was in there,'' manager
Jimy Williams said, ``he's probably going to come out in a game
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's only dilemma Saturday came when he went to the mound
before the game, when he had to choose which ball with which to
warm up. Inexplicably, there were four baseballs strewn around the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, playing without third baseman John Valentin, still
woozy after being beaned the night before, batted around for the
second time this season in jumping on the White Sox. Merloni, who
has started games at short, second, and third this week, singled
after Offerman's leadoff double, then hit a bases-loaded double on
his second at-bat in the inning, clearing the bases and missing a
grand slam by a couple of feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' five home runs matched their season high, as Stanley
and Jason Varitek hit back-to-back home runs off Chicago reliever
Scott Eyre leading off the fourth. Varitek also had two doubles,
giving him four doubles in two games.
</P>
<P>
   Every batter in the Boston lineup had at least one hit except
for outfielder Darren Lewis, who went hitless in five trips. The
Sox had nine extra-base hits, with four doubles in addition to the
five homers.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who last week posted a sign above his locker advising
reporters that he wouldn't be talking that day, posted another
missive after the game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good today, both physically and mentally,'' he said.
``The day belongs to my teammates for their offensive production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,
</P>
<P>
   Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, to make sure no one could possibly misinterpret his
absence, Martinez added one word and circled it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
