<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON T PARTY: TRADES, TWINS, TIRADE 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Known the world over for its Tea Party, Boston Saturday
took its place in National Hockey League annals as the town of
Trades and Twins in the league's final entry draft of the 20th
Century.
</P>
<P>
   The twins, star Swedish lookalikes Daniel and Henrik Sedin, were
selected by the Vancouver Canucks, who were at the center of the
league's busiest and biggest trade meet in history.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs with the top four picks _ Tampa, Atlanta, Vancouver,
and Chicago _ opened the afternoon on Causeway Street with a series
of interlocking deals that left Vancouver with the Sedins (picks
Nos. 2 and 3), Atlanta with promising forward Patrik Stefan (the
No. 1 pick), and the Rangers with Pavel Brendl (No. 4).
</P>
<P>
   Few hockey fans this side of Flin Flon know anything about
99-plus percent of the draftees. A precious few will turn into the
league's leaders in the next century. As of Saturday, they were
simply wide-eyed kids with dreams of fame and fortune. An
overwhelming percentage never will play a shift, even in a league
that adds franchises faster than McDonald's (as of next October it
will the Original 30, with billions and billions served).
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, selecting 21st overall, chose a 20-year-old
defenseman, Nick Boynton, who this spring was arrested on assault
charges for allegedly aiding a teammate in the beating of a cab
driver outside an Ottawa bar. According to newspaper accounts,
Boynton's teammmate, Mark Bell, was arrested at the scene. Boynton,
alleged to have fled the scene, wasn't collared until four days
later, the arrest made after police telephoned his home and asked
him to come in or face the prospect of being taken into custody in
his home.
</P>
<P>
   Boynton said Saturday that no charges remain pending. He also
added that he learned from the experience. It could not immediately
be learned if the charge was dropped, or otherwise settled.
</P>
<P>
   The draft, never before held in the Hub, got rolling shortly
after noon when Bruins president and general manager Harry Sinden
stepped to the podium and was soundly booed by the hometown crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spend some money, Harry!'' bellowed one leatherlung.
</P>
<P>
   The locals have grown restless after 27 years without a Stanley
Cup, and Sinden, in their eyes, is now the President Pinata. The
primary overseer of one of the league's great budget operations,
and biggest profit-makers, Sinden long ago became the focal point
of the faithful fans' ire.
</P>
<P>
   After enduring the embarrassing Bronx cheer from the crowd of
some 8,000, Sinden sardonically referenced the ``warm and loving''
greeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always remember it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden then quickly handed the proceedings over to team captain
Ray Bourque. Never has one of his teammates been so glad to let
Bourque lug the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Burke, the Harvard-trained attorney who a year ago became
the Canucks GM, sounded like a Wild West gunslinger when describing
the events leading up to his landing the Sedins.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was leaving with the twins but us,'' said Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Only 18 years old, the Sedins made it clear months ago that they
don't plan to play in North America this season. They made it
equally clear that their preference was to be drafted by the same
club. Like most all athletes in the '90s, they got their wish. It
is now up to Burke to sign them and try to convince them that
beautiful British Columbia is the place they want to be. It
shouldn't be a tough sell. They'll both be guaranteed $3
million-plus for three years of work, with the chance to double
their earnings through performance incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay boss Rick Dudley was the key behind-the-scenes
orchestrator of the high-profile moves that kicked off the draft.
He made the daring decision to give up the No. 1 overall pick in a
deal that brought him two Rangers, goalie Dan Cloutier and left
wing Niklas Sundstrom. The Cloutier-Sundstrom acquistions finally
should make the Bolts competitive in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Once Dudley budged on the No. 1, the rest of the moves fell into
place, with Atlanta moving up from No. 2 to No. 1, Vancouver adding
the No. 2 pick to its No. 3, and the Rangers slotting into
Chicago's original No. 4 spot. The Blackhawks picked up Vancouver
defenseman Bryan McCabe in the swap and also the Canucks'
first-round pick in either 2000 or 2001. The entire convoluted
transaction came together only some 10 minutes before the
selections began.
</P>
<P>
   Former Boston defenseman Mike Milbury, who made the fifth,
eighth, and 10th picks for the Islanders, was at his seething best
when addressing reporters under the Vault's stands. Milbury was
incensed by what he depicted as a runaround by Rich Winter, agent
for Stefan, who was picked No. 1 overall by Atlanta. Stefan had two
concussions during the season while playing with the Long Beach Ice
Dogs of the IHL, and Milbury said he never could get a documented
answer from Stefan or Winter about the center's neurological
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury labeled Winter a ``disgrace,'' said his actions were
``despicable,'' and accused him of ``scurrilous behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the diatribe, Milbury spotted a familiar face
among the Boston media, interrupted his salty soliloquy, and said,
``How do you think I'm doin'?''
</P>
<P>
   Twins, trades, and a tirade. What could be better?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 0217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
