r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-SPORTS-TEX     06-27 1765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-SPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROG HEAVEN: TCU WAS FRUGAL BUT FEROCIOUS IN '50S FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About midday on an autumn afternoon in 1954, a train made an
unscheduled stop in Norman, Okla., and discharged a rather unusual
cargo. Hopping off the train at a remote siding a few hundred yards
from the Oklahoma Sooners' massive stadium was the TCU football
team, running a bit late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got off the train, carrying all our gear, and started
walking toward the stadium,'' recalls Buddy Dike, TCU's fullback.
``It was two oat fields away. We crossed those fields, climbed one
or two fences _ I don't remember which _ and walked into the
stadium, which was packed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma had already finished its warmups, and we went into
the dressing room and put on our gear as fast as we could. We
nearly missed the kickoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting the Horned Frogs was a juggernaut on the verge of
back-to-back national championships and in the midst of a historic
47-game winning streak. Never in that entire span did Bud
Wilkinson's legendary Sooners stand as close to defeat as they did
that day.
</P>
<P>
   With a sophomore-laden team _ the second in the 14-year tenure
of a folksy coach named Othol ``Abe'' Martin _ the Frogs rocked the
Sooners back on their heels and stymied the OU option with a weird
4-4 defense concocted by the athletic director, former coach Dutch
Meyer. Two long fourth-quarter punt returns by Buddy Leake finally
delivered a 21-16 win to the Big Red.
</P>
<P>
   TCU lost, in part, because captain Johnny Crouch informed the
officials that Ken Wineburg had trapped _ not caught _ an end-zone
pass that had already been ruled a touchdown. It was '50s football,
and the Frogs would beat you square or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   It was an era in which TCU produced nine All-Americans and five
nationally ranked teams, including four in the Top 10 and one
(1955) ranked fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very different era, and a much simpler one,'' says Frank
Windegger, a sophomore on that '54 team who subsequently spent 40
years as coach and administrator at TCU, including 24 as AD.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the two biggest things around here then were TCU
football and the Fort Worth Cats baseball team,'' Windegger
recalls. ``Around the state, all the news coverage was about the
Southwest Conference. There was no professional football in Texas,
and television had not become a major factor. Schools ran their
entire operation on gate receipts, and budgets were well under $1
million. Donor money was not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, it was the one-platoon era, which meant that the
(smaller) private schools could compete equally.''
</P>
<P>
   A salient aspect of the program was an impressive nonconference
record against a collection of national heavies, including twin
20-7 wins by the '54 team against Rose Bowl-bound Southern
California and Eastern power Penn State, led by the first two black
players to perform in Amon Carter Stadium _ Lenny Moore and
Roosevelt Grier.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's first team in '53 lost a 26-19 decision to defending
national champion Michigan State, which went on to win the Rose
Bowl. And Ohio State's Rose Bowl champions had to share the '57
national title with Auburn because of one blemish _ an 18-14 loss
to TCU.
Ever-frugal
</P>
<P>
   TCU's accomplishments came frugally _ the Frogs negotiated oat
fields and fences, Dike recalls, ``Because Dutch always had this
deal about putting us on a train when we traveled and having us
spend the night on the train so he could save hotel money. But in
this case, the train was two hours late leaving Fort Worth, and he
had to talk the conductor into putting us off on a siding.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also accomplished through skillful recruiting and the
remarkable character of Martin _ the ``Jacksboro Philosopher'' _ a
man full of pithy warmth and wisdom whose standard promo of an
impending big game was, ``Aw, we gonna have us a sheep-shearin' out
here come Saturday, yew bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Expressing his philosopy of command in a letter to Windegger
years later, Martin wrote, ``There is never much happiness to be
found in a program of tough discipline, where all are nobodies
except the head man.''
</P>
<P>
   Another '54 soph, Chuck Curtis, was a widely sought quarterback
from Paris who committed to TCU and then began having second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma was offering me some things, and I pretty much
decided to go there, when Coach Martin showed up at my house,''
Curtis recalled. ``We went out and sat in a swing on the front
porch to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he says, `Chuck-a-Luck, you remember that the last time we
talked, you said you were coming to TCU?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `Yeah, coach, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``And he slaps me on the knee and says, `Well, good, I just
wanted to make sure we were straight on that.' And he gets up and
gets back in his car and drives off ... leaving me sitting there on
the porch, swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in that class was a halfback from Rusk that TCU had taken
on the word of assistant Allie White, who said he had good moves _
on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Jim Swink became the most devastating offensive weapon
in college football, averaging 8.2 yards per carry while rushing
for 1,283 yards and scoring 20 touchdowns, including a 235-yard
effort in a 47-20 rout of Texas. He finished second in the voting
for the Heisman Trophy, leading TCU to a 9-1 season and the SWC
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a little ol' rubber-legged outfit that nobody can
catch,'' said Abe, when questioned about his star.
`Hurricane Game'
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, TCU harbored dreams of a national title. But on a dark
afternoon in College Station, they blew away in a storm.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as a showdown of unbeatens _ TCU was 3-0 with a No. 4
national ranking, Texas A&AMP;M was unbeaten with a tie _ it has
instead been remembered as the ``Hurricane Game'' for a bizarre
gale that struck in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   TCU threatened repeatedly, held a wide statistical edge, and
lost, 7-6, when the Aggies finally mustered an 80-yard,
fourth-quarter drive. By that time, the Frogs had missed two field
goals, had a TD called back, lost a fumble at the A&AMP;M 2, and thrown
an interception in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   As TCU launched its first drive, the early afternoon sky had
turned pitch black. Rain _ and then hail _ was falling in
horizontal sheets, the light standards at Kyle Field were swaying
like palm trees, and small aircraft at the nearby airport were
being overturned. Most of the capacity crowd of 42,000 was huddled
under the stands, and the wind, Swink recalled, ``was so strong you
had to turn your head to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of it all, TCU hammered at the A&AMP;M goal.
Ultimately, the game hinged on two disputed plays, when the Frogs _
to this day _ say Swink scored and the officials said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one, I led the play through the hole and wound up lying in
the end zone,'' Dike says. ``Swink was lying on top of me,
clutching my shirt tail. The official closest to the play signaled
touchdown _ but another one, with rain splattering his glasses so
he couldn't even see, came running up and said no score.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis figured he could have saved everyone the trouble by
calling a bootleg on the second play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were stacked to stop Swink, and I could have walked into
the end zone,'' he said. ``But I was afraid to change the play
because the hail was bouncing off our helmets so hard that no one
could hear me.''
</P>
<P>
   With A&AMP;M on probation, the second-place Frogs consoled
themselves with a Cotton Bowl victory over a Syracuse team led by
Jim Brown. Rebuilding in '57, they upset Ohio State in a game
fueled by Jim Shofner's 90-yard punt return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that when we came off the field in that game, those
people up there were cheering us,'' recalls Hunter Enis. ``They
were just great fans who appreciated someone playing a good game.''
A green pea called Lilly
</P>
<P>
   As the starting quarterback in '58, Enis directed the Frogs to
an 8-2 season, an SWC title, and _ unsuspected by anyone at the
time _ what has been their last Cotton Bowl appearance, a scoreless
tie with Air Force on a muddy field.
</P>
<P>
   In moments of stress, Enis was often comforted by old pal
Sherrill Headrick, a ferocious guard-linebacker who occasionally
hummed the Lone Ranger theme while chasing down ball-carriers.
Before a big game, he would drape a fatherly arm over the
quarterback's shoulders and say, ``Remember, we got this game won _
unless you mess it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs also displayed a large, mobile sophomore tackle named
Bob Lilly, fetched from Oregon by a recruiting letter from Allie
White.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a big ol' green pea,'' said Abe, ``but he'll stand in
there for you like a picket fence.''
</P>
<P>
   More like a bridge abutment. Lilly, a 1960 All-American and
eventual Pro Football Hall of Fame selectee, grew up in
Throckmorton, but the family had moved to Oregon because of a
severe drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we left Throckmorton, there were only about 1,200
people left, and we just couldn't make it,'' Lilly recalled. ``but
I wanted to play for TCU, so when the letter came I grabbed the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a freshman, I was 1,700 miles away from my parents,
and my dad had a heart attack. He eventually recovered, but it was
pretty rough for a while. Abe just took me under his wing like I
was one of his own kids, and became like a second father to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved playing for Abe, and later for Tom Landry. They were
very much alike _ two gentlemen, good for their word, who had
tremendous character and integrity. I learned a lot about life from
each of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for a time as ``The Purple Cloud'' after landing on an
unfortunate quarterback in an end zone that had been dusted with
purple chalk, Lilly also became a figure of awe on campus after
holding up the rear end of a car while a student without a jack
replaced a flat tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, it was just a little ol' Renault,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Lilly, All-Americans Don Floyd and Jack Spikes, and swift
halfback Harry Moreland, the '59 Frogs went 8-2, closing with seven
consecutive wins and a No. 7 national ranking.
</P>
<P>
   The final image of TCU's decade of greatness is that of Moreland
running 56 yards on a field recently cleared of ice with the score
that felled previously unbeaten Texas, 14-9. The Frogs shared the
title with Texas and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, three professional football teams arrived in
Texas, and the NCAA soon passed legislation that would do away with
the one-platoon system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Abe telling me at the time,'' Lilly said, ``that
this would be end of the private schools.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
