<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-SPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
 
THE FIRST TIME: WHAT WAS NEW IN THE 1950s 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
The first time Shot clock in basketball: The NBA adopted a
24-second shot clock for the 1954-55 season on the advice of
Syracuse Nationals owner Danny Biasone. The goal? Increase the
action, and the scoring, which it did. ``It was the single most
important rule change in the last 50 years,'' Boston Celtics
president Red Auerbach said. Celtics star Bob Cousy said, ``I think
it saved the NBA at that time. It allowed the game to breathe and
progress.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two-platoon football: On Jan. 20, 1950, the modern era of
professional football began when the NFL approved free
substitution, paving the way for two-platoon football and
specialization. Two-way players were still common throughout much
of the '50s, but gradually dwindled until becoming all but extinct
in 1962, when Philadelphia's Chuck Bednarik _ the last full-time
two-way player _ retired.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated: On Aug. 16, 1954, the sports magazine
debuted. It was aimed at the American middle-class consumer and the
budding TV sports spectator. The magazine reflected a move from
active participation to spectator status for many Americans. It
also became a leader in investigative and serious reporting of the
sports scene.
</P>
<P>
   The American Football League: On Aug. 14, 1959, Dallas
millionaire Lamar Hunt brought six other wealthy men to Chicago to
discuss the formation of a new pro football league to compete with
the established NFL. Eight days later, the formation of the AFL was
announced, with franchises in Dallas, Houston, Denver, Minneapolis,
Los Angeles and New York and play scheduled to begin in 1960. Two
more teams _ Buffalo and Boston _ would be added later in the year,
and the Minnesota franchise was replaced by Oakland. The league's
first draft _ the first shot in a long and bitter war that
eventually ended in a merger _ was held on Nov. 22. It lasted 33
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Face protection: Facemasks on football helmets were introduced
in the early part of the decade, evolving from a single bar to a
clear plastic shield to multiple bars. By the end of the '50s,
facemasks were standard equipment. On Nov. 1, 1959, Montreal's
Jacques Plante became the first NHL goalie to wear a mask as part
of his regular equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Widening the free-throw lane: Because of the increasing
dominance of big men such as George Mikan, the NBA widened the
free-throw lane from 6 to 12 feet for the 1951-52 season in order
to move the taller players farther from the basket. College
basketball followed suit for the 1956-57 season.
</P>
<P>
   The run-and-shoot: Four wide receivers might seem like a modern
concept, but it was first used by the Los Angeles Rams of the early
'50s. The Rams split halfbacks Elroy Hirsch and Glenn Davis wide
along with ends Tom Fears and Vitamin T. Smith to take advantage of
strong-armed quarterbacks Norm Van Brocklin and Bob Waterfield.
Using the wide-open offense, the Rams won the 1951 NFL title. On
Sept. 28, 1951, Van Brocklin passed for 554 yards, a single-game
record that still stands.
</P>
<P>
   TV blackouts: After the Los Angeles Rams televised all of their
games in 1950, attendance dropped by 50 percent. When the Rams
blacked out their home games in 1951, attendance doubled. NFL
commissioner Bert Bell became convinced that the league needed to
act as a single negotiating unit when TV contracts were involved.
When the league owners made him director of NFL television in 1952,
he instituted a leaguewide blackout rule covering teams' home
games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 0225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0996 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLDRAFT-BRUINS-B     06-27 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BANKING ON BOYNTON 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-BRUINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins worked on moving up in the NHL draft at the
FleetCenter Saturday but remained at No. 21 and chose defenseman
Nick Boynton of the Memorial Cup-champion Ottawa 67s.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of factors in Boynton's favor, but there are
also some negatives. Bruins assistant general manager Mike
O'Connell said the team weighed all the pros and cons and went with
Boynton, hoping he will provide help in training camp this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Boynton, a 20-year-old native of Nobleton, Ontario, who was the
MVP of this year's Memorial Cup _ the championship of Canadian
junior hockey _ originally was drafted ninth overall in 1997 by the
Washington Capitals. However, Washington couldn't come to terms
with the 6-foot-2-inch, 210-pounder, haggling over a three-year
pact worth $1.4 million, so Capitals management gave the Chicago
Blackhawks permission to negotiate with Boynton just before last
March's trade deadline. No deal was made, and Boynton went back
into the draft pool.
</P>
<P>
   Boston believes he's two years closer to playing than the
18-year-olds available at No. 21. Also, Boynton could play in
Providence if he didn't make the big club, while 18-year-olds would
have to return to their junior teams.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem regarding Boynton, however, was an off-ice
incident April 25 outside a bar called Stoney's in Byward Market in
Ottawa. Boynton and teammate Mark Bell were charged with assault,
accused of beating up a cab driver.
</P>
<P>
   Published reports in Ottawa, which Boynton Saturday termed
``wrong,'' said the cab driver, sitting outside the bar, heard a
thump against his vehicle. Bell and Boynton then got into the cab,
according to reports, and the driver refused to take them anywhere
because he believed they were the ones who hit his car. A fight
reportedly ensued between Bell and the cab driver, and Bell was
arrested. Boynton, who left the scene before police arrived,
reportedly was later identified by witnesses and told that if he
didn't turn himself in, he would be arrested at his home. Another
version of the story, put forth by a source from Ottawa Saturday,
was that Boynton actually went to the aid of Bell after Bell and
the cabbie began fighting and other cab drivers jumped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much all been taken care of,'' explained Boynton.
``That's not something I have to worry about anymore. It was
something to learn from. I'm pretty sure (all charges) have been
dropped.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said the incident was investigated by the team and the
Bruins are satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, it's not a major issue to us,'' said
O'Connell. ``We're just happy to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Boynton had 11 goals and 59 points in 51 games last season for
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a terrific defenseman,'' said O'Connell. ``For
us, he was probably the best defenseman who was available in the
draft. He was the Memorial Cup MVP, a first-round pick a couple of
years ago, and he's two years closer to playing than most of these
other kids. With the depth we have on the blue line, we feel he'll
get a chance to play this year for us. If not, he'll play in
Providence, which is a huge plus for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to take care of my own end first and offense is
second,'' said Boynton, who received his Bruins sweater at the
podium from Ray Bourque. ``If there's a hit, I take it. I try to
play two ways the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the draft, he said, ``It's a lot better the second
time around. I'm in awe. I didn't know where I was going to go, and
to go here is just a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' pick was met with great hostility by the Blackhawks,
who planned to take Boynton at No. 23. ``We'll see how tough Harry
is going to be,'' said GM Bob Murray. ``If he gets that (the new
cap maximum of $1,025,000), Harry Sinden should be shot. I'm sick
of hearing, `Harry Sinden this' and `Harry Sinden that.' It's about
time Harry Sinden backed up his words. If you're going to talk,
he'd better back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of Murray's comments, Sinden smiled and said he agreed
he should be shot if he offered Boynton the cap maximum.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' Sinden said, ``I'm not worrying about being shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said Boynton wouldn't have been there in the 23d spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Chicago) wouldn't have got him anyway,'' said Sinden.
``Philly was going to take him anyway (at 22).''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will maintain the same philosophy they always have
when it comes to salary negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do what's proper and if it's not enough, we won't sign
him,'' said Sinden. ``When you run the risk of putting yourself
back in the draft, you run certain risks as a player. Agents should
know that. That's the risk he ran. He was drafted ninth and then
with two years more experience, he was drafted later.''
</P>
<P>
   Boynton felt Chicago and Washington didn't make enough of an
effort to sign him. ``The deal from Chicago that was offered to me
wasn't fair for where I went,'' said Boynton. ``I just want a fair
deal. It's not about money. I just want a fair deal and I'm sure it
will be worked out with the Bruins. Washington said they didn't
have the money to sign me. Whether that's true or they just didn't
like me, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to be ready for this year. I've played four years in
junior and this year we won the Memorial Cup and that's pretty much
it for me in junior. I'd like to make the step right away. I'm
pretty confident that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, with the 56th pick, the Bruins took
20-year-old center Matt Zultek. Zultek was another player put back
into the draft because he wasn't able to come to terms by the June
1 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Zultek, who was not in attendance Saturday, was taken No. 15
overall by the Kings in 1997. Although Los Angeles general manager
Dave Taylor went to the wire trying to make a deal, he wasn't
successful. Zultek, a 6-foot-4-inch, 222-pounder, played on the 67s
with Boynton last season and had 33 goals and 66 points in 56
games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 0226EDT &QL; 
