<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS WORKS OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Center fielder Jim Edmonds shagged fly balls in the
outfield at Edison Field on Saturday afternoon but warned, ``It's
very early'' in his recovery from surgery on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked out Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like starting spring training,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's workout was conducted by Angels part-time coach Sam
Suplizio. Suplizio, whose specialty is working with outfielders,
had Edmonds working on getting good jumps as the ball came off the
bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the time he has not been playing, his instincts are
still sharp,'' Suplizio said. ``And he worked very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds had surgery on April 19 and isn't expected back until
mid-August at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Suplizio was in the news recently when he was banned from the
Angels dugout permanently by the league. Teams are allowed five
coaches on the bench during games, but the rule hadn't been
strictly enforced, allowing Suplizio to make selected trips with
the team.
</P>
<P>
   But in Toronto on the last trip, Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi
told Suplizio he wasn't going to allow the Angels to have an extra
coach that day. When the American League got word of the story,
they announced the five-coach rule would be strictly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 35 years in the game, it hurts,'' said Suplizio, who was
still able to crack a joke. ``But I'm getting a mask made.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill update: Ken Hill's status for his next start won't be
decided until today when throws on the side and has his inflamed
right elbow re-evaluated. But he will not start Monday against the
Rangers, his normal turn in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it will be Chuck Finley, who will pitch on three days
rest. Tuesday's starter will either be Hill or a replacement from
the minors. Mike Fhyrie has the best numbers, but he pitched
Friday. Jarrod Washburn, who pitched well against the Rangers last
season, is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Outfielder Matt Luke had an MRI on Saturday, which
revealed a partial muscle tear in his right rib cage. He is
expected to be placed on the disabled list today.... Pitcher Jack
McDowell, recovering from shoulder surgery Feb. 2, threw a
four-inning simulated game Saturday and felt fine. He'll pitch
another simulated game Wednesday....
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game was billed as ``Turn ahead the clock night at
Edison Field.'' Both teams wore futuristic uniforms, supposedly
representing the year 2021.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels wore bright red jerseys with the new logo taking up
the entire front of the jersey. Said one Angels player: ``All we
need are red bottoms and we have the perfect pair of pajamas.''...
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina is back from injury, and even though
he's off to a slow start offensively (2 for 10 going into
Saturday's game), his presence in the lineup is making a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   With DiSarcina in the lineup, players like Jeff Huson and Andy
Sheets are back where they belong _ coming off the bench and
contributing late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Huson had the game-winning hit Friday and began a late rally
Tuesday in Seattle. Sheets made a standout defensive play in the
ninth inning of Tuesday's game in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing what they're supposed to do, manager Terry
Collins said. ``And it helps that these guys got a lot of playing
time when Gary was out.''...
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and A's play the final game of their three-game
series today at 5:05 p.m. Steve Sparks (2-5, 5.02 ERA) will start
for Anaheim against Oakland's Kenny Rogers (4-2, 3.80). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
