<HEADLINE>
SUMMERALL FORESAW GREATNESS FOR LOMBARDI, LANDRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mid-1950s, New York Giants head coach Jim Lee Howell may
have had the easiest job in the NFL. His top offensive assistant
was legend-in-the-making Vince Lombardi. Heading his defense was
another future Hall of Fame coach, Tom Landry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing the head coach did was look at his watch to see
how long before practice was over,'' former Giants player Pat
Summerall recalled. ``He didn't coach much, but with those two guys
around he didn't need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell hired Lombardi and Landry soon after taking the Giants
job in 1954 _ Landry was a player-coach that season _ and by 1956,
they had turned a 3-9 team into an NFL champion. New York also
played for the title in 1958 and '59, losing both times to
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   After the '58 season, Lombardi left for Green Bay, where he won
five NFL championships and the first two Super Bowls. The Super
Bowl trophy is named after Lombardi. Landry moved to the expansion
Dallas Cowboys in 1960 and helped build one of the most successful
franchises in sports history over the next three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were two totally different personalities,S Summerall
said. RLandry was so unreadable. You never knew where you stood
with Landry. With Lombardi, you knew instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landry would come in and tell you, `Here's what you're going
to do. Do it my way and we'll win.' And he was usually right.
Lombardi was such a teacher, probably the best teacher I ever had
in anything, not just football. He knew his subject so thoroughly.
You could see he was headed for greatness. Both he and Landry. You
knew they were going places.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lombardi had such command. Before my first practice with the
Giants I went into the offensive team meeting. Some guy was trying
to call roll, but he couldn't get anyone quiet. I was sitting next
to Charley Conerly and we were kind of laughing about it. Then this
other man walked in and just cleared his throat and the whole room
fell silent. I whispered to Conerly, `Who is that?' and he said,
`That's Lombardi, and you'll find out who he is soon enough.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
