<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGEL-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN UGLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ You've heard of winning ugly?
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' futuristic jerseys that were part of a ``Turn ahead
the clock night'' promotion Saturday night at Edison Field
certainly won't be featured in fashion magazines any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   And although the jerseys might have strained the eyes of 29,957
in the seats, the Angels felt good inside after beating the Oakland
A's 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   It was their fifth win in their last six games and moved them to
within 7{ games of the AL West-leading Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   One Angels player said a matching pair of red pants would have
made the uniform a ``perfect pair of pajamas.'' Another said the
pants clashed because ``pinstripes will be out in 2021.''
</P>
<P>
   What looked good to the Angels was Gary DiSarcina's two-out,
two-strike, RBI single to right field in the sixth that tied the
game at 4-4 and capped a rally from a 4-0 deficit. And Darin
Erstad's spectacular diving catch of Miguel Tejada's liner to left
in the top of the seventh with the potential go-ahead run on second
base.
</P>
<P>
   And Garret Anderson's RBI single in the seventh that gave the
Angels a 5-4 lead and turned out to be the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   There also was the pitching of relievers Mike Magnante (31/3
scoreless innings) and Shigetoshi Hasegawa to set up closer Troy
Percival (21st save) after starter Tim Belcher left the game with a
sprained finger after four innings. Belcher went for X-rays after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys did a tremendous job,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said, ``starting with Mike Magnante. To come in and have to
shut them down like he did _ he did a tremendous job. I really
think that's the ballgame right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher tagged out Ryan Christenson in a play at the plate,
ending a rundown to close out the fourth inning. He was initially
diagnosed with a sprained pinky finger on his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   While Belcher was knocked out of the game by injury, it didn't
hurt the Angels' chances Saturday. Signs that Belcher was off his
game were evident early. With two out in the first, Belcher fell
behind in the count to Ben Grieve, then grooved a 3-1 pitch that
Grieve sent into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Belcher walked three batters but got help
from his defense.
</P>
<P>
   With two on and nobody out, Mike MacFarlane hit one to the
center-field fence. But Anderson made a leaping catch and doubled
up Matt Stairs at first via a relay by second baseman Randy
Velarde. The Angels nearly got a triple play out of it, but the
throw to second to get John Jaha was late.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher didn't escape so easily in the third inning, yielding a
three-run homer to Jason Giambi for a 4-0 A's lead. Belcher worked
his way out of a fourth-inning jam but couldn't make it out for the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels climbed back in on an RBI single by Velarde in the
third inning and a two-run fourth, highlighted by Steve Decker's
RBI double and Orlando Palmeiro's RBI single to cut their deficit
to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   That set up the game-tying and game-winning hits by DiSarcina
and Anderson, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's still in spring-training shape,'' Collins said of
DiSarcina. ``But this guy has a knack of getting big hits. He just
does it. I wish I knew what his thought process is. He just gets
big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's hit came only a week or so after he was mired in a
0-for-30 slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just come out and keep playing,'' Anderson said. ``You go
about things the right way and good things will happen
eventually.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
