<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA THRASHES AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-THRASHERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ted Turner _ surprise, surprise _ once again got top
billing.
</P>
<P>
   New to the National Hockey League, enamored with the relatively
unknown Georgia state bird, the thrasher, Turner already had gotten
his way by naming his newly hatched team the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Turner was, he probably just shrugged when word out of
the FleetCenter was that Atlanta had acquired the top pick in
Saturday's NHL draft. Turner, after all, has been on top before.
</P>
<P>
   But two men at the FleetCenter did much more than shrug Saturday
afternoon. Patrik Stefan, the Thrashers' top choice, understandably
was ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, you know, it's unbelievable,'' said the 18-year-old
center from the Czech Republic who came to the United States two
years ago with perhaps five words of English in his vocabulary. ``I
am so excited, so happy to be No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan had bolted up to the FleetCenter podium, sporting the
widest of smiles. The smiles of Atlanta vice president and general
manager Don Waddell and president Harvey Schiller were nearly as
wide. A mere 10 minutes earlier, Atlanta had completed a complex
three-way trade with Tampa Bay and Vancouver to make all this
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Standing off to the side during this time was another man, an
investment trader, a long-time Los Angeles Kings season-ticket
holder, a fan of the Long Beach Ice Dogs of the International
Hockey League and a friend of Ice Dogs coach John Van Boxmeer.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Robert Butkus, barely could control his happiness. He
has helped ease Stefan into the American culture by housing the
prospect over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time I've known him, he's been totally dedicated to
this moment in his life,'' said Butkus. ``To play in the NHL . . .
that was his entire focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer had asked his friend to house his newest foreign
player, one with ``only a little plastic bag with him and that was
it,'' said Butkus. ``He had that plastic suitcase, his clothes in
it, and that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized he was (17) and if he immersed himself in the
language he would pick it up, and he did. He just learned by
conversation. I spent hundreds of hours with him just talking about
hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan learned about the trade that made him No. 1 just before
the announcement at the FleetCenter. ``I was so nervous,'' he said.
``It comes true. It was my dream to be No. 1. Atlanta can be a
great team. They will be a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Burke, the Vancouver general manager, had engineered the
three-way deal so the Canucks could obtain the talented Sedin
twins, Daniel and Henrik. Burke talked from midnight to 3 a.m. with
Atlanta and Tampa Bay, slept for three hours, and then began the
talks anew at 6. The deal finally left Atlanta with the top choice,
Vancouver with the next two picks, and Tampa Bay with the fourth,
which the Lightning packaged in another trade with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Stefan nor Waddell was concerned by the player's two
concussions suffered last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not scared about, you know, going to corner,'' said
Stefan. ``Lots of persons have concussions; they come back. That
are still great players.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``That's what I be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
