<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-SPORTS-'50S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOONERS WERE BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two-time All-America tackle Jim Weatherall was the most
dependable of kickers, but a misfire on an extra point on Oct. 7,
1950, against Texas A&AMP;M nearly cost the Oklahoma Sooners much more
than a game.
</P>
<P>
   On the line was a 22-game winning streak, a national
championship and the opening act to becoming the most dominant team
in any sport during the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   After Weatherall's miss, the Sooners kicked off to the Aggies
with a little more than three minutes left and trailing 28-27.
Oklahoma held the visiting Aggies and forced a punt with 1 minute,
46 seconds left. OU quarterback Claude Arnold then led a 69-yard
drive of machine-like efficiency to the end zone for the victory.
Oklahoma coach Bud Wilkinson called the game the greatest comeback
he had ever seen. It was the key victory in OU's first national
football championship season.
</P>
<P>
   The final polls, voting Oklahoma as No. 1, had already been
announced when the Bear Bryant-led Kentucky Wildcats upended the
Sooners in the 1951 Sugar Bowl, 13-7, ending the Sooners' 31-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   That streak paled in comparison to a 47-game mark the Sooners
racked up from the third game of the 1953 season through the eighth
game of the 1957 season, when Notre Dame upset OU. Oklahoma also
was voted national champion in 1955 and 1956.
</P>
<P>
   OU finished the '50s with a 93-10 record (.902 winning
percentage) and a 58-1 mark against conference opponents. The only
conference loss was to Nebraska, 25-21, on Halloween, 1959.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
