</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY LOVES RAYMOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bruins president and general manager Harry Sinden
stepped onto the NHL Draft 1999 stage Saturday to a
less-than-rousing reception.
</P>
<P>
   Then he quickly turned the jeers to cheers.
</P>
<P>
   It was simple, really. He announced that the team and the
FleetCenter were dedicating the day _ the 20th anniversary of the
draft that made Ray Bourque a Bruin _ to the captain.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque highlights took over the scoreboard screen above the
floor. Bourque scoring. Bourque passing. Bourque checking. Bourque
diving head-first to catch up to and break up a play. Bourque with
Bobby Orr. And Bourque taking the No. 7 shirt off his back and
handing it to Phil Esposito so it might hang in the Garden and then
FleetCenter rafters.
</P>
<P>
   And then Gord Kluzak, the No. 1 overall pick in 1982 and master
of ceremonies, introduced Bourque and he came to the microphone
through a door cut in the black backdrop to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque addressed the draftees-to-be and their guests. He
recalled his draft being done over the phone, not in front of
thousands of fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great ride,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Have a passion for the game, he reminded all. And keep that
passion for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never forget the passion,'' he said. ``That's what keeps me
going.''
</P>
<P>
   And going. And going. And going.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love you, Ray,'' shouted one fan.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody loves Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   With that he was gone, to return a couple of hours later to more
cheers to announce the Bruins' first pick of defenseman Nick
Boynton at No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   There remains little doubt Bourque prefers facing a crowded
crease with a stick to facing a crowd with a mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate that,'' he said in a hallway between appearances on
stage. ``Give me a hockey stick and I'll play as long as you want
me to play and I'll have fun. But give me a mike . . . I'm a guy
who sweats a lot, but I don't have to be moving to sweat with a
mike in my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, just back with his family from Aruba for the occasion,
then took on several subjects:
</P>
<P>
   --On the NHL's deciding to play four-on-four in overtime to
lessen the number of games ending in ties: ``I don't like it. As
far as I'm concerned, I don't like any kind of changes. I wish
they'd wait until I'm out of the game before they make any kind of
changes. Four-on-four might open it up a little more, but if they
want to end games fast, just have a shootout.'' You get the decided
impression Bourque, always the traditionalist, would dislike that
even more.
</P>
<P>
   --On Brett Hull's controversial
was-he-or-was-he-not-illegally-in-the-crease goal that gave the
Dallas Stars the Stanley Cup: ``I thought of Washington, that was
my first thought,'' said Bourque, talking of the Bruins' goal that
was taken away in the playoffs a year ago when Tim Taylor's toe was
in the crease. ``The rule, it's so tough to have something like
that happen. The only reason a goal should be called back is if you
bump the goalie or cause interference. Other than that, it's goal,
goal, goal.'' He likes it that the NHL has ruled that such
man-in-the-crease situations no longer will be subject to video
review.
</P>
<P>
   --On Group 2 free agent goalie Byron Dafoe, whom the Bruins are
working on signing: ``He's the ace for us. He was our MVP for last
year, the Vezina finalist. We definitely have to sign Byron. I
talked to him the other day and it seems like they have gotten off
to a pretty good start. I'm optimistic and I think everyone knows
for us to be the team we want to be and keep going forward, Bysie's
a big part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   --On his personal plans, which continue to be to play out the
final year of his contract next year and then decide whether to
play more: ``It certainly makes things easier when you have fun and
win hockey games and have success. Everything is a lot more upbeat.
For now, I'm going to focus on getting ready for this year and play
this year and hopefully have a great year. And then, at this time
next year, we'll probably be talking about the following year and
what's going to happen with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
