<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-WANVIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANVIG SLIPS INTO HANDS OF BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins selected Kyle Wanvig of the Kootenay Ice of
the Western Hockey League in the third round of the NHL draft
Saturday at the FleetCenter, and the Wanvig gang whooped it up.
</P>
<P>
   Wanvig, a 6-foot-2-inch, 204-pound right wing, had slipped in
the eyes of the draftniks as last season progressed, so his
selection in an early round likely was a relief.
</P>
<P>
   In the Central Scouting Service's midterm report he was ranked
No. 19 among North Americans and by the final ranking he was No. 57
in the list, which does not include goaltenders or Europeans.
Saturday, he was picked No. 89 overall.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth round, the Bruins took Jaako Harikkala, an
18-year-old defenseman from Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins director of scouting Scott Bradley said the team sees
Wanvig as a ``projected power forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He shows you flashes,'' Bradley said. ``We want consistency
and we want him to dedicate himself to becoming a player. If he
does that, we could have a pretty good player who could crack our
lineup some day. He skates real well for a big guy and he has a
good frame already.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanvig was the first to bring up his season of underachieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a slow season this year and dropped off a bit,'' Wanvig
said. ``I just had a bit of trouble around the net scoring goals.
That's what I was supposed to do and I didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanvig had 17 goals and 12 assists in 62 games two years ago in
the WHL, and last season had 10 goals and 12 assists. He had 119
minutes in penalties and doesn't mind mixing it up.
</P>
<P>
   His ice time tailed off as the season went on and that made it a
little hard to evaluate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go in to see him some times and he'd get three or four
shifts,'' Bradley said. ``But then they played the Calgary Hitmen
in the playoffs and he was one of their better players. He picked
it up and they played him more minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Excited about being picked by the Bruins, Wanvig figures he'll
spend another year or two in juniors, but is looking forward to his
first professional camp this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to get a feel for it and make a good first
impression,'' he said. ``To have a good rookie camp and maybe stay
for the full camp. I'm just excited about going to camp right now.
Every kid dreams about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harikkala has been playing in the Finnish Elite league, and the
earliest he would be expected around these parts would be for camp
next summer, according to European scout Sven Svenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big, home-staying defenseman,'' Svenson said. ``He's a
good passer and moves the puck well. He's strong, 6-2 and over 200
pounds. We were surprised he was still around. Big defensemen
normally are very popular.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
