<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION BURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Revolution were weakened by injury, heat, and
humidity Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. But they gave a strong performance before
falling, 2-0, to the Dallas Burn, their first regulation-time
defeat since May 23.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams played confidently, but carelessly, leading to many
scoring opportunities. The Revolution hit the crossbar once and the
post twice, and the Burn scored in the 37th minute when Jorge
Rodriguez finished a Leonel Alvarez cross.
</P>
<P>
   But what promised to be a high-scoring game soon settled into a
battle of attrition as Dallas retreated into a defensive shell and
the Revolution spent the second half unsuccessfully probing for
openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas is a good team but I don't think they played better
than us,'' said Revolution midfielder Jair. ``Once they got ahead,
it was easier for them because we had to go forward and score. We
had our chances in the first half, but some guys got a little tired
in the second half. We lost and we've got to live with that and get
ready to beat New York at home next Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have earned 15 points in 15 matches, good enough
for third place in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Torres hit the crossbar in the 14th minute, and Joe-Max
Moore and Giovanni Savarese hit the post in the 24th and 41st
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who had four goals in his last four games, including one
for the US national team, drilled a free kick past Burn goalkeeper
Matt Jordan off the right post. Jordan inexplicably chased a
back-header to the corner flag midway through the first half,
leaving the goal wide open for Torres, but Torres's shot was
blocked for a corner.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn was under siege, but defensive midfielders Alvarez and
Chad Deering, plus Jason Kreis and Oscar Pareja, kept Dallas poised
in counterattack. After a throw-in, Alvarez played a combination
with Kreis, slipped a tackle, and penetrated to the end line to
cross to Rodriguez for the goal. Kreis hit the post seconds later.
The Revolution regrouped, but Savarese headed off the post and
Moore scuffed a point-blank opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, which played without starters Richard Goulooze
(Achilles' tendon) and John Harkes (hamstring), nearly lost Jair
after a menacing tackle from behind by Alvarez. They did, however,
lose Dan Calichman with a shin bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Dante Washington strained a right knee ligament and the Burn,
second place in the Western Conference, played the final 15 minutes
with only 10 men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disappointing loss,'' Moore said. ``We were in the
right spots but we couldn't finish. We made a couple of mistakes
and all of a sudden they were through. If you give those guys the
opportunity they will capitalize.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
