<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMARZO STAYS OUT OF TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE _ A.J. Dimarzo's strategy of running his own race paid
off.
</P>
<P>
   The Saugus resident avoided two ugly crashes to win the NASCAR
Super Late Model race Saturday night before a crowd of 4,101 at
Irwindale Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Dimarzo, running safely in third, watched leader Craig Rayburn
and second-place Ben Walker take each other out of the race and
Dimarzo took the lead and held off Brian Kelley for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is plenty of room to race here,'' Dimarzo said. ``I just
ran my race and stayed out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   T.K. Karvasek of North Hills won the 25-lap Super Stock feature
race, pulling away from Thousand Oaks' Doug McComb down the
straights. But Karvasek was disqualified, giving the victory to
McComb. In the 25-lap Legends feature race, Art Nevill passed Ben
Asquith with five laps to go for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Rayburn, from Simi Valley, led the Super Late Models with four
laps to go and Santa Clarita's Walker close behind. Rayburn says he
received ``a love tap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind getting bumped, but I do mind being bumped and
then have him throttled up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, 18, said Rayburn ``got loose.'' Walker said he was
already on the throttle and when Rayburn hit the brakes, he hit
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to have an accident,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, from Arleta, went from last to challenge Dimarzo for the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   On lap 19, Kelley tapped Scott Davidson into the turn 4 wall.
Top qualifier Greg Voigt went underneath Davidson and Brian Barron
landed on top of Voigt, bringing out a red flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfortunate that someone tried to do something he
couldn't do,'' Voigt said. His damaged car will probably have to be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Police were called in as the drivers nearly came to fisticuffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Mechanix Speed Truck Challenge finished at 11:09 p.m., nine
minutes after the curfew. Troy Green won the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
