<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CHILDREN-COX     06-27 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHILDREN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: with chart material Children's-TV-Data
 &HT;    Electronic Age Creating ``Vid Kids''
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American kids spend much more time per year in
front of electronic screens in their homes -- TV, computers and
video games -- than they spend in school, according to a new
national report on children and the media.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that nearly half of all homes with children
aged two to 17 have at least one television, a VCR, video game
equipment and a home computer. Three of every five kids aged 12-17
have a TV in their rooms. In homes with children, subscriptions to
the Internet are nearly as common as subscriptions to newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result researchers found more teenagers could name the
cartoon characters on the popular TV show ``The Simpsons'' than
could identify the Vice-President of the United States, Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although television is still dominant, with the introduction
of new media, young people are now spending an average of four and
a half hours every day sitting in front of a screen of some kind,''
said Jeffrey Stanger, Washington director of the Annenberg Public
Policy Center of the University of Pennsylvania. The data is found
in four reports that the center is releasing today at its fourth
annual Conference on Children and Television.
</P>
<P>
   The four and a half hours per day in front on a screen comes to
about 1,642 hours per year. The average American child spends about
1,000 hours per year in school, according to the U.S. Department of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The introduction of new media continues to transform the
environment in American homes with children,'' concludes the report
``Media in the Home,'' based on a national survey of parents and
children. ``Rather than displacing television as the dominant
medium, new technologies have supplemented it, resulting in an
aggregate increase in electronic media penetration and use by
America's use.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids spend about two and a half hours per day watching
television programs and another two hours with video games,
computers or the VCR, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Other findings: Home computers are now almost as common as cable
television subscriptions. The number of computer homes with
Internet access has doubled since 1996. Video games are available
in nine out of 10 homes with children -- either on home computers
or video game equipment such as Gameboys or both.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are so profound that, in its fourth year, the
Annenberg Center has renamed one report, ``Media in the Home''
rather than ``Television in the Home.'' This report is based on a
national random television survey in April and May of parents of
children aged two to 17 and a random sample of their 10 to 17 year
old children in homes with televisions. The margin of error was
plus or minus 2.9 percent in the parents survey and plus or minus
5.7 percent for the smaller sampling of kids.
</P>
<P>
   Parents opinions of children's television is at its lowest point
in the four years of the survey. Only 13.6 percent had a positive
view of programming for their children. However, the number of
parents who said they have established rules about TV viewing has
fallen from a high of about 69 percent in 1997 to about 62 percent
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming the influence of television, the study found that
while 93 percent of the 10 to 17 year-olds knew that ``The
Simpsons'' has characters named Homer, Bart and Maggie, only 63
percent could name Al Gore as the vice president. However, the
parents were also more familiar with ``The Simpsons'' -- with 84
percent correctly naming the TV show and 80 percent correctly
naming the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are also increasingly worried about their children's
exposure to the Internet. Although television still tops the list
of biggest media concerns, the Internet has surpassed music lyrics
as the second biggest worry. Two in five parents (19.8 percent)
named the Internet, up from 12.9 percent last year. For the first
time, fewer than half the parents (43.8 percent) were most
concerned about television, compared to 55.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed that more and more families are going online.
Indeed, in households with annual incomes over $75,000, about 72
percent have Internet connections, compared to 67 percent with
newspaper subscriptions. In all homes with children, 41 percent
have Internet connections and 48.5 percent have newspaper
subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   In a second study, ``The 1999 State of Children's Television
Report,'' the Annenberg researchers found that the quality of
children's television has begun to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found 1,324 programs for children available in a
week of all cable and broadcast channels in the Philadelphia
television market. That was a 12 percent increase over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The venue with the most children's programs was the Cartoon
Network with 269 shows aired over one week, followed by PBS
offerings (on four PBS stations) with 265 programs. Nickelodeon
came in third with 187 shows in a week,'' the researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   Basic cable channels air 55 percent of the children's
programming, followed by PBS stations with 20 percent and premium
cable with 11 percent. Only about four percent of the programs for
children aired on the major commercial networks -- ABC, CBS, NBC
and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the proportion of children's programs
containing no enriching material at all dropped to 25 percent from
48 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the improvement in children's television may be
attributed to the (Federal Communication Commission's) 'Three Hour
Rule','' said Amy B. Jordan, director of Annenberg's children's
television analysis. The rule requires broadcasters seeking
expedited license renewal to air at least three hours of
educational programming for children each week.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that virtually all commercial broadcast stations
are airing these programs at times when children are awake and in
the audience and that most of the programs do have educational
value. However, only 6 percent of programs for children are aired
during prime time in the evenings.
</P>
<P>
   The Annenberg Public Policy Center is a community of scholars at
the University of Pennsylvania that sponsors research and
conferences addressing public policy issues at the federal, state
and local level. It has several ongoing projects concerning the
media and society.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
