<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONKONG-MIGRANTS-BOS &LR;      06-27 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONKONG-MIGRANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING OVERRULES HONG KONG HIGH COURT'S IMMIGRANT RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In a move with profound implications both for the
autonomy of Hong Kong and for hundreds of thousands of divided
families, China's parliament Saturday overturned a controversial
supreme court ruling that would have allowed an estimated 1.6
million children to immigrate here from mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of would-be migrants demonstrated outside government
offices Saturday to protest the interference by Beijing in Hong
Kong law. Some families have been waiting more than 20 years for
their children to be allowed entry to Hong Kong, blaming red tape,
long waiting lists and sometimes corrupt practices by Chinese
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the human face of the controversy, however, is the
question of Hong Kong's judicial independence from China. Legal
activists, the local bar association and opposition legislators
denounced Saturday's the Chinese parliament's ``interpretation'' of
an earlier ruling by Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal as a dangerous
precedent undermining the promise of ``one country, two systems.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when China gained control of Hong Kong from Britain,
Beijing vowed that the freewheeling capitalist enclave would retain
autonomy on almost all matters, including legal issues, for at
least 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The first test of that promise has come with a now two-year
battle over who has the right to live in this prosperous territory.
Hong Kong's constitution, the Basic Law, grants the right to reside
here to all mainland-born children of permanent Hong Kong
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The local government argued in court that illegitimate children
and children born only after their parents acquired permanent
residency, 1.6 million people, according to government estimates,
should not share that right. Government leaders are terrified at
the possibility of a 25 percent jump over the next 13 years in Hong
Kong's population of 6.4 million. The government said the influx
would cost the territory $90 billion and strain schools, hospitals,
the economy, and social order.
</P>
<P>
   But the goverment lost its case in court, and turned to the the
Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress in
Beijing, which has the right to ``interpret'' Hong Kong's Basic
Law. The Standing Commmittee Saturday said Hong Kong's highest
court should have consulted with the committee before issuing its
verdict. The committee also said the court misunderstood the Basic
Law.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong legal advocates said Beijing's critique missed the
point, that Hong Kong judges were promised the right to interpret
local laws themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of the end of the rule of law in Hong
Kong,'' said an outraged Martin Lee, chairman of the leading
opposition Democratic Party and a prominent lawyer. In any court
case, he added, ``The government is telling the whole world that if
government wins, it's final, but if the government loses, it's not
final, because the government will then go to Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said Saturday's action dissolved any pretension that Hong
Kong is running its own affairs. ``It's impossible to think there
was no collusion'' between the Hong Kong government and Beijing.
``Of course they're working hand-in-glove.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tung Chee-hwa, a former shipping tycoon whom China
handpicked as Hong Kong's chief executive, defended his request for
a legal interpretation from Beijing as ``entirely legal and
constitutional. We treasure the rule of law as one of the most
important pillars of Hong Kong's success.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary for Justice Elsie Leung told reporters, ``You must
accept that there's a new constitutional order. . . . This is part
of our system: a higher authority overruling a lower authority.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hong Kong was a British colony, Leung said, whenever the
courts ruled against the government, it would lobby the legislature
to amend the law. ``Nobody ever complained that that was an erosion
of judicial independence.'' Since the return to Chinese rule, she
added, ``the local legislature has neither the power to interpret
nor amend the Basic Law.''
</P>
<P>
   Tung, the chief executive, also noted that newspaper surveys
show that a majority of Hong Kong residents support the
government's efforts to stop the feared influx of migrants.
``Everyone wants families to be reunited. We, in making a decision,
have to balance humanitarian concerns with the long-term interests
of our community as a whole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's ``interpretation'' from Beijing will not affect an
estimated 900 mainland Chinese who have proven their parentage and
who came to Hong Kong after the July 1, 1997, return to Chinese
rule. A a court ruling on Jan. 29 this year granted them the right
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Another 2,700 people who arrived during that period, but whose
claims have not yet been verified, will have to return to China or
have already returned, and their applications will be processed
``in due time,'' the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 1.6 million people who became eligible to live
here under the January court ruling, only those born out of wedlock
after their parents became permanent residents, roughly 170,000,
will retain that right, government officials said. The government
has never disputed the eligibility of an additional 98,000
mainlanders whose parents were married and had resident status.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not satisfy hundreds of would-be immigrants who
chanted slogans, waved signs, and briefly scuffled with police
outside government offices here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents are worried that we may now be deported,'' said
Chen Shui-chung, 22, who has overstayed her visitor's visa since
March 1998. Chen and her sister have been waiting 20 years in
China's Fujian province to join her father, and nine years to join
her mother in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no close relatives in China,'' she said. ``But our
parents cannot follow us back if we are forced to go, because they
have to make money to live, and with the economy as it is in China,
they can only do that here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
