<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN28-COX     06-27 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A new beginning in the end of entitlements
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Finally the Rehnquist court has rendered a decision
that will give its conservative majority a place in history. Like
it or not, the U.S. Supreme Court's recent ruling bolstered
federalism to a degree not undertaken since the New Deal era when
the court struck down much of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt's
national economic legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, Chief Justice William Rehnquist and his four
conservative colleagues _ Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas,
Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony Kennedy _ looked as if they might
continue to play with the moral agenda. I have always argued that
constricting individual liberties, as the socially conservative
agenda does, conflicts with traditional conservative principles. At
long last, though, the Rehnquist court spoke to the more important
framework of government instead of the details of moral issues that
have made the conservative majority look as if it were tinkering
instead of shaping democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, Kennedy said the federal government cannot, in
effect, treat states as provinces or corporations. It must treat
them with the respect due joint participants in a federal system.
The court ruled that state employees cannot sue the state without
its permission in its own courts _ and that Congress cannot totally
abrogate that sovereign principle.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean state workers in Maine had no remedy for the
failure of the state to pay them back wages they should receive
under a federal law. As Kennedy pointed out, the federal agency, in
this case the Labor Department, could have easily sued on behalf of
them in state court.
</P>
<P>
   Congress clearly has the power to declare a federal law binding
and enforceable in state court. Maine surely recognizes that, as do
all of the states. But if Congress can use state courts to make a
state cough up economic damages that lie within the power of a
federal agency to enforce, state sovereignty, the majority said, is
out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Although many will think the immediate outcome for the workers
is unfair, this is not the first time a case brought by people
concerned with their own interests has been used by the high court
to define a greater overarching constitutional principle. That was
also true when William Marbury felt his justice of the peace
commission had been wrongly snatched from him in 1801. The famous
case, Marbury vs. Madison, established the lasting principle that
only the Supreme Court has the right to declare acts of Congress
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy decision leaves unanswered questions: Does it mean
age discrimination laws or the Americans with Disabilities Act, if
allegedly violated by a state, can't be enforced by state employees
in state court?
</P>
<P>
   States' rights are important in our constitutional scheme,
though no one would return to the era when they were code words for
wrong decisions _ such as that in the famous Dred Scott case, in
which Chief Justice Roger Taney declared Congress could not bar
slavery.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy decision was the kind of bold mark a conservative
court should leave in the evolution of democracy. The liberal
Warren court marked the end of state school segregation and
confirmed the legalization of abortion. The Rehnquist court
declares that Congress does not have total power over the states,
however. A hundred years from now, scholars are likely to say the
decision was important to our federal system.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
