<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Searching for signs of survival in unforgiving Southwest
territory
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAJITAS, Texas _ My wife is skittish about wildlife along the
roadside, so as we drove we didn't discuss the matter of the
chihuahua herds.
</P>
<P>
   We'd read in the Desert Candle, a free publication picked up in
Alpine, about the ``stealthy, tiny but deadly'' feral chihuahuas of
the Big Bend area.
</P>
<P>
   Don't stop in the desert, it warned, not so much as to irrigate
a yucca, lest they amass: ``beasts capable of encircling any prey
and nibbling them to death from the bottom up.''
</P>
<P>
   Even minivans?
</P>
<P>
   The Candle, a dusty tongue in its cheek, is pulling our legs.
But you could easily imagine dogged ankle-high predators taking
over some of these these parts. No one else would challenge them.
</P>
<P>
   Even the camels gave up.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Civil War, the U.S. military tried patrolling the
border region by camel. The experiment got shelved because of the
war, with the camels left to roam. They'd all died off before the
turn of the century. Not tough enough, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Other wildlife thrive in Big Bend, mule deer and javelinas in
particular, say the parks people. This should give us new respect
for these creatures. It is merciless territory, depending on which
side of the equinox you're on.
</P>
<P>
   When we drove through Lajitas in the afternoon swelter, the lone
welcome was from a party of one, advertised as ``the world's only
beer-drinking goat.'' We didn't stay to visit him in his
chicken-wire quarters, assuming a goat's breath to be vile enough
on hay alone.
</P>
<P>
   Terlingua, home of the famous world chili cook-off, advertises a
ghost town in its midst. In heat like this _ 98 when I dared to
check _ one is challenged to decide which part of town is haunted
and which is just vacated.
</P>
<P>
   Think of those camel mounties. Though they had time to admire
the jagged croppings and auburn hues of Big Bend, one imagines a
whole lot of them in searing August wondering why in Hades we were
trying to hang onto this chunk of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred miles or so northeast are the ruins of abandoned Fort
McKavett. Now a state park with some of the quarters restored, it
sits as a stony sentinel above the San Saba valley, still waiting
for action.
</P>
<P>
   Its mission was to defend against Comanches and Apaches. When
the Civil War heated up, however, the fort was no more necessary
than a dromedary squadron. The troops were pulled _ those who
hadn't bolted into the desert already.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Parks and Wildlife literature cites ``isolation that
compelled bored soldiers to desert or recklessly spend their wages
in the bawdy houses of nearby Scabtown.''
</P>
<P>
   You've got something short of four-star accommodations when a
place called Scabtown makes your mouth water.
</P>
<P>
   The last detachments at Fort McKavett, after the war, were
federal Buffalo Soldiers, black troops suited for the task no doubt
by having seen indignities worse than this.
</P>
<P>
   Like any frontier, there is beauty out here, and there is misery
for the poorly suited, like the parched traveler whose freon is low
and who just wants a pallet and a Slurpee.
</P>
<P>
   A group called the Texas Camel Corps, based in Valley Mills,
will be recreating the 19th-century expeditions in Big Bend Ranch
State Park in July and August. You can call (915) 229-3416 to
reserve a hump.
</P>
<P>
   I will pass. I think about those camels of yore. What became of
their numbers? A hint may come from one of their points of origin
into Big Bend, from the expedition that led them through a place
called Dog Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Theory: They tried to retrace their steps back to blessed
Arabia. Whereupon the chihuahuas ate them.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinon page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
