u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRANDY28-COX     06-27 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANDY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brandy isn't down on touring anymore
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brandy came into the music business just wanting to be
down.
</P>
<P>
   If her 1994 self-titled debut sold a million copies, ``That
would be awesome!'' she exclaimed then, in typical 15-year-old
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   If some awards came along with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just die!''
</P>
<P>
   And if by chance the McComb, Miss., native happened to meet her
idol Whitney Houston _ ``Oh my God! Oh my God! Oh my God! I would
be in another world!''
</P>
<P>
   But, as the chorus of her first single insists, she basically
just wanted to be ``down'' with you, the listener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to just hear me,'' Brandy said earnestly in
November 1994, minutes after performing at Atlanta's Crim High
School. ``And then maybe, hopefully, like me.''
</P>
<P>
   A simple request _ to which audiences responded by buying 4
million copies of ``Brandy.'' ``I Wanna Be Down'' was the first of
what would be six consecutive Top 10 pop singles.
</P>
<P>
   And she didn't just get to meet Houston; they co-starred
together in a TV version of Rodgers and Hammerstein's
``Cinderella,'' ABC's most-watched movie in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was the teen star that started all of the interest
in teen stars now,'' says Gary Glenn of the Atlanta quintet Silk,
which is touring with Brandy and is managed by her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made people take us seriously,'' adds Atlanta teen
vocalist Monica.
</P>
<P>
   And now, at 20, throaty, Grammy Award-winning Brandy has decided
to return to the concert stage. In the meantime, she has become as
big a star on television (``Moesha'') and movie screens (``I Still
Know What You Did Last Summer'') as in music. Not so long ago she
vowed never to set foot on the concert stage again, reeling from
crowd reaction during her tour with Boyz II Men.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before beginning her first headlining tour, she agreed
to answer some questions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened?
</P>
<P>
   A: I really don't know. When I was on tour with Boyz II Men, I
had just come out. And it wasn't like I was comfortable with the
fans. Because it wasn't like they'd really come to see me. It's not
like this tour. My tour. You know, I hate saying I headline the
tour, because I don't want to make people feel like I did. So let's
just say I go on last. I have the most people onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's this about there being seven costume changes in your
show? Picking up a few tips from Diana Ross?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Laughs.) That was my dad's idea. But I was like, ``I don't
think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've said you want to be a combination of Janet Jackson and
Whitney Houston on tour. How do you plan to do that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, believe me, I know vocally and physically that's hard to
do. Singing and dancing and singing on key, without running out of
breath? Oh, my God! It's taking some training.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've given up the McDonald's fries?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm trying to give up McDonald's fries. Overall, I'm just
trying to stay healthy and work out a lot. Drinking a lot of water.
I've lost 20 pounds doing Tae Bo.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was it like to be a part of ``VH1: Divas Live 2'' with
Whitney Houston and Cher? Did you feel like you belonged?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was scared to perform there, too. The thing that really
tripped me out was being onstage with Tina Turner. She is Janet and
Whitney onstage. Before the show, though, I was hearing people say
I was too young to be considered a ``diva.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think so?
</P>
<P>
   A: It didn't matter to me. Evidently VH1 thought I was supposed
to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you passed any advice to other young stars, like Britney
Spears?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've met Britney a couple of times. And basically I told her
to make the money. Don't let the money make you. And don't worry
about the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the media get wrong about you?
</P>
<P>
   A: The media wants to portray me as a little girl, and I'm not.
I'm smarter than what people think. But people always want to ask
me silly questions, like about my bellybutton. ``Why can't you show
your navel?'' Or it's, ``So I heard you got a tattoo.'' That's not
interesting to me. It's never, ``Brandy, what do you read?'' or
``Why do you think Lauryn Hill is so deep?'' (It's) ``Did I really
have a fight with Monica backstage?'' That's not interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And not true either, right?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what are you reading these days?
</P>
<P>
   A: A book called ``A Course in Miracles.'' Basically it's saying
nothing real is threatening and nothing unreal exists. Herein lies
the peace of God.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
