<HEADER>
A1051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENY-SHOPPING28-COX     06-27 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENY-SHOPPING28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Generation `Buy'
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Strolling at nearly a jogger's pace down the corridors
of Perimeter Mall, Cade Grisham busts a Larry with his friend Chris
Barry, heading to the shirt racks in Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, an
upscale shop whose ear-splitting music, bright lights and young
sales staff attracts teen-agers like bugs to candles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool,'' says Cade as the two plop down on a plump couch to
plot strategy. ``Yeah, but expensive,'' Chris responds, as other
chattering teens wander in and out, gently touching garments and
placing them back respectfully on neat stacks.
</P>
<P>
   Cade and Chris are 16-year-olds. They're among the core of
what's known as Generation Y, the offspring of baby boomers. These
are kids who wouldn't be caught dead in the tattered, tacky,
tie-dyed garb their nonconformist parents wore as marks of
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Rebellion doesn't really fit Gen Y. Coming of age during the
prosperous, peaceful '90s, it's the richest, savviest, most
optimistic generation ever, marketers who study the kids say. And
the biggest-spending one, too. The teen-age Gen Y'er already spends
nearly $84 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Good-bye Gen X slackers, hello Gen Am-Ex.
</P>
<P>
   That spending, combined with Gen Y's sheer size _ there are 31
million American teens now, and the number will continue to grow
until 2010 _ means they're capable of creating and killing trends
almost overnight, says Michael Wood, director of research for
Chicago's Teenage Research Unlimited, one of the many think tanks
that have popped up like pimples to help retailers rake in their
share from teens' deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's critical for stores such as Abercrombie to
``have a cool feel,'' Wood says. Stores turn up the music and stay
attuned to the fickle, flexible minds of kids who can turn a hot
item cold almost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Take baggy jeans. A year ago they were so hot retailers couldn't
get them fast enough. Now many stores are stuck with jeans that
won't even sell on sale.
</P>
<P>
   Even Nike, the once-dominant sneaker brand, is now barely ahead
of once-forgotten Adidas in teen popularity.
</P>
<P>
   And beware, managers at the Gap: ``I think Gap stuff has fizzled
out,'' says Anita Kim, an 18-year-old Emory University freshman,
fingering a rainbow of pastel shirts at Gadzooks, a chain growing
in popularity. ``Gadzooks is more trendy. More cool. Cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   To grab hold and increase their share of this ever-changing
market, businesses have to hop to be hip, to shift their focus from
aging baby boomers, says economist Charlie Carter of Clark Atlanta
University.
</P>
<P>
   They need to employ people who speak the lingo, knowing, for
example, that to ``bust a Larry'' means hang a left, that to
``hang'' means to relax, and that ``sup'' can mean anything from
``what's new'' to ``what are you doing tonight,'' says Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generation Y's parents dominated culture for several
decades,'' Wood says. ``Gen Y will dominate the next few decades,
so it's critical that we know more about them, what they think,
what they want to do and where they want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In broad terms, Gen Y is more entrepreneurial and upbeat about
the future than their predecessors, the more cynical and less
numerous Generation X'ers. And definitely into shopping. Teenage
Research Unlimited says the average teen visits a mall 54 times a
year, compared to 39 for other shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, teens are somewhat thoughtful shoppers. They don't
generally spend on a whim but save money for CDs, videos and
movies, says Irma Zandl of the New York-based Zandl Group. As
shoppers, they have a powerful tool previous generations didn't _
the Internet. Most Gen Y'ers at least have access to the Web, using
it to browse and buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're price conscious,'' says Laura Hay, 18, a high school
grad who's headed to the Pratt Art Institute in Brooklyn, N.Y.
``Most kids our age work.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Alaina Johns, 14, browsing in American Eagle, says,
``Whenever I need something, I get it. But I also baby-sit and
save.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Keller, a 14-year-old freshman in suburban Atlanta,
insists she's a frugal shopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get CDs cheaper at other places than the mall,'' she
says. ``I'd never buy them here.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds friend Amanda Feldman, 14, also a freshman: ``I baby-sit
and save. If I want something and it's expensive, my parents will
split the cost. But I don't get stuff just because I want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of kids who look like they're shopping, might not be. TRU
found in a recent poll that 87 percent of Gen Y'ers go to malls to
shop, but 73 percent also go just to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Between yelps of ``yes'' and ``awwright'' as he furiously pushes
buttons on a video game at Perimeter's Tilt arcade, Chris Williams,
13, says he mainly goes to malls to be with friends.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also managed to aquire the right clothes. He looks
like a model for a Hilfiger ad. He's also into the FUBU and Zonz
brands. ``I have enough money to keep me happy,'' he grins.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the money come from? A lot comes from parents.
</P>
<P>
   The booming economy has filled the pockets of boomers, many of
whom are easy marks when their kids open their palms, says Dr.
Michael Popkin, an Atlanta child psychologist. He urges parents to
avoid giving in too easily.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not solely boomer affluence that's responsible for the
Gen Y spending spree. Guilt is another factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time poverty,'' says economist Jeffrey Humphreys of the
University of Georgia. ``Parents have money, and in more than 50
percent of marriages both partners work.
</P>
<P>
   ``And parents who're divorced or single try to offset guilt by
giving money when asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Page Morgan, 42, feels she's spoiling her two sons, ``but I
absolutely can't help it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both she and her husband work and are too exhausted to devote as
much time to their kids as they'd like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I work as hard as I do is so I can give my children
more,'' says Morgan, a real-estate agent. But, she says, ``I worry
we're not teaching them how to appreciate a dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen Y'ers money also comes from the ambitious teens' jobs.
According to Teenage Research Unlimited, 55 percent of Gen Y'ers
get at least some of their money from their parents on an as-needed
basis, 47 percent get it from odd jobs, 44 percent get it from
gifts, 30 percent get it from part-time jobs, 28 percent get it
from allowances and 12 percent get it from full-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the economy turns sour, some of those sources will
start to run dry. Which is sure throw the Gen Y shopping culture
for a loop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a rude awakening,'' says Carter. ``The savings
rate is lower than it's been since the Depression. Personal debt is
at an all-time high, and so is credit card debt and bankruptcies.
They can only keep spending as long as good times roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
