</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNED-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECLAIMING LIFE: BURN VICTIM, FAMILY CELEBRATE PROGRESS DESPITE
LONG ROAD TO RECOVERY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Today is cq for Monday) 
 
By TERRY KLIEWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTER, Texas _ Three hundred sixty-five days ago, Robert
Middleton had a birthday, his eighth, and he got a most
extraordinary gift: his life.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Robert will be 9, but no present will rival what he
already has been given.
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking might seem outlandish for a boy whose world is
defined by burn dressings, compression wraps, daily physical
therapy and bimonthly surgery. Robert is, after all, a boy for whom
ordinary childhood is now long ago and far away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a facsimile of boyhood is still his to enjoy. Just now he's
sitting up, carefully, in the office of his uncle's glass shop,
playing a computer game for the first time. His wheelchair is
parked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   He's maneuvering the computer mouse and following the screen
action with his right eye. He murmurs excitedly to his aunt,
hovering at his shoulder, as he scores points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't ever done this before,'' he tells a visitor. ``I
like it better than video games, but it's harder.''
</P>
<P>
   His words, some syllables garbled because of his missing lower
lip, are testimony to his boyish priorities. His bright voice
delivers the smile that his scarred face cannot. Enough said, he
turns eagerly back to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   On June 28, 1998, Robert Middleton stumbled, aflame from head to
foot, from the pine woods near his home near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   What first looked to be a devastating accident was revealed to
be far more sinister when, as he lay awaiting emergency evacuation,
he told his mother that he had been set on fire by a neighborhood
boy.
</P>
<P>
   The motive remains uncertain, but questions about what happened
on that forest pathway quickly became secondary to saving Robert's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Burned over virtually his entire body down to the third layer of
his skin, doctors said &UR;  &LR; Robert faced only the most remote chance of
survival when he arrived at Shriners Burns Hospital-Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he was alive at all was cause for hope.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, he was undergoing the first of what became a
procession of skin grafts. Within days he was beginning to
stabilize and endured torturous daily bathings, skin debridement
and dressing changes.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks he was recovering from surgical grafts of cultured
skin _ tissue grown from his own skin, using state-of-the-art
technology _ and showing promise for an altogether miraculous
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Through all of those numbing days and nights, Bobby Ray and
Colleen Middleton stood by the youngest of their three children.
Robert's initial hospital stay was seven months. For seven months,
his parents held their breath.
</P>
<P>
   His mother's great ambition once had been to finish the makeover
that she and her husband were giving their Splendora-area home, a
bungalow that the Middletons occupied on a rent-to-own basis.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to caring for an adventurous 8-year-old; a
12-year-old son, Clint; and a daughter, Heather, 14; Colleen
Middleton, 34, worked in the Porter glass shop run by Mark Wise,
her brother. Bobby Ray, 36, worked there also. After eight years,
the Middletons had done enough work on the house to see the end in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   All that changed on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Robert was hurt and expenses began to mushroom,
the Middletons had to vacate their home. They now live at an
undisclosed location elsewhere in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd spent a lot of money and time on that house,'' Colleen
says nostalgically. ``We wanted to stay there the rest of our
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, literally, the Middletons became around-the-clock
nurse trainees at the Galveston hospital where Robert struggled to
recover. For three months after his hospital admission, the couple
stayed in an apartment provided by the Shriners.
</P>
<P>
   They spent hour after hour at Robert's side _ in his room, in
physical therapy, outside the operating room or in the debridement
facility _ learning how to tend to his wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary, especially the debridement,'' his mother
remembers. ``You remove the compression bandages, then the gauze,
then the dressings. Then you wash the skin very gently. Then you
use tweezers to peel away dead tissue. It's like the thinnest
tissue paper. One wrong move and it can all peel away, just like
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert was very brave. He'd only cry when it hurt really
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Middletons knew a day both joyous and fearful lay ahead: the
day Robert would leave the hospital _ if not permanently, then at
least for weeks and eventually months at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father had to return to work after 90 days in
Galveston, but he made the trip to the hospital every weekend.
Robert's mother stayed on for an additional four months.
</P>
<P>
   When he drove Robert home for the first time Jan. 9, Bobby Ray
Middleton had much to think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always on my mind that a lot of work and responsibility
was facing us,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He could not avoid recalling happier times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert was always good with his hands. He was always taking
scraps of wood and trying to build something. Once he built me a
toolbox. Another time he decided to smash a golf ball with a
hammer. The hammer flew back and hit him in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   The father chuckles softly at the memory. A few feet away,
though appearing to focus on the computer game, Robert is
eavesdropping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't ever do that again,'' he chirps, tilting his head for
a sly glance at his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Robert was made comfortable in his new home, but recollections
of his old home and what had occurred there would intrude. Says his
mom, ``He'd mention wanting to go back, and he'd bring up what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The scenario alleged by authorities for that grim summer
afternoon has been widely reported:
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Robert was attacked by a former neighborhood
friend, Don Collins, 13, who doused him with gasoline and set him
afire. The teen allegedly was angry that Robert had accused him of
stealing his fireworks, but investigators admit they still aren't
sure about a motive.
</P>
<P>
   Robert's mother says her son identified Collins as his assailant
in those heart-crushing moments before emergency personnel arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks about it every so often _ I try not to bring it up _
and he asks mostly why it happened,'' she says. ``I tell him that
some people are just mean. I don't know how to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins was taken into custody soon after the attack and
remained in juvenile detention until January, when he was released
to an uncle with whom he has stayed since.
</P>
<P>
   Like Robert, Collins is being home-schooled to keep him up to
speed with his schoolmates, says Bill Hall, his lawyer. Hall will
say little beyond that, other than to note that his client is glad
to be out of detention.
</P>
<P>
   Hall says the teen denies harming Robert or having even been
present at the scene of the torching.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County prosecutor Bill Patillo says he expects to
take his evidence to a grand jury next month. Since the case
involves a juvenile, Patillo will file what is called a petition
with the grand jury, and the jurors will decide what charges, if
any, are warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Patillo has spoken with Robert several times. He says Robert's
account of that day remains ``materially'' unchanged from what he
provided a year ago. He expects him to testify if a trial takes
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very forthright about events of that day,'' says Patillo.
</P>
<P>
   For now, for the Middletons, trial proceedings are somewhere
over the horizon. Their journey is strictly day by day, step by
step.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent milestone for Robert has been just that: steps.
With the aid of a walker, he now can take short, stiff-legged
steps, no longer a prisoner of his wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, while I was out of the room, he got himself out
of his wheelchair and made it over to the sofa,'' says his mother.
``That was a huge achievement'' _ the very sort that his daily two
hours of physical therapy are designed to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   On July 7, the Middletons will make another trip to Shriners in
Galveston for another surgery. This one will ``release''
scar-constricted tissue around Robert's neck, chin and mouth in
hope of restoring his lower lip.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons also will open his burn-blinded left eye, now
half-covered by facial tissue draped across the socket for
temporary protection. A corneal transplant, like the one he has had
on his right eye, is being contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   Family members say they hope these refining operations will
prepare Robert to re-enter school as a third-grader this fall.
Robert says he's eager to return. He already has been visited by
some of his friends from school. The Shriners hospital will provide
special counseling for Robert and his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   As Robert's recovery proceeds, expenses mount, of course. The
Shriners already have provided, for free, about $1 million in
surgery, therapy and other support, hospital officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Much more will be required.
</P>
<P>
   The Middletons and their relatives have incurred at least
$100,000 in nonhospital costs for everything from bandages to the
minivan they had to buy to transport Robert.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wise and his wife, Kendra, say the trust fund established
to handle donations to help Robert has covered almost all of those
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everything's being taken care of and will be for
the next several years,'' says Mark Wise.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the picture isn't clear.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Robert will face new rounds of surgery to release
stiffened elbows, knees and shoulders, to attach prosthetic ears
and, as he matures, to periodically remove and replace skin grafts
he has outgrown.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way will be countless hours of debridement and
rebandaging and therapy _ and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a religious man, and I'm thankful for everyone's prayers
for our son,'' says Bobby Ray Middleton. ``I feel like God has
answered our prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors who are around Robert even briefly shouldn't be
surprised to find themselves wondering deeply about the meaning of
life. He's still a little boy and can't help them much in their
reflections, except by example.
</P>
<P>
   And that may be enough. His existence is his message: Life is
precious.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him what he thinks his future holds and he'll reply, simply
and happily, ``I'm going to live _ live for the rest of my life!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
