   KOSOVO PACKAGE:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Belgrade) _ The collapse of Greater Serbia can be
told through the story of one Serbian family, expelled from
Croatia, resettled near Belgrade, then bounced to Kosovo, and now
living in squalid housing outside Belgrade again. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOMB-DAMAGE (Dateline TK) _ Did NATO destroy as much of
the Yugoslav army as it said it did during the 78 days of bombing?
By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-DRUGS (Undated) _ How American drug companies have
supposedly donated worthless drugs to aid Kosovo and taken massive
tax deductions at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VILLAGE (Slovinje) _ The old Balkan cycle of fear and
revenge meets NATO's attempt to impose order. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MISSING (Dateline TK) _ About those still missing; many
of whom may be still held in prisons in Serbia. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Dateline TK) _ Two people were shot dead overnight
in the Kosovo capital and at least one of them had links to an
international organization. Other developments. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERNATIONAL NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DRUNKS (Moscow) _ Accidental deaths in Russia due to
drunkeness are on the rise in the hot summer months, with two dozen
men drowning in Moscow rivers. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ Hundreds of non-governmental
agencies have suddenly begun flexing their muscles now that
Indonesia's dictator is gone. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-TUDJMAN (Zagreb) _ For a leader whose small Balkan state
is unable to pay pensions, save banks from collapse, or stem
mounting discontent, Croatia's President Franjo Tudjman seems
strangely preoccupied with history. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-RDP (Dublin) _ David Trimble, the first minister of the
Northern Ireland Assembly, says the stalled peace effort in Ulster
could be saved by a simple statement that the IRA is committed to
disarming by May 2000. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   BARBARY-LIONS (Hoedspruit, South Africa) _ Veterinarians who
examined some abandoned circus animals now say that a lion in the
group is one of the few Barbary lions left in the world. The last
one in the wild was shot in 1921 in Morocco, and for a few months,
there were claims that the circus lion was the only Barbary left.
But the excitement over finding him led small European zoos and
circuses to pipe up, ``Hey _ we've got a lion that looks like
that.'' One of them even agreed to ship its lioness to South
Africa, and now the possibility exists that the subspecies can be
bred back into viability. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONSERVATIVES (Manchester, N.H.) _ Conservative
Republicans are distressed at George W. Bush's dominance of the
presidential primaries. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   WHALE-NOISE (Friday Harbor, Wash.) _ A concert of sorts brought
the best sounds humans have to offer to the whales _ Monteverdi's
vespers, Afro-Brazilian music, and more. The whales were out in
force, making lots of their own noise. The result was a
fascinating, unusual scene of whales being whales, and humans,
trying to reach out and connect with another species, being human.
By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-NUWABIANS (Eatonton, Ga.) _ Eatonton is home to a cult
called the Nuwabians. They migrated to Georgia from Brooklyn and
built a compound whose main feature is pyramids. They walk around
in a kind of Egyptian attire. The basis of the cult seems to the
leader's belief that a spaceship will come and take them all away
someday. Once a year, on the occasion of the leader's birthday, the
cult opens the compound to the public. The cult is also in the
middle of a minor legal dispute with the county over property
taxes.
</P>
