<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILKEN-LIBEL-BOOK-2TA     06-27 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILKEN-LIBEL-BOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWELL MILKEN'S UNUSUAL   INVESTMENT : A LOAN FOR LAWSUIT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first chapter in this long-running legal soap
opera dates back to 1991 when the fallout from Wall Street's
insider trading scandals sent Michael Milken, the junk bond king,
to federal prison and inspired a best-selling book about carriage
trade criminals, ``Den of Thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael F. Armstrong, a criminal defense lawyer, was mentioned
only briefly in the book, James B. Stewart's account of powerful
Wall Street titans brought down by their own greed in the takeover
frenzy of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong parsed the words and struck back at the author and
the book's publisher, Simon &AMP; Schuster, with a $35 million libel
suit over one paragraph, a legal dispute that the publisher, Simon
&AMP; Schuster, scoffed was a ``frivolous'' waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later the lawsuit endures, largely funded, as it
turns out, by a quiet legal patron who said he did not want to
expend the ``negative energy'' to sue: Lowell Milken, the brother
of Milken and Armstrong's former client.
</P>
<P>
   Newly filed court documents indicate that Lowell Milken and his
wife set up a general partnership, Skyline Partners, to lend
Armstrong and his law firm up to $1.6 million for legal expenses,
which need not be repaid fully if the lawsuit fails or a damage
award is too paltry to cover costs. Lowell Milken was indicted in
1989 on securities violations, but the charges were later dismissed
as part of a deal with Michael Milken to plead guilty to six
felonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just simply did not want to devote the time to be involved
day to day in connection with a lawsuit,'' Milken said in
depositions, explaining why he had chosen to become a lawsuit
patron instead of suing himself in connection with the book by
Stewart. ``And I also felt that it was going to involve a lot of
negative energy and I really didn't want to do that at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, lawyers for Simon &AMP; Schuster, which is a unit of
Viacom Inc., filed a motion for a summary judgment in state Supreme
Court in Manhattan, seeking a court decision on the merits of the
case, which a company spokesman, Adam Rothberg, now characterizes
as a ``legal extravagance that has gone on for seven years too
long.'' But the costly and time-consuming legal wrangling over the
book has become a cautionary tale in the book industry, where
publishers have generally been able to prevail ultimately in court
against libel claims.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for instance, St. Martin's Press, won a jury verdict
in a libel dispute following a 10-day New Hampshire trial that
pitted the New York publishing house, which is owned by Holtzbrinck
GmbH, against Robert F. Gray, a prominent Washington public
relations executive and former Eisenhower administration official
whose suit centered on four descriptions of him in a book by Susan
Trento called ``The Power House.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, book publishers are much less likely to be sued for
libel than newspaper publishers or television broadcasters,
according to the Libel Defense Resource Center in New York, a
clearinghouse for information about libel and privacy claims. In
the last 19 years, just 11 libel suits over books have actually
reached trial, with verdicts split about evenly between the
publishers and plaintiffs, Sandra Baron, the executive director of
the libel center, said.
</P>
<P>
   But victory or not, cases like the long-running ``Den of
Thieves'' lawsuit cast a certain pall over the publication of other
critical investigative books because of the potential costs of
dealing with libel lawsuits that could destroy a book's
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle involving Simon &AMP; Schuster, both sides have spent
more than a $1 million in a lawsuit that has come down to the
meticulous examination of a few hundred words.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, 66, is a well-known criminal defense attorney who was
a member of the judicial selection committee that advised the
former Republican New York senator, Alfonse D'Amato, on judicial
appointments. He said that he no longer was Lowell Milken's
attorney, but that Milken remained a friend who offered to pay
legal fees because he considers the lawsuit a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that I'm some sort of stalking-horse for him is not
correct,'' Armstrong said. ``I would have sued whether he did or
not. I told him that whatever happened, I would sue because my wife
said to me that she didn't want the grandchildren taking the book
off a shelf somewhere in a business school and not knowing I went
all the way to fight it.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal sparring began shortly after the book was published in
September 1991. Armstrong, then representing Milken, confronted
Simon &AMP; Schuster executives on his client's behalf with a list of
concerns about the book.
</P>
<P>
   The book essentially consisted of two parts, an account of an
intricate scheme of illegal insider trading crafted by Wall Street
figures that included the arbitrageur Ivan Boesky and Michael
Milken, the driven investment banker who headed the high-yield junk
bond department at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. The second part was
the government search to track down violators.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Milken, who eventually pleaded guilty to six felonies
and went to prison, was described in a much harsher light than
Lowell Milken, a lawyer who is depicted as a cold hatchet man who
assisted his brother on tax and partnership issues.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Lowell Milken who challenged the accuracy of the
book, taking issue with 19 elements ranging from descriptions of
expensive art hanging in his office to an incident when he emerged
from his office to see his brother in a faint at his trading desk
before wordlessly returning to his own office and closing the door
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Armstrong, had two complaints, which eventually
became the core of his libel suit. In the lawsuit, which was filed
in September 1992, he argued that a paragraph in the book wrongly
suggested that he prepared a false affidavit for a witness to sign
that exonerated Lowell Milken on charges of violating security
laws.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The passage concerns an affidavit that Armstrong was preparing
with information from an in-house lawyer, Craig Cogut, who worked
on partnership issues for Lowell Milken. The intent of the
affidavit was to support Milken, who was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The critical part of the paragraph about Armstrong starts with a
description of Armstrong submitting an affidavit to Cogut for his
signature. It goes on: ``Cogut read it over and had only one
problem: the facts weren't true. He angrily refused to sign, and
began looking for new lawyers, eventually hiring Los Angeles
lawyers Tom Pollack and Ted Miller.''
</P>
<P>
   The paragraph does not explicitly state who was the source of
the account. Nor does it include a response from Armstrong reacting
to that version. The book's list of sources note that in disputed
descriptions, Stewart accepted the speaker's version in those
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's argument is that the total passage makes it appear
that ``I prepared a bunch of lies, gave it to my client and he
didn't sign it.'' In court documents and further comments, he
points out that the affidavit presented to Cogut was a draft that
he believed to be true at the time, but subject to further
corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster argues that there were a number of sources for
the passage: Cogut, his wife and other unidentified people. In
depositions, Cogut said that `` Armstrong had pressured me to
significant degrees to say things beyond what I was comfortable
saying'' and that Cogut was ``furious'' over those events. After
hiring a new lawyer to represent him, Cogut eventually signed a new
version of the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong contends that Stewart and his researcher never
bothered to check with him about the passage, although the author
in turn contends that he did leave messages for him to call. Since
he sued, Armstrong said he has received support from others who
told him, ``By God, I'm glad somebody did this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that Stewart is an extreme example of the kind of
thing that goes on a lot,'' Armstrong said. ``People write
inaccurate books with no real recourse on the part of the people
whom they target. They're not going to write books in response.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Den of Thieves,'' Stewart, is at work on another
book that is expected to be published in the fall, ``Blind Eye: How
the Medical Establishment Let a Doctor Get Away With Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the libel lawsuit had taken a toll whether he
wins or loses. The book, Stewart said, ``simply told the truth
about some enormously wealthy and powerful people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain a defendant in a multimillion dollar lawsuit that
from the beginning has felt like an attempt to harass and punish
me,'' he said. ``It is unpleasant, time-consuming and distracting.
Its existence has clouded my credit rating and made it difficult
for me to get a mortgage. I am sure it has intimidated other
journalists and publishers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Milken, who now presides over the Milken Family
Foundation in Santa Monica, Calif., did not respond to calls for
comment. But in depositions that he gave for the libel case, he was
asked if his intention was to punish the publisher and author.
</P>
<P>
   The reply came in the calculus of an investment, which Armstrong
has agreed to repay at more than 12 percent interest from any
proceeds of a successful libel claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an interest in loaning Armstrong money,'' Milken said.
`` Armstrong is maintaining his own lawsuit. If Armstrong is
successful, then I get repaid. If that ends up hurting the
defendants, then that's a result of the lawsuit. I assume that
paying money is not something that they like to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
