<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN FORCES ANNOUNCE CURFEW IN SOUTHERN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all to add map and photo notes)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ART ADV:  Locator map  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ German forces here announced Sunday that
they will impose a curfew at night to cut down on lawlessness,
which continues around Kosovo in the form of yet more slayings,
burning of houses and looting.
</P>
<P>
   A man and a woman were shot to death overnight in Dardanija, a
northern suburb of the capital city, Pristina. While officials said
they did not know the motive, another 14 people were reported slain
in Pristina on Friday, many of them Serbs killed in revenge by
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In the west, Albanian refugees returning home burned and looted
an entire village, Belo Polje, inhabited until these past few days
by Serbs who are now in flight.
</P>
<P>
   Here in southern Kosovo, the German commander, Brig. Gen. Fritz
von Korff, said Sunday that three Gypsies led his soldiers to a
basement where they claimed they had been tortured by members of
the Kosovo Liberation Army, 130 of whom live in the upper floors of
the house. He said that torture instruments were found there.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a rise in crime here _ just two weeks after the
jubilation that many Albanians felt when NATO forces arrived _ the
general said he would impose a midnight to 5 a.m. curfew. With the
curfew, he said soldiers could better distinguish criminals, who
are stealing cars and looting vacant houses, from ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are running around the town, it will be easier to
catch them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The German base was also visited Sunday by the Czech president,
Vaclev Havel, whose own country, unlike the former Yugoslavia,
moved out of communism a decade ago with virtually no bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all surprised what is possible at the end of the 20th
century in Europe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Havel strongly condemned the acts of revenge carried out by
Kosovo's majority Albanians, saying that they must ``live in peace
with the Serb minority, so that the Serbs have no reason to flee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans oversee one of five sectors in Kosovo, divided in
the peace agreement which is aimed at ending the NATO bombing of
Yugoslav forces, and allowing the return of roughly 1 million
Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But the refugees' return _ weeks or months after they fled or
were kicked out of Kosovo by Serb forces _ has not been smooth:
Many Albanians, whose relatives were killed or who are returning to
destroyed houses, are seeking revenge against Serbs and their
property. In fear, tens of thousand of Serbs have fled Kosovo north
into Serbia proper.
</P>
<P>
   In the western city of Pec and the villages around it, the
houses of Serbs and Gypsies, often allied with the Serbs in Kosovo
against Albanians, have been burning for the last few days. In Belo
Polje, just outside Pec, Albanians with wheelbarrows looted the
houses on Sunday, saying that they were doing to the Serbs what the
Serbs had done to them.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, one of the two slaying victims, found dead outside
a post office, was a former employee with the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe, which had monitored a
cease-fire in Kosovo last year. The employee was reportedly a
native of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Neither victim was identified Sunday night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A week after the last of the Serb military forces withdrew from
Kosovo, the next phase in the agreement between NATO and the KLA is
set to take place at midnight on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Already, KLA soldiers are not permitted to carry weapons in the
open or operate checkpoints, two prohibitions that seem largely to
be obeyed. But there are exceptions: on Sunday outside the western
town of Junik, half a dozen soldiers in KLA uniforms armed with
AK-47s were stopping cars to ask where passengers were going.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the KLA is required to have cleared its minefields
and booby traps, and to leave fighting positions and establish
sites for storing weapons, which NATO will be able to inspect.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday on Mount Pastrik, the mountain in southwestern Kosovo
that was a major battlefield in the war, KLA soldiers dragged
wagonloads of ammunition down a steep and rocky road. Nexhat Shala,
one of two soldiers guarding the cache itself _ mortars,
rocket-propelled grenades, land mines and bullets scattered in a
remote clearing _ said the ammunition had been brought over from
Albania in the last week or so.
</P>
<P>
   He said he assumed it would be handed over to NATO, although no
spokesman for the KLA could be reached for confirmation or comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Dietmar Jeserich, a spokesman for the German command,
said they were aware of the cache on Mount Pastrik and would make
sure it was properly reported and stored in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know about this,'' he said. ``And we will look at this
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
