(HLW)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Kosovo-related stories that The New York Times is
planning for Monday, June 28, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service day
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Belgrade) _ The collapse of Greater Serbia can be
told through the story of one Serbian family, expelled from
Croatia, resettled near Belgrade, then bounced to Kosovo, and now
living in squalid housing outside Belgrade again. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOMB-DAMAGE (Djakovica) _ In the two weeks since NATO
forces arrived in Kosovo, alliance officials have scaled back their
initial estimates of the damage inflicted by the 78-day air
campaign on the Yugoslav army, which they concede remains a force
capable of maintaining Slodoban Milosevic's grip on power. While
NATO and Pentagon officials stand by their claims to have
significantly damaged the Yugoslav army and special police, they
acknowledge that the units that withdrew from Kosovo a week ago
were clearly not as damaged as they had believed. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-DRUGS (Undated) _ Last month, Project Hope, the
American medical charity, shipped $1.5-million worth of emergency
supplies to the Kosovo refugees. But relief workers desperate for
syringes, penicillin, and insulin found many of the hundreds of
boxes instead contained ChapStick, Preparation H, and anti-smoking
inhalers _ given by American companies that got a tax break for the
donations. The outpouring of aid from corporate America and
elsewhere for the roughly 700,000 refugees that flooded Albania and
Macedonia during the war between NATO and Yugoslavia was indeed
massive and included many badly needed medicines. But the World
Health Organization said about a third to half of all of the
shipments were essentially useless and are likely to just gather
dust in warehouses or be destroyed at government expense.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VILLAGE (Slovinje) _ They came here last Monday with a
simple but daunting mission: hold together one of the few villages
left in Kosovo where Albanian and Serb lived side by side. Backed
by helicopter gunships, the 30 British soldiers, seasoned officers
and infantrymen who had served in Northern Ireland or Bosnia, were
among the NATO troops in Kosovo most familiar with the bitter
divisions wrought by fear, revenge, and violence. In this farming
village of some 600 homes and 3,500 people in central Kosovo, the
British met a community that was in some ways an exception in this
ruined province. In Slovinje, Serbs and Albanians had lived in
relative harmony for decades. Yet, even here, the attempt to hold a
community together went wrong. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MISSING (Dateline TK) _ About those still missing; many
of whom may be still held in prisons in Serbia. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Prizren) _ German forces here announced Sunday they
will impose a curfew at night to cut down on lawlessness, which
continues around Kosovo in the form of yet more slayings, burning
of houses and looting. A man and a woman were shot to death
overnight in Dardanija, a northern suburb of the capital city,
Pristina. While officials said they did not know the motive,
another 14 people were reported slain in Pristina on Friday, many
of them Serbs killed in revenge by ethnic Albanians. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo; map)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-UPDATE (Undated) _ A brief recapitulation of
Kosovo-related events.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these, we have a related story:
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-TUDJMAN (Zagreb) _ For a leader whose small Balkan state
is unable to pay pensions, save banks from collapse, or stem
mounting discontent, Croatia's President Franjo Tudjman seems
strangely preoccupied with history. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
