<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMINO-THEATER-REVIEW     06-27 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMINO-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CAMINO REAL': TRUE TO TENNESSEE WILLIAMS' VISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(rk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ For a bunch of burned-out souls, the
travelers along that lonely road known as the Camino Real are
sending off plenty of sparks. The inaugural production of the
Williamstown Theater Festival's new season finds the bright bounce
and energy, not to mention a gutsy sense of humor, in a thickly
poetic allegory of expiring hopes and trampled ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camino Real'' takes its title from its setting, a brutal,
carnivalesque limbo that mirrored the geography of the soul of its
author, Tennessee Williams, as he slid into an unmoored middle age.
``As personal as a nightmare'' was how Elia Kazan, who directed the
play's premiere in 1953, described it. Williams wrote that the
work, which puts Don Quixote, Camille, Casanova and Lord Byron all
on the same stage, was ``nothing more nor less than my conception
of the time and the world I live in.''
</P>
<P>
   That world was, as Williams saw it, an ogre that crushed its
romantics and ate its artists for breakfast. This vision, as it
turned out, had its elements of immediate prophecy. ``Camino Real''
signaled the first serious rupture in the love affair between its
author and his public. Audiences of 1953 were bolting by the first
intermission, and critics choked on their disgust with the play's
pretension and obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   The more charitable suggested that perhaps this feverish
exercise in symbolism was meant simply to be read, as poems are.
Nonsense, Williams responded: ``Of all the works I have written,
this one was meant most for the vulgarity of the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The interpretation at Williamstown, which has been directed at a
breathless clip by Nicholas Martin and memorably stars Ethan Hawke
as the ultimate American innocent, takes Williams at his word. It
is quite willfully vulgar, awash in neon colors and garish
costumes, with staging that evokes vaudeville, burlesque and the
Keystone Kops.
</P>
<P>
   But if the show sometimes muffles the play's more tender
lyricism, it also taps the vitality in despair that made Williams
such an essential theatrical force. You can't read a biography of
him without coming across a description of his laugh: a piercing,
hyenalike cackle that would erupt at the most unseemly moments.
This production seems to channel that laugh, creating a sense of
appalled hilarity, of guffawing defiantly at death's door.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Williams wrote ``Camino Real,'' his fame had begun
to smother him, and the paranoia that would dominate his later
years, fed by fears of betrayal and of loss of talent, had started
to fester. The play, he wrote in a letter to Kazan, was ``the story
of everyone's life after he has gone through the razzle-dazzle of
his youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's production _ designed with lurid flair by James Noone
(sets), Michael Krass (costumes) and Kevin Adams (lighting) _ picks
up on this sense of a head-splitting hangover, of a world turned so
bright and ugly that it is best viewed through dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   The setting, a hotel-framed plaza with a Spanish accent, brings
to mind a misfired MGM musical of the 1950s, shot in sour
Technicolor. The choruslike ensemble variously suggests cartoon
versions of jet-setters, vampire prostitutes and sideshow barkers.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriately named Gutman (Jeffrey Jones), an oily Sidney
Greenstreet type, suavely and tyrannically presides over the
evening. And death shows up regularly, to the frantic piping of a
calliope, as a pair of giggling, simian street cleaners (Craig
Pattison and Ben Fox).
</P>
<P>
   Wandering through all the grotesquerie is a band of archetypal
figures who embody Williams' notions of how romance can tarnish.
The action, such as it is, is sprung by the arrival of Don Quixote
(John Seidman), the great, delusionary defender of heroic values,
who promptly falls asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Casanova (Richard Easton) is now an aging cuckold, and the woman
he adores, Marguerite Gautier (Blair Brown), aka Camille, has moved
beyond sacrificial love to seedy pickups and opium dens.
</P>
<P>
   Proust's Charlus (Christian Carmago), the gay esthete baron, has
been reduced to squalid trysts in the local men's flophouse. Lord
Byron (also Carmago) arrives to fret majestically, in some of
Williams' most heartfelt prose, over the squandering of his
vocation. And then there is Kilroy (Hawke), a onetime boxing
champion with ``a heart the size of a baby's head,'' who has been
told he could die at any instant.
</P>
<P>
   Kilroy is the essence of crude American idealism and
unquenchable energy, and Hawke plays him with a sweet, athletic
robustness that gives the production its motor and keeps it from
sinking into a parade of metaphors. This young actor, best known
for his work in stylishly hip mainstream movies, gives off a
kinetic intensity and exaggerated naivete that suggests a
contemporary answer to commedia dell'arte.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderful performance, both disciplined and spontaneous,
and when this Kilroy goes courting, in some of Williams' wittiest
dialogue, the evening approaches perfection. It helps that the
object of Kilroy's affections, Esmeralda, a lithe sexual commodity
in a harem costume, is played by the enchanting Hope Davis, who
once again appears right at home in a surreal situation. The shades
of satire and poignancy these performers mine from the words ``I am
sincere,'' which they repeat over and over, are remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown, television's winsome Molly Dodd in the 1980s, would
seem an odd choice for Camille. But the actress, who was terrific
as the frumpy landlady in the current Broadway revival of
``Cabaret,'' has been full of surprises lately, and she brings just
the right weary pragmatism to her over-the-hill courtesan. Like
Hawke, she has found a comfortable formula for playing allegory,
poised between caricature and emotional honesty, and she is well
matched by Easton's perpetually indignant, dignified Casanova.
</P>
<P>
   Not every performance works. Carmago, while a darkly amusing
Charlus, fares less well with Byron's fiery laments. Jones' Gutman
doesn't always get his mouth around his character's elaborate
running commentary. And the chorus often suggests those eager
extras in student productions who stand around muttering,
``Rhubarb, rhubarb.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is, on the other hand, Kristine Nielsen as Esmeralda's
mother, a predatory Gypsy fortuneteller who looks and rather
behaves like Carmen Miranda. Ms. Nielsen was the electrifying
center of Christopher Durang's ``Betty's Summer Vacation,'' seen at
Playwrights Horizons in Manhattan this season under Martin's
direction, and both actress and director have imported the same
anarchic zing to ``Camino.''
</P>
<P>
   In his memoirs, Kazan wrote regretfully of ``Camino,'' saying
the naturalism with which he infused his interpretation ill served
the play. Martin doesn't make that mistake. There are still
passages of labored and literal-minded symbolism to wince over, and
it doesn't do to pause and linger too much in presenting this play;
in fact, it could kill it. Mercifully, this production, like
Hawke's Kilroy, stays alive by always moving, with flash and
frenzy, without trivializing the broken heart beneath.
</P>
<P>
   In the years after ``Camino,'' Williams' predictions of betrayal
and rejection were fulfilled. By the end of his career he was
scorned as a sad self-parody, at least in his own country.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 16 years after his death, theater artists are finding
treasure in Williams works long neglected or dismissed. Think of
the Drama Dept.'s inspiriting revision of his fabled flop,
``Kingdom of Earth,'' or Trevor Nunn's stunning resurrection of the
early, previously unproduced ``Not About Nightingales.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in his art as in his life, Williams could be grotesquely
excessive and sloppy. But whatever he wrote, he tore it straight
from his soul, and in this age of irony there is something
especially nourishing in such sustained depths of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say with any personal conviction that I have written a
good play,'' Williams wrote in his preface to ``Camino Real.'' ``I
only know that I have felt a release in this work which I wanted
you to feel with me.'' Martin, Hawke and company gleefully lead us
to this very peculiar but undeniable catharsis.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CAMINO REAL'
</P>
<P>
   By Tennessee Williams; directed by Nicholas Martin; sets by
James Noone; costumes by Michael Krass; lighting by Kevin Adams;
sound by Kurt Kellenberger; composer, Peter Golub; choreography by
Hernando Cortez. Presented by the Williamstown Theater Festival,
Michael Ritchie, producer; Deborah Fehr, general manager; Jenny
Gersten, associate producer. At Adams Memorial Theater, 1000 Main
St. (Route 2 east), Williamstown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   With: Lewis Black (The Loan Shark and Nursie), Blair Brown
(Marguerite Gautier), Christian Camargo (Baron de Charlus and Lord
Byron), Hope Davis (Esmeralda), Richard Easton (Jacques Casanova),
Ben Fox (Street Cleaner), Ethan Hawke (Kilroy), Jeffrey Jones
(Gutman), Kristine Nielsen (The Gypsy), Craig Pattison (Street
Cleaner), Mary Lou Rosato (La Madrecita), John Seidman (Lord
Mulligan and Don Quixote) and Daniel Sunjata (First Officer).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
