<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VILLAGE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH TROOPS FAIL TO STEM TIDE OF SERBS LEAVING VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLOVINJE, Yugoslavia _ They came here last Monday with a simple
but daunting mission: Hold together one of the few villages left in
Kosovo where Albanian and Serb lived side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by helicopter gunships, the 30 British soldiers, seasoned
officers and infantrymen who had served in Northern Ireland or
Bosnia, were among the NATO troops in Kosovo most familiar with the
bitter divisions wrought by fear, revenge and violence.
</P>
<P>
   In this farming village of some 600 homes and 3,500 people in
central Kosovo, the British met a community that was in some ways
an exception in this ruined province. In Slovinje, Serbs and
Albanians had lived in relative harmony for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even here, the attempt to hold a community together went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The maelstrom of bloodshed and the emotions it engenders proved
more powerful than the British appeals for reason, or the bonds
that had survived the past decade of repressive Serbian rule of
Kosovo's majority Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   For this village was not spared the last three months of war. On
April 15 and 16, masked Serbian paramilitaries swept into the
village, killing some 40 people, including four women, according to
Albanians who say they witnessed the attack. In early May, local
Serbian police unearthed 16 bodies from two mass graves, and
allowed Albanians to rebury them.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was especially treacherous, Albanian villagers said,
because their Serb neighbors promised them the night before that
Slovinje would not be targeted.
</P>
<P>
   After the massacre, and the reburials, many of Slovinje's
Albanians fled, mostly to nearby Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last Monday, the British arrived. Over the next five days,
hundreds of embittered Albanian families streamed back into the
village, where some 30 of the original 40 or so Serb families
remained.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Graham Shannon, a boyish-looking 26-year-old, and his
soldiers struggled to surmount Balkan notions of just retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides will test us, seeing how we react,'' Shannon said,
hours after arriving in the ramshackle yellow schoolhouse turned
military base that the British soon dubbed ``the Alamo.'' ``But
it's something that our boys are used to.''
</P>
<P>
   The men of the British Army's Royal Irish Regiment indeed became
swiftly embroiled in confrontation. Five of the six cars they
stopped in the village on Monday had weapons. All were driven by
Albanians. The British suspected them of being Kosovo Liberation
Army soldiers filtering into town from the hills. As word spread of
the spot checks, fewer guns were found.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Albanian villagers streamed to the schoolhouse
with accounts of the massacre and names of local Serbs that they
said were perpetrators, recognized despite their masks. Shannon
took careful notes.
</P>
<P>
   When darkness fell, the British dispatched standard patrols,
four men on foot or in an armored personnel carrier, and began a
cat-and-mouse game they would play for nights_ chasing returning
Albanians who, finding their own homes looted, pillaged homes
abandoned by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   One Albanian had returned to find that the Serbs had led a cow
inside his home. Herding it up to the second floor, they slashed
the animal's throat, gutted it and placed a live hand grenade in
its mid-section. Stinking pieces of rotting flesh hung from every
wall.
</P>
<P>
   The British arrested two looters that first night, dispatched
them from the schoolhouse to a larger British base 15 miles away,
where they were interrogated and, hours later, released.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon hoped the arrests might act as a deterrent. But dozens
of other looters had escaped into the night, and Serbs were
terrified.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday started quietly, but swiftly dissolved into chaos with
the kidnap of a 20-year-old Serb, Zoran Stanisic.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon and his men frantically launched foot, vehicle and
helicopter searches at 1:30 p.m. Meanwhile, Stanisic's 53-year-old
father, Milenko, who unlike most Kosovo Serbs speaks Albanian and
had long maintained ties with local Albanians, threatened his
Albanian neighbors of many years with death if they did not tell
him where his son was.
</P>
<P>
   The British spent 15 minutes calming the terrified Bytyqi
family, who just returned from a refugee camp in Macedonia, but Lt.
Shannon declined their request for a guard, saying he did not have
enough men. At 4:30 p.m., the Serb family came to the schoolhouse,
complaining that not enough was being done to find their son.
Stanisic said he had harmed no Albanians and even brought them tea
as they hid in the woods during NATO's air campaign. He asked why
his son had been kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of bad things happened here,'' Shannon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't do it,'' Stanisic replied.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Shannon grew exasperated. ``You won't talk to the Albanians and
the Albanians won't talk to you,'' he said. ``We're stuck in the
middle here. The only way things are going to get better is if
people talk to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   After British soldiers escorted the Serb family home, Albanian
villagers disputed Stanisic's claim that he had brought them tea.
They said he and his son were not involved in the Slovinje
massacre, but that did not give them clean hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe his father was a paramilitary somewhere else and someone
wants to revenge him,'' said Izadin Pacolli, 27.
</P>
<P>
   As afternoon turned into evening, Albanians approached the
schoolhouse to report suspected mines or booby traps left by Serbs
in their homes. Shannon dispatched soldiers when he could, but
often told Albanians to lock a dog in the house for an hour and see
if it triggered a mine.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:45 p.m., the Serb family reported that an Albanian passed
by their house and drew a knife across his own throat. They begged
for a permanent guard. Again, Lt. Shannon refused, fearing by now
that everyone in the village would request such security.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at dusk, two Kosovo Liberation Army soldiers in uniform,
carrying ammunition but no weapons, appeared near the Serb family's
home. The British arrested them, citing a new accord between NATO
and the KLA that forbade the wearing of the uniform. Like the
looters before them, the KLA soldiers were questioned by military
police at the larger British base, then released. All that night,
the looting intensified, despite continuous British patrols.
</P>
<P>
   By midday Wednesday, Serb families were streaming out of
Slovinje, their possessions loaded on cars and tractors. Shannon
and his men urged them to stay. The Serbs complained that NATO
soldiers were not protecting them, and departed.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Trajkovic, 47, insisted as he left that he did not know
that Serbs were going to attack the village in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew the military was coming I would have taken my own
family away,'' he said. ``Because of all the military did, we are
paying.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibush Bytyqi, a 49-year-old Albanian who was principal of the
local elementary school, scoffed. He said local Serbs planned the
April attack, claiming as other villagers did that some of the
masked paramilitaries seemed to pick out victims as if they knew
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what they've done and they won't be back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With ever more Serb houses standing empty, the British
confronted even more widespread looting on Wednesday night. A
patrol found an abandoned horse and cart and refrigerators, stoves
and washing machines placed beside a road, ready for pick-up. Two
looters were arrested, and again released after hours of
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday dawned with the last Serb families in the village
loading their wares onto wagons. By then, Slovinje's Albanian
population had swelled to nearly 2,000 as refugees returned,
sometimes by the busload.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon got word that a Serbian man stopped at the checkpoint at
the entrance to town was on a British Army list of those suspected
of taking part in the April massacre. Military police arrested the
man that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:45 p.m., Stanisic, the father of the kidnap victim,
departed on his tractor. ``I am alone. That's why I'm going. I
wanted to stay until they found him,'' he said, referring to his
still missing son. ``I am the last Serb to leave the village.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Slovinje, a village now purely Albanian, was calm and
tranquil. The Serbs may eventually be back, but the British were
frustrated nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The hate and fear they see here, they said, resembles what they
saw in Northern Ireland. In both places, they argued, their
presence at least limits the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do save lives in Northern Ireland, definitely, and we do
the same here,'' said Cpl. John Anthony Brennan. ``The weapons we
confiscated are used to kill people. We're doing good that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon agreed, but seemed haunted by Stanisic. ``He is broken.
He is absolutely broken,'' the young lieutenant said. ``All he
wants is to get his son back. But I believe his son is dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
