<HEADER>
A1166 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-NYT &LR;      06-27 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN REFUGEES TIRED OF RUNNING FROM CONFLICTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRAGUJEVAC, Yugoslavia, _ Behind a door without a doorknob, in a
filthy school basement lighted by a single bare bulb, nine homeless
Serbs offered themselves Sunday as human report cards on Slobodan
Milosevic's crusade to cut a ``Greater Serbia'' from the ruins of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine years in hell. That's my life,'' explained Radovan Grtic,
who came to the basement two days ago, after fleeing Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Grtic and the eight other Serbs in the room were all born in the
former Yugoslav republic of Croatia. That's where Milosevic's
nationalist schemes turned them into destitute wanderers,
threatened with death when they lived outside of Serbia and hustled
off to the hinterlands when they attempted to live inside its
borders.
</P>
<P>
   They have been chased from Croatia by the Croatian Army, then
hustled out of Serbia by Serbian police, then chased out of Kosovo
by vengeful Albanians and finally washed up here on the outskirts
of this down-on-its-luck factory town in central Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to American bombing during the Kosovo war, the sprawling
Zastava car and weapons plant that was the dominant employer in
Kragujevac has been ruined. The 6,000 Kosovo Serbs who have fled to
this city in the past two weeks are joining a local population of
about 150,000 people for whom unemployment is epidemic and where
local journalists say the major economic activity is smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   The dismal travels of the Serbs in the basement are a useful
guide in deciphering what three ethnic wars have wrought for the
two million or so Serbs who lived outside of the Serbia when
Milosevic came to power in 1988. Their grim, then grimmer and now
grimmest fortunes may also prove predictive of what lies ahead for
all 10 million Serbs as Greater Serbia has devolved into a
shrinking, impoverished, pariah state led by an indicted war
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a clever man,'' said Grtic, who was a farmer before
he fled Croatia and a gravedigger before he fled Kosovo. ``But I
can see that my homeland in Croatia is not a part of Serbia. The
Serbs in Bosnia are not part of Serbia. Kosovo is not a part of
Serbia. Maybe next year, I think, it will be bloody all over
Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Serbs in the school basement, the war that led to their
first forced exodus began with a quick and rather intoxicating
series of victories, as have all three of Milosevic's military
adventures in Croatia, Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Yugoslav Serbian Empire that Milosevic forcibly created
reached its territorial peak in the autumn and winter of 1992, the
fruit of Serb offensives, first in Croatia in 1991 and in Bosnia
the following year.
</P>
<P>
   That empire controlled about a third of Croatia and 70 percent
of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, then, was constitutionally entitled to be an autonomous
province inside Serbia, where the Albanian majority would govern
most of their own affairs. But that autonomy had been crushed by
Serbian police and Yugoslav army forces.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's empire, however, lasted just three months at its
territorial fullest. It has been shrinking spasmodically ever since
_ most visibly this month when 21,000 NATO forces poured into
Kosovo, in effect, shearing it off from Serbia, which is the
dominant republic inside what is left of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The shrinkage started in Croatia in January of 1993, when the
Croatian army took back some strategic towns in the Krajina region.
The big loss, though, took place in August of 1995, when the Croats
launched an invasion that violently and, often savagely, pushed
about 170,000 Serbs out of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Grtic, then 19 years old and living in the scenic village of
Dvor Na Uni in eastern Croatia, was a farmer and Serb militiaman
when he learned the Croats were coming. He said he walked away from
his home and then hopped a truck.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of weeks, he said, he found himself in the western
Serb town of Valjevo, which he liked and where he wanted to stay
and build a life.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, thinking back, I most blame the Serb police who forced
me to leave Valjevo,'' Grtic said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was forced to ``volunteer'' to be a settler in
Kosovo, a territory that Kosovar Serbs had been fleeing from for
decades because of conflicts there with the growing ethnic Albanian
population. The Milosevic regime, having risen to power on promises
of maintaining control in Kosovo, which many Serbs regard as their
holy land, tried to pressure Serb refugees from Croatia and from
Bosnia to move to the poor and mostly rural province.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, only a few thousand Serbs, mostly poor people
without any family or business connection inside Serbia, were
unable to figure out a way not to go to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Grtic was among those who had no alternative but to do as Serb
officials instructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me I would be given a house in Kosovo and a job,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in the Kosovo city of Pec, however, Grtic was
taken to a resettlement center, where he spent nearly four years
sharing a room 14 other displaced Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Down in the basement Sunday, Juba Tesla, 48, a Serb farmer who
lay on a bed surrounded by his wife and four children, told a
similar story of being elbowed out of Serbia in 1995 after Croats
from his birthplace in the Krajina region of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Croats were coming, we ran away,'' said Tesla, who
drove out of Croatia in a tractor, pulling a wagon loaded with his
family and his life's possessions. ``In Bosnia, we were led to a
train and I went to sleep thinking that I would wake up in
Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   Tesla, though, woke up in Kosovo, where he was encouraged by
Serb authorities to settle in the town of Dzurakovac, not far from
Pec. He worked there for nearly four years as day laborer, until
NATO's 10-week war with Yugoslavia over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, when hundreds of thousands of Albanians fled
Kosovo and many thousands were killed by Serb forces, Tesla and
Grtic said they took no part in forcing the Albanians to flee. But
they also made it clear that they were not especially upset to see
them go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbs have had enough of the Albanians,'' said Grtic. ``Serbs
have suffered from them since 1389.'' He referred to the fateful
Battle of Kosovo, which was won by the Ottoman Turks but is
regarded by the history-obsessed Serbs as a glorious show of
courage in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Grtic said he was aware that atrocities were committed by Serbs
against Albanians in Pec and he thought it was prudent to get out
of town before their angry relatives and friends came back.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived here in Kragujevac with a suitcase and, he said, no
idea of where he was going to go now or what he was going to do.
Asked who he blames for his multiple exiles inside the former
Yugoslavia, Grtic grunted, ``Slobo,'' the popular name of
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took Serb forces out of Kosovo. It is not safe for me to
live there. He allowed the Albanians everything they wanted,''
Grtic said.
</P>
<P>
   On a basement bed next to Grtic, Tesla was not willing to single
out any politician. He said he blamed the leaders of Croatia,
Bosnia and Serbia equally. But he said he and his family were not
angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not angry, we are desperate,'' he said. ``We haven't
got the energy for anger. We don't know long we will have to
travel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
