<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QWEST-MARKETPLACE-NYT     06-27 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: PRICE ISN'T THE WHOLE GAME IN A PHONE INDUSTRY
BIDDING WAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the board of the Frontier Corp. meets Monday, as expected,
to discuss the unsolicited bid made by Qwest Communications
International Inc., the debate will be far from elementary.
</P>
<P>
   That's because nothing is ever as simple as it looks. Global
Crossing Ltd., Qwest's telecommunications rival, agreed to buy
Frontier, the nation's fifth-largest long-distance phone company,
in March. Global is offering $63 in stock for each Frontier share
as long as Global's shares trade within a range of $34.56 to
$56.78. Global also recently agreed to merge with U S West, the
smallest of the regional Bell telephone companies, offering $60 in
Global stock plus a $1 special dividend for each U S West share.
</P>
<P>
   But Qwest surprised investors two weeks ago, making hostile
offers for both Frontier and U S West and then revising its bids
last week to make them more appealing than Global's. Qwest is
offering Frontier shareholders a total of $68 ($20 in cash and $48
in Qwest stock or cash) and U S West shareholders $69 in stock or
cash as long as Qwest's stock trades in a range of $30.50 to
$43.50.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the offers appear clear-cut. But under the
terms of their deals with Global Crossing, the boards of both
companies have to conclude that Qwest's offer is adequately
``superior'' to Global's before they can begin negotiations with
Qwest. (U S West's board is expected to meet later this week.) Some
of the issues they will be discussing include these:
</P>
<P>
   STRATEGIC VALUE: Few investors are fully convinced of the
soundness of the strategic rationale of either Qwest or Global
Crossing. U S West, often called ``U S Worst'' by analysts, is one
of the most troubled Bell companies. But U S West and Frontier have
what Qwest and Global Crossing, both upstarts, say they need _ cash
and customers. In essence, what the boards of U S West and Frontier
have to decide is whether Global Crossing or Qwest has the better
vision to take their companies into the new telecommunications age,
combining conventional cable and copper wires with the digital
universe of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   William Deatherage, a telecommunications analyst at Bear,
Stearns, warns that a company created by the merger of U S West,
Frontier and Global Crossing would still not have ``the critical
mass of other national companies,'' like AT&AMP;T. Speaking of Qwest's
bid, he noted that the company has several hurdles to overcome but
added that a combination of Qwest, U S West and Frontier would have
``the makings of a credible competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Qwest, a two-year-old company, is further along in its
development than Global Crossing. Already, Qwest has 8,500
employees, and it had 1998 revenues of $2.24 billion. In the United
States, it has more than 18,500 miles of fiber optic cables and is
set to complete that nationwide network this month. It is also
expanding into Mexico and has joint ventures in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing has one operating undersea cable, with several
others still under construction and expected to be complete within
a year. It went public last year, and revenues at the end of 1998
totaled $424 million. By the end of this week, it will employ about
1,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   DEAL STRUCTURE: Global Crossing has signed merger agreements
with U S West and Frontier and said it did not plan to increase its
bid. Global plans to create two kinds of stock in the combined
company, one representing shares of its high-growth Internet
assets, the other made up of the slower-growing telephone assets.
But the deal's structure, while novel, poses a challenge to
investors who want to compare it with Qwest's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest said it would combine fast- and slow-growing assets into
one telecommunications hybrid. That concerns investors who bought
Qwest shares with the hope of turbo-charged growth. An acquisition
of U S West could cut Qwest's growth rate nearly in half.
</P>
<P>
   Because the demand for a global telecommunications network is
being driven by expansion of the Internet, Qwest's and Global
Crossing's shares experience the sharp swings characteristic of
Internet stocks. When Qwest revised its bid on Wednesday, it added
the trading range to protect Frontier and U S West shareholders in
case Qwest's stock should plummet further.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Nacchio, the chief executive of Qwest, said the company
made the move in response to concerns expressed by Frontier and U S
West. (Downside protection was a sticking point in Global
Crossing's negotiations with Frontier, too.) But it is yet to be
seen if the range _ Qwest is trading near the bottom _ provides
enough comfort to appease both boards.
</P>
<P>
   REGULATORY RISKS: Here Global Crossing and Qwest are faced with
similar issues: U S West is restricted from offering long-distance
service in its 14-state territory until it proves to regulators
that its local markets are open to competition.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, which is based in Bermuda, has no assets yet in
the United States, so its regulatory concerns are limited to
Frontier's customer overlap in U S West's territory. Qwest doesn't
have it so easy. It is the fourth-largest domestic long-distance
company and Frontier is No. 5. For Qwest to buy both Frontier and U
S West, it would need to shed a considerable number of
long-distance customers in U S West's region. Qwest has said it
would do whatever is necessary to satisfy regulators. Like any
deal, this one could take months to close, giving U S West time to
open local markets. But the uncertainty is something the boards
will have to consider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
