<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, June 28. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Belgrade) _ The collapse of Greater Serbia can be
told through the story of one Serbian family, expelled from
Croatia, resettled near Belgrade, then bounced to Kosovo, and now
living in squalid housing outside Belgrade again. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOMB-DAMAGE (Djakovica) _ In the two weeks since NATO
forces arrived in Kosovo, alliance officials have scaled back their
initial estimates of the damage inflicted by the 78-day air
campaign on the Yugoslav army, which they concede remains a force
capable of maintaining Slodoban Milosevic's grip on power. While
NATO and Pentagon officials stand by their claims to have
significantly damaged the Yugoslav army and special police, they
acknowledge that the units that withdrew from Kosovo a week ago
were clearly not as damaged as they had believed. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GAY-SEX (New York) _ A study of homosexual men in New York
City has found that they have significantly reduced their levels of
risky sexual behavior; the number of men infected with the AIDS
virus has dropped sharply.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MENTAL-HEALTH (New York) _ A recent tragedy on the city
subway system illustrates the city's failure to find and treat
mentally-ill people.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ASBESTOS (Washington) _ Congress prepares for a
legislative solution to asbestos litigation. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
