<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening low pressure colliding with a very warm and humid
air mass over the southern Great Lakes will trigger many showers
and thunderstorms on Monday. As the low moves to the east, abundant
amounts of moisture in the atmosphere will lead to thunderstorms
with locally heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   A jet-stream disturbance at 18,000 feet passing over the
Carolinas will bring an area of clouds, showers, and thunderstorms
to the Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a weak warm front pushing through northern New
England will usher showers into parts of Maine and New Hampshire.
This front marks the leading edge of a very warm and humid air
mass. The Northeast and much of the Middle Atlantic States will
experience yet another day of sultry conditions, with scattered
afternoon storms possible.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure sliding along the northern border of North Dakota
will draw cooler, drier air to the south over the northern Plains.
On the southern periphery of this high, a moist flow from the
southeast will encourage thunderstorm development over the
mountains of Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Northwest will stay unseasonably cool and damp, as
yet another upper-air disturbance brings clouds and a few showers
to parts of the Washington coast and into the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest will remain very hot and dry, with only a few
afternoon thunderstorms developing over the mountains of Arizona.
Some of this very warm air aloft will move over parts of Texas and
Oklahoma, preventing the development of any regions of widespread
storms.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Northern Contrasts
</P>
<P>
   Two surges of hot air into upper Michigan sent the mercury to a
record high of 89 degrees early Saturday afternoon and then 90
degrees later in the day at Marquette. Meanwhile, at daybreak
Sunday, the temperature fell to 34 degrees at Williston, N.D.,
eclipsing the previous record by 5 degrees. The contrasting records
in the northern tier indicate a strengthening jet stream, which is
driven by such thermal contrasts. Indeed, weather systems that
drifted across the nation last week will pick up the pace this
week, bringing frequent changes to the border states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
