<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY 
Even a non-tennis fan can appreciate today on Centre Court at
Wimbledon: American Jim Courier tries to topple British favorite
Tim Henman, former champ Boris Becker plays what should be his
final match on the All-England facility against Patrick Rafter, and
then there's all the glitter of Venus Williams vs. Anna Kournikova.
Jolly good. Wimbledon, Channel 4 and HBO, 9 a.m. (NBC and HBO have
weekday coverage each morning). 
TUESDAY 
You hear about those people who, in a fit of despair, fancy jumping
off the Golden Gate Bridge. But imagine how it could be prevented
if a permanent bungee-jumping platform was installed this week
during the X Games. Here, you give them a chance to reconsider,
right? See, the X Games can benefit society. On the other hand, HBO
has this hour-long documentary that dispels the myth that sports
isn't a life-or-death situation. X Games: Bicycle stunt riding,
skateboarding and sky surfing, ESPN2, 6 p.m. and ESPN, 10 p.m.
(Airs each day at the same times on ESPN2 and ESPN, with ABC's
``Wide World of Sports'' devoting an hour to it Saturday and Sunday
at 2 p.m.); ``Xtreme: Sports To Die For,'' HBO, 8 p.m. 
WEDNESDAY 
With the first pick of the 1999 NBA Draft, the Chicago Bulls select
Richard Simmons _ to pull Jerry Krause from the buffet table, chain
him to a Stairmaster and try to make him at least presentable in
public. NBA Draft, TNT, 4:30 p.m. 
THURSDAY 
In the quarterfinal elimination match, our beloved U.S. team faces
Brazil/Germany/Italy. Win or lose, we've got to find a way to
stretch this thing another three weeks. Women's World Cup
quarterfinals, ESPN, 4 p.m. and ESPN2, 6:30 p.m. (ESPN also has two
quarterfinal games Wednesday at 5 p.m. and 9 p.m.) 
FRIDAY 
The real fireworks don't start until after Sunday's matinee, but
the fuse should be lit for these two all weekend. Giants at
Dodgers, Channel 5, 7:10 p.m. (Fox Channel 11 has Saturday's game
at 1:05 p.m.) 
SATURDAY 
Last year's Pepsi 400 was supposed to be the first auto race ever
broadcast live in prime time on network television, but wildfires
in Daytona Beach and the surrounding areas snuffed that one out. So
they'll try it again this year. Gentlemen, start your headlights.
NASCAR Winston Cup Pepsi 400 from Daytona Beach, Fla., Channel 2, 5
p.m. 
SUNDAY 
Since this will be the last Fourth of July of the 1900s, we'd like
to see Bud Collins in red, white and blue striped pants doing
commentary on an all-American men's final at Wimbledon. We're
banking on Pete Sampras steering clear to make it to a match
against Andre Agassi, if he's up to it. As for Collins, he
represents why we had the revolution in the first place _ to gain
the freedom to make as big a fool of ourselves as we want to.
Wimbledon men's final, Channel 4, 6 a.m. (NBC also has the women's
final Saturday at 6 a.m.). 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
