A1203 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMICS-BOONDOCKS-SPI &LR;      06-27 1683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMICS-BOONDOCKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOONDOCKS' CREATOR HAS MANY PEOPLE TALKING ABOUT COMIC STRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You are bright-eyed and 24.
</P>
<P>
   You sketch a comic strip that features hip, at times flip, black
kids.
</P>
<P>
   You watch as readers rave, then rant, then _ uh oh! _ rant some
more.
</P>
<P>
   You hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   Some people call your strip humorous and fun, and praise its
cutting-edge coolness. Others say it is ugly, divisive, offensive,
witless, racist and bad. ``This thing is worthless!'' one adult
reader in Seattle growls.
</P>
<P>
   You now have a hint of how it feels to walk in Aaron McGruder's
shoes. The brainy and unflappable creator of ``The Boondocks,'' a
new nationally syndicated comic strip, has folks buzzing from
Atlanta and Chicago to Washington, D.C., and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   McGruder's comic strip was first published this spring in dozens
of U.S. newspapers, including the Seattle Post-Intelligencer, and
is now carried in more than 180 papers. Whether it is clever
commentary or self-indulgent drivel is an argument playing out in
several arenas, from letters to the editor, to phone calls from
readers, to huddles in office gathering spots.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer Managing Editor Ken Bunting says the
newspaper has had ``lots of negative feedback from readers'' since
the strip began. He and other P-I editors are watching carefully as
the strip and its story line develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious that Aaron is a real talent, with a fresh,
unique approach that has an edge,'' Bunting says. ``The question
for me will be whether he can touch on topics like race, class and
human relations in a manner that is funny and provocative, without
also being so offensive to so many readers. I don't have my
definitive answer yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But amid the controversy, one thing is clear: At an age when
many artists are lucky to get any audience for their work,
McGruder, one of just a handful of black syndicated comic-strip
artists, is breaking ground _ and striking a nerve in the papers
that venture into ``The Boondocks.''
</P>
<P>
   His distinctive drawing style delivers edgy figures with sweet _
if not always smiling _ faces. Overall, he says his work gives
voice to a slice of life that gets little ink in the conservative
arena of the funny pages: the suburban experience of young blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Few comic strips, for example, would dare get tangled up in the
politics of black hair or have a black character make random
traffic stops of white motorists as part of ``Operation
Klanwatch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the strip is ultimately about is who we are as black
people, what it means to be black and black self-identity,''
McGruder says, his voice competing with a blaring television.
``It's a racial satire. A social satire. Sometimes a political
satire.''
</P>
<P>
   He quips, ``It's definitely not `The Cosby Show.'''
</P>
<P>
   The strip focuses on four inner-city kids _ three black boys and
one biracial girl _ who are negotiating the unpredictable terrain
of a predominantly white and suburban world.
</P>
<P>
   Let's meet them:
</P>
<P>
   Huey R. Freeman, the protagonist, is a black nationalist who
believes that he is ``blacker than Richard Roundtree,'' the actor
who immortalized ``hood hipness'' in the 1970s ``Shaft'' movies.
Huey is pretentious, but has a kind heart. (McGruder says he would
be most like Huey if he were a kid.)
</P>
<P>
   Riley, Huey's younger brother, wears a deep scowl and is a
``gangsta'' wannabe. Caesar, Huey's best friend, is fun-loving and
totes a microphone. Jazmine, a young biracial neighbor, is
struggling with her racial identity.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the strip's humor is generated from how the characters
balance issues of racial politics, self-pride, youth and current
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not see much point in doing the thing some black artists
usually do,'' McGruder says, ``by coming out and saying `I'm not a
black artist, I'm just an artist.' I think that is kind of silly.
So I am unapologetically black. I do a black strip.''
</P>
<P>
   McGruder believes some black artists duck black themes because
they fear they won't attain mainstream success.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have never seen pop culture working that way,'' he says.
``I think that white people who want to buy into black culture
would rather buy into something that's authentic rather than
something that is watered down for their sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Many P-I readers have not been amused; 31 out of 33 local
readers who have contacted the paper's reader representative line
about ``The Boondocks'' have expressed anger. (The Los Angeles
Times received about 100 letters of complaint through early June.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I want to read about angry, bitter, racist
characters?'' one Seattle reader asked.
</P>
<P>
   Another caller fumed: ``This is probably the most disgusting
example of an excuse of a cartoon that I have ever seen in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   One reader called Huey ``an obnoxious little twit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It perpetuates bad stereotypes and there is certainly nothing
funny about it,'' says Karen Ahern, co-chairwoman of the Bainbridge
Unity Coalition, a community group that fights intolerance on
Bainbridge Island, near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 9-year-old daughter, Mariah, thought it was just a really
bad example of African American behavior.'' Ahern adds, ``The
cartoon has mellowed out lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Salem, the editorial director of Universal Press Syndicate,
which picked up ``The Boondocks'' after discovering McGruder two
years ago, says the syndicate was attracted to ``a singular form of
humor and writing we haven't seen. We wanted to take the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, McGruder's work does not sit on the page, it leaps off
it.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of his work dwells on race.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent strip, one of the characters compares the random
killing of insects to the arbitrary nature of U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Neither McGruder nor executives at the syndicate, however,
anticipated the public fallout from the June 4 ``Boondocks'' strip.
</P>
<P>
   In it, a demure white girl is knocked down when Riley hits her
on the head with a toy light saber. Looming over her, Riley huffs,
``See?! You're still alive! This thing is worthless!''
</P>
<P>
   The public reaction was swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is too violent and it's not helping the relations between
blacks and whites,'' slammed Seattle-area resident Jan Rios.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ride public transportation and I hear kids in the bus saying
I think (this strip) is bad stuff,'' another P-I reader criticized.
</P>
<P>
   One man says: ```Boondocks' ... seems not so much a comic strip
as a promotion of hostility and confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   McGruder has been flummoxed by the reaction. The young
cartoonist, who counts ``Bloom County'' and ``Calvin and Hobbes''
as his primary comic-strip influences, just wanted to show Riley
``being a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no clue that it was going to be a problem for
anybody,'' he says. ``The light saber week has been by far the most
controversial of the strips. ... I was dumbfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses and gathers his thoughts. ``I intended (the light
saber strip) to be some very simple Calvin-and-Hobbes-type
childhood mischief thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he says the strip became a litmus test for what he
calls a ``huge double standard'' in how America views depictions of
white violence vs. those of black violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calvin and Hobbes was an extraordinarily violent strip.
There's strips where Calvin is trying to get explosives. ...
Calvin's blowing up his elementary school. ... These were things
that were done quite some time ago, which lead me to believe that a
toy light saber was not going to be that big of a deal,'' McGruder
says with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lindsay, managing editor for features at the Los Angeles
Times, found it interesting that people accepted Calvin as violent
and mean, but seem to be less willing to embrace a Huey.
</P>
<P>
   The recent school shootings at Colorado's Columbine High School
has diminished the tolerance readers have for portrayals of
violence in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the history of comics is spiced with less than savory
characters. Dick Tracy offended readers with its political views
and violence; Andy Capp was blasted by female readers for being an
alcoholic and abusive to his wife. Yet both of those strips
entertained _ or peeved _ people for years.
</P>
<P>
   McGruder says he is still growing into his strip. Salem says
reader reactions to ``The Boondocks'' _ pro and con _ are ``good
for newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   And the strip has die-hard fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me think,'' one e-mailer wrote the L.A. Times.
</P>
<P>
   Another person told that newspaper: ``It makes us take a look at
the whole stupidly ridiculous way we view race here in America. ...
It does my head and heart good to have (my stereotypes) put in the
spotlight and laughed about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the strip. I think it is a good strip,'' said David
Zeeck, executive editor of The News Tribune in Tacoma, which
started ``The Boondocks'' on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Zeeck said early reaction was largely negative. But after the
paper published negative letters, several readers came out of the
woodwork with letters of support for the strip.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks some parents view the comics page as being for
light-hearted, fun topics, not as a forum to deal with prickly
racial issues. ``And Huey's a hard case,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Some newspapers have considered moving the strip away from the
funny pages, to the classified section or perhaps the editorial
pages.
</P>
<P>
   McGruder is taking the attention in stride. Just two years ago,
he was a fresh-faced kid out of the University of Maryland, where
he started the strip for a campus publication.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he lives at home with his parents in suburban Maryland,
and doodles in his bedroom, which has ``Star Wars'' bedsheets.
</P>
<P>
   But life is changing at light-speed. Two weeks ago, he got his
first paycheck from the syndicate _ a sign that perhaps he soon
will be moving into a a galaxy all his own, away from mom and pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's Porsche pay,'' he says with a chuckle.
``Miata pay might be a better way to describe it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NET-DOMAIN-NAMES-2TAK     06-27 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-DOMAIN-NAMES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE IN INTERNET NAME REGISTRATION IS DELAYED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (lb) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The protracted effort to introduce competition into
the lucrative business of registering Internet addresses has been
delayed for at least three weeks because of escalating tensions
among the Clinton administration, its handpicked successor for
running the global network and the government contractor that has
had a monopoly on the business.
</P>
<P>
   The delay is just the latest sign that the debate on the issue _
which has previously been confined largely to Internet insiders _
is quickly turning into a high-profile, high-stakes political game
of chicken, the results of which could lead to a dangerous tug of
war over what is essentially the Internet's telephone directory.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers on the move to break up Network Solutions
Inc.'s hold on the business of registering the so-called domain
names that people use as Internet addresses in the popular
directories of .com, .net and .org. The company has had the
exclusive worldwide right since 1993 to assign Internet addresses
that end in any of those three-letter suffixes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in what was to be the final step in a decade-long
process of transferring control of the Internet to the private
sector, the Commerce Department created the Internet Corp. for
Assigned Names and Numbers, or ICANN, to oversee the network.
</P>
<P>
   ICANN's charge was to open up the registration of Internet
addresses to competition. But the creation of ICANN and just about
everything its interim board has proposed have stirred opposition
and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The latest delay comes on the heels of a letter-writing campaign
by Ralph Nader and tax watchdog groups and an inquiry from the
chairman of the powerful House Commerce Committee, Rep. Thomas
Bliley, R-Va., questioning the actions and the authority of the
Commerce Department and ICANN. The potential fallout of the dispute
threatens both the centralized structure of the Internet and the
ability of ICANN to carry out its task.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great political theater,'' Michael Roberts, the interim
president of ICANN, said of the intense lobbying from both sides
that has moved to Capitol Hill and high levels of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said discussions about the dispute and its potential
effect on how the Internet operates have reached both the Pentagon
and the president's Critical Infrastructure Assurance Office.
</P>
<P>
   Those questioning ICANN say they are concerned that the interim
board is overstepping its authority. They have seized on the
board's refusal to hold open board meetings and its decision to
impose a $1-a-year fee on every domain name registered.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley sent blistering letters to Commerce Secretary William
Daley and to Esther Dyson, the interim chairwoman of ICANN, on
Tuesday. That was the same day a special congressional commission,
headed by Gov. James Gilmore of Virginia, convened its first
meeting on Internet tax policy in Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley's accompanying news release offered a preview of the
potential political fallout that some fear could find its way into
the campaigns against Vice President Al Gore, who has positioned
himself as a champion of a tax-free, unregulated Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this ironic,'' Bliley said, ``just as Gov. Gilmore is
working hard with the Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce to
encourage the growth of electronic commerce, ICANN is imposing a
tax on the Internet behind closed doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliley's letters ask for records and information about the
process used to select ICANN's interim board members and set its
$5.9 million budget, as well any analysis of its legal authority to
levy the $1 fee. The letters also seek information about statements
that ICANN officials made threatening to terminate the authority of
Network Solutions, a Virginia company, to register new Internet
addresses during its last meeting, in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   After that threat, Network Solutions began a full-scale lobbying
effort in Washington, seeking an investigation of ICANN. ICANN,
meanwhile, has accused the company of ``funding and otherwise''
fostering much of the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Although ICANN has since acknowledged that only the Commerce
Department has the authority to cut off Network Solutions' right to
register domain names, the company is also deadlocked with Commerce
officials over crucial details for opening its registry to
full-scale competition.
</P>
<P>
   One of five companies picked in April for the first round of
competition with Network Solutions, Register.com, has been
successfully registering names for several weeks. And ICANN and the
Commerce Department had hoped to open the system to more companies
on Friday. Instead, they announced the three-week delay, and people
close to the process said that they expected it to drag on even
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides making sure that the technical bugs can be worked out to
ensure that the $20 million system that Network Solutions built
will run smoothly when multiple competitors come online, the two
sides remain deadlocked on key issues that were supposed to have
been ironed out months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The major question is who has rights to the Network Solutions
database that holds the information about who owns the more than 5
million registered domain names.
</P>
<P>
   They are also wrangling over how much the companies entering the
business will have to pay Network Solutions to administer the
central registry. Network Solutions also must reach an agreement on
terms under which it will recognize ICANN's authority. Network
Solutions has refused to sign the contract ICANN has developed,
saying it is overly restrictive and gives ICANN more power than the
administration intended when it drafted its plan for handing
Internet oversight to the private, nonprofit body.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, meanwhile, insists that if Network Solutions refuses to
compromise, the Commerce Department and ICANN could find another
company to take over administration of .com, .net and .org. But
that could not be done quickly or easily and would likely cause
some disruptions for Internet users and electronic commerce.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario could also force a split in the root of the
Internet, which is essentially the phone book of the Internet.
Roberts said ICANN was preparing to move the main root server for
the network from Network Solutions' headquarters in Herndon, Va.,
to California.
</P>
<P>
   But unless Network Solutions agrees to hand over the
corresponding data for that root, it might not immediately be able
to find all of the names that Network Solutions has registered.
That could create chaos on the Internet because computer users or
their Internet service providers would have to know the so-called
IP address of any site they wanted to visit or send e-mail to _ for
example, 204.177.154.13 instead of www.amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions, meanwhile, could continue running its own
root server, meaning that Internet service providers would have to
either choose between the roots, set up their systems to recognize
both or create their own roots.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Burr, a senior Commerce Department aide leading the
negotiations, said she remained optimistic that the problems would
be resolved without such drastic measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we'll get there,'' she said on Friday. ``I
believe it is in everybody's best interest not to swing threats
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so sure. A group of Internet technical experts
has begun talking about what the Internet might look like without a
central root system _ and without ICANN.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Auerbach, a video network developer for Cisco Systems Inc.
who has been involved in the Internet's engineering task force for
years, says he does not think a split root would be such a bad
thing. He said a split would essentially force Internet service
providers to create a competing list of directories, much as
telephone companies do.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would result is that each of the root systems would try
to be more inclusive than its neighbors, and the net result would
be that they all end up being essentially the same as everybody,''
he said. ``The number to Fred's Barber Shop would still be the
number to Fred's Barber Shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a system, he said, could also allow Internet service to
cater to certain cultural or age groups, meaning they could set
their directories to keep their customers' Web browsers from
reaching certain sites that they might find offensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
