<HEADLINE>
FRONTLINE SHOW ON WORKINGS OF IMF IS UNSETTLING, FRIGHTENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Need a good scare? Don't wait for Jan de Bont's remake of ``The
Haunting'' next month. Just watch ``Frontline'' on Tuesday night.
If it doesn't make you start hoarding quarters, you've got what it
takes to be a global capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Me? I'll be busy with the travel brochures and Heloise's hints
on stowing away aboard Boeing jets. There must be someplace in the
world where the International Monetary Fund isn't welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF is easily the bete noire in this ``Frontline'' piece,
airing on PBS. Described dispassionately as ``a kind of credit
union for countries in crisis,'' it also is characterized more
pointedly as ``the Typhoid Mary of emerging markets.''
</P>
<P>
   That last remark is from Harvard economist Jeffrey Sachs, a
critic of economic policies promoted by the U.S. Treasury and the
IMF. Sachs and others believe big-time investors no longer fear
losing their shirts in high-risk overseas ventures because they
figure the IMF will always bail out troubled economies and keep
high-rollers' shirts in place. This decade, the IMF has done
exactly that when the economies of Mexico, Asia, Russia and Brazil
got stuck in the toaster.
</P>
<P>
   In examining the rickety underpinnings of the new global economy
that many Americans hail as the slickest thing since pay-per-view,
``Frontline'' wonders if there's a big economic crash in our own
future.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tuesday's program is titled ``The Crash'' because it
harks back to last Aug. 31, when the Dow Jones industrial average
dropped 512 points and had a lot of investors wondering if it was
time to do the Kevorkian. Of course, the Dow has risen an
incredible 40 percent since then. Three thousand points in 10
months! But what our 401(k) statements don't show is that 40
percent of the world is in a recession, and millions of poor people
who became middle class during the ``tiger economies'' of the early
'90s are poor again. Not the big-time investors, mind you, but the
people who live in the countries where the economies went south
after tying their fortunes to the dollar and opening themselves up
to a flood of speculative foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
   For people not versed in the everyday jargon of arbitrage,
producer Sherry Jones does a splendid job of making a point that's
easy to miss when the paper money is rolling in. Here's how Robert
Johnson, a former portfolio manager for Soros Fund Management, puts
it: ``Our stock market's at an all-time high. (But) it's a little
bit like fiddling while Rome burns, because the world is struggling
all around us.''
</P>
<P>
   With due diligence, Tuesday's ``Frontline'' lets the IMF have
its say _ the official line is that the world crisis is not as bad
as advertised _ but, in typical ``Frontline'' style, the message of
``The Crash'' remains clear and well-stated: Don't get greedy.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   After three years at Fox News Channel, Catherine Crier is
leaving for Court TV to tap into her training as a lawyer. Paula
Zahn, who anchors Fox's evening newscast, will also host a new
prime-time program in place of ``The Crier Report,'' which airs at
7 p.m. and midnight in the West. ... Though The WB has scheduled
the postponed season finale of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' for
July 13, the fate of another pulled episode, originally scheduled
for April 27, is still up in the air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
