<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1212 &Cx1f; tth-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ASHLAND-REVIEW     06-27 2352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ASHLAND-REVIEWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINI-REVIEWS OF SHAKESPEARE PRODUCTIONS AT ASHLAND FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOE ADCOCK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Henry IV, Part Two. To emphasize the boys-will-be-boys nature
of this political and military action/adventure story, ``Henry IV,
Part Two,'' director Libby Appel uses an all-male cast.
</P>
<P>
   As with any might-makes-right drama in which authority, majesty
and venal institutions are glorified, ``Henry IV, Part Two'' is
hard to take at times. But Appel's casting experiment certainly
pays off. The feats of virtuoso acting are fun to watch. Dan
Donohue, for example, is boyish and then manly as England's royal
prince. Donohue also plays the lowly clowns Wart and Fang. Even
better, G. Valmont Thomas plays both the doughty rebel knight
Colville and the ludicrous innkeeper Mistress Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Also funny and outrageous is Ken Albers as the parasitical and
opportunistic Sir John Falstaff. Albers starts buoyant and
dissolute. Over the course of the play's nearly three hours, he
steadily declines into demoralized exhaustion. Falstaff is a
barometer of ``Henry IV, Part Two's'' political climate. He blooms
in the early atmosphere of cozy chaos. He withers when
law-and-order comes into its own.
</P>
<P>
   _ Othello. The rap on this bizarre tragedy is that it is
preposterous and unbelievable. The title character is brilliant but
stupid. The villain, Iago, is driven. He's a fiend. But it's hard
to comprehend what it could possibly be that is driving such
outrageous fiendishness. That's all on the level of sociological
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Director Tony Taccone is not concerned with sociological reality
in this brilliant, stirring production. His ``Othello'' looks and
sounds like a powerful ritual. It moves on the level of emotional
and spiritual realities.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of candles loom in the background during the killing
scene, making death seem like a religious sacrifice. A
nowhere/anywhere world of Venetian blind slats creates a scene of
spying, hiding and hampered perception. Music suggests a pounding
heart, occasionally disrupted by shattering dissonances. The
characters wear costumes that are part long ago and far away and
part here and now.
</P>
<P>
   In this irrational but compelling world, Othello and Iago and
their many unfortunate cohorts are comprehensible. As Othello,
Derrick Lee Weeden is a cunning soldier, professionally, and a
befuddled innocent, romantically. His beloved Desdemona as played
by Amy Cronies is enough of a flirt and a sexual manipulator to
make Iago's accusations of infidelity a little plausible. Anthony
Heald, as Iago, is one of those borderline personalities we all
meet from time to time: glib and desperate, halting and inventive,
absurd and yet somehow convincing. He's delusional, paranoid and
compulsive.
</P>
<P>
   As Cassio, the lieutenant who has supposedly, according to
Iago's allegations, seduced Desdemona, Andrew Borba is unusually
interesting in a role that can come off as no more than a plot
device. Fight choreographer John Sipes does a fantastic job with
the crazed brawl that Cassio sets off in his alcoholic fury.
</P>
<P>
   Taccone's presentation of infatuation and dishonesty, passion
and madness, give the bizarre incidents of ``Othello'' the look of
things that, alas, happen every day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Much Ado About Nothing. This dark comedy has an all-out
villain, but Don John is merely a plot device. He helps to weave a
background fabric. The fabric serves one purpose: it gives the
celebrated Beatrice and Benedick a foundation on which to work out
their intricate needlepoint of wit and love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much Ado'' holds the world record for eavesdropping and
deception. Two ninnies, Hero and Claudio, mean to marry. The
nefarious Don John slanders Hero. Claudio backs out of the
marriage. Through the good offices of a team of clown constables,
the baselessness of the libel comes to light. So the ninnies marry
after all.
</P>
<P>
   But that background is mostly stage dressing for the Beatrice
and Benedick show. Elizabeth Norment and Mark Murphy make an
unusually nuanced B and B. Their put-down humor is funny. But it
has a certain awkwardness; it has the poignancy of unduly prolonged
adolescence. Pride takes a beating if a person is playing catch-up
in the game of romance. Norment and Murphy are good with that agony
and urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Director James Edmondson has worked out ample visual humor. He
emphasizes the comic aspect of this dark comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson has chosen to set this ``Much Ado'' in early
20th-century Argentina. Lots of military braggadoccio. Lots of
preening machismo. Lots of punctilio about virginity and such. And,
best of all, the Argentine milieu provides a pretext for a flashy
tango finale.
</P>
<P>
   Other shows
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Seven Guitars'' by August Wilson. This tragedy is set in
Pittsburgh's black ghetto in 1948. The seven guitars referred to in
the title are actually four men and three women. Like members of a
jazz ensemble, each player has a particular temperament and tone, a
characteristic tempo and volume. Each has his or her characteristic
riffs. Each tells stories that define individual and collective
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   And like any blues tune, ``Seven Guitars'' is never exactly the
same piece twice. Director Benny Leon's version is both livelier
and quieter than what we've grown used to in Seattle from Wilson's
preferred director, Lloyd Richards. When the characters are rowdy,
they really bounce and whoop. When they are meditative, the theater
becomes as still as a Zen temple. And when anger flashes, it looks
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The personification of anger and danger is Derrick Lee Weeden as
a West Indian immigrant, Hedley, who has been driven half-mad by
degradation and disappointment. As Hedley, Weeden conveys delusions
of grandeur as skillfully as he portrays Othello's crazed loss of
grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Leon draws out high definition, high-energy characterizations
from his whole ensemble: G. Valmont Thomas as a bouncy drummer,
Kevin Kenerly as a quirky harmonica man; Ken LaRon as a passionate
and desperate singer/guitarist; Susan Champion as a young woman who
has ``a certain effect on men''; Andrea Frye as a brassy beautician
who is wised-up and sassy; and Deidrie Henry as a mature woman torn
between desire and fear, hope and despair.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Rosmersholm'' by Henrik Ibsen. According to that pioneering
drama critic Aristotle, an effective tragedy ``purges'' us.
Different tragedies purge different things for different people at
different times.
</P>
<P>
   For me, just now, the excellent festival production of Ibsen's
1886 tragedy ``Rosmersholm'' helps purge all that Monica
Lewinsky/Whitewater/Ken Starr stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen's protagonist is an ineffectual but prominent man. He has
vague ideals. He talks a lot. He accomplishes little. Along comes
an irresistible young woman. Trouble. Along comes an
arch-conservative, prurient, nosy self-appointed special
prosecutor. More trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels are not exact. But the denouement is so absolutely
decisive, so final.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is using a new translation from the Norwegian by
former artistic director Jerry Turner, who also stages the show.
Ibsen can seem stilted on the American stage, but Turner's
``Rosmersholm'' might be a respectable older cousin of ``The Young
and the Restless.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Goodwin Nordli is subtlety itself as the lovely yet
sinister Rebecca West. She's part ruthless Nietzschean superwoman
and part Victorian sweety pie. Anthony Heald is energetically
futile as the prominent, ineffectual man. Richard Farrell is
remorselessly priggish as the special prosecutor. Progressively
bleaker decor and lighting help the scary work of dramatic
purgation.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Good Person of Szechuan'' by Bertolt Brecht. This thorny
epic bristles with bitter satire, high-stress melodrama, class
conflict skirmishes, sardonic little songs, farcical theology and
brain-spraining dialectical materialism. It requires a dozen
actors. They play 30 roles. Then there are some musicians. The show
runs three hours. It is definitely a major undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Director Penny Metropulos' production is a triumph of style:
beautiful set, expressive costumes, dramatic lighting and
high-voltage acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Person'' is a Dr. Jekyll/Mr. Hyde tale. Shen Te, a
prostitute, is compassionate and generous. When three deities come
to earth looking for a truly good person, they find only one: Shen
Te. They reward her with $1,000. She buys a tobacco shop. Her
compassion and generosity nearly bankrupt her.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that compassion and generosity are not effective
business strategies, Shen Te devises an alter ego. She disguises
herself as a man, her alleged cousin, the cunning and hard-driving
Shui Ta, who quickly becomes a tobacco magnate.
</P>
<P>
   Brecht was cynical to the point of nihilism. He has an abstract
abhorrence of poverty. But the actual poor people in his plays are
manipulative, dishonest and generally repulsive.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the interest of ideological neatness, Brecht contends
that there is ``an answer'' to poverty, inequality, injustice and
exploitation. By the time Brecht died in 1956, ideological neatness
was eclipsed by political messiness. The supposed ``answer'' was
East Germany, where Brecht lived as a celebrity, a member of the
new privileged class.
</P>
<P>
   Director Metropulos' production of ``Good Person'' is not just a
triumph of style. It is also a triumph of aesthetic discipline over
political indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   In the title role, BW Gonzalez is a wonder of energetic
versatility as the romantic and emotional Shen Te and the mean and
crafty Shui Ta.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``El Paso Blue'' by Octavio Solis. This tragi-comedy could be
``Othello's'' Chicano cousin. Al, a Texas Mexican, marries Sylvie,
a lovely blonde (``third runner-up in the Miss Texas contest!'').
Al, unlike Othello, has ample reason to be jealous. His own father,
Marcelo, becomes Sylvie's lover while Al is in jail.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``El Paso Blue'' is even more bizarre,
preposterous and unbelievable than ``Othello.'' But like
``Othello'' director Tony Taccone, the director of ``El Paso
Blue,'' Tim Bond, stages this 100-minute one-act in such a way that
it casts a compelling spell.
</P>
<P>
   Bond cross-breeds Yankee hyper-realism with Latino magic
realism. His actors walk and talk like Rio Grande marginals, El
Paso desperadoes. But set, lighting, music and dramatic structure
conjure up dreams and paranormal marvels. As Sylvie, Linda Halaska
stops being a drunken slut from time to time and sings, sometimes
in English, sometimes in Spanish. In a whiskey soprano she evokes
bluesy versions of ill-fated love. She is accompanied by the
composer of these songs, Michael ``Hawkeye'' Herman, who is seated
with dobro, guitar and other musical essentials in the bed of a
broken-down pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   I would recommend adventurous playgoers who happen to be in
Ashland take time to see ``El Paso Blue.'' But they will have to
get here by June 26, the day of the play's final performance.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Chicago'' by Maurine Watkins. Violence as entertainment,
justice as farce and hypocrisy as a prerequisite to successful
public life _ very up-to-the-minute. The festival puts these
seemingly timely disgraces into historical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago'' (the 1926 play on which the musical of 30 years ago
was based) has been revived by director Kenneth Albers. His show is
a lot like a Saturday morning ``Kartoon Kaper'': loud,
two-dimensional and aggressively unsubtle. But a cartoon runs for
20 minutes, max. ``Chicago's'' noisy caricatures of city life,
lawyers, prosecutors, police, husbands, jailers, inmates, jurors
and even journalists run a little over two hours. After about 20
minutes, the yelling and posturing become monotonous.
</P>
<P>
   Playwright Watkins covered crime for the Chicago Tribune in the
'20s. In 1924 she got months of Page One bylines with sensational
stories about two lovely confessed murderesses who, what with one
thing and another, were acquitted. ``Chicago'' is based on that
experience. It was a Broadway hit. DeMille Pictures made it into a
(blessedly) silent movie. In 1942, Ginger Rogers starred in a film
version called ``Roxie Hart.''
</P>
<P>
   As she grew older, Watkins was loath to permit further stagings
or adaptations of ``Chicago.'' It was not until after her death in
1968 that Bob Fosse could buy the rights to create a musical
version. Watkins had profound reservations about the cynicism,
flippancy and farcical satire of ``Chicago.'' Well she might.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Three Musketeers,'' adapted by Linda Alper, Douglas
Langworthy and Penny Metropulos from Alexandre Dumas' novel. This
is twaddle. But at least it is well-aged, vigorous twaddle. Dumas'
1844 novel has been brought to life by at least a dozen filmmakers
and almost that many playwrights. Yet the old war horse will
probably be a crowd pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   The story doesn't really have a plot. But it has enough
conflicts to fill 50 tales: Catholics vs. Protestants, King Louis
XIII vs. Cardinal Richelieu, Queen Anne vs. husband Louis, Queen
Anne vs. the cardinal, the cardinal's guards vs. the king's
musketeers, England vs. France, Athos vs. the Countess de Winter;
the countess vs. D'Artagnon _ and on and on. Love relationships,
flirtations, seductions, friendships and romances are almost as
plentiful as animosities.
</P>
<P>
   Holding all this loosely together are the events of 1625 to 1628
as they pertain to D'Artagnon. He comes to Paris, a boy bumpkin
from Gascony. The three musketeers turn him into a Real Man. John
Hansen is fiery and gallant as D'Artagnon. He comports himself
honorably in the swinging-on-a-rope bit without which no ``Three
Musketeers'' (or ``Tarzan'') show would be complete.
</P>
<P>
   Metropulos stages the spectacle with lavish everything: fencing,
romancing, dancing, fleeing, chasing, quivering and raging. There
are some 30 major characters and about half that many
supernumeraries. Composer Todd Barton provides musical underscoring
that makes sure we know when to get excited, when to get sad and
when to get mushy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
