<HEADLINE>
AS THEY LIKE IT: OREGON FESTIVAL RIDING HIGH ON BARD'S WAVE OF
POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOE ADCOCK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHLAND, Ore. _ Thank you, Gwyneth.
</P>
<P>
   Big movies have advertising budgets that run into the millions
of dollars. America's largest non-profit theater venture has hardly
any ad budget at all.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the Oregon Shakespeare Festival is getting a sort
of ricochet promotional bounce from celebrated movies such as
``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' and
``Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   William Shakespeare is currently prominent on the ``A list'' of
bankable Hollywood names.
</P>
<P>
   And his hot status is not likely to cool off quickly. More
Shakespeare-based movies will be coming along in the near future:
``Titus'' with Anthony Hopkins, ``Love's Labour's Lost'' directed
by Kenneth Branagh and starring Alicia Silverstone, and ``Hamlet''
with Ethan Hawke.
</P>
<P>
   ``When `Shakespeare in Love' won the Oscar,'' says festival
executive director Paul Nicholson, ``we were featured on the
`Today' show, we were written up in USA Today. That kind of
publicity no amount of money could buy. This is the year of
Shakespeare, and for a lot of people, we are Shakespeare's official
representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Festival artistic director Libby Appel says ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' which featured Oscar-winning performances by Gwyneth
Paltrow and Judi Dench, is essentially a ``wonderful Hollywood
romance.'' But, she adds, ``I couldn't be more thrilled about
anything that helps people see that Shakespeare is timeless and
universal. His work is about our lives and times, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, of course, the movie publicity has been good for our
box-office business,'' Appel says.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which kicked off its outdoor summer shows last
weekend, has just completed its best spring season ever.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the festival had no advertising budget. Media
coverage and word of mouth kept three theaters operating at 90
percent capacity, an astronomical rate by performing-arts
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we have a minuscule advertising budget, something
like $35,000,'' Nicholson says. ``One of the festival's goals is to
reach not more people necessarily but a broader spectrum of people.
So we've been experimenting with ways to draw in the Hispanic and
African American communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in 1935, the Ashland festival has grown into
one of Southern Oregon's major industries: $14.6 million budget,
762 performances, 354,147 tickets sold.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the festival plans to open a new $8 million intimate
showbox with about 300 seats, replacing its tiny 138-seat Black
Swan Theater.
</P>
<P>
   As usual when Ashland makes changes, there has been a local
outcry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are really fond of the Black Swan, they love the
intimacy,'' says Nicholson. ``But from a producer's point of view,
the Black Swan is not intimate. It's cramped.''
</P>
<P>
   In its usual manner when it is contemplating change, the
festival staff is setting up meetings with community groups and
officials to smooth ruffled feathers and to consider local
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the right to do whatever we want, within zoning and
building regulations,'' Appel says. ``We don't need permission. But
we don't want the community to go ballistic. We're in partnership
with the community in a sense. And 14 of our 30 board members are
locals.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO ...
</P>
<P>
   Ashland, Ore., is nine hours south of Seattle via Interstate 5
or 90 minutes by air (to Ashland's neighbor Medford).
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to Oregon Shakespeare Festival productions range from
$11 for standing room to $49 for box seats. The festival offers
discounts for students, seniors and groups. An hour before
showtime, unsold tickets are sometimes available at half-price. The
festival box-office number is 541-482-4331.
</P>
<P>
   The festival operates three theaters: the 600-seat Angus Bowmer,
the 1,200-seat open-air Elizabethan and the 140-seat Black Swan.
Productions at all three theaters continue through the end of
October. Tickets prices are reduced 15 percent starting Oct. 5. In
addition to dramatic productions, the festival offers lectures,
exhibits, play readings, concerts and tours.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is not the only live entertainment in the Ashland
area. The slickest of the so-called ``off-Bardway'' enterprises is
the Oregon Cabaret Theatre. Its current production is the
country-western musical comedy ``Pump Boys and Dinettes.'' Tickets
are $14-$21. Food and drink are available; 541-488-2902.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the Shakespeare Festival brochure is an extensive
guide to accommodations, camping, golf, shopping, sightseeing,
bicycling, child care, river trips, exhibitions and restaurants
throughout the Ashland area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
