<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1214 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GRIFFITHS-SPI &LR;      06-27 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GRIFFITHS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA'S RACHEL GRIFFITHS FAST COMING INTO HER OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ During Australia's early '80s film renaissance,
Britain was sometimes depicted as the evil empire.
</P>
<P>
   Directors such as Peter Weir and Bruce Beresford excoriated
Mother England in movies such as ``Gallipoli'' and ``Breaker
Morant.''
</P>
<P>
   My, how times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   A new wave of talent from Down Under that has crashed upon the
international film shore _ Cate Blanchett, Geoffrey Rush and Rachel
Griffiths, among others _ has embraced England and, better, won a
pile of British Academy and Golden Globe awards and Oscar
nominations because of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth,'' ``Shakespeare in Love'' and ``Hilary and Jackie''
are examples of England and Australia (and half a dozen other
countries as well) aligned artistically in an industry where, as
Blanchett once told me, ``there's no such thing as real nationalism
any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Griffiths may be the least common household name of the
three Aussies, but she's fast coming into her own. The 31-year-old
actress brings a knowing intelligence to each role she undertakes,
and as actor Rush suggested in our 1996 interview, ``She's really
sexy, isn't she?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have sex appeal in a blue cheese kind of way,'' laughs
Griffiths during a recent phone interview. ``You either like it or
you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths won the best supporting actress award in Australia for
her first role as Rhonda, the wild, game-for-anything best friend
in P.J. Hogan's 1995 tragi-comedy, ``Muriel's Wedding,'' and she
hasn't looked back. A string of well-regarded, if little-seen
movies made by Australians followed: ``To Have and to Hold,''
``Cosi,'' ``Amy'' and ``Children of the Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Griffiths took the leap. She co-starred in ``Jude,''
British director Michael Winterbottom's relentlessly grim
adaptation of Thomas Hardy's equally dour novel, and won acclaim in
her brief but sexually charged screen portrayal of Arabella, Jude's
duplicitous wife.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she's worked primarily in England _ ``Among
Giants,'' ``Divorcing Jack'' and her picture-stealing,
Oscar-nominated role in ``Hilary and Jackie,'' which propelled her
career and gave her the pick of projects.
</P>
<P>
   She did a favor to Hogan by making an indelible comedic
appearance in his box office hit ``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' and
then directed the whimsical ``Tulip,'' a short film based upon a
story her mother told about her great uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Now she has returned to England.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths has called to talk about ``My Son the Fanatic,''
another made-in-England venture.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Griffiths plays a prostitute named Bettina who falls in
love with a kind, middle-aged Pakistani taxi driver, played by Om
Puri. The unlikely romance is set against a backdrop of religious
and political upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   The actress is friendly and funny, and she admits she can't
``keep a secret.'' As she discusses her career and life, she's
forthcoming and candid. Yes, she once arrived topless to protest
the opening of a casino in Melbourne, and she believes she has a
responsibility to the world, though ``I don't actually see myself
as political.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a social responsibility, a responsibility
as a person in society to care about, and respond to, how people
are treated. I'm lucky because I have a profile,'' she says,
``though I don't care for politics at all _ or politicians. But I
definitely have very strong feelings that society should care for
its less fortunate and people should be equally respected despite
religion, color or sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should just keep my mouth shut,'' she laughs, ``but I
think many actors have done marvelous work to bring an awareness to
issues that otherwise wouldn't be visible. That might be perceived
cynically by journalists or the public at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths, who grew up in a middle-class Catholic family, says
she sometimes selects roles based upon how her social consciousness
responds to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain kind of human values that I was raised
with, and it has influence on the kind of stories I want to tell.
But more than the roles, I think I'm just more interested in
telling particular stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The different parts you play do affect you. And I've done
roles where I wasn't laughing and joking between takes. In `Hilary
and Jackie,' the role was so oppressive to me and I had to keep so
much of myself contained that between takes I had to get
hyperactive and the kid in me had to come out and run around and be
obnoxious so I could be still on camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I did a role recently in a comedy called `Me, Myself and
I,' and I had to look after my own energy to make sure my onscreen
energy had life and dynamic. I think on `Muriel's Wedding,' I had a
lot of nervous energy. I must say that different roles affect me in
different ways, and I might run around laughing and joking but in
truth, I take my work terribly seriously, and from the moment I
start a job to the wrap party where I write myself off, I live with
the character 24 hours a day. It gets exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   That diligence also has earned Griffiths much attention. The
term ``best-kept secret'' and adjectives like ``hot,'' ``next big
thing'' and ``brink'' are often attached to her name, but the
actress just shrugs off the fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to separate yourself and one's own
self-definition from the way the world defines you. I think if you
really start to rile against the way you're perceived and certainly
the little boxes journalists stuff you in for a quick byline,
you'll get so frustrated and it's just not worth the effort.
Sometimes it amuses me but occasionally I'm right offended for
different reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's why she takes character roles rather than
conventional leads. She likes to buck the system and, with her
recent directing stint, may be looking for alternate ways to ensure
career longevity. But she shrugs at that, saying at the moment
she's not putting ``too much pressure'' on herself to continue
directing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My acting career is going very well right now and I'm doing
some other things, like writing. Directing `Tulip' was an
experience I really enjoyed a lot. But I don't know.'' She laughs
and says, ``I'm certainly not going to publicly commit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
