<HEADER>
A1215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAUX-PROFILE-ART-NY     06-27 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAUX-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL-MAKING ADDS SPICE TO A CAJUN SENATOR'S CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Breaux, D-La., smells some action, some
movement, maybe, down the road, the possibility of a deal. This
makes Breaux a happy man, because he loves making deals.
</P>
<P>
   It clearly still rankles the 55-year-old senator, who was
chairman of the bipartisan commission on Medicare, that he was
unable to deliver a deal on restructuring the 34-year-old health
insurance program for the elderly. His commission disbanded in
March, under fire from President Clinton and utterly polarized over
a proposal that Breaux thought was a workable compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But now the game is on again. ``I love it,'' Breaux declares,
sprawled in a Senate office that is a shrine to guydom: tennis
trophies, stuffed birds shot by the senator back home, fishing
paintings, Mardi Gras posters, family portraits of the four
children and two grandchildren. Breaux says he is pushing forward
with his Medicare proposal in the Senate; the Senate Finance
Committee is trying to move on the issue, and at this very moment
on this Friday morning, two White House aides are outside Breaux's
office, waiting to brief him on Clinton's soon-to-be-unveiled
Medicare plan.
</P>
<P>
   If he cannot be ambassador to France _ more on that later _ what
better challenge than trying to find a lasting remedy for a big,
expensive, endangered program with a fearsome constituency?
</P>
<P>
   Breaux is good at capturing the nervous congressional dance
around Medicare. ``In even years we cut the program, in odd years
we put the money back in,'' he says. ``We cut, last year, $113
billion out of the program, and this year, we'll put money back in
because everybody's hollering. Next year we'll cut it again, then
the year after we'll put the money back. That's the SOS approach _
same old same old _ and it's not doable anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he seems an unlikely player in the Medicare debate, which
tends to have its own wonky priesthood steeped in the arcane
liturgy of managed competition, adverse risk selection and provider
reimbursement rates. This is, after all, a man who takes his
identity with Louisiana seriously. He includes favorite recipes on
his official Senate Web site and never misses a Mardi Gras, which
he celebrates lavishly both here and in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   He first went to Congress in 1967 as an aide to then-Rep. Edwin
Edwards, one of the more flamboyant politicians ever produced in
America, and declares that, ``Being dull would be, to me, just the
ultimate sin.'' He notes that he regularly performs on a stage with
a washboard during Mardi Gras. ``Nobody in Louisiana is going to
get upset,'' he says, ``they've seen hundreds of pictures of me up
on the stage playing the washboard, or running around with an
umbrella.'' Breaux's most famous utterance probably came in 1981
when he declared that his vote could not be bought, ``but it is
available for rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Breaux takes his politics seriously. He was elected to the
House at the age of 28, succeeding Edwards, and after 14 years
there moved to the Senate in 1986, where he landed a seat on the
Finance Committee, ground zero for most of the big tax and health
care issues. In many ways a classic Southern Democrat, always
hunting for the middle of the road, he was a longtime believer in
the Democratic Leadership Council, eventually served as its
chairman, and still preaches its ``third way,'' centrist dogma of
``opportunity, responsibility and community.''
</P>
<P>
   He argues that Medicare is a creaky program with an outdated
benefit package _ notably lacking coverage for prescription drugs _
and an excessively bureaucratic structure. He would replace it with
a competitive system that would offer the elderly an array of
choices, from different managed care plans to the traditional
fee-for-service option that is the norm today; the federal
government would give beneficiaries a fixed amount of money to pay
for the plans.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is anathema to many liberals, and Clinton assailed
it on several grounds, contending its drug benefit was too scanty
and it lacked sufficient safeguards for the traditional Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Breaux go way back, but Breaux insists he has no
hard feelings over Clinton's rough critique. ``Didn't bother me in
the least,'' Breaux says. ``Everybody running around saying, `My,
God, he threw you out to sea without a boat and a paddle.' Didn't
even faze me. He was responding to a large constituency in the
Democratic Party that was very strongly opposed to the
recommendation of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Now change is in the air. Breaux says he thinks the Clinton plan
will be ``a positive good start.'' The two had talked about it
briefly by phone the night before, when the White House tracked
Breaux down at a local steakhouse. For his part, Breaux says he
will begin the hunt for the center. What if there is no center in
this brutally polarized Congress on this ultimate third-rail issue?
``Everything has a center,'' he says with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   It can be fun to be a wonk, Breaux says. ``Clinton obviously is
a wonk, the ultimate wonk, but God he has fun being a wonk,'' the
senator said. ``He got in trouble he's had so much fun being a
wonk.''
</P>
<P>
   His press secretary cleared her throat.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, another dream job for this Cajun whose
father spoke French before he spoke English: ambassador to France.
That moment has probably passed, he acknowledges. ``I asked Clinton
one time, `Do you think I could handle France?''' Breaux says
slyly. ``He said, `The question is whether France could handle
you.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
