<SLUG> BC-TV-GUNS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING FROM ALL SIDES IN BATTLE ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Ill., Mich., Japan) (Eds.: Production notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's gun week on A&AMP;E, five hourlong reports on gun fanciers and
opponents, the companies that make guns, the lobbyists who champion
them, the youngsters who own them and associated matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns in America'' begins Monday night with a look at people
for whom the gun is a recreational tool or a means of defense or a
way to make a living. We meet several ``cowboy action shooters''
who gather from time to time in Wild West garb and play-act events
involving Jesse James, Buffalo Bill and the Deadwood Stage. The
action shooters, who pull their triggers only in fun and never in
anger, are against gun regulations of all sorts.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Nevada, a gun-friendly state, finds Japanese tourists
drawn there to try out weapons that are not available to them at
home. At a Soldiers of Fortune convention featuring slogans like
``Fight Crime, Shoot Back,'' reporters are warned that they are in
``a hostile environment.'' Members of the Michigan Militia are seen
in the woods playing war games, and women who have been victims of
assault are seen perfecting their shooting skills.
</P>
<P>
   Professional gun advocates like Larry Pratt, who speaks for Gun
Owners of America, make a case that gun ownership is in an American
tradition of defending one's homes and families against big
government, and John Lott, the author of ``More Guns, Less Crime,''
reports that his research has persuaded him of the beneficial
consequences of having a gun or two around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, promises Bill Kurtis, the narrator,
``Investigative Reports'' will focus on the National Rifle
Association; on Wednesday, Kurtis interviews Mayor Richard J. Daley
of Chicago about his plans for suing gun manufacturers and dealers;
Thursday turns to the manufacture and sales of guns, and Friday
ends the series with ``Young Guns,'' on children's ``right'' to own
and carry weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns in America'' confirms that despite a post-Littleton surge
of support for gun-control laws, the fight is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INVESTIGATIVE REPORTS: Guns in America'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET, Monday through Friday, on A&AMP;E &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kurtis and Michael Cascio, executive producers; Laura
Fleury, coordinating producer.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night: ``Gun Life,'' written and directed by Heidi Ewing;
produced by Jonathan Stack; Gabriel Films.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: ``Inside the NRA,'' produced and directed by Stephen
Crisman; Patty Tobin, co-producer; Ben Robbins and Tom Folsom,
associate producers; Crisman Films production.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: ``The Gun Effect,'' produced by Ken Arkow; Nicole
Ewing, supervising producer; Seamus Gallagher, associate producer;
Kurtis Productions.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: ``The Gun Makers,'' produced and directed by Crisman;
Chuck Webb, Robbins and Tom Folsom, associate producers; Crisman
Films.
</P>
<P>
   Friday: ``Young Guns,'' produced by Nick London; BBC/A&AMP;E
production; and ``Teen-Agers Under the Gun,'' produced and directed
by Steve Rosenbaum; Dave Goldberg, senior producer; a BNN
production.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
