<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pitchers duel ends with Braves victory
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine have good pitches, good
control, and a good commercial. Their timing ain't bad either.
</P>
<P>
   Picking the N.L. Central leading Astros on the last roadtrip and
the New York Mets this weekend, the dynamic duo won back-to-back
games again just when the Braves needed it. The Mets were in town,
looking for some hope and a pennant race, but left with a 1-0 loss,
their second in a row, and another four-game deficit to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine's seven innings of outstanding work in Saturday's 7-2
win was topped only by Maddux's eight innings of two-hit scoreless
ball on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monkey see, monkey do,'' was Maddux's cerebral explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux moved to 7-5 and dropped his ERA under 4.00 for the first
time since April at 3.87. He took another step toward making May
look flukish and reminding the Mets that Glavine and Maddux don't
stay down long, for what that's worth in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that big of a deal,'' Maddux said. ``Maybe mentally
it's good for us to win two out of three. We want to stay in first
place. Still got a ways to go. We know that.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Braves' run came in the third inning via a liner to
left by Eddie Perez, who was 5 for his last 44 (.114) entering the
game, and Ozzie Guillen's double to right center to score him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Venezuelan run,'' Perez declared. ``All this talk
about Curacao.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen, who'd hit .319 in his previous 17 games as Walt Weiss's
replacement at shortstop, extended his hitting streak to five
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a pretty good hitter to be Punch and Judy,''
said Guillen, who's a career .265 hitter. ``I'm playing the way I
always play ... (But yeah) it's a lot better when you know you're
going to play the next day. You get a chance to make adjustments
from one at-bat to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux pitched four perfect innings before giving up a couple of
two-out singles in the fifth inning, but the only time his 1-0
seemed in jeopardy was after he walked Brian McRae in the eighth.
But he stranded McRae at third with a two-out strikeout of pinch
hitter Matt Franco on a 3-2 changeup.
</P>
<P>
   With Maddux tiring, the Braves turned to John Rocker, who struck
out Rickey Henderson for the first out. He then gave up a single to
Edgardo Alfonzo and watched him take second on a John Olerud
groundout. Manager Bobby Cox decided to walk Mike Piazza to bring
up Robin Ventura, which looked good after Rocker struck Ventura out
with a slider for his 16th save of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to put the winning run on,'' Cox said. ``Could have
gotten burned, but once you make a decision, you live with it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
