<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan one HR away from 100 milestone
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves cleanup hitter Brian Jordan hit the road for
Montreal on Sunday afternoon sitting on home run No. 99 of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't 500,'' Jordan said before Sunday's game. ``Just a
milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Jordan, who leads the Braves with 15 home runs, it's
pretty significant considering he hasn't been that big of a power
hitter throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's 25 home runs with the Cardinals was a career high.
He'd hit 22 in 1995 but otherwise never topped 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my potential is as a home run hitter,''
Jordan said. ``I've never hit a lot of home runs, even in college.
I was usually a doubles, triples, stolen base guy. But with
experience and learning how to hit and using a natural swing I'm
becoming more of a home run hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan flirted with No. 100 in the seventh inning Sunday when he
yanked a Mosato Yoshii pitch just a few inches foul of the left
field fair pole before grounding out on the next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But as is usually the case, Jordan said he does better when he's
not trying for home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go out and try not to hit them and that's when they come,''
Jordan said. ``I try not to worry about it. My focus is 100 RBI,
100 runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudek called up; Speier sent down
</P>
<P>
   The Braves recalled reliever John Hudek from his 30-day
rehabilitation assignment in Richmond and optioned Justin Speier to
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Hudek was 0-0 with a 6.35 ERA in 12 games in Richmond. He
pitched 11.1 innings, gave up 14 hits, eight earned runs, five
walks and 17 strikeouts. Hudek went on the disabled list
technically for a blister on his third finger but theoretically to
regain his form. He had an 11.17 ERA when he left Atlanta in May.
</P>
<P>
   Speier, who was first called up on April 14, leaves with a 5.65
ERA after allowing 11 runs in two of his last three outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just go down there and work my butt off and pitch the way
I'm capable of pitching,'' Speier said. ``It's been fun. I'll go
down there and keep my focus and work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez banged up
</P>
<P>
   This playing-every-day business has turned out to be a lot
harder than Eddie Perez had figured.
</P>
<P>
   One look at him and it's plain to see. The catcher, who's
started the last seven games since Javy Lopez went on the disabled
list with a sprained knee, looks like a boxer who lost a fight _
stitches recently taken out from over his eye after a home-plate
collision, a purple-colored right eyelid, a ball-sized red and
purple bruise on his right shoulder from a foul tip, and another
one on his thigh from a foul tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My wife) doesn't even want to look at me,'' said Perez with a
smile. ``I thought it was going to be something easy, but it's
killing me. Maybe when (Lopez) gets back, I'll go on the D.L.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
