A1227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-USCHAMPIONSHIP28-     06-27 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-USCHAMPIONSHIP28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Devers leaps over leg problems for 100-meter win
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ No doubt about it, Gail Devers is back. And
Andria King has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Just a month ago, the 32-year-old Devers was told her season
might be over. Her right hamstring badly strained, the Olympic
champion could barely walk, let alone harbor thoughts of hurdling.
</P>
<P>
   In a testament to modern medicine, Devers held up well enough to
power her way to victory over the 100-meter hurdles in 12.54
seconds Sunday at the USA Track and Field Championships. Earlier,
Devers finished a strong second in the 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   That's the stuff the track world has come to expect of Devers,
who makes her home in Alpharetta after starring in the Atlanta
Games.
</P>
<P>
   But King, who graduated from Georgia Tech this month, startled
even herself by finishing third in a career-best 12.73, and earning
a trip next month to the World Championships. King celebrated with
her parents and put in a call to her boyfriend, former Tech
basketball star Matt Harpring, while Devers stepped off the track
to take a call from her parents watching on TV back in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my season was over,'' said Devers, in her first
hurdles competition since the Atlanta Olympics. ``I had so many
problems with my leg recently. I pulled my hamstring in three
places. I was having problems with my thyroid again. They
discovered I was anemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could do is believe in myself, and hope I could get
through it. I honestly believe I have a guardian angel on my
shoulder, a guardian angel looking out for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Devers took it cautiously through the first two rounds, but at
the urging of her longtime coach Bobby Kersee she was her old self
for Sunday's final, aggressively attacking the wooden barriers en
route to a comfortable win.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say hurdling is like riding a bike, you never forget
it,'' Devers said. ``For me, it's amazing how much you do forget
after three years. It's getting used to going over the hurdles,
getting all the bumps and bruises again.''
</P>
<P>
   For King, the pain has been in the finish _ never an NCAA
champion, four times a runnerup. She came here eager for a step up
in class, to ready herself for the World University Games and her
first tour on the European circuit this summer. If she advanced to
the finals, she'd have been delighted.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, King, had to pinch herself as she stood on the medal
podium with Devers, later relishing in a victory lap around Hayward
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think this would happen in my wildest dreams,'' said
King, a Marist graduate who turned 23 last week. ``I grew up
idolizing Gail Devers. She was like Michael Jordan to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being around Gail, she's real nice. All the girls have been
very nice. Nobody makes me feel like a white girl, a young girl _
all of which I am.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, a U.S. teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
