<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1233 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOMB-DAMAGE-1S     06-27 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOMB-DAMAGE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR WAR MAY HAVE DONE LESS DAMAGE THAN NATO THOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Inserts sentence at end of graf that begins ``Milosevic's
government,'' and sentence at end of graf that begins ``According
to.'' Deletes 2 grafs following the second insertion.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ In the two weeks since NATO forces
arrived in Kosovo, alliance officials have scaled back their
initial estimates of the damage inflicted by the 78-day air
campaign on the Yugoslav army, which they concede remains a force
capable of maintaining Slobodan Milosevic's hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO and Pentagon officials stand by their claims to have
significantly damaged the Yugoslav army and special police, they
acknowledge that the units that withdrew from Kosovo a week ago
were clearly not as hobbled as they had believed.
</P>
<P>
   And those forces, they acknowledge, could be employed by
Milosevic again, at least to squelch domestic disturbances within
Serbia, and at most to either foment or face down a separatist
threat from Yugoslavia's lesser republic, Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exaggerated,'' said a former senior allied official, who
spoke to top European leaders in recent days, referring to NATO's
early damage estimates. ``NATO hit a lot of dummy and deception
targets. It's an old Soviet ploy. Officials in Europe are very
subdued. No one's pounding their chest over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Djakovica, for example, NATO obliterated the Yugoslav
army's World War II-era base. In what was left of the motor pool,
18 military vehicles, including one armored personnel carrier, were
scattered Sunday in charred, twisted heaps.
</P>
<P>
   Up close, however, it was clear that most of the destroyed
vehicles were old wrecks, assembled there by the Serbs for repairs
or junking. NATO's warplanes had not destroyed Yugoslavia's
front-line fighting vehicles, but rather a junkyard.
</P>
<P>
   From blown-out military barracks to exploded fuel tanks, the
devastating results of NATO's bombing are obvious all across
Kosovo. But the damage brought down on the Yugoslav army itself _
particularly the tanks, armored fighting vehicles and artillery
batteries at its core _ is less clear.
</P>
<P>
   Even in those places where allied bombers launched intense
attacks _ in Junik and the villages around Mount Pastrik in
southern Kosovo where Yugoslav forces had massed against the Kosovo
Liberation Army in the last weeks of the war _ there are few signs
of the scorched carcasses of tanks or other military equipment that
NATO officials expected to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is here,'' Lt. Col. Dietmar Jeserick, a spokesman for
the German peacekeeping troops based in Prizren, said Sunday. ``We
found positions. We found bomb damage in those positions, but we
didn't find any vehicles or tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   While some vehicles were removed from Kosovo by Serb forces to
break down for spare parts, NATO officials themselves acknowledge
that fewer pieces of military hardware were destroyed than the
alliance had first estimated.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, said last week that
the alliance had, for example, destroyed 110 of the roughly 300
tanks that the Yugoslav army had poured into Kosovo. But that
number was less than the 150 tanks NATO believed it had destroyed
in the waning days of the war, one senior NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and other NATO and Pentagon officials emphasize, however,
that NATO's bombing ultimately accomplished its mission, which was
to force Milosevic to end his brutal campaign against Kosovo's
ethnic Albanians and turn the province over to a NATO-led
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective, we're satisfied we destroyed enough
stuff to get him to say, `Uncle,''' Capt. Stephan Pietropaoli of
the U.S. Navy, the spokesman for the Pentagon's Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   But whether it was indeed the pain inflicted on his military
that formed Milosevic's prime motivation for ending the standoff
over Kosovo is an open question.
</P>
<P>
   One senior NATO official said that many leaders at NATO believed
that it was not the damage to the Yugoslav forces that finally
forced Milosevic to relent, though the alliance intercepted
communications from Serb commanders saying that their troops were
suffering heavy losses in the battles around Mount Pastrik.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the official said, Milosevic relented when Russia, long
a supporter, came to accept NATO's conditions and the consensus for
considering a ground campaign to oust his forces from Kosovo
appeared to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Such an assessment may gain still greater currency as NATO takes
full stock of the size of the Yugoslav army that completed its
withdrawal from Kosovo a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the Serbs pulled out over 11 days, NATO commanders counted
220 tanks, 300 armored personnel carriers and 308 artillery
batteries, along with hundreds of other vehicles and all manner of
military equipment loaded on trucks, according to NATO officials
here and in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   There were also 47,000 soldiers and police who left the
province, several thousand more than intelligence reports showed
during the height of Milosevic's campaign. The officials attributed
the discrepancy to paramilitary units, whose movements were harder
for NATO to track. But the large numbers also appeared to undercut
NATO's claims to have killed 5,000 to 10,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's government, eager to obscure the fact that it lost a
province considered by many Serbs to be Serbia's cultural,
religious and historical birthplace, has used state-run television
to show troops returning triumphantly from Kosovo. The government
also claimed that only 576 soldiers and policemen had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to reporters while visiting Kosovo last week, Clark
dismissed questions about the extent of NATO's punishment and
ridiculed Milosevic's claims as absurd. ``Just because the air
campaign stopped doesn't mean the Serb propaganda campaign
stopped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that a complete picture would not be known until
NATO sends analysts here in the coming weeks to assess the success
of the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has also announced that the deputy secretary of
defense, John Hamre, and the vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, Gen. Joseph Ralston, would lead a thorough review of the
war, including the damage done to the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   In war, initial assessments of damage are often overblown; the
oratory almost always is. After the Persian Gulf war ended in 1991,
the Pentagon learned that it had not hurt the Iraqi army nearly as
much as was first thought. The bombing and ground invasion by the
U.S.-led coalition left it badly beaten, but still strong enough to
put down rebellions in northern and southern Iraq and threaten
Kuwait again only three years later.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, there are several explanations for scaling back the
damage assessments now, officials said. Careful reviews of cockpit
video footage showed that pilots in some cases mistakenly believed
they had destroyed a target. They also showed that some of the
targets hit were not tanks or artillery batteries, but rather
clever decoys made by the Serbs to fool pilots flying three or four
miles up in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Outside its armed forces, however, Yugoslavia as a whole clearly
suffered enormous damage, particularly to its roads, bridges and
industry after 11 weeks of increasingly intense bombing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to a Pentagon assessment compiled after Milosevic
agreed to NATO's demands, allied warplanes destroyed Yugoslavia's
oil-refining ability, nearly half of its military fuel-storage
facilities and many of its factories producing military equipment
and ammunition. The alliance also reported eviscerating
Yugoslavia's air force of its most sophisticated jets and
inflicting some heavy damage on Yugoslav ground forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, a senior analyst on the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said that 60 percent of the barracks and other facilities of
Yugoslavia's Third Army in Kosovo had been either damaged or
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single building at the army base in Djakovica was
habitable; many were leveled entirely. NATO bombs dug huge craters
in the earth, strewing debris everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also clear that the Serbs took advantage of the
restraints that kept allied pilots at high altitudes and under
orders to avoid civilian casualties, to escape greater destruction
of their heavy ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Up and down western Kosovo, there are revetments where Serb
tanks and artillery pieces hunkered down, well hidden, particularly
at the foot of Mount Pastrik.
</P>
<P>
   There are also scores of decoys. Some of them involve older
vehicles fashioned to look like tanks. Others are comical. A few
miles west of Pristina, there is still a ``bridge'' of logs and
black tarp 100 yards from the main road. On either end were two
``tanks'' made of wood and plastic sheeting, with long tubes
protruding toward the sky.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, the decoys would fool no one, and NATO officials
said pilots quickly learned to distinguish them, but a fake bridge
near Djakovica took a missile right through its center span.
</P>
<P>
   At least one tank rests in a charred heap on a hill at a
military base near Urosevac, and local Albanians said several
remained in the hills above Junik, an area inaccessible because of
land mines.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger mystery is what happened to the tanks and other heavy
equipment that NATO did destroy. The senior NATO official said that
the retreating Serbs took a lot of damaged tanks with them,
ferrying them back on flatbed trucks to use as spare parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took out every last scrap they could,'' he said, ``so
when they get back to Yugoslavia, they can cannibalize bits and
pieces to put things back together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
