<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Issues Go Beyond Price for Frontier and U S West
</P>
<P>
   When the boards of Frontier and U S West meet to discuss the
hostile bid made by Qwest Communications International, the debate
will go beyond the dollar value of the competing offers made by
Qwest and Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of their deals with Global Crossing, the boards
of Frontier and U S West have to conclude that Qwest's offer is
adequately ``superior'' to Global's before they can begin
negotiations with Qwest. To do that, they will need to examine the
strategic fit, the possible structure of any deal and the
regulatory risks.
</P>
<P>
   New Paper to Chronicle Deal Making
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Wasserstein, the high-rolling deal maker and author of a
book on deal making, is about to introduce a newspaper about
high-rolling deal making called The Daily Deal. The paper, which is
scheduled to start five-day-a-week publication on Sept. 15, intends
to provide in-depth coverage of deals, their progress, financial
and legal architecture and how they panned out.
</P>
<P>
   Libel Trial Revisits Murder Case
</P>
<P>
   A woman who was identified by a detective as a suspect in the
murder of her husband, a Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing
executive, but was never charged, has sued the detective and a
television station for libel. The trial is being closely watched by
the media and legal communities.
</P>
<P>
   Human Element of E-Commerce
</P>
<P>
   Electronic commerce companies have spent millions of dollars
trying to make their sites more ``personal,'' with technology that
allows them to customize their product offerings to shoppers' needs
and software that automatically responds to customer inquiries by
e-mail. Now those sites are trying a novel approach to
personalization: real people.
</P>
<P>
   For Ease of Computing, the iToaster
</P>
<P>
   Microworkz.com, a maker of low-price computers in Seattle, has
introduced a computer it contends is as easy to use as a toaster
oven and has aptly named it the iToaster. It is a combination
word-processing, home-finance and Web-browsing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Account Reviews Going Online
</P>
<P>
   In another example of how the Internet is transforming the way
Madison Avenue does business, a French company is offering an
Internet service intended to assist in conducting account reviews
online. Other companies have already been capitalizing on the
benefits of interactivity for agency reviews by offering Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn Upsizing
</P>
<P>
   Saturn, the small-car brand that General Motors created a decade
ago to win back baby boomers from imports, will begin selling a
midsized car in July and plans to add a small sport utility vehicle
in about two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
