<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1247 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAPER-WASSERSTEIN-NYT     06-27 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPER-WASSERSTEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINANCIER IS SET TO PUBLISH A NEWSPAPER TO COVER DEAL MAKERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ancient Roman rulers had their likenesses carved in stone,
Renaissance princes and Dutch burghers had theirs painted on
plaster or canvas. Now, in the media age, prominent people carve
their likenesses on new publications: Martha Stewart, the
life-style guru, created a magazine about life styles; Steven
Brill, the reporter-turned-entrepreneur-turned-media baron, started
a magazine about the media.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Bruce Wasserstein, the high-rolling deal maker and
author of a book on deal making. His publishing company, American
Lawyer Media Inc., is about to introduce a new newspaper about
high-rolling deal making.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about two very different things,'' Wasserstein, who
emerged in the 1980s as a player in deals like Time's 13.4 billion
acquisition of Warner, said last week. ``First, covering the
financing and the deal communities, the corporations, the business
people, the financing, things of that sort. Second, covering the
transactions themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The new entry is called The Daily Deal; it is set to start
five-day-a-week publication on Sept. 15, when the investment
bankers and corporate lawyers and executive vice presidents for
strategic planning have returned from vacation.
</P>
<P>
   There is little question it will have deals to cover, at least
for now. In 1996, the total value of domestic mergers and
acquisitions was $653 billion; in 1997 it was $970 billion; last
year, it jumped to $1.6 trillion. Wasserstein, William L. Pollak,
the president and chief executive of American Lawyer Media, and
Robert Teitelman, the new publication's editor in chief, want to
provide in-depth coverage of deals, their progress, financial and
legal architecture and how they panned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tactics and tax structures are also going to be of great
interest to our readers,'' Pollak, a former executive vice
president at The New York Times, said last week at The Daily Deal's
half-filled offices on Madison Avenue in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelman, in a separate interview, added that ``the paper is
not designed to be strictly an M &AMP; A paper.'' He added, ``there are
a huge amount of private equity funds out there to cover.'' And
when the bull market ends? ``We'll also cover, when the time come,
bankruptcies and restructurings.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's editors say, they want to create a new community
of readers out of the sliced-and-diced audience of perhaps 125,000
people who now subscribe to scores of financial newsletters
(including American Lawyer Media's own newsletter on mergers and
acquisitions) and financial newspapers like The American Banker and
The Bond Buyer. For $3.50 an issue and a list subscription price of
$750 a year, they hope to attract an audience of 15,000 in the
first year.
</P>
<P>
   That is the game plan. The initial reality, of course, is that,
like any start-up, the editors are planning to give away thousands
of subscriptions to corporate executives _ perhaps 10,000, all told
_ through free six-week trials, to build up interest, according to
Jack Berkowitz, American Lawyer Media's executive vice president
for strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   They do, however, have built-in advantages. The Daily Deal will
be American Lawyer Media's 22nd publication. Its legal
publications, like The New York Law Journal, give it an
infrastructure of offices, staff, printers, distributors and
subscriber lists that are costly to build from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Lawyer is in the business of delivering newspapers
around the country,'' Pollak said. He would not confirm the
start-up cost, beyond agreeing that it was in ``single-digit
millions.''
</P>
<P>
   One major issue for the newspaper will be logistics. Faced with
the reality of trucking time needed to get The Daily Deal from New
York to Washington and Boston, or from its San Francisco plant
around California, the editors and the business executives are
still trying to figure out when their deadlines will be _ 5:30
p.m.? 6:30 p.m.? 7:30 p.m.?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the deadline is, Pollak and his managing editor, Ed
Paisley, said, it will inevitably mean that late-breaking
information will not make it into the hard copy of the newspaper
but would make it onto its Web site. And Pollak, who followed The
National, the ill-fated national sports daily, during its
16-and-a-half-month life span, is well aware that late-breaking
news, like timely delivery, is crucial. Pollak said that, among the
problems of The National, which folded in 1991, was its inability
to provide late scores.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Larry Gelfand, the publisher of The Daily Deal, ``We
are fortunate to be launching in the era of the World Wide Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Access to the newspaper's Web site comes as part of the
subscription price, and the 35 or so editorial staffers, along with
a network of stringers in financial capitals around the world, will
supplement the wire services that feed fast-breaking news into the
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial issue for the new publication, however, may not be
its timeliness but its distinctiveness. The proliferation of
financial news _ from wire services to newsletters to Web sites _
has made it harder to find resources, from journalists to ad
salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's bold, and I think its entrepreneurial,'' said
Debra Cope, an executive editor at The American Banker, which, as a
164-year-old daily tabloid with a circulation of 17,280, has a
profile not so different from the one The Daily Deal hopes to
create. She added: ``It's also risky. They have got a lot to
prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill, the founder of The American Lawyer magazine, who sold his
stake in the enterprise in 1997, before U.S. Equity Partners LP, a
private equity investment fund managed by Wasserstein Perella Group
Inc. bought it, advised Berkowitz that The Daily Deal would need to
grab attention immediately. ``You have to move markets with your
first issue,'' Berkowitz quoted Brill as saying. Brill confirmed
the remark.
</P>
<P>
   Pollak, however, said that American Lawyer would back the new
publication through two years of losses, in the hopes it would be
as valuable to its readers as Daily Variety was to the
entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and what about covering Wasserstein himself, the chief
executive of Wasserstein Perella and chairman of American Lawyer
Media Inc.?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a rule,'' said Wasserstein. ``The rule is there are
no features, pro or con, about us. But if we're part of the
ordinary coverage of an event, treat us like everybody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
