<HEADLINE>
HATCH CRITICIZES ADMINISTRATION'S HANDLING OF INTELLIGENCE
MATTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Orrin Hatch, the Utah Republican who last week
became the most recent candidate to enter the race for president,
on Sunday condemned the Clinton administration's handling of
intelligence affairs, saying, ``We're not taking counterterrorism
as seriously as we should.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on ``Fox News Sunday,'' Hatch offered a blunt response
to an article in The New York Times on Sunday that described how
senior White House officials were warned as early as 1995 that
China might have stolen nuclear secrets from the United States, but
failed to investigate aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   That ``really shouldn't go on,'' Hatch said. ``I'm sick of it.
That's one reason I'm running, and I'm going to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, administration officials said they were launching a
wide-ranging review of the government's counterintelligence effort,
including revamping the FBI office that handles it. Coming after
revelations about Chinese scientific espionage, the review is a
tacit admission that the United States has not kept pace with
spying in the post-Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not putting the effort into it,'' said Hatch, who is a
member of the Senate Intelligence Committee and chairman of the
Judiciary Committee, which oversees the Justice Department and the
FBI. ``We're not putting the leadership into it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The rest of the world depends on us. Let's do it.
Let's do what's right. And that's one thing I could bring to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said that raising money would be difficult. ``George Bush
seems to be scarfing up everything,'' he said, referring to the
Texas governor, who is the early leader among the Republican
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name a policy matter on which he and Bush disagree,
Hatch replied, ``I think probably we agree, by and large, you know,
on most things.'' But he sought to distinguish himself from both
Bush and the leading Democratic candidate, Vice President Al Gore,
by drawing attention to his working-class roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush and Al Gore have been born and raised in
privilege. I was not,'' said Hatch, 65, whose only public office is
the Senate seat he first won in 1976. ``I was born in a family that
was quite poor. In fact, I had to work my way through college. I
worked as a janitor.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would establish an exploratory committee, which would
enable him to begin raising money ``within the next week or so.''
And he said he planned to visit Iowa and New Hampshire, the states
with the earliest presidential contests, soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
