u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MISSING-900&AMP;AD     06-27 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MISSING-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING REFUGEES WONDER ABOUT THE MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LABJAN, Yugoslavia _ Milazim Kelmendi walked through the gate of
his house on Saturday and took his family completely by surprise.
They had last seen him on May 7 when he and dozens of other men
were taken away by Serb police, and were convinced he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had had no news, whether he was dead, massacred, or what,''
his mother, Have Kelmendi, said Sunday. ``I wasn't this happy even
the day he was born.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were crying all the time, thinking he was dead,'' said his
younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   Pale and gaunt and with his head shaven, 26-year-old Milazim had
survived a month and a half in Serb prisons, first in the Kosovo
town of Pec and then in Zajecar in Serbia. ``He looks like they
have taken him out of the ground,'' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Milazim was one of 166 prisoners, all men, released by Serb
authorities two days ago from two prisons in Serbia, in the towns
of Leskovac and Zajecar. They had all been detained around May 7,
when trying to flee to Albania with their families. The men had
been separated from the women and children and marched away.
</P>
<P>
   Their release, which came unexpectedly, has ended the anguish
for some families and raised hopes for others still searching for
their relatives. The Serb prison authorities handed the men over to
representatives of the International Committee of the Red Cross.
The director of one of the prisons said the men were being released
in a gesture of good will, said a Red Cross spokeswoman, Daloni
Carlisle.
</P>
<P>
   The release served as confirmation of the reports that Albanian
prisoners were being held in Serb prisons after being transferred
from Kosovo. The 166, who all came from the Pec region, in western
Kosovo, are probably just a small proportion of the total being
held in Serbia, aid agencies believe and some of those released
also say. And they are only a small fraction of the total number of
Albanians who remain missing from the war.
</P>
<P>
   Serb officials have told the Red Cross that they have a list of
2,070 people from Kosovo in their prisons. The officials have yet
to make such a list public, and it is not clear how comprehensive
it might be, but they have shown a list to some relatives seeking
news of missing men. They say the list is available to relatives,
but given the tension between Serbs and Albanians in Kosovo, many
Albanians may be hesitant to approach Serb officials to see it.
</P>
<P>
   The tally of missing Albanians may end up far higher. As
refugees are returning home to Kosovo, the authorities and aid
agencies are beginning to compile lists of missing people. Many are
feared to be dead.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is complicated since there is no clause in the
U.N. Security Council resolution on Kosovo covering the return of
prisoners, nor is there a mention in the military-technical
agreement signed by NATO and the Yugoslav army that ended the war.
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Djakovica and surrounding villages, in western
Kosovo, 1,500 local people already have been listed as missing. In
southern Kosovo, the German contingent of NATO forces has already
listed the names of 855 people reported missing in their area of
operations. The German sector is just one of five areas of control
that NATO forces oversee.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights organizations and members of the international war
crimes tribunal at The Hague, Netherlands, say it is too early to
estimate accurately how many people are missing or have been
killed, but they say they fear it will run to much more than a few
thousand. ``From driving around the province, my gut tells me it
could be 10,000,'' said one investigator.
</P>
<P>
   The prisons in Serbia are perhaps the source of the greatest
hope for finding men alive. They not only hold men arrested in
Kosovo, but Kosovo Albanians arrested in Montenegro and in Serbia
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Nine Kosovo Albanian students who had been in school in
Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, are thought to be in prisons there.
Five were arrested on May 2 and the others on May 13, said Natasa
Kandic of the Belgrade-based Center for Humanitarian Law, a
respected human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   All were close to graduation and model students, she said. They
had been studying to become doctors, veterinarians, pharmacists and
educators, and had stayed on in Belgrade after the war started,
intent on completing their studies.
</P>
<P>
   The five arrested on May 2 were later shown on state television,
along with an array of weapons. They were accused of being fighters
for the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army and of preparing some
terrorist action for public places in the capital. The other four
have not been heard of since their arrest, which was witnessed by a
fellow student. Police, prosecutors and prison authorities in
Belgrade have said they have no records of the second group, Ms.
Kandic said.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects of finding people who were abducted or who
disappeared during heavy fighting are even bleaker. Several people,
both Serbs and Kosovo Albanians, are thought to have been abducted
or killed by members of the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carlisle, the Red Cross spokeswoman, said her agency has
lists of about 140 people who disappeared during the first year of
fighting in Kosovo and another group of a similar number who
disappeared over the last three months in the NATO bombing campaign
and increased violence.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel leaders have told the Red Cross they are not holding
anyone, but the organization is persisting in asking for details on
the missing, she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The lack of any agreement on the return of prisoners complicates
the work of organizations like the Red Cross to secure the release
of prisoners and will prolong the agony for many families, Ms.
Carlisle said.
</P>
<P>
   For the families still searching for news, the most agonizing
part is not knowing, they say. Fehmi Kuci pined away after her
husband was taken away by Serb forces in May. ``She shrank so much
that you could hold her in the palm of your hand,'' said her sister
Fitore Kelmendi, 19, in another household in the Kosovo town of
Labjan.
</P>
<P>
   When the prisoners arrived home Saturday, they did not bring
Fehmi's husband, Izet, but they brought news that they had seen him
and he was alive in a Serb prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday she was flying when she found out he was alive,''
Fitore Kelmendi said.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Xheva Kelmendi, said, ``We thought they had been
taken away and killed on a hill. We were so scared.'' As it was,
Ms. Kelmendi returned to find her husband's burned body inside
their charred house.
</P>
<P>
   The women of the family are hoping now that at least one of
their men might be returned to them. They had heard more prisoners
might be released in a week or two, but the fear and anguish still
kept its hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am scared that someone might kill them now,'' Fitore
Kelmendi said. ``Without seeing him with our own eyes, we are still
afraid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
