<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOROCCO-MONARCH-ART-9     06-27 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOROCCO-MONARCH-ART-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEIR TO MOROCCO'S THRONE IS PLAYING A LARGER ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARRAKESH, Morocco _ As King Hassan II approached a royal gala
in the El-Badiaa palace recently, huge studded doors swung open,
guards in flowing white robes and red fezzes snapped to attention,
and guests erupted in resounding hurrahs: ``Long live his majesty
the king!''
</P>
<P>
   It is a tribute that has resonated even more strongly since the
death of Jordan's King Hussein in February made King Hassan, after
37 years on the throne, the Arab world's longest-surviving ruler.
But the tributes of the court have been shaded, too, with new
uncertainty ever since King Hassan, who is 69, sent his heir,
35-year-old Crown Prince Sidi Mohammed, to represent him at the
funeral of his fellow monarch and old friend in Amman, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Although no official reason was given for the king's absence
from the Amman rites, palace aides acknowledged that the Moroccan
ruler, a victim of recurrent ill health, was unwell. His medical
problems continued into the spring, with other episodes that kept
him out of the public eye. But palace officials have denied
suggestions from Western diplomats that King Hassan is seriously
ill, describing his problems as an aggravated form of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   If the king is beginning to withdraw, it is with a stature among
Moroccans that is vastly transformed from his reputation as a
despot, renowned for heading a government that tortured political
foes and banished them for long years to grim desert forts.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, he has recast himself as the author of ``Hassanian
democracy,'' a hybrid that has widened political freedoms while
retaining the paramount political power of the Alawite dynasty that
the king heads.
</P>
<P>
   Among those hailing the monarch at the palace gala were Cabinet
ministers from left-wing parties who were appointed last year after
years under house arrest, in detention or in exile. Moroccan
officials have described the king's appointment of an
``opposition'' government composed of old adversaries, some of whom
once plotted to overthrow him, as a first for the Arab world, where
many governments continue to impose tight constraints on political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of King Hassan's flexibility have included the
establishment of an elected lower house of parliament, in which
leftist parties gained the largest bloc of seats in elections in
1998. The king also ordered a ``cleanup'' of Morocco's human rights
record that has included the release of dozens of political
prisoners and _ another first for the Arab world _ $500-a-month
compensation payments to families of prisoners who disappeared or
died.
</P>
<P>
   With the leftist parties now co-opted into government, Islamic
radicals who have a strong power base on college campuses and among
millions of unemployed youths pose the most severe challenge.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the old political system that has not been
reformed are the restrictions on political activity by hard-line
Islamic parties, who are forbidden by the king to form political
parties or contest elections. Many Moroccans fear that these could
eventually cause an eruption that might overwhelm a less
experienced political leader.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns have led Moroccans to focus new attention on
Prince Sidi Mohammed. The royal heir, like his father when he was
the crown prince, had a reputation as a playboy, more interested in
nightclubs, fast cars and other indulgences afforded by the royal
family's vast wealth than in affairs of state.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, as he began representing his father on important state
occasions, that reputation has begun to fade. But in a Muslim
society that emphasizes family ties, the crown prince has remained
unmarried past the age at which Moroccans start families.
</P>
<P>
   When King Hassan succeeded his father, King Mohammed V, who died
unexpectedly during minor surgery in 1961, the new king, then 31,
was regarded as ill suited to the task of governing an ancient,
often unruly kingdom that had gained independence only five years
before, after 44 years as a French protectorate. His success in
confounding his early detractors has encouraged court officials,
who predict that the same will be true for Prince Sidi Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
   The monarchy has been sustained by Moroccans' reverence for the
Alawite dynasty, which has provided the country's sultans since the
mid-17th century. Like his predecessors, King Hassan bears several
titles _ ``Commander of the Faithful,'' ``Savior'' and ``Shadow of
the Prophet on Earth'' _ that reflect the dynasty's claim to be
directly descended from the Muslim prophet Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
   King Hassan has been careful to foster his image as spiritual
leader, soliciting public donations to build a $500 million mosque
bearing his name beside the Atlantic coastline in the heart of
Casablanca, the country's main commercial center. Completed in
1990, the mosque features a powerful laser beam aimed at Mecca from
atop its 700-foot minaret.
</P>
<P>
   The king regularly lectures the ulema, or Muslim clergy, on
Islamic doctrine, and reminds the nation frequently that he is
``the person entrusted by God to lead you.''
</P>
<P>
   The king's claim to a pure Islamic bloodline poses a challenge
for Islamic radicals. Abdessalam Yassine, 70-year-old leader of the
largest radical organization, the Justice and Charity Movement, who
has been under house arrest for nine years, mocked the king in the
past as ``my dear nephew of the Prophet,'' but also noted that
Morocco is unique in having a ruler directly descended from
Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
   The king has his own wry riposte. ``Don't forget,'' he has said,
speaking of the radicals, ``that I am a fundamentalist, too.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his dynastic authority, even the king's critics credit
him with political astuteness for surviving in a region that had
become, by the 1960s, deeply hostile to monarchy. In 1962, rebels
in Algeria, Morocco's closest neighbor, won their independence war
with France and set out to make Algeria a socialist state.
</P>
<P>
   Other Arab monarchs _ Egypt's King Farouk in 1956, Iraq's King
Faisal in 1958, and Libya's King Idris in 1969 _ fell to rebellions
inspired by Arab socialism and pan-Arab nationalism, then the
dominant political passions of the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   In his early years, the Moroccan ruler survived several
attempted coups. In 1971, 1,400 soldiers opened fire on his
birthday reception, killing 100 guests but missing the king, who
hid in a bathroom. The following year, Moroccan air force jets
attempted unsuccessfully to shoot his Boeing 727 plane down as it
carried the monarch home from a trip to France.
</P>
<P>
   After the failed coups, the defense minister, Gen. Mohammed
Oufkir, was shot, and 30 officers were confined in a notorious
desert fortress, Tazmamert, where they were tortured and died.
Oufkir's wife and six young children had their Rabat home razed
before being carried off to 25 years of desert banishment and house
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In the same uncompromising manner, the king waved aside
international protests in 1975 and sent troops to occupy the
contested territory of Western Sahara, precipitating a 16-year war
with the pro-independence guerrillas of the Polisario Front. After
an eight-year truce and accumulated costs for Morocco that cabinet
ministers estimate at $20 billion, about equal to a national debt
that is among the highest for any Arab country, the dispute remains
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   But the king's admirers say the most important decisions he made
were the things he did not do. Unlike many developing nations,
Morocco was never a one-party state. While Algeria and many other
Arab states adopted Soviet-style central planning, King Hassan
opted for a market economy. From the start, he retained close ties
to the West, making Morocco the odd man out in north Africa, where
Soviet influence was strong.
</P>
<P>
   He was also an early advocate of peace between Arab states and
Israel, making secret diplomatic overtures in the early 1970s, when
much of the Arab world was nursing the wounds of the 1967 war. U.S.
diplomats credited him with easing the way to the 1979 Camp David
accords, and he has played host to visiting Israeli prime
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   After shunning the right-wing government of Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, he used a recent visit of 50 Israeli
parliamentarians to signal a readiness to push for peace again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, many of the choices the king made at an early stage of
his reign look very obvious, but they weren't then,'' said Andre
Azoulay, a Moroccan who made a career as a prominent Paris banker
before returning in the mid-1990s to serve as the king's financial
adviser. ``Now, we can qualify him as a visionary, well ahead of
his time.''
</P>
<P>
   Much will depend now on the new political system. A new
constitution in 1996 created a fully elected lower house of
parliament for the first time. But the king retains ultimate
authority, with wide powers to dismiss individual cabinet ministers
or entire governments, to dissolve parliament, to veto legislation,
and even to rule by decree.
</P>
<P>
   He also presides at Cabinet meetings, appoints all senior civil
servants, and remains commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Under a deal worked out last year, after elections resulted in
the appointment as prime minister of Abderrahman Youssoufi, a
74-year-old socialist who spent 15 years in exile, the king
appointed his own loyalists to the ministries of foreign affairs,
justice, interior and Islamic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful man in the country, after the king, remains
Driss Basri, the interior minister, a palace hard-liner accused of
authorizing widespread abuses against the king's political
opponents during his 20 years in the post.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 months in office, the Youssoufi government has prompted
grumbling among ordinary Moroccans who hoped for swifter action on
the country's social problems. These include widespread illiteracy,
unsafe drinking water in the villages, and unemployment so severe
that dozens drown in the straits of Gibraltar each year attempting
to migrate illegally to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Youssoufi has said that the government's hands are tied by tight
constraints on the national budget. With nearly 85 per cent of
outlays going to government salaries and payments on the national
debt, there is little left for social spending. But being in the
government makes it difficult to blame the country's woes on the
king. ``We have the responsibilities, but not the power,'' one
former communist serving in the Youssoufi government said
dolefully. ``It's not an ideal arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing restiveness makes fertile ground for the Islamic
radicals. Abdelwahad Motaouwakil, a spokesman for Justice and
Charity, the largest Islamic movement, predicts that Moroccans will
eventually tire of ``Hassanian democracy'' and embrace a society
based on the Koran. ``The Youssoufi government is the king's last
card,'' he has said. ``It's bound to fail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
