<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FARMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH YEAR IS PROJECTED FOR FARMS OF RUSSIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A blisteringly hot summer and the reverberations from
Russia's economic crisis have taken a devastating toll on the
nation's crops, making it likely that Moscow will appeal for
American food aid, according to Russian and American officials.
</P>
<P>
   Russia had hoped to harvest 70 million tons of grain this year.
But Western experts estimate that Russian farms will yield no more
than 55 million tons.
</P>
<P>
   The setback comes on the heels of last year's harvest, at 47.8
million tons, the worst in Russia in more than 40 years. Instead of
the turnaround in food production the Kremlin had hoped for,
Russian government officials have begun to prepare the public for
another tough year.
</P>
<P>
   While formal talks on additional aid have not yet begun,
Agriculture Minister Vladimir Shcherbak told reporters last week
that Moscow wanted America to donate animal feed, like soybeans,
soy meal and maize.
</P>
<P>
   By using donated feed to sustain its cattle, Russia would have
more grain available to feed people. The government also hopes to
sell the donated animal feed at home and use the proceeds to
improve agricultural production, Shcherbak told Reuters news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Entering a superheated political year, the Kremlin has powerful
political incentives to try to keep Russian consumers and farmers
happy _ or at least to make them somewhat less unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Communists will be angling to expand their control
over the legislature when parliamentary elections are held in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Next, candidates will be maneuvering to succeed Boris Yeltsin in
presidential elections scheduled for next summer, and Yeltsin has
taken a strong interest in determining his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's food needs are an important political factor in the
United States, as well. Expanded food aid to Russia would be a boon
to the American farmer, a consideration for the Democrats as they
seek to keep control of the White House next year.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has agreed to provide 3.2 million tons of
grain, meat and other food to Russia. Much of the approximately
$700 million worth of food was donated, while the remainder was
financed by a 20-year loan at nominal interest. Washington also
footed the transportation costs, bringing the total value of the
aid effort to around $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But with American stocks of grain, beef and pork at near-record
levels, the Clinton administration is ready to provide even more
help.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons why Russia has failed to produce enough
food. The collective farms established during the Soviet Union have
been reorganized more in name than in fact. Last year's financial
crisis impeded the already lagging investments in seed, fertilizer,
animal feed and farm equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Russia was hit by another spell of bad weather. The
scorchingly hot and dry weather so far this summer has been
particularly severe in southern Russia along the Volga River, an
important agricultural region. Russia's Agriculture Ministry had
initially hoped for 70 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, however, the estimates have been revised downward.
Shcherbak, the agriculture minister, said last week the grain
harvest may yield only 55 million to 60 million tons.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western specialists say even that is too optimistic. One
expert said Russia would likely harvest no more than 53 million to
55 million tons of grain. Of that, no more than 30 million tons
would be wheat.
</P>
<P>
   Russia could use some of its better-quality feed grain to
sustain Russian consumers instead of cattle. That, however, could
hurt livestock production, which has been steadily decreasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing has to give: food or feed,'' a Western expert said.
``They need support to make ends meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Grain reserves have been depleted in the effort to make up last
year's grain shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves food aid, which Russia's former agriculture
minister, Gennady Kulik, raised informally during talks in
Washington in March. His successor, Shcherbak, apparently alluded
to those proposals in his comments last week. Sensitive to wounded
Russian pride, however, he insisted it not be called aid.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is also sensitive to potential
political risks of further aid, in particular charges that it would
be undermined by Russian corruption. Now that more than one-third
of the promised 3.2 million tons have been delivered without
allegations of major abuse, Washington appears ready to discuss
further assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
