<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GODINA DELIVERS THREE WORLD BESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Who could blame John Godina for feeling a little
tired in the last three rounds of the shot put in the USA Track and
Field Championships on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Godina produced the three longest throws in the world this year
to open the competition, including a career-best 72 feet, 3 inches
en route to his second national title in a row before a Hayward
Field crowd of 8,913.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little worn out from celebrating,'' said Godina, who
finished second in the discus Saturday. ``I don't know if I should
have done that so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Godina's exceeded his previous best by three-quarters of an
inch. In addition, his winning effort marked the first time the
two-time defending world champion had broken 72 feet since Godina
captured the world title and NCAA championships as a UCLA senior in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   C.J. Hunter, the husband of Marion Jones, finished second at
69-2{ and Kevin Toth was third at 66-11\. The top three finishers
advance to the World Championships in Seville, Spain, in August.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who finished second in the long jump Friday, rebounded
from her first defeat to an American since 1997, winning the 200 in
22.10.
</P>
<P>
   Godina, who trains under UCLA weight coach Art Venegas with the
Reebok-Bruin Track Club, opened with a put of 71-8\, improved to
72-3 in the second round and followed it with a mark of 70-9 on his
third attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Godina shared the spotlight with pole vaulter Jeff Hartwig on
the final day of the four-day meet. Hartwig cleared 19-9 to break
his own American record by half an inch. He took three tries at
6.10 meters in an attempt to become the first American to clear 20
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene won the 200 in the absence of world-record holder
Michael Johnson, who withdrew because of a quadriceps injury.
Greene clocked a wind-aided 19.93 to edge world indoor champion
Rohsaan Griffin by 5/100s of a second despite stumbling out of the
blocks at the start.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Jacobs became the first woman to win the 1,500 and 5,000
in the same year and wound up the meet's only double winner.
</P>
<P>
   The 1981 graduate of Argyll Academy (now Campbell Hall) clocked
15:24.80 to win the 5,000 for the second year in a row, going 29.8
for the final 200 and 2:12.6 for the last 800 to pull away from
Cheri Kenah (15:26.60) and Elva Dryer (15:27.26). On Saturday
night, Jacobs won her eighth national title in the 1,500. Amy
Skieresz, an Agoura graduate and a seven-time NCAA champion in
cross country and track at Arizona, was ninth in 16:00.33.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Crear of Valencia and Gail Devers won the 110 high hurdles
and 100 hurdles in wind-aided marks of 13.09 and 12.54, the fastest
time in the world under any conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Gray of Agoura Hills, 39, came up short in his bid for
his eighth national 800 title, finishing fourth in 1:46.62 in a
race won by Santa Monica Track Club teammate Khadevis Robinson in
1:45.92.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
