<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE DRUG-BENEFIT PLAN TO BE UNVEILED THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human
services, moved on Sunday to head off criticism of the cost of
President Clinton's plan to help buy prescription drugs for older
Americans, saying that the new Medicare benefits ``will not be as
generous as people think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about just adding some new lush benefit,'' Shalala
said on CBS News' ``Face the Nation.'' ``This is critical to health
care.''
</P>
<P>
   More than one-third of the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries
have no insurance to cover prescription-drug costs. On Tuesday,
Clinton will unveil a plan for the government to offer subsidized
drug coverage to all beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The plan depends, in its entirety, on approval by Congress. It
is impossible to predict with any certainty what Congress will do.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the premium for drug coverage
would start in the range of $20 to $25 a month and then climb
gradually in subsequent years toward $45 a month. Under the plan,
the government would pay about half the cost of prescription drugs,
up to a certain level to be specified by law, and beneficiaries
would pay the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   As of noon Sunday, an administration official said, the maximum
annual benefit _ the amount payable by the government _ had not
been decided. But like the premium, it could rise over time, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Comments by Clinton and his aides suggest that the
administration is open to a deal with Congress: Democrats would win
Medicare coverage of prescription drugs, and Republicans would get
some of the tax cuts they want.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, met last week with
Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who is chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, where tax bills usually originate.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Archer said he tried to keep the meeting secret because
he feared it would feed the suspicions of liberal House Democrats
who worry that Clinton will cut a deal with Republicans in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said the cost of Medicare drug coverage would not ``spin
out of control,'' but she refused to say how it would be financed.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the White House economic adviser, said the cost
to taxpayers would be manageable. ``The reason why it is going to
cost very little is because the plan overall is going to include
significant savings in the Medicare plan,'' he said on CNN's ``Late
Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Clinton's proposal would save
large amounts of money by extending provisions of the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997, which cut Medicare payments to most health-care
providers.
</P>
<P>
   That idea is sure to meet fierce opposition from doctors,
hospitals, nursing homes and home health-care agencies, which are
lobbying Congress to restore money cut in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week to Republican lawmakers, Rep. Bill Thomas
of California, one of the party's leading experts on health policy,
suggested questions that should be raised about Clinton's drug
plan.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Thomas asked: ``Is it targeted to individuals that
need coverage? Does it give a benefit to those who already have
coverage, possibly jeopardizing the munificent benefits they
already receive? Would the benefit be available to retired
millionaires who do not need assistance?''
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's plan, insurance for drug expenses would be
offered to all Medicare beneficiaries, including those who now have
such coverage from former employers. The government would also
offer subsidies to employers to encourage them to continue
providing drug benefits to retirees, perhaps to supplement
Medicare's coverage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A lobbyist for a large labor union said: ``A lot of employers
may decide they're better off putting their people into the
Medicare drug program. Employers could pick up drug costs that
Medicare does not cover, and they might pay the premium for
Medicare drug benefits too.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kaplan, vice president of Segal Co., an employee benefits
consulting concern based in New York City, said, ``Anything the
government does to pick up prescription-drug expenses under
Medicare could provide a windfall for private employers, unions and
state and local governments that offer retiree health coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   If Medicare covers prescription drugs, Kaplan said, employers
might curtail retiree health benefits or might try to control
rapidly rising costs by giving retirees a lump sum of cash, which
the retirees could use to buy private health insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
