<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1287 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-27 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FREE PILLS FOR GEEZERS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Free milk for babies'' was the battle cry of
social reformers a century ago. Today the bumper sticker of those
pressing for inclusion of prescription drugs in Medicare might read
``Free Pills for Geezers.''
</P>
<P>
   (I'll get mail from members of my age cohort whining about
``geezer'' as a demographic slur, but it's no more pejorative than
``young whippersnapper.'')
</P>
<P>
   Just as free milk was good for youngsters, free pills will be
good for indigent oldsters. Medication, especially in geriatric and
psychiatric treatment, is often better and always cheaper than
hospitalization. Insurance coverage of most prescriptions for the
aging is an idea whose time has come; the only question is how best
to pay for it without more speedily bankrupting Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few days ago, the White House had its answer: Sock the
middle class and wealthy in Medicare with a bigger premium to cover
the costs of prescriptions for poor people. Through a ``means
test,'' Mr. Clinton would be Dr. Robin Hood.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Congress popped that trial balloon in a hurry.
Raise premiums on the old folks? Political suicide. Republicans
agreed, asking why retirees who saved and invested to build a nest
egg all their lives should be penalized for their prudence by
becoming targets of a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   After some frantic scrambling, Clinton came up with a fallback
plan to be announced Tuesday. How, without a new premium increase,
do you add a prescription benefit to Medicare, which already faces
insolvency in eight years?
</P>
<P>
   His answer: out of the pocket of the taxpayer. According to
Robert Pear, who consistently comes to work earlier than anyone in
the New York Times Washington bureau, ``Medicare would get a huge
infusion of cash from the federal treasury: $700 billion,
representing about 15 percent of federal budget surpluses
anticipated over the next 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Stipulate that a new benefit will never be taken back. Remember
that all official projections of federal deficits and surpluses for
the past 15 years have been wildly mistaken. Then ask: Can we be
sure that the business cycle will become an arrow straight upward,
that no tax reduction will ever be needed to stimulate a faltering
economy _ in essence, that Miss America is Rosy Scenario?
</P>
<P>
   Optimism is in, but to base the solvency of Medicare on the
willingness of the next generation of taxpayers to subsidize a
planned, ever-increasing tide of red ink is more than a little
risky.
</P>
<P>
   Beware reliance on a permanent surplus. Twenty years from now,
the children of today's boomers might not want to carry the heavy
tax burden to support a generation that bet on the come,
irresponsibly refusing to plan ahead to insure itself.
</P>
<P>
   Beware, too, of killing the goose that lays the golden pills.
The most troubling two words in the Clinton 80-minute news ramble
touched on the prescription drugs to be dispensed under Medicare:
They had to be ``properly priced.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Washington to decide on what price is ``proper'' for a new
drug? It's fine for government to help negotiate volume discounts
for purchases, but destructive to snatch the pricing function from
the free market.
</P>
<P>
   If Medicare listens to demagogic complaints about greedy profits
for the latest pharmaceuticals and dictates the price it will pay,
private investment risking its capital in discovering new
treatments will dry up. Take it from one who wrote Nixon's speech
imposing price controls; they don't work.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, do we make it possible now for a poor Pop to pop a
pill? It's not rocket science and requires no universe-wide
government takeover of the health care system.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, the bipartisan Breaux-Thomas Medicare commission
came up with a sensible plan of premium support that would help
Medicare recipients pay for a health plan of their choosing. It's
not ``free pills for all,'' but it's similar to the generous
federal-employee plan, and the better-off can buy more benefits.
What's needed now is to add a prescription-drug benefit to the
basic benefits package.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stiffed the commission's proposals: not expensive
enough, provided no political issue, and the Clinton name was not
on them.
</P>
<P>
   But it's practical and doable this year. If you want
prescriptions covered through Medicare, raise your voice, Gramps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
