<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-CITRUS-ART-995(     06-27 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CITRUS-ART-995(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG FREEZE BLIGHTS A CITRUS CROP AND WORKERS' LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTERVILLE, Calif. _ When winter threw a fit last Christmas,
slamming through the Central Valley and scaring the life out of the
citrus groves, people here were sure 1999 was over.
</P>
<P>
   It was. By the time the ice storms backed off four days later,
the orange and lemon crops were nearly gone and so were the picking
and packing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The freeze destroyed more than $700 million worth of produce in
the Central Valley, the United States' largest food producer,
including more than 75 percent of the valley's navel oranges, about
83 percent of its Valencia oranges and virtually all the lemons.
The storms left from 14,000 to 28,000 farm workers unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a year later, with the sunlight pressing on the
valley like a hot compress, the damage from the freeze is getting
worse. Growers and packing-house owners are up to their chins in
debt; workers are up to their eyes in it.
</P>
<P>
   To see the dusty towns in freeze-struck counties like Tulare,
which grows many of the nation's navel oranges, one would never
know that this nation is richer than ever. People stand in long
lines for boxes of free government-issued food _ white cans with
big black letters that say ``pork,'' ``peaches'' and ``peas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people are moving from houses and apartments into decrepit
trailers, to save on rent. Others have pulled up stakes, packing
their children and setting out in pickup trucks to hunt down jobs:
two weeks picking cherries in Stockton; two weeks working the
strawberry fields in Oregon. Then maybe on to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Even in good times, the Central Valley's core, from Stockton to
Bakersfield, is a vivid reminder that there are swaths of this
country where families must literally count their pennies.
Unemployment in Tulare County, where the freeze hit hardest,
usually hovers around 15 percent, more than 40 percent in some
towns.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a long time to recover from one fierce display of
nature. Unemployment is now more than 20 percent countywide _ 50
percent in some rural areas. Most people do not expect life to
return to normal again until the navel orange harvest begins in
late fall, or to fully recover for at least another year.
</P>
<P>
   The last freeze struck in 1990, and people say they are still
recovering from that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to leave this time,'' said Victor Espinoza, who said
he had spent 25 years working the lemon and orange orchards of
Tulare County. Sitting in his front yard in Porterville, a town the
freeze laid flat on its back, he said he was stir-crazy after
nearly seven months without work. He has a wife and teen-age
daughter to support, and he has bills to pay, same as everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go to Stockton or Washington,'' he said. ``But
friends said: `Don't bother. There are too many workers, working
too little.'''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Porterville, which has 37,000 residents, thousands of
ruined oranges _ their insides like little straw balls _ lie strewn
all over the groves. Nearly everyone depends on the crops one way
or another. If they do not grow, ship, pick or pack, their
customers do. So downtown, J.C. Penney, the multiplex movie theater
and the Cookie Jar Cafe are all eerily empty.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies, government and otherwise, have helped. The Federal
Emergency Management Agency has handed out $4.6 million in mortgage
and rental assistance to more than 2,700 workers. The state
Legislature, after lobbying by nonprofit community organizations
and the United Farm Workers, temporarily increased the maximum
amount a worker can earn and still receive unemployment benefits
from $25 a week to $200 so that workers called for a few hours will
not lose more by working than by collecting $150 unemployment
checks.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture is providing food to affected
workers, as are churches and private food pantries. The state has
handed out grants. Small numbers of workers have obtained temporary
community-service jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the aid has not reached everyone, or even most people. Most
of the out-of-work laborers are immigrants, some legal, some not.
``There are some enormous cracks'' in the system said James Gordon,
the chief executive officer of Proteus, a nonprofit community
organization in Visalia that has a contract from federal and local
governments to provide freeze relief.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, men who have not registered for selective
service are not eligible for emergency aid, though many are
immigrants who arrived in the United States after age 26 or who
never knew about the selective-service requirement.
</P>
<P>
   During the last freeze, changes in welfare laws meant that
undocumented workers, who make up an estimated 50 percent of the
pickers, could no longer receive emergency aid. Even some people
with legal work permits have been too intimidated to apply for
help.
</P>
<P>
   Guadalupe Arceo, a 30-year-old mother of three, is one of those.
Ms. Arceo, who is separated from her husband, has neither worked
nor received any aid this year. When she applied for rental
assistance, she said, she was told _ wrongly, relief workers say _
that she might hurt her application for permanent-resident status
because the Immigration and Naturalization Service would not look
kindly on applicants who might be a public burden.
</P>
<P>
   Although eligible, Ms. Arceo has never applied for food stamps
or aid for her children, ages 3 to 11. Since December, she has paid
the $280 rent for her apartment in a public housing project with
loans from relatives. Last month, she said, they told her their
money had run out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Arceo says she will have to move to New York City to
get a job to pay her bills. After eking out a life here so that her
children could be happy, it is her only choice, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll live with my brother's family in Manhattan through the
summer, make enough to pay the rent here and more, and come back
when the season starts again in November,'' she said, plane tickets
in hand. ``I don't see any other remedy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Grape workers are also in trouble because they are not eligible
for any freeze relief, even though they, too, were affected. Many
of their jobs were taken when labor contractors replaced them with
laid-off citrus workers willing to work for minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio and Melania Gomez, who have spent more than 20 years
picking grapes in Tulare County, and who scraped together enough
money to buy a little house in Porterville nine years ago, have
barely worked three weeks this year. Their bills are stuffed into a
letter holder in their living room, months of utility bills, not
including the high-interest loans they have taken from
acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   Their bank, they said, told them that it would turn them over to
a collection agency if they missed just one mortgage payment, and
they were turned down by every agency they asked for help. They
cannot receive welfare (``Not that we've ever wanted that!'' Mrs.
Gomez said) because they own a house. It is a very humble house, in
a poor neighborhood, but a house nonetheless. They are raising a
3-year-old grandson, but they receive no aid for him because they
are not his legal guardians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beg,'' Mrs. Gomez said, blushing deep red, as her husband
left the room to get Cokes for his guests. ``I drive to the nearby
towns, stand on the corners and put out my hand. I stand on line
for food and I stand on corners for money, because otherwise we
would starve, and we would sleep on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The grape harvest, which was supposed to begin again in the
first week of July, has been delayed a week or more by a mid-April
cold snap. The Gomezes worry that all the extra laborers will
finish the season's work early and they will never catch up on
their debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so disillusioned that we're putting the house up for
sale,'' Mrs. Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers are relatively lucky. Mirna Gonzalez, who earned a
reasonable living working in a large packing house, is one of 16
citrus workers now employed as temporary community organizers for
the National Farmworkers Service Center. The group offers advice to
workers and, with the state Department of Social Services and
Foodlink, a nonprofit organization, distributes food boxes in 32
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gonzalez's husband, also a citrus worker, is one of 8,000
laid-off workers collecting unemployment. ``When I visit other
families,'' Mrs. Gonzalez said, ``especially those who are not
documented and are not getting any help, I think we're very
lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers who live in the worst conditions are in shedlike
cement buildings, 12 men to one house, and in trailer parks where
chickens and pigeons roam on the pitted dirt roads.
</P>
<P>
   Ramona Martinez, an undocumented citrus worker, has spent eight
years picking oranges while living in a one-bedroom trailer with
her husband, three sons and her 68-year-old mother. She said the
family was starting to earn enough to move up. But that hope was
wiped out by the freeze. She and her husband, who are both trying
to become legal workers, pay their $200 rent with money they
receive in aid for their American-born children, and they buy food
with $150 a month in food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The husband, also an orange picker, has just taken a two-week
job as a mechanic's assistant, while the eldest son, who is 11,
does odd jobs _ packing groceries or pumping gas or stocking
shelves _ for tips. Then he gives his mother the money.
</P>
<P>
   The son ``keeps saying, `Let's go back to Mexico, where we could
live better,''' Mrs. Martinez said with a laugh. Like many
immigrants in Tulare County, the family comes from a dirt-poor town
in Michoacan, in central Mexico. She said she tells her son that
they are still better off here than there, or just the same when
there is a freeze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
