<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHY PLATO IS IN THIS HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, R.I. _ Plato couldn't make it, but Byron ``Whizzer''
White, Ken Dryden, Donna Lopiano, Yasutaka Matsudaira and Kwaku
Ohene-Frempong did. And Bill Bradley stopped by the night before.
</P>
<P>
   They were here for Sunday's inaugural induction ceremony of the
International Scholar-Athlete Hall of Fame, a charming white
building whose architecture might best be described as Grecian
Colonial on the University of Rhode Island campus.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find leather football helmets or cracked goaltender's
masks here, but you will find tributes to 20 people who took
studying as seriously as they took sport. As more of today's
college athletes should.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never considered myself a scholar or an athlete,'' said
Dryden, the Toronto Maple Leafs' president. ``I was just somebody
who loved to play and loved to learn. I came to realize that the
best kind of learning came with play, and the best kind of play
came with learning.''
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural inductees were selected by a panel of more than
2,000 academicians, journalists, Olympic officials and former
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to honor the great athlete,'' said Dan Doyle, the
founder of the Institute for International Sport, which is
conducting the U.S. Scholar-Athlete Games here this week.
``Meanwhile, we praise the scholar-athlete, but never really honor
him or her. This hall of fame will honor the world's greatest
scholar-athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the inductees will be familiar, but why Plato? Because
the Greek thinker, who is believed to have been a wrestler in the
Isthmian Games that were a warm-up to the ancient Olympics, argued
for the scholar-athlete ideal of mind and body, that physical
training should complement philosophical education for the best men
and women.
</P>
<P>
   The other inductees:
</P>
<P>
   Tenley Albright Blakeley, a graduate of Radcliffe and Harvard
Medical School, is a Boston surgeon. In 1956 she was the first
American woman to win gold in Olympic figure skating.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Ashe, a graduate of UCLA, won the first U.S. Open tennis
title in 1968 and Wimbledon in 1975. He later emerged as a
worldwide sociological voice for African-American athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Bannister, a British neurologist, was the first to break 4
minutes for the mile, running it in 3 minutes 59.4 seconds in 1954.
He's a past president of the International Council for Sport and
Recreation.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, a Rhodes scholar and basketball all-American at
Princeton, is a former senator from New Jersey and currently a
presidential candidate. He was on the Knicks' two championship
teams.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush, the 41st president of the United States, was a Phi
Beta Kappa economics graduate of Yale and the captain of its 1948
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre de Coubertin, a French educator, proposed the first
modern Olympics in 1896 to promote world peace and education
through sports.
</P>
<P>
   James ``Doc'' Counsilman, a Ph.D., was a two-time U.S. Olympic
swimming coach. At age 58, he swam the English Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Anita DeFrantz, a Connecticut College graduate and an Olympic
rower, is the first female vice president of the International
Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Dryden, a graduate of Cornell and McGill Law School, was the
Montreal Canadiens' goaltender on six Stanley Cup championship
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Ford, the 38th president of the United States, was the
center on two University of Michigan national championship football
teams. As a Yale Law School graduate, he served 25 years in the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Jones, a lawyer who was a graduate of Georgia Tech and
Harvard, completed golf's Grand Slam in 1930, sweeping the U.S.
Open, British Open, U.S. Amateur and British Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Lopiano, a Southern Connecticut State graduate,
participated in 26 national championships in softball, basketball,
volleyball and field hockey. She is the director of the Women's
Sports Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Yasutaka Matsudaira, a graduate of Keio University in Japan, is
credited with revolutionizing volleyball with his multiple
quick-attack system. He coached Japan to Olympic gold in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   James Naismith, a Canadian educated at McGill University and
Presbyterian College in Montreal, invented basketball in 1891 as a
physical education teacher at what is now Springfield College in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Kwaku Ohene-Frempong, a Ghana native who excelled in soccer and
track at Yale, is a hematologist, the chief medical officer of the
Sickle Cell Disease Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Robeson, a Phi Beta Kappa and all-America running back at
Rutgers, emerged as a compelling African-American actor and singer.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Benoit Samuelson, now an author and a trustee of her alma
mater, Bowdoin, won the first women's Olympic marathon in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Snell, who won three Olympic gold medals in the 800 and
1,500 meters for New Zealand, is the director of the Human
Performance Laboratory at the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Byron ``Whizzer'' White, a U.S. Supreme Court Justice for 31
years, was Phi Beta Kappa, a Rhodes scholar and an all-America
running back at the University of Colorado before joining the
Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're driving I-95 with your kids, take the Kingston exit
and stop by a hall where fame is more than a game. Plato would like
that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
