</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S CHECKETTS' TURN AS SEASONS CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Now the New York Knicks' season is officially
over.
</P>
<P>
   Tears from Friday's loss baked dry by Sunday's hot midday sun,
disappointment softened by the passing of nearly 48 hours. The
Knicks arrived at their practice facility in cars and sport utility
vehicles to clear out lockers, coordinate summer plans. One by one
they emerged, looking backward and forward.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs recalled Friday's 1-point loss at Madison Square
Garden that brought San Antonio the National Basketball Association
championship. ``Watching them celebrate on our court was not
enjoyable,'' Childs said. ``That was motivation enough to work
harder during the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby spoke exuberantly of summer league competition and
getting stronger. Allan Houston spoke of staying in shape, not
becoming puffed up by Knicks fans telling the team how great it was
just to come close. Latrell Sprewell, resurrected as savior if not
quite a saint, came out and spoke briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Patrick Aloysius Ewing emerged and was immediately
mobbed. If Sprewell and Camby were the unexpected stars of the
Knicks' championship run, Ewing is the central figure of whatever
will come next. He was injured through the stretch run and watched
the final round from the bench as the Knicks compensated for his
lost presence with quickness, speed and heart. A perfect fit for an
ambush season. Could Ewing fit back in?
</P>
<P>
   What do the Knicks need to do to get over the top?
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to play, that's it,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   Will the lineup work with Ewing joining Sprewell and Houston? He
said that was the coach's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the dagger question, the question that has dominated
Knicks debates since Ewing's Achilles' tendon problems limited his
effectiveness and then ended his season prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his role would change, Ewing winced and said he
was tired of reading how the Knicks would be better off without
him. ``My role is not going to change,'' he said. ``I have a lot of
great players on my team, we just have to believe in each other and
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked if Ewing was ready to do what David Robinson did _
give up some shots, as Robinson did for for Tim Duncan. ``I gave up
shots,'' Ewing said. ``And on that note you all have a nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   When the season started in February, the pressure was on
Sprewell and Camby to perform; Sprewell for what he had done, Camby
for whom he replaced. They did their part. In the process, they
helped transform the Knicks into a faster, younger team from a
plodding halfcourt team built around Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pressure is squarely on Dave Checketts, the Madison
Square Garden president. The new Knicks are poised to be
juggernauts for the next two or three seasons, but they need some
answers. Can the Knicks retain the same up-tempo flow and still use
Ewing's low-post presence? Checketts is like the chess player who
has gained great position and superior material but at the moment
of truth needs a brilliant move.
</P>
<P>
   The move may be making Ed Tapscott, currently the Knicks' vice
president of player personnel, the team president and general
manager. The problem with Knicks general managers was that they
either had basketball sense or intelligence but never both
simultaneously. Tapscott, a lawyer and former head coach at George
Washington, who helped the deposed Ernie Grunfeld orchestrate some
of the Knicks' better acquisitions, has both.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are a smooth-running team with two charismatic
players in Sprewell and Camby, a ``clean-cut'' emerging star in
Houston, and Ewing, the mainstay. What to do with Ewing? ``They
need me to play,'' he said. ``That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy agreed, saying, ``I always emphasize to
Patrick that the importance of him has not changed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Knicks need is a governor, someone to control speed,
pressure, pace emotion and loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   As this Knicks became a quicker, faster-playing team, I wondered
whether Van Gundy really enjoyed this new style of play or simply
enjoyed surviving and winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Style doesn't matter,'' Van Gundy said.``It might matter to
people who watch it, but methods don't matter, results do. You play
however you feel you can best win. If I feel it's best to win
trying to keep it at 50-48, that's how I'll keep it. And if I think
it's best to play 120-118, that's how we'll play because methods
don't matter. Results do.''
</P>
<P>
   Style does matter, and Van Gundy better not try that 50-48
nonsense next season; Checketts better not let him. Knicks fans
didn't simply enjoy the ride to the championship series, they
enjoyed the way they got there. The speed, excitement, the
take-no-prisoner attitude and schoolyard dunks made the Knicks' old
50-48 signature seem prehistoric.
</P>
<P>
   How ya gonna keep `em down on the farm, after they've seen
Paree?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LPGA-INKSTER-NYT &LR;      06-27 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LPGA-INKSTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BIRDIES IN A ROW, IT'S INKSTER'S DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RON SIRAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Time and again, Juli Inkster tapped into an
inner reservoir of strength and found the big shot she needed. Time
and again, she made an important putt and accentuated it with a
tight-lipped smile, and followed a disappointing miss with a
grunted lecture to herself.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, it seemed as if she might lose the struggle
being waged deep within and let her flirtation with history slip
away.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just when it appeared as if she might be going to the well
for miracles too often, Inkster closed brilliantly Sunday to win
the McDonald's Ladies Professional Golf Association Championship
and become only the second woman to complete the modern career
Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Dancing and fist-pumping her way to a close of eagle, birdie,
birdie with a scintillating series of putts for a final-round 65,
Inkster finished at 16-under-par 268, four strokes ahead of
Liselotte Neumann and five better than Mardi Lunn and Nancy
Scranton.
</P>
<P>
   Added to the U.S. Open that Inkster won three weeks ago, she
ended an odyssey that began in 1984 when she won the Nabisco Dinah
Shore and the du Maurier Classic, the other designated LPGA majors,
to join Pat Bradley as the only women to win all four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won two pretty quick and I didn't think it was going to be
that tough,'' Inkster said about waiting 15 years to finish the
Grand Slam. ``I can't comprehend it. I want to savor this. I worked
really hard the last three years to get back to where I should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   That climb back came after she negotiated her daughters Hayley,
9, and Cori, 5, through infancy. Inkster's first three majors _ she
also won the Dinah Shore in 1989 _ came before her children were
born.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 39, she has won two Grand Slam events since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just doing what any mother would do,'' Inkster said.
</P>
<P>
   Greatness in an athlete is frequently found in how they perform
when they are not at the top of their game. And Inkster was not
hitting on all cylinders when Sunday's round started at DuPont
Country Club. The frustration, and perhaps the pressure, was
evident.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster started the round sharing the lead with Scranton and
Cristie Kerr, and she seemed tense as she missed 4-footer after
4-footer on the practice green. It was a trend that carried over
into the round.
</P>
<P>
   On the third tee, Inkster glared back at the second green where
she had just missed a 5-foot birdie putt, and hissed an emphatic
``Man!'' snapping her head forward to stress the point. After
missing an 8-foot birdie try on No. 6, she stood with arms folded
and stared at her shoes. Then her momentum changed when an 8-foot,
par-saving putt found the bottom of the cup on No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Looking relaxed for the first time, Inkster strolled to the back
of the eighth tee, and talked with her husband, Brian. Moments
later she was rolling in her first birdie putt of the day _ a
20-footer _ and followed that with a 15-footer on No. 9 to take a
lead she never surrendered, although she was forced to share it
briefly with a game group of challengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really got me going,'' she said about saving par on No.
7. ``Brian said, `Good work,' and told me to just keep doing what
I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster put on an awesome putting display over the last 12
holes, needing only one putt nine times, including consecutive
10-foot, par-saving putts on Nos. 13 and 14. At that point, Inkster
appeared to be relying too heavily on miracles, but then she
reached inside and found something even more special.
</P>
<P>
   The par-saving putts on 7, 13 and 14 won the tournament, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several players performed very well on this sultry Sunday, but
no one could run with Inkster when she kicked toward the finish
line. At one point _ with Neumann through 16 holes, Inkster through
15 and Scranton through 14 _ there was a three-way tie at 12 under
par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really good when I made that birdie at 16,'' Neumann
said. ``I was right in the hunt. Then Juli played the last three
holes four under par. It's hard to put pressure on someone playing
that well.''
</P>
<P>
   On No. 16, Inkster hit a 5-wood she described as a career shot
from 232 yards to within 18 feet, and made the eagle putt.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was an 8-iron to six feet on No. 17, and a 7-iron to 20
feet on the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one was like I was putting into a bucket,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she did at Old Waverly where she won the U.S. Open, Inkster
was able to acknowledge victory after her approach shot to the
final green. This time she sprinted forward, wrapped playing
partner Meg Mallon in a warm hug and raised both arms high above
her head in what amounted to a symbolic V for victory.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was her fourth of the year on tour and the $210,000
first prize put Inkster at the top of the money list with $952,994.
She is now only one point away from qualifying for the LPGA Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doable,'' she said. ``It would be nice if it happened
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems almost certain that the Hall of Fame is an honor
Inkster will not need another 15 years to claim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
