<HEADLINE>
BUNKER MENTALITY WINS FOR WALDORF ON 19TH HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ Running out of holes, and running out of
opportunities, Duffy Waldorf picked the perfect time for a birdie
binge on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by two strokes with two holes left in regulation,
Waldorf birdied Nos. 17 and 18 to force a playoff, then birdied the
first playoff hole (No. 18) to win the Buick Classic in dramatic
fashion over Dennis Paulson. Waldorf and Paulson both finished
regulation at 8 under par (276), one stroke ahead of Chris Perry,
who finished third, and two strokes ahead of Scott Hoch.
</P>
<P>
   It was a special victory for Waldorf, who had won just once
before on the PGA Tour, but who rose to the occasion when others
could not.
</P>
<P>
   Two superb bunker shots were the key to Waldorf's victory. At
No. 18 during regulation, Waldorf delicately floated a full-swing
bunker shot 30 yards from the cup to within 5 feet, setting up the
birdie putt that forced a playoff. Then in the playoff, Waldorf's
bunker shot from 40 yards landed just 12 feet past the cup, setting
up the tournament-clinching birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   Not often does a player facing two long bunker shots get up and
down twice for birdies to win a tournament. But Waldorf did, and at
age 37 he left Westchester Country Club with a $450,000 first-place
check, his first tour victory since 1995, and the knowledge that he
was still good enough to defeat the world's best players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never, never had a finish like this,'' said Waldorf,
whose other tour victory came at the 1995 LaCantera Texas Open.
``If you looked at the bunker shots I hit all week, those were my
two best without a doubt. I kind of let my instinct take over,
because a long bunker shot is one of the hardest. That was a great
way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldorf had just two rounds in the 60s (70-67-68-71), but he was
resilient as he overcame six bogeys in his final round to win. He
enjoys writing messages on his golf balls, and the ball he used on
the final four holes was adorned with this message, ``It's up to
you, N.Y., N.Y.'' It was fitting, because when it was up to
Waldorf, he delivered.
</P>
<P>
   For Paulson, who shot a final-round 67, it was a difficult
defeat, but a career-best showing for a 36-year-old player who has
never won on tour. Starting the day at 4 under par, four strokes
behind Waldorf and Perry, Paulson teed off 54 minutes before
Waldorf and played a terrific final round to take the clubhouse
lead. Then Paulson waited nervously to see if any of the remaining
contenders could beat him.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, other players eliminated themselves with costly
mistakes, falling like dominoes. But Waldorf finally forced the
playoff, making a 6-foot birdie putt on No. 17 to start his birdie
run. Afterward, Paulson was a gracious loser. Perhaps the one shot
Paulson wanted back was an 18-foot birdie attempt that he missed on
No. 18 during regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing in one sense, but I hit a lot of good putts
that didn't go in the hole,'' said Paulson, a good friend of
Waldorf, who grew up playing many junior golf tournaments against
him in California. ``Duffy hit great bunker shots. I can't tell you
how great that bunker shot was he hit to get into the playoff. He
had to commit to swinging hard. It was a pretty impressive shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulson made a costly mistake with his second shot on the
playoff hole, the par-5, 526-yard No. 18. After hitting his drive
in the right fringe, Paulson hit a 3-wood from 245 yards that faded
right. It landed in the rough behind the right green-side bunker,
underneath a tree that made it impossible for Paulson to play a
high wedge shot onto the green.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 yards from the pin, Paulson was forced to attempt a
difficult low punch shot that had to carry the bunker, yet land
softly on the green. The shot hit a branch and stopped short of the
green, still about 30 feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Waldorf had reached the left green-side bunker in two
shots. His final bunker shot was pure, rolling across the green,
and stopping on the fringe, about 12 feet past the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Then Paulson hit a poor chip shot that rolled 18 feet past the
cup, and he missed his putt coming back for a costly bogey. At that
point, Waldorf knew he could 2-putt from 12 feet and still win. But
he wasted no time, making the putt for birdie and then celebrating.
A wine connoisseur, Waldorf knew how he would celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was at home, I'd open up every wine I had, all the most
expensive ones,'' he said. ``I have a couple of bottles picked
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
