<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-KOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS GO THE BENCH; RESULT IS STILL FIRST-RATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ On a night when four starters rested, the
United States showed the depth of its bench by overpowering North
Korea, 3-0, in the final match of group play in the Women's World
Cup. Tisha Venturini scored two goals and celebrated with a back
flip, bringing a little spring into the Americans' step after a
torpid, scoreless first half.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon MacMillan also scored a goal and collected two assists
as the Americans (3-0) advanced to the quarterfinals to play
Germany on Thursday night at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium in suburban
Washington. By reaching the quarterfinals, the United States also
qualified to defend its title at the 2000 Summer Olympics in
Sydney, Australia, and it remains on course as the favorite to win
this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The first goal came in the 58th minute, awakening a somnolent
crowd of 50,484 at Foxboro Stadium. MacMillan, a hero on the 1996
Olympic team who was starting her first match of this World Cup,
took a pass from Julie Foudy on the left flank and laced a short
hopper inside the left post. The North Korean goalie Kye Yong Sun
should have stopped the shot, but she could only manage a futile
dive.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, MacMillan fielded a cross from Tiffeny
Milbrett and chipped a pass to Venturini, another first-time
starter, who headed the ball into the net for the second American
goal. In the 76th minute, MacMillan found Venturini on a free kick
for another header, which Venturini saluted with a back flip. She
had been an Olympic starter, but her role had been diminished in
recent years. On Sunday night, she demonstrated the resourcefulness
of the American team, which is deeper than any other in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo Facchin, coach of the Italian team that tied Germany, 1-1,
in group play last Sunday, said that the reliable, organized German
team could give the Americans trouble. But the Germans have proved
to be a step slow, and in allowing a goal in extra time Sunday in a
3-3 tie with Brazil, they have shown vulnerability in protecting a
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the U.S. will have difficulty with Germany,'' Facchin
said. ``They know how to keep the level of the game controlled. I
think if the U.S. can raise the level of the match with speed, it
is going to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   With advancement certain, barring a complete collapse, the
Americans had the delicate task Sunday night of trying to rest some
of their players while not losing the momentum the team had gained
in shutting out Denmark, 3-0, and routing Nigeria, 7-1. Having
scored 10 goals and surrendered only 1, the United States had
covered itself regarding the first tie-breaker in group play, goal
differential.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a quarterfinal match Thursday and a potential semifinal
match next Sunday in Palo Alto, Calif., along with the rough
tackling style of North Korea, coach Tony DiCicco gave four
starters the night off.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Michelle Akers, the star of the 1991 Women's World
Cup has chronic fatigue syndrome and has to ration her playing
time. Kate Sobrero, a gritty defender, sat out the match, resting a
wrenched ankle for the quarterfinal. Foudy also took a rest in
midfield, as did the team's leading scorer this season, Milbrett.
</P>
<P>
   Inserted into the lineup along with MacMillan and Venturini were
the speedy Sara Whalen and Tiffany Roberts in defense. Brandi
Chastain was moved forward from defense to the midfield in the
restructured lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With a previous victory and a defeat in group play, the North
Koreans needed to defeat the Americans to advance over Nigeria into
the quarterfinals against Brazil on Thursday. Given their
precarious position, the North Koreans took no chances. They were
content to play with five defenders, packing the penalty box,
hoping to smother the relentless American attack and perhaps get a
counterattack goal or a penalty shot at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four minutes into the match, North Korea had already
collected two yellow-card warnings for rough tackles. The
Americans, meanwhile, seemed torpid, the urgency gone from their
game along with four starters. Perhaps their energy was sapped by
the muggy air or the knowledge that they would advance as long as
they were not humiliated. Or maybe they missed Akers' ability to
control the midfield and spray passes ahead.
</P>
<P>
   By patiently working the ball from side to side, the Americans
gradually began to find seams in the North Korean defense. Cindy
Parlow floated a shot just over the crossbar. MacMillan fired a
blast from point-blank range that was stopped by a sliding save.
Carla Overbeck launched a rocket from the top of the penalty box.
But nothing found the net as the Americans kept missing high, like
a Mark Wohlers fastball.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea threatened only once in the first half, as Jin Pyol
Hui lofted a shot from the left wing that U.S. goalie Briana Scurry
did not appear to immediately lock onto with her personal radar.
But Scurry backpedaled gracefully, tracking the shot down and
swatting it away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
