<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-810(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECKER AND TEEN-AGERS MAKE WEEK 1 THEIR OWN
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A soap opera on some days, a nostalgia
festival on others, and suspiciously rain-free through the first
week, Wimbledon has been nothing if not a portent that the more
things change, the more they stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   Although this may be his final joy ride, Boris Becker still
gallops around Center Court with the impunity of an overgrown
Napoleon. And although this may be their first brush with Grand
Slam success, ruthless little girls still stop at nothing to grab
the brass ring of the fast-track carousel they have been hoisted
onto by ambitious parents.
</P>
<P>
   Over on the men's side heading into the round of 16, the
31-year-old Becker is going for glory one last time, Pete Sampras
is aiming for a Grand Slam record with a sixth Wimbledon crown and
Andre Agassi is proving his 1999 French Open title, which made him
the first man since Rod Laver to scale all four Grand Slam events,
was no New Age fluke.
</P>
<P>
   But in the women's quadrant, flux and unfamiliar faces, along
with a noxious gossip quotient, are providing the plot. These days,
gaining a high profile in women's tennis is a little like marrying
Henry VIII. You're apt to lose your head.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Martina Hingis, the top-ranked teen-ager humbled
in Wimbledon's opening round, gone slinking off to lick her wounds,
and repair an ill-timed estrangement from her mother, then three
younger teens, each of them as driven as the suddenly defunct
Hingis, sprang up to take her place.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of Hingis, the century's youngest No. 1 when she was 16
and Wimbledon's youngest champion in 1997, has devolved into a sob
story in 1999. Hingis, now 18, seems to have come into her
adolescent rebellion belatedly, and so far she and her results are
suffering for it.
</P>
<P>
   Her verbal outbursts have included a derogatory reference to
Amelie Mauresmo, runner-up to her in the Australian Open, as ``half
a man'' after she announced her lesbianism there; a description of
Jana Novotna, her discarded doubles partner and Wimbledon's
defending singles and doubles champion, as ``old and slow,'' and a
snide remark about Steffi Graf being over the hill in a game
populated by a group Hingis likes to call the Spice Girls of
Tennis.
</P>
<P>
   When Graf defeated her for the French Open title earlier this
month, Hingis put on a tantrum notable for a trespass onto Graf's
side of the court to argue a line call and a pair of defiant
underhand serves on match points, prompting the fans to boo her off
the court. After her mother/coach, Melanie Molitor, insisted that
she return for the trophy presentations, Hingis did, but it was
apparently the last time she followed advice from Molitor.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wimbledon began, the two agreed to distance themselves
from each other, and when Hingis was trampled by 6-2, 6-0 in the
first round by 16-year-old Jelena Dokic, a Slovak-born prodigy whom
Molitor and Hingis tutored on their backyard courts this spring,
Molitor was back in Switzerland instead of in the Friends Box.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Friends Box lacked prominent occupants. Under close
scrutiny by the British press, as well as officials of the WTA
Tour, was Dokic's father, Damir, who introduced himself to the
limelight three weeks ago by getting thrown out of the Edgbaston
event for causing a ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   Damir Dokic then lay in the middle of the road and had to be
removed by the Birmingham police, who cautioned him about his
drunkenness but let him sleep off his troubles in their jail and
returned him to the custody of his daughter without pressing
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his mouthing off about England, which he disparaged as
far inferior to Sydney, Australia, the home base he selected for
his prodigy when she was 9, his behavior has been unremarkable ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   But Damir Dokic, who recently dismissed Lester Bowrey, the
Australian Fed Cup captain, as his daughter's coach and tennis
confidant, has been given the tabloid label ``the tennis father
from hell.''
</P>
<P>
   He seems to be replacing the parent of another of Wimbledon
1999's emergent teens. It was exactly a year ago that Mirjana
Lucic, the Croatian talent who won her first professional event at
15, decided to flee from Zagreb to Florida with her mother and
three siblings after having a violent argument with her father and
coach, Marinko, during Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Lucic has since accused her father of physically and emotionally
abusive conduct and has cut all ties to him. Now 17 and based at
the Bollettieri Sports Academy in Bradenton, Fla., Lucic is making
a comeback after settling her domestic woes and hiring a coach, Joe
Giuliano, skilled in the art of constructive, not destructive,
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was used to pressure a lot, because I had it from all over,
always,'' said Lucic, who called the juxtaposition of teen stars
with parent-coaches an ``almost impossible'' relationship for a
family to survive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After Lucic, whose game is reminiscent of Graf's in the same
vein that Dokic's resembles that of Hingis, outgunned Monica Seles
to reach her first Grand Slam Round of 16, Giuliano said he had
needed to rebuild her emotional core before bothering to fine-tune
her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to build back her self-esteem,'' Giuliano said. ``She
had to be able to think of herself as a good person first before
she got the chance to be a great player.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were basically saying that Lucic was through, that she
couldn't play anymore, but we wanted to come here and make a
statement that yes, she's back, and with a vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano previously worked with Dokic's next opponent, Mary
Pierce, whose coach and father, Jim, was expelled from the circuit
for five years because of improper conduct similar to that ascribed
to Marinko Lucic.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the two European-born teens, both of whom turned
professional at 15, Wimbledon served as a coming-out party for
18-year-old Alexandra Stevenson, a California-based powerhouse with
an absentee father but a mother, Samantha, who groomed her
6-foot-1-inch daughter for this career path by retracing the
intricate coaching steps taken by another Southern California
standout, Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson's Wimbledon idyll has not been free of controversies,
generated by remarks made by her mother during impromptu news
conferences. According to Samantha Stevenson, a freelance
sportswriter whose work appears in The New York Times as well as
other publications, Alexandra, who is black, has been subjected to
racist remarks and a general lack of respect by opponents on the
WTA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The Stevensons are also in a dispute with the tour, which
maintains that Alexandra _ who decided to turn pro for this
tournament _ entered the tournament as an amateur and is not
entitled to prize money. Samantha Stevenson says that she informed
the tournament committee at the Wimbledon qualifying tournament
about Alexandra's intent to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson decided to reject a scholarship offer from UCLA in
order to follow in the footprints of her role models Venus and
Serena Williams. Stevenson, who upset 11th-seeded Julie
Halard-Decugis to earn a round of 16 berth, was the giddiest of the
teen threesome making moves at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought a pair of shoes, these really cool high platform
shoes, like Spice Girl shoes, and a really cool green dress,'' said
Stevenson, who wants to win Wimbledon by age 19. ``I will be ready
with my serve-and-volley game and forehand; I'm taking it one match
at a time and looking one step forward. I'm in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, they all are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
