<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROGAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cancer takes Lt. Gov.'s wife
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Mary Brogan, the wife and childhood
sweetheart of Lt. Gov. Frank Brogan, died with him by her side
Sunday at Tallahassee Memorial Hospital two years after being
diagnosed with cancer. She was 44.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columba and I are saddened beyond words at the loss of Mary
Brogan,'' said Gov. Jeb Bush, who ordered the state's flags to be
lowered in her honor. ``We have lost a true friend, Frank has lost
a true partner and the people of Florida have lost a true public
servant with a big heart.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Martin County school teacher and assistant principal,
Mrs. Brogan was first diagnosed with cancer in 1997 when she
discovered a lump in her breast. Doctors found the cancer had
spread to her bones and she underwent a mastectomy and bone marrow
transplant at Shands Hospital at the University of Florida in
Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   She was in remission for more than a year when, in December
1998, doctors once again found cancer. This time it had spread to
her brain. The treatment for her cancer was so painful that she
confided that she dreaded going through treatments again.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a whisper, she said, ``It's not me I'm worried about. I
worry about Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank and Mary Brogan were Catholic school students when they
met as teenagers in Cincinnati, Ohio. After college they came to
Florida where they both eventually became teachers in Martin
County. Both became school administrators and Frank Brogan was
elected schools superintendent in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Bright, funny, articulate, hard working, telegenic and
ambitious, Mrs. Brogan proved to be an able political partner when
the couple decided that Frank Brogan should run for state education
commissioner in 1994. Mrs. Brogan's popularity often overpowered
her husband's and the couple seemed to have unlimited
possibilities. Many Republicans believe Frank Brogan could be
governor or a U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he was picked to be Bush's running mate. In October,
Mrs. Brogan joined the campaign's final bus tour of the state.
Still in remission, she stood outside the bus one afternoon and
said she believed, with her fingers crossed for luck, that the
worst was behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Days before Christmas, doctors gave her the bad news that the
cancer was back. In January, when her husband was sworn in as
lieutenant governor, scores of women wore hats in a show of support
for Mrs. Brogan who had taken to wearing hats due to hair loss
caused by therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No story about Mary would be complete without children,'' said
Betty Coxe, who used to teach school with Mrs. Brogan in Stuart and
remembered her constantly being surrounded by students. ``She had
that Pied Piperette-ability to have all the kids worship and adore
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Not having children of her own, Mrs. Brogan once said that ``if
you're dedicated, education becomes so much a part of your life
that the children, the teachers, the parents and the community
become your family.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the Brogans were never shy about showing their genuine
affection for each other. Once when the couple visited the Orange
Avenue Charter School in Fort Pierce a third grader asked Brogan _
``Is your wife a queen?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services in Tallahassee and Martin County were still
being planned Sunday. The Brogan family is asking that donations be
made in her memory to the Mary J. Brogan Scholarship Fund, care of
Martin County Community Foundation II. In addition to her husband,
Mary Brogan is survived by two sisters, Jane Leisring and Carol
Stacey, both of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
