<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-27 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE WOMEN CATCH UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ Women's soccer is catching up with men's
soccer. This is not necessarily all to the good.
</P>
<P>
   The American and North Korean women, with separate agendas,
played basically separate games in a slow-developing 3-0 American
victory Sunday night. The steamy evening went along with the
survival brand of soccer often seen toward the end of first-round
games in the men's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   After finally breaking through the Korean wall, the Yanks play
Germany in the quarterfinal round in suburban Maryland on Thursday
night and the North Koreans go home.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks, who needed only to avoid being beaten by double
figures, used the game to work in fresh players, let some excellent
subs win their varsity letter and save some regulars for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans, who had needed a victory, were eliminated
after doing what they had to do _ shorten the field, pack the
defenders and hope for some grotesque mistake by the Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shame to have such a dull and scoreless first half
after the excitement generated by the women in the first week. The
skill and charisma of the Americans and other teams had captivated
enough people to form a new layer of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer has come of age in the past decade, marked by
aggressive offense and very little of the diving and flopping
exhibited by the men. Because women are smaller and less powerful
than the men, the field seems bigger, with more room for creativity
and initiative.
</P>
<P>
   From Portland to Chicago, San Jose to New Jersey, some of the
passes and runs and saves and tackles have been exquisite, bringing
aficionado cheers in the stands _ and more than a few exclamations
of ``Nice ball!'' in the press box.
</P>
<P>
   There were not many shouts of ``Nice ball!'' Sunday night. The
North Koreans played with a 1-1-10 defense (that's a bad soccer
joke; each team is allowed only 10 field players) and the
Americans' lineup was so radically altered that the players seemed
to be working things out as they went along.
</P>
<P>
   The best game of the day was on the tube, direct from Jack Kent
Cooke Stadium. It is an official soccer law that every World Cup,
male or female, must have a Group of Death. The noted German
player, Juergen Klinsmann _ now retired and gone to heaven in
California _ has been apologizing profusely for picking the
``wrong'' name out of the hat during the official draw in February,
thereby putting his homeland in the Todtgruppe.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had incentives to win Sunday _ avoiding the United
States in the next round. Brazil, whose women wear the same
hallowed blue and yellow garb as its men, showed why it is always
the spiritual favorite. Trailing after 90 minutes of regulation
time, Maicon of Brazil lofted home a soft, graceful shot that gave
Brazil a 3-3 tie, and the players cavorted just as you would expect
Brazilian players to do.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there was a sense of tension and emotion in this World
Cup because the good teams have generally been bombing the mediocre
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the action moved to this steamy outback of New England.
With absolutely nothing to gain, Italy beat Mexico, 2-0, in the
first game. One family right in front of the press box displayed
absolute equal opportunity _ the girl had a HAMM jersey, the boy
had a MALDINI jersey, for the stylish captain of the Italian men's
team.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has had only moments of terror in the first
round. Denmark hung on for a while before a 3-0 loss. Then Nigeria
scored the first goal before succumbing, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   In a nice gesture, totally supportable by the depth of the
American team, Tony DiCicco started three of his gold-medal players
from the 1996 Summer Games in Georgia who had not started to date:
Tiffany Roberts, Tisha Venturini and Shannon MacMillan. He also
started Sara Whalen, a young defender.
</P>
<P>
   With the Koreans packing the defenses, hoping for a miracle, the
Americans took a long time to get untracked. The new formation
never got untracked. In fact, their goalkeeper, Briana Scurry, did
have some desperate moments, slapping away one soft, high lob,
smothering another low shot off a breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks finally broke through in the second half, with one
goal by MacMillan and two by Venturini, from the 1996 gold-medal
game. Venturini celebrated her second with a backflip, the kind
that Ozzie Smith used to perform on the last day of the baseball
season.
</P>
<P>
   The backflip was quite likely to be seen on the sports highlight
shows that normally avoid any sighting of soccer, as if to keep
loyal Americans from being contaminated by such subversive doings.
However, a backflip by the lithe Venturini is the stuff of
highlight tapes. Maybe she even planned it, the way male basketball
players plan their dunks, with an eye toward the replay. The women
are catching up with the men, in every way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
