<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      06-27 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A MEMORABLE RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 28:
</P>
<P>
   The laws of basketball finally caught up with the New York
Knicks Friday night, when their thrilling and improbable run at the
National Basketball Association championship ended in a 78-77 loss
to the San Antonio Spurs. They were too short and too banged up to
compete against a taller, healthier ball club that genuinely
deserved the title. Yet when the Knicks were finally done, when
Latrell Sprewell missed a last-second, off-balance jump shot, the
crowd at Madison Square Garden gave them a winners' ovation. They
deserved it. Despite crippling injuries, the Knicks somehow
contrived to defeat three favored teams in the playoffs and give an
honorable account of themselves in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   The national television ratings were down, probably because
Michael Jordan was not around and because the viewers decided this
was a mismatch. Too bad for the viewers. They missed the formal
certification of the Spurs' Tim Duncan as a true superstar and _ in
Sprewell's 35-point performance on Friday _ one of the great
individual displays in playoff history. Above all they missed the
magical, real-time evolution of the Knicks from primitive plodders
to creative artists.
</P>
<P>
   In Sprewell, Allan Houston and Marcus Camby, three explosive
players, the Knicks have the nucleus of a championship team. But
can they mesh with Patrick Ewing, the Knicks' all-star center? It
was Ewing's injury, after all, that forced Jeff Van Gundy, the
coach, to turn Sprewell, Camby and Houston loose. The Knicks have
left warm memories, and some pleasurable off-season puzzles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1326 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-PEACE-BOS &LR;      06-27 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
  
 PEACE PROCESS STALLED, BUT MANY IN ULSTER EXPECT IT TO GO ON
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BELFAST _ Last year, when compromise finally came to Northern
Ireland, native son Seamus Heaney was moved to write that it was a
time when hope and history rhymed.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, history is not rhyming so much as repeating
itself in a place where intransigence has been widely regarded as a
strength, and compromise a sign of weakness.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after the people of Northern Ireland
overwhelmingly approved a referendum that created structures
designed to move the conflict from the battlefield to the political
arena _ and basked in the international acclaim that followed _ the
peace process is stalled.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland Assembly, held up as the cornerstone of a
new, more equitable society, is in danger of being shelved even
before it regains the powers the British government summarily took
over in 1972 when the violence, which has killed more than 3,500
since 1969, was at its worst.
</P>
<P>
   As it has been since the Irish Republican Army called an initial
cease-fire in 1994, the sticking point is the fate of the IRA's
weapons. Protestant unionists refuse to sit in a power-sharing
government with Sinn Fein, the IRA's political representatives,
until the IRA begins disarming.
</P>
<P>
   But the Good Friday Agreement, which was reached in April 1998,
and endorsed by 71 percent of the voters in Northern Ireland and 95
percent in the Irish Republic, says only that the decommissioning
of paramilitary weapons should be completed by May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has categorically ruled out turning in its weapons,
saying that would amount to a surrender it did not agree to. The
IRA remembers what happened in 1969, when it was caught unarmed as
loyalist mobs overran Catholic neighborhoods, a humiliation it has
vowed will never be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   But unionists say that unless the IRA disarms, it will be
impossible to build a genuine democracy, because there will always
be the threat that the IRA will go back to war if its political
representatives don't get their way.
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments have set Wednesday as the
deadline for agreement, and for creating the power-sharing
government. On Friday, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his
Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, gave the parties a proposal to
break the stalemate. It calls for Sinn Fein to be allowed into
government, but insists the party must accept firm timetables that
call for the IRA to disarm by May 2000, and face expulsion from
government if the timetables are not met.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews here with leading politicians suggest that both the
unionists and Sinn Fein are prepared to let the deadline pass.
Although Blair says he has no Plan B, there is little hope that
Plan A will be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Unionist leader David Trimble said the proposed compromise falls
short of the unionist demand that some weapons be turned in at the
outset. Sinn Fein has made no response, but privately, leading
party officials said the governments are expecting them to deliver
the undeliverable: IRA guns.
</P>
<P>
   More fundamentally, Sinn Fein says it won seats in an election
and is entitled to take them without preconditions. In an
interview, Martin McGuiness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator and
former IRA chief of staff, said unionist demands for a token
surrender of weapons is a smokescreen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about decommissioning. The unionists don't want
Fenians in government,'' McGuinness said, using the 19th century
term for Irish separatists, which Protestants use as a derogatory
term for Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   McGuinness said he was prepared to see the Northern Ireland
Assembly suspended, which just may happen next week if the two
sides refuse to compromise. Beginning  &UR; today &LR; , negotiations will
resume at Castle Buildings, the drab office building where last
year's historic Good Friday Agreement was hatched.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a long way from the heady days of just a year ago
when politicians here surprised the world, and even themselves, by
signing an agreement that acknowledged that Northern Ireland would
remain part of the United Kingdom, but called for reform of a
political and police system that had systematically discriminated
against Catholic nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble and the moderate nationalist leader, John Hume, shared
the Nobel Peace Prize last winter. But while a real degree of
normality has evolved, the dispute over the IRA's weapons has
stalled the effort to get politicians in Northern Ireland to run
their own affairs, something the two governments consider crucial
in proving that democratic politics offer an alternative to
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Elliott, a political scientist at Queen's University,
said people are overreacting to the arms dispute, especially
because of the deadline set by Blair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a process, not something dictated by deadlines,'' he
said. While Blair has warned that widespread violence could resume,
Elliott believes the major paramilitary groups will take a
wait-and-see attitude if the deadline passes.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon, the moderate nationalist who is second to Trimble
as head of the imperiled assembly, warned that politicians here had
grown complacent in the past year and were looking for others to
resolve their problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary people, more accustomed to their politicians bickering
than forging mutually beneficial compromises, seem worried, but no
more than usual at this perennially volatile time of year, when
tensions between Catholics and Protestants rise dramatically
because of the latter's celebrations of 17th century military
victories over Catholic forces.
</P>
<P>
   Many people seem to think the peace process is stronger than the
will of reluctant politicians. Last year, the standoff in
Portadown, where Protestant marchers have been refused permission
to parade through a Catholic neighborhood, led to major
confrontations, and the horrific firebomb murder of three Catholic
boys by Protestant extremists. A month later, republican dissidents
killed 29 people in Omagh with a car bomb, the greatest loss of
life in any single incident during the Troubles. But those
atrocities strengthened rather than weakened public support for the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Since Omagh, only eight people have been killed, five by
loyalist extremists, three by republicans. Based on the average
rate of killings in the years before the Good Friday agreement,
Hume calculates that about 100 people are alive  &UR; today &LR;  who would
have been killed in the time since the agreement was signed.
</P>
<P>
   In Belfast, where new hotels and restaurants have sprung up in
the last year, many people think it crazy to even consider throwing
the growing normality and prosperity away on so-called points of
principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come so far,'' said Helen Scallon, who works in one of
the new hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Deehan, who heads a recycling company in Londonderry, said
the politicians should be sequestered, as they were last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should put them all in a room and make them stay there
until they come out with an agreement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when an aide to Blair began calling around to the
various parties, saying there would be marathon talks beginning
 &UR; today &LR; , he said, only half-jokingly, ``Bring your sleeping bags.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-COUNSEL-NYT &LR;      06-27 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-COUNSEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FIXING THE INDEPENDENT COUNSEL ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 28:
</P>
<P>
   The Independent Counsel Act will expire on Wednesday, and
unfortunately most members of Congress would just as soon see the
law fade into history. But that response unwisely assumes that
Kenneth Starr's protracted investigation of President Clinton ought
to be the measure by which the law is judged. Without an
independent counsel law, power to investigate the president and
other high officials would revert back to the attorney general, who
cannot credibly oversee inquiries into the highest levels of the
administration of which he or she is a part.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of rejecting the independent counsel mechanism, Congress
should seek to improve it. A strong bipartisan plan crafted by
Sens. Susan Collins and Arlen Specter, both Republicans, and Joseph
Lieberman and Carl Levin, Democrats, would go a long way toward
curing the weaknesses of the act, and prevent future independent
counsels from making the mistakes that marred Starr's work.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, expected to be introduced on Tuesday, would reduce the
number of positions covered by the law from roughly 200 to the
president, the vice president, Cabinet members and the White House
chief of staff. It would prohibit the expansion of an independent
counsel's jurisdiction to matters unrelated to the initial
investigation. This would prevent the kind of accretion of
unrelated allegations that turned Starr into a multipurpose
prosecutor. The bill would also limit investigations to two years,
with one-year extensions for good cause.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require that independent counsels submit budgets
to the General Accounting Office for review to discourage
overspending. It would help prevent bias on the federal three-judge
panel that appoints independent counsels, when the attorney general
makes such a request, by picking panel members by lottery from the
federal appeals courts. There were charges that the panel that
appointed Starr was partisan. The bill would require independent
counsels to work full time, so that they would not continue to
represent paying clients as Starr did. It also eliminates a
provision in the current law that directs the independent counsel
to make judgments about what constitutes impeachable conduct, an
acceptable step toward leaving that judgment to Congress alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, which supported the act in 1994, now
opposes it. Starr testified to Congress this spring that the act
which has empowered him for nearly five years is hopelessly flawed.
Yet it was the combined actions of Clinton and Starr that
undermined public confidence in the independent counsel law. It
would be a disservice to the nation if Congress used their conduct
as an excuse to scrap an important mechanism that can hold top
leaders accountable for wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990627.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
