</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETER SITS, BUT SOJO HOMERS AS YANKS DOWN ORIOLES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Before batting in the ninth inning Sunday, Luis Sojo
turned to teammates on the New York Yankees' bench and predicted he
would hit a home run, which is like Ross Perot guaranteeing he is
going to be elected president or Larry Johnson promising he is
going to utter something noncontroversial. Sojo had not hit a home
run in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   Lo and behold, Sojo whacked Arthur Rhodes' slider into the
left-field stands, ensuring the Yankees' 6-2 victory against
Baltimore _ a fitting end to this road trip for the Yankees, who
won all six games, against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays and the fading
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had been struggling for runs when they left New York
a week ago, and in six games their offense exploded. They batted
.377, scored eight runs per game and bashed 11 home runs, including
two by Bernie Williams Sunday, his 12th and 13th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the slumping Yankees saw their batting averages ascend
with the alacrity of America Online stock. Chuck Knoblauch went
from .249 to .262, Paul O'Neill from .272 to .286, Tino Martinez
from .252 to .276 and Williams from .324 to .341.
</P>
<P>
   Their starting pitching has been terrific, and Mariano Rivera
has succeeded in 20 of his 21 save chances. Derek Jeter sat out
Sunday's game because of a cramp in his hamstring and Sojo, his
replacement, slammed a home run. The Yankees (45-28) are playing
their best baseball of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of streak we look for,'' said Joe Torre, the
manager. ``And hopefully, we'll have more.''
</P>
<P>
   They have beaten Orioles (32-42) 36 of the last 58 games in
Baltimore in the 1990s. But the Yankees' lead Sunday was in
jeopardy into the eighth inning. Orlando Hernandez (9-6) gave up
two runs early, throwing 30 pitches in the third inning. He was
tentative, Torre thought, as if he were pitching ``the seventh game
of the World Series'' _ and at one point, he seemed unsure what to
throw, shaking off catcher Joe Girardi repeatedly. Hernandez
settled to retire 11 straight batters, from the fourth inning
through the seventh, but his pitch count reached 112 after seven
innings, with the Yankees leading, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick, B.J. Surhoff and Albert Belle, Baltimore's Nos. 2,
3 and 4 batters, were due to hit in the eighth, and the left-hander
Mike Stanton warmed up in the Yankees' bullpen. Torre could let
Hernandez pitch to Bordick and then call on Stanton to face the
left-handed-hitting Surhoff, or leave Hernandez in the game to face
the first three hitters and then, if needed, Stanton could pitch to
the Nos. 5 and 6 batters, left-handers Harold Baines and Will
Clark. Torre was well aware, of course, that Baines had bashed
Stanton's fastball for a three-run homer Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Torre determined to keep Hernandez in the game for the three
batters. After going ahead no balls and two strikes on Bordick,
Hernandez walked Bordick, and Surhoff singled. Two on and nobody
out for Belle, Baines and Clark, the lead only one run.
</P>
<P>
   Torre stayed with his plan, Hernandez pitching to Belle; he had
struck out Belle in the first inning. This time, Hernandez
challenged Belle with fastballs and whiffed him on four pitches,
the last a 94-mile-an-hour fastball. Torre went to the mound to
replace Hernandez, who shook his manager's hand and then stopped in
front of the stands to bow slightly and doff his cap.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton warmed up and felt his fastball was subpar, so he went
after Baines with consecutive curveballs. Baines took the first for
a strike, swung at the second and pulled a grounder toward the
first-base hole.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had seen Girardi set his target outside, guessed
Stanton would throw a breaking ball and figured Baines would hit
the ball in his direction. Surhoff, leading off first, waited for
an instant, trying to block Martinez's view, but the first baseman
saw the ball, dived to his right and gloved it. Martinez threw to
second base for a forceout on Surhoff, and Sojo fired to first with
Surhoff bearing down on him.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton was there, the throw arrived _ and Baines was safe.
There were two outs, the potential tying run at third and Baines at
first as the possible lead run. Stanton turned his attention to
Clark, throwing breaking balls again, until the count was 2-2. He
spun a slider, Clark struck out and the Yankees in the dugout began
clapping. A crisis averted. Stanton, Hernandez would say later, was
magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   Sojo was to be the Yankees' third batter in the ninth inning,
and he was taking good-natured grief from Jeter, Jorge Posada and
others for his weak swings. He turned to them and said, ``I'm going
to hit the ball out of here,'' and they laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes struck out the first two batters, throwing his fastball
94 to 95 mph. With a 1-2 count, Rhodes chose to throw a slider _
``He was doing me a favor,'' Sojo said _ and Sojo turned on it,
driving it into the seats, his first home run since July 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sojo kept his smile in check until he crossed home plate, turned
toward the dugout and saw Jeter waiting for him _ and the grin
broke through, the face of the Yankees on this road trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
