<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MORE SETBACKS FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ If it weren't for bad luck perhaps the Anaheim
Angels would have no luck at all. On Sunday the team learned the
bad news about two more players, Tim Belcher and Matt Luke.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials said Sunday that X-rays done on Belcher's right
hand indicate he suffered a fracture in his pinky finger and his
status is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher hurt his hand making a play at first Saturday against
the Oakland A's. He left the game after pitching four innings.
</P>
<P>
   As for Luke, the right fielder had a partial tear of the right
oblique muscle, which is located just below the rib cage. He tore
the muscle Friday against Oakland making a throw from right field
in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Luke is the 13th Angel placed on the DL this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting silly,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said.
``Matt Luke just got into the lineup and boom, like that he's
out.''
</P>
<P>
   In eight games for the Angels in 1999, Luke batted .438 with
three runs scored, two home runs and four RBI. His replacement will
be Mike Holtz, from the Triple-A Edmonton farm team.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, a left-handed pitcher, was 2-1 with one save and a 2.66
ERA in 18 games at Edmonton. Earlier in the season he was with the
Angels and posted a 1-1 record with a 1.42 ERA in 10 games before
he was optioned.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher's injury comes at a time when Collins is struggling to
keep his squad healthy. It could be a tough blow to take in light
of the elbow injury to starter Ken Hill earlier in the week against
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   For now the team is going with a modified four-man rotation.
Chuck Finley (4-7, 4.56 ERA) will get the start today and Omar
Olivares will take the mound Tuesday night against the Texas
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   As for Belcher?
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure he won't pitch for a while,'' Collins said. ``And on
top of that we're going to have to wait on Kenny Hill. Still,
there's a lot of options at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   No place like home: West Covina native Jason Giambi invited his
father John into the A's clubhouse Sunday. He admitted he was glad
to be home, if only for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing here,'' Jason said. ``The family all comes out
and it's fun. It's nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheets gets chance: Andy Sheets got the start for the Angels at
short Sunday against Oakland and pitcher Kenny Rogers. He was there
largely because starter Gary DiSarcina is 3-44 lifetime against
Rogers, which adds up to a batting average of .068.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to give him (the day off),'' Collins said. ``I
compare Rogers to (Gary) Maddux and those type guys. It's not easy
against him. He's the type of hitter who, when he gets ahead of
you, he can expand the strike zone and that's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers ahead: Going into Sunday's game, the Angels were already
assured of winning the series against the A's, and Collins hoped to
do the same against the first-place Texas Rangers in the three-game
series that begins tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I keep saying, we need to win series right now,''
Collins said. ``And after a couple of weeks we can look up at the
standings and see that we're in striking distance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
