<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 06/27/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- June 27, 1999 -- PAPER-WASSERSTEIN-2, 6-27
-- Executives at the offices of The Daily Deal. The Daily Deal
which is set to start a five-day-a-week publication on Sept. 15.,
has some built-in advantages. For one, the newspaper is American
Lawyer Media's 22d publication. There is also little question it
will have deals to cover, at least for now. In 1996, the total
value of domestic mergers and acquisitions was $653 billion; in
1997 it was $970 billion; last year, it jumped to $1.6 trillion.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- June 27, 1999 -- PAPER-WASSERSTEIN-1, 6-27
-- The Daily Deal which is set to start a five-day-a-week
publication on Sept. 15. There is little question it will have
deals to cover, at least for now. In 1996, the total value of
domestic mergers and acquisitions was $653 billion; in 1997 it was
$970 billion; last year, it jumped to $1.6 trillion. (Edward
Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PORTERVILLE, Calif. -- June 27, 1999 -- CALIF-CITRUS-2,
6-27 -- A citrus grove in Porterville is still suffering from the
effects of a winter storm last year, with many oranges lying
ruined, their pulp as dry as straw. Last Christmas a storm
destroyed $700 million worth of crops in the fertile Central Valley
of California, and also left 14,000 to 28,000 people out of work.
With the sunlight pressing on the valley like a hot compress, the
damage from the freeze is getting worse. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PORTERVILLE, Calif. -- June 27, 1999 -- CALIF-CITRUS-1,
6-27 -- Unemployed grove workers line up for boxes of food,
distributed by the National Farmworkers Service Center in
Porterville. Most people in the fertile Central Valley of
California depend on the citrus crop, and as it has failed, the
town has been hit hard. Growers and packing-house owners are up to
their chins in debt; workers are up to their eyes in it. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 27, 1999 -- REMNICK-NEWYORKER-MEDIA,
6-27 -- David Remnick, the editor of The New Yorker magazine and
Pulitzer Prize winning author. The author of four books, including
``Lenin's Tomb,'' which won the 1994 Pulitzer Prize, Remnick favors
longer pieces and has added more local political coverage, more
international political coverage, more criticism, even more words
in general, but little of it has generated the noisy, often
outraged clamor in the news media that many advertisers appreciate.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 27, 1999 -- NY-GAY-PARADE, 6-27 --
People attending the Gay Pride Parade on Sunday celebrate in front
of the Stonewall Inn on Christopher Street, where the parade began
in 1970 as a grassroots commemoration of the 1969 Stonewall Riots.
Millions of members of the gay community turned out to celebrate
their pride in New York on Sunday. The Stonewall Riots began when
patrons of a gay bar in Greenwich Village fought back against a
police raid in 1969. (Billy Smith 2d/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UROSEVIC, Yugoslavia -- June 26, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SERBIA,
6-27 -- Serbs in Urosevic, fearful of reprisals from Kosovo
Albanians, wait outside NATO headquarters for a bus to take them to
Pristina. NATO hopes the arrival of 3,600 Russian peacekeepers will
make Serbs feel safer in Kosovo, but reports of revenge attacks by
ethnic Albanians continue. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) FRIDAY HARBOR, Wash. -- June 27, 1999 -- WHALE-NOISE,
6-27 -- Fred West, director of Seattle's City Cantabile Choir,
plays the flute for Orca whales on the waters of northern Puget
Sound, during a concert at sea for the whales. In the audience,
there was no clapping of hands and no standing ovation, but the
killer whales, also known as orcas, showed up, nearly surrounding
the boat at times, cutting the surface of the water, their
black-and-white coloring spectacularly visible. (Larry Davis/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- June 27, 1999 -- BREAUX-PROFILE, 6-27 --
Sen. John B. Breaux, 55, D-La., says he is pushing forward with his
Medicare proposal in the Senate. Breaux seems an unlikely player in
the Medicare debate, which tends to have its own wonky priesthood
steeped in the arcane liturgy of managed competition. This is,
after all, a man who takes his identity with Louisiana seriously.
He includes favorite recipes on his official Senate Web site and
never misses a Mardi Gras, which he celebrates lavishly both in
Washington and in New Orleans. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- June 27, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP, 6-27
-- A British paratrooper tries to stamp out part of a fire caused
by Molotov cocktails thrown at a Serb owned cafe on Sunday. The
latest weekend of murder, arson and looting in the devastated
southern Serbian province, highlights the vacuum created when Serb
forces withdrew from Kosovo earlier this month, leaving the region
without a civilian force to maintain law and order. (Alan Chin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SLOVINJE, Yugoslavia -- June 27, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VILLAGE-2, 6-27 -- An Albanian man stands in front of a
British base in Slovinje, where a small detachment of British
soldiers have been trying to hold this mixed community together. In
Slovinje, Serbs and Albanians had lived in relative harmony for
decades. But this village was not spared the last three months of
war. The hate and fear that British forces now see and feel here,
they say, resembles what they encountered in Northern Ireland. In
both places, they argue, their presence at least limits the
violence. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SLOVINJE, Yugoslavia -- June 27, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VILLAGE-1, 6-27 -- As many Serb families stream out of
Slovinje, Jasnina Stanisic, 23, at left, gives the Serbian national
salute. Mileva, 48, at right, is her mother and the driver is a
family friend. Jasnina's brother, Zoran, 20, was recently kidnapped
and is still missing. Despite continuous British patrols in
Slovinje, where some of the village's original 40 or so Serb
families remain, Serbs complain that NATO soldiers have not been
protecting them. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MOUNT PASTRIK, Yugoslavia -- June 27, 1999 --
KOSOVO-KLA-FLOATER, 6-27 -- A Kosovo Liberation Army soldier
surrounded by an assortment of ammunition, feeds his dogs in the
mountains of southwestern Kosovo on Sunday. By Monday at midnight
the KLA is to tell NATO how much equipment they have and where it
is located so it can be monitered and inspected throughout Kosovo.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 27, 1999 --
KOSOVO-BOMB-DAMAGE-2, 6-27 -- Hajdar Kameri, an ethnic Albanian,
chops up wood in Djakovica, an area once believed to be a Serb
military base. From blown-out military barracks to exploded fuel
tanks, the devastating results of NATO's bombing are obvious all
across Kosovo. But the damage brought down on the Yugoslav army
itself -- particularly the tanks, armored fighting vehicles and
artillery batteries at its core -- is less clear. (Tyler Hicks/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 27, 1999 --
KOSOVO-BOMB-DAMAGE-1, 6-27 -- Ethnic Albanians walk past a crater
at a junkyard in Djakovica, once believed to be a Serb military
base, which was bombed by NATO. While some vehicles were removed
from Kosovo by Serb forces to break down for spare parts, NATO
officials themselves acknowledge that fewer pieces of military
hardware were destroyed than the alliance had first estimated.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
