<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES' MADDUX IS TOO MUCH FOR METS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His time had passed. So said Greg Maddux's critics
earlier this season. They were obviously wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux pitched the Atlanta Braves to a 1-0 victory over the New
York Mets Sunday afternoon in a 2-hour-6-minute game in which he
displayed all his old trademarks: precision, speed and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old right-hander had also demonstrated to the Mets
that while they might be closer than ever to challenging the Braves
this season, they still have some distance to go after dropping the
weekend series, two games to one.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux (7-5) tossed eight shutout innings of two-hit ball,
outdueling an aching Masato Yoshii (6-6) and sending the Mets to a
series against Florida at Miami four games behind the Braves in the
National League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you listen to our announcers, you'd think he's been
terrible,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said of Maddux, his longtime
ace, whose ERA was an uncharacteristic 4.65 just four starts ago.
``But he's had a bunch of games like today's.''
</P>
<P>
   They have just been fewer than in seasons past. But even though
Maddux lowered his ERA to 3.87, he needed help from the Braves' new
closer, John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Why remove Maddux after just 93 pitches? ``He said, `I'm a
little tired,''' Cox said. ``And when he indicates that, he's
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux departed after striking out pinch-hitter Matt Franco on a
full-count changeup to end the eighth inning with the tying run on
third base. ``I'm just aiming it down the middle and hoping it
doesn't end up there,'' Maddux said. ``I'm serious. A coach told me
that when I was 13 or 14 and it still works. But I was tiring.''
</P>
<P>
   So on came Rocker to pitch the ninth. And again the Mets _ who
had just six runners on base the entire game _ put the tying run in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo rifled a one-out single into center field.
Pinch-runner Melvin Mora took second on John Olerud's grounder as
Atlanta first baseman Brian Hunter slipped while fielding the ball.
And then the Braves intentionally walked Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed-hitting Piazza is batting .377 against
left-handers. Rocker is left-handed. And the left-handed-hitting
Robin Ventura, who was batting .281 against lefties, was due up
next.
</P>
<P>
   Mets manager Bobby Valentine figured the Braves would have
walked Piazza even if the Mets had only had a runner on first. Cox
said he wouldn't have gone that far. ``But the thing that made it
tough was that Ventura hits left-handers so well,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard-throwing Rocker, after getting ahead of Ventura on
the strength of his fastball, fooled him with 1-2 breaking ball.
Ventura swung and missed. and Rocker had picked up his 16th save in
19 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Maddux was asked what impresses him most about
Rocker. ``Changing speeds,'' said Maddux, who might be the best
ever at just that. ``A lot of guys throw hard, but not many know
how to change speeds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's totally wasted,'' Valentine said of
Yoshii's seven-inning, four-hit, one-run effort. ``He can build on
it. Sometimes you just run up against a buzzsaw. Yoshii just made
one more mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, who strained his right quadriceps warming up for the
game, said he was excited about the prospect of facing Maddux, a
four-time Cy Young award winner.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux retired the first 14 Mets he faced, but then Brian McRae
and Roger Cedeno laced consecutive singles in the fourth. Rey
Ordonez grounded out, however, to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yoshii, who had been fitted with a knee brace, did
all he could to keep up the brisk pace. But with Eddie Perez on
second and two out in the third, Ozzie Guillen lunged at a 2-2
forkball at his feet. It was not in the dirt, as Valentine had
wanted it. ``But when he hit it, I thought it was going to be a
routine fly ball to center,'' Yoshii said through his interpreter.
Instead, it was a run-scoring double that found the gap in
right-center. And Maddux made the run stand up.
</P>
<P>
   Before the series even began, Cox had criticized the schedule
makers for making the Braves and Mets wait until late June to face
each other. The Mets now must feel the same. Because while it might
have taken the heretofore struggling Tom Glavine and Maddux a
couple of months to adjust to the new strike zone, they both shut
the Mets down this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And so, what did the teams learn about each other that they
didn't know before? Nothing yet, said Cox. ``I don't know,''
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Others said they learned more.
</P>
<P>
   `That the Braves are still a very good team,'' Mets general
manager Steve Phillips said. ``And so are we.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae put it another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a better team than we were last year,'' he said. ``But
they're not as bad as people want to make them out to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-27-99 2246EDT &QL; 
