<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIDE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-27 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIDE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AGAINST THE TIDE': BEACH HOUSE UP, BEACH HOUSE DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By ANN FINKBEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My night-school geology professor explained how the wired-rock
walls and straightened banks of nearby Stony Run just let the
stream run faster so that downstream, erosion gets worse. And true,
right where the wired-rock walls stop, next to a monumentally
graceless apartment house, Stony Run's banks are gouged out and
raw.
</P>
<P>
   I have a dream. No one is going to notice those banks cutting
back, deeper with each storm, until they fatally undermine the
apartment house and it crumbles into Stony Run. The point here is,
water always wins.
</P>
<P>
   The point is the same for American beaches. Humans are drawn to
beaches: Our ancestors hauled themselves out of the ocean, crawled
up on the sand and, eventually, built beach houses. Even the Bible
says this was not smart: a foolish man ``built his house upon the
sand: and the rain descended, the floods came, and the winds blew
and beat upon that house; and it fell: and great was the fall of
it'' (Matthew 7:26-27).
</P>
<P>
   Cornelia Dean, science editor for The New York Times, writes in
``Against the Tide: The Battle for America's Beaches'' about the
reasons those houses fall, the measures taken to prevent their
falling again, the failure of those measures, and solutions for the
whole soggy mess. Ms. Dean begins with the deadly 1900 Galveston
hurricane. On Sept. 8, the local newspaper had a news item on a
storm moving across the Gulf of Mexico. On Sept. 9, the same paper
consisted of a single page bearing two columns of names that began,
``Following is a list of dead as accurately as News men have been
able to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Galveston is on a beach _ actually a barrier island, a narrow
strip of sand built and maintained by the ocean _ and the hurricane
simply swamped it; more than 6,000 people died. Afterward,
Galveston built a seawall against the ocean three miles long, later
expanded to six. The wall has held off not only subsequent
hurricanes but also the sand with which the ocean once replenished
the beaches. So Galveston now markets itself not for its absent
beaches but for its famous hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   This state of affairs repeats itself on nearly all American
beaches. Mountains, meadows and apartment buildings are washed away
and eventually ground into sand. Some of the sand is dumped into
sandbars offshore, some ends up on beaches. Storm waves carry sand
from the beaches back to the sandbars and quiet waves bring it
again to the beaches, so the beaches narrow and widen, erode and
return. They are not so much beaches as cycles.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and '80s nearly half of all construction in America
was on or near the coastline. To protect our houses, roads and
T-shirt shops, we've armored our beaches with seawalls,
breakwaters, jetties, groins and bulkheads. The armor, in place
after place _ Long Island, Hilton Head, Palm Beach, Santa Monica _
interferes with the cycle of sand and waves, and generally wipes
out the beaches. We truck in another beach from elsewhere;
sometimes we just do without the beach. Most eastern and southern
beaches are narrow barrier islands through which storms routinely
cut new inlets. Boats from the inland side have a nice new route to
the ocean, so bridges, roads and marinas get built.
</P>
<P>
   But the sand keeps flowing, carried not only by waves but also
by a longshore current of sorts called a littoral drift. To keep
sand from closing the inlets, people build groins jutting out into
the ocean, on the up-current side of the littoral drift. And sure
enough, the inlet stays open because sand piles up on the
up-current side of the groin.
</P>
<P>
   But now the down-current side doesn't get its usual sand flow,
and each storm erodes more beach. So the down-current people
complain, and the up-current people build big blowers and blow
their excess sand over the inlet to the down-current beaches, from
which _ to everyone's surprise _ it again erodes. If someone's
watching from Mars, we must look like nitwits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three approaches to coastal erosion,'' Ms. Dean
writes. ``Armor, beach nourishment and retreat.'' By the time she
finishes, the reader has no doubt which she supports. The first two
approaches are short-term and high-maintenance, and people who use
them _ those who make up what she calls ``a constituency of
ignorance'' _ would rather ignore the water-wins rule than lose
their investments. Ms. Dean advocates the third approach, retreat.
The solution she likes best is when the National Park Service or
the Nature Conservancy or a private billionaire buys the beaches
and lays down the law: Enjoy the beach, just don't build on it.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the usual environmental book, a genre whose
reduction of nature's complexity to a simple-minded battle between
nobility and greed easily arouses the curmudgeon. If it's good
enough for dinosaurs, the reader snarls, it's good enough for
spotted owls. The snarl _ my snarl, anyway _ is mostly suspicion
that such advocacy skews the story. But Ms. Dean is smarter than
that; she knows that the best advocacy is to lay out the whole
story, all sides, fairly and neutrally, and bet that readers will
see what she sees.
</P>
<P>
   She also doesn't pretend the problem is simple. Coastal
geologists understand any given beach, but each beach is different.
Armor won't necessarily destroy a beach or destroy it wholly.
Decisions about the beaches are made by so many people _ federal
agencies, state governments, developers, the Corps of Engineers,
lawyers, insurance companies, property owners, environmentalists,
coastal geologists _ they have trouble agreeing on the problem let
alone on the solution. The constituency of ignorance might be
geologically short-sighted, understandably influenced by politics
and finances and not terrifically bright, but it is mostly composed
of people who love their beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dean has made her case so clearly and cleanly, with such
persuasive examples, and so much credit where it is due, that I'm
convinced. Let the Stony Run apartment house fall, I cry. Save the
spotted owl.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AGAINST THE TIDE'
</P>
<P>
   The Battle for America's Beaches
</P>
<P>
   By Cornelia Dean
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 279 pages. Columbia University Press. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
