<SLUG> BC-MINN-LIBEL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV STATION'S LIBEL TRIAL REVISITS OLD MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ When Dennis Stokes, a Minnesota Mining and
Manufacturing executive, was shot to death in 1993 in a nearby
suburb, Forest Lake, an Anoka County detective gave his theory of
the murder to a local television station: It appeared Stokes'
widow, Terri, killed her husband with a shotgun blast while he
slept in their bed.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Ms. Stokes has not been charged with the crime
and says she has spent the better part of six years fending off
media and police inquiries into what, if any, role she played in
the murder. Hoping to escape the spotlight, she says, she moved to
Idaho; but now she is back in it, trying to erase what she contends
were false accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The murder is now being relived in a Minneapolis courtroom where
Ms. Stokes has sued the detective, the county and WCCO-TV, a
station owned by CBS, for libel. The trial is being closely watched
by the news media and the legal profession.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers around an interview shown in an April 1994
news broadcast in which the detective, Tom Johnson, said Ms. Stokes
was the only suspect and described the evidence that pointed to
her.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Stokes was not arrested and no one was ever charged with
the crime. In her suit, Ms. Stokes contends that Johnson had become
obsessed with his suspicions of her and that he failed to
acknowledge exculpatory evidence. As a result, she argues, the
detective focused his investigation too narrowly on her.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the liability of Johnson and the county, media law
experts say that holding a news organization liable for the words
of a public official speaking on the record could pose an
unsettling precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major issue for those of us in the media who on a
regular basis rely on public sources to talk about issues on the
record,'' said Bill Babcock, director of the Silha Center for the
Study of Media Ethics and Law at the University of Minnesota. ``If
the media can be held liable for reporting what a public official
has said on the record, to say it would have a chilling effect on
the media would be too mild. It would be devastating. If we can't
report on what is the public record and what is being said by
public officials, what can we report on?''
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances have also turned this civil defamation suit into
more of a murder trial. To make their case, defense lawyers are
trying to show that Johnson's statements were true. They will
review Ms. Stokes' extramarital affairs and argue that she stood to
gain financially by her husband's death.
</P>
<P>
   Media experts have pointed to a series of cases in Minnesota and
nationwide that have gone against news organizations and say
another could be detrimental.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important case for news organizations and
particularly television stations,'' Lucy Dalglish, a media lawyer
in Minneapolis and former reporter, said. ``Plaintiffs are now
saying, `I don't care if it's an official source. I don't care
where your information came from _ if it's false, you're not going
to be able to stand behind it anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has already lost several key battles, most notably a
ruling last fall denying a defense motion to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Federal District Judge David Doty rejected the defense's
contention that repeating statements in the public record or made
by government officials is protected speech. The judge called the
broadcast ``highly slanted'' and said the reporter failed to
adequately question the detective's exaggerated statements.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the trial began, Ms. Stokes settled with another
defendant, King World Productions, which included an interview with
Johnson on its ``American Journal'' program in December 1994.
Several other defendants were also dropped from the case before the
trial, which began last week and is expected to last a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
