<HEADER>
A1357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEILL-CENTENNIAL-2TAK     06-27 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEILL-CENTENNIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURT WEILL'S HERITAGE: HONOR REPLACES SCORN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEMNITZ, Germany _ For lovers of great melodies, Kurt Weill is
the composer of ``Mack the Knife'' and ``September Song.'' For fans
of 1940s musical comedies, he wrote the scores of ``Street Scene''
and ``One Touch of Venus.'' For opera goers, he bequeathed at least
two classics to the modern repertory with ``The Threepenny Opera''
and ``The Rise and Fall of the City of Mahagonny.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in this eastern German industrial city, where celebrations
of next year's 100th anniversary of Weill's birth began with a
flourish this month, the multitalented German-born composer is
being remembered above all as a Jew, a seemingly peculiar reminder
that it was Weill's very Jewish identity that forced him to flee
Germany in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The two-season centennial was nonetheless inaugurated with the
Old Testament pageant opera ``The Eternal Road,'' Weill's only work
written from a strictly Jewish point of view. The production, the
opera's first since 1937, will return to Chemnitz in November and
then go in early 2000 to the Brooklyn Academy of Music in New York,
the New Israeli Opera in Tel Aviv and the Opera Krakow in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   How ``The Eternal Road'' became a highlight of the ``Kurt Weill
2000'' program reveals more about Chemnitz today than about Weill
in his lifetime. Weill himself, who died in 1950, probably never
set foot here. And after he fled Germany in 1933, he made a point
of never returning. Yet with this production, Chemnitz has turned
him into a powerful symbol of its campaign to make amends for past
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nazis took power in January 1933, the city's 350,000
inhabitants included a thriving community of some 3,500 Jews. By
the time the city's synagogue was burned down on Kristallnacht,
Nov. 9, 1938, most Jews had fled and some had been arrested. In
1945, when Chemnitz became part of East Germany, there were 59
Jewish survivors living here. And when Germany was reunited in
1990, the Jewish community was down to just 17 people.
</P>
<P>
   For Chemnitz, renamed Karl-Marx-Stadt by the Communists, the
past had become a void because, while West Germany showed penitence
for the Holocaust, East Germany denied all responsibility for the
Nazis' barbarities. It was only when Chemnitz began to reflect on
life before 1933 that it recognized an outstanding debt to Jews and
understood what was lost with the destruction of its Jewish
community. Courageously, the city decided to act.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, the municipal council instituted annual Days of
Jewish Culture, with concerts, plays and lectures, to which it
began inviting Jews who fled Chemnitz in the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   The city informed the German government that it would welcome
Jewish migrants from the East, notably Russia (it now has some 300
Jewish residents). And, instigated by the Social Democratic mayor,
Peter Seifert, the city decided to build a $6 million synagogue.
And it was this project that led to ``The Eternal Road.''
</P>
<P>
   The opera _ it is also often described as a Jewish oratorio _
takes place in a synagogue where a Jewish community is seeking
refuge from a pogrom. To give heart to the Jews, the rabbi begins
reading from the Torah. He conjures images from the Old Testament,
including familiar stories of Abraham, Moses, David, Solomon and
the Prophets, which are then enacted onstage. Finally, soldiers
drive the Jews from the synagogue, but they are consoled by the
promised coming of the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   The opera was born of a suggestion by the American producer
Meyer Weisgal that the renowned German director Max Reinhardt put
together a musical drama based on the Old Testament. Reinhardt
turned to Weill for the score and Franz Werfel for the
German-language libretto. The three, all Jews already in exile,
worked on the project from 1934 to 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Der Weg der Verheissung,'' or ``The Road of Promise,''
the opera was renamed ``The Eternal Road'' in its English
translation. And eventually, after immense difficulties, it had its
premiere at the Manhattan Opera House in New York on Jan. 7, 1937
(with Weill's wife, Lotte Lenya, in the cast). It was a critical
success but a commercial flop, and it closed after 153
performances.
</P>
<P>
   For Weill it was a transitional work between his German life and
his American life, between what have become known as the ``Two
Weills.'' In Germany he was known as an avant-garde composer whose
main theater works _ ``The Threepenny Opera,'' ``Mahagonny'' and
``Seven Deadly Sins'' _ were written to librettos by Bertolt
Brecht.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, where Weill settled in 1935, he adjusted
quickly and successfully to the demands of Broadway musicals, with
Ira Gershwin, Langston Hughes and Alan Jay Lerner among his
librettists. ``The Eternal Road,'' meanwhile, literally
disappeared, its orchestral score long believed lost.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, when Rolf Stiska was assistant director of the
Berliner Ensemble, the theater company founded by Brecht, his
research into the Weill-Brecht partnership led him to the opera.
Subsequently, as assistant director of the Berlin Staatsoper, he
suggested presenting it. And when he was appointed director of the
Theater Chemnitz in 1992, he brought the idea with him. But it was
Chemnitz's new interest in its Jewish past, along with talk of a
new synagogue, that suddenly made a production of ``The Eternal
Road'' seem viable.
</P>
<P>
   It would not prove simple. Weill's musical legacy is effectively
controlled by the New York-based Kurt Weill Foundation, which was
not immediately persuaded that an opera house in a little-known
German city was the right place for a revival of ``The Eternal
Road.'' Long negotiations followed, with the foundation insisting
on the right to approve the production's conductor, director,
designer and principal soloists as well as any changes in the
libretto.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all very complicated,'' recalled Karl-Hans Moeller, the
theater's chief dramaturge and Chemnitz's chief negotiator. ``The
foundation also wanted Israel and the Brooklyn Academy of Music
involved. It said it wanted an experienced conductor and mentioned
John Mauceri, who had done a lot of Weill before. I had never heard
of Mauceri and he had never heard of Chemnitz, but it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauceri, principal conductor of the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra,
was delighted. ``It was Chemnitz that made it happen after I had
spent 15 years trying to get others to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting production team is appropriately international:
Mauceri is American; the director, Michael Heinicke, is German; the
set and costume designer, David Shahir, is Israeli; and, bolstering
Oper Chemnitz's 56-member chorus, the 140-strong chorus includes
singers from the Opera Krakow and the Leipzig Synagogue Choir
(formed mainly by non-Jews interested in Jewish religious music).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With its huge cast, frequent costume changes and complex
re-enactments of Biblical scenes _ from worship of the golden calf
to Moses and the burning bush _ ``The Eternal Road'' comes across
as a powerful visual spectacle. Where this production differs from
the 1937 version and Werfel's text, though, is that when the
uniformed men invade the synagogue, they now shoot a character
called the Adversary, who sacrifices his life to save the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to change the end because we couldn't pretend that
Auschwitz did not happen,'' Moeller explained. ``When the opera was
written in the mid-1930s, even though things were bad for Jews, no
one had yet imagined the Holocaust. But we now know that the Jews
weren't just allowed to leave to continue their wandering. We
didn't want to show the camps, so we added the shot and the
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the story builds to an emotional climax, so does Weill's
score grow in strength as the drama unfolds. At times, the music is
rich in references _ to ``Don Giovanni,'' to ``Nabucco,'' to Wagner
and Mahler, even to Weill's own rendering of American jazz _ but it
also takes on a grandeur of its own. Comparing it with an earlier
work, Weill himself described it as ``much stronger, richer, more
varied _ more Mozartean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Weill is telling an eternal Jewish story, but he is also
saying goodbye to Germany by placing it within the tradition of
great German ecclesiastical music,'' Mauceri said. ``I believe the
echoes of Bach, Handel, Mozart, Wagner are all intentional. The
wonderful thing about Weill is that he was not afraid of being
popular. I think he disappointed the critics because his music did
not get progressively more complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, before and after the 100th anniversary of Weill's birth
on March 2, 2000, and the 50th anniversary of his death on April 3
next year, there will be ample opportunity to judge both his
symphonic and his theatrical music.
</P>
<P>
   Already last month, Weill's 1931 opera, ``Die Buergschaft,'' had
its U.S. premiere at the Spoleto Festival in Charleston, S.C. In
New York next year, along with the six performances of ``The
Eternal Road'' at the Brooklyn Academy in late February and early
March, the New York Philharmonic will play a concert sequence from
``Street Scenes'' on March 9, while a 12-hour free music marathon,
``Wall-to-Wall Weill,'' will be presented at Symphony Space on
March 25.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the scores of performances of Weill's music planned
for Europe and the United States in the coming months, there may be
few more poignant moments than seeing middle-class German audiences
giving ``The Eternal Road'' standing ovations at successive full
houses here this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember that East Germany was an atheist state,''
Moeller said, ``so many people don't know even the most familiar
Old Testament stories. `The Eternal Road' is a wonderful chance for
people in Chemnitz to learn the reality of a religion and its
roots. It has also made people sensitive to the need to build a new
synagogue, which after all means spending a lot of money on a very
small Jewish community. But I'm sure it will happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
