<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET WINS HOLLYWOOD GOLD CUP WITH A LATE MOVE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Real Quiet, last year's 3-year-old champion and
winner of the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness, sneaked through on
the rail in the final 150 yards Sunday to snatch the $1 million
Hollywood Gold Cup by half a length over Budroyale.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey, riding the winner of the Gold Cup for the fourth
time, nudged Real Quiet past Budroyale and Malek just before they
crossed the finish line in a tight race contested by only four
horses. It was only the second time in six races that Real Quiet
had won since last year's Preakness, but it was the 17th time in 20
races that he ran in the money, sending his career earnings past
$3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little hairy for a while,'' Bailey said by telephone
from Hollywood Park in Los Angeles. ``I wasn't sure a spot would
open for me. I had the feeling that Kent Desormeaux on Puerto
Madero was trying to bottle me up the whole race. But patience paid
off. I had a lot of horse left and, when a hole did open, we shot
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey flew to California overnight after watching in the
Belmont Park paddock Saturday while his mount, Three Ring, reared
and fell in a fatal accident before the Mother Goose Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, who trains Real Quiet, praised Bailey for his
calmness under pressure, and said: ``He rides as though he's got
ice water in his veins. He waited, and a hole opened for him on the
rail in the final yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet, third behind Behrens in the Massachusetts Handicap
one month ago, ran the 1 1/4 miles in a fast 1:59 3/5 as the 4-5
favorite in the small field. The race turned out to be a downer for
Richard Mandella, the trainer of Malek and Puerto Madero, who
finished third and fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat and humidity hanging over Belmont Park Sunday, the
sadness seemed even heavier in the barn area. But no information
was offered on the grim fate that struck down the star filly Three
Ring while she was being saddled for the Mother Goose Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not supposed to happen,'' said Eddie Plesa Jr., who
trained Three Ring for Barry Schwartz, chief executive officer for
Calvin Klein Industries and a trustee of the New York Racing
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Three Ring was being fitted for blinkers in her stall in the
outdoor paddock when she suddenly reared, fell and fractured her
skull against the post separating her from the filly in the next
stall. Dr. Anthony Verderosa reported that ``it was not something
that she could survive,'' and he administered an injection that
ended the life of the 3-year-old filly.
</P>
<P>
   Three Ring, who ran 19th and last in the Kentucky Derby last
month after her saddle slipped during a rough ride, won six races
in 10 starts and finished in the money nine times with earnings of
$773,440. She won the Acorn Stakes three weeks ago, and was aiming
for the Mother Goose, the middle race for fillies in the Triple
Tiara series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she gets hurt in a race, that's what she's here for,''
Plesa said. ``But this is tough. It's like one of your loved ones
is crossing the street in front of you and gets hit by a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreams Gallore, who ran second to the leading filly
Silverbulletday in her last two races, won the Mother Goose by 7{
lengths. Her trainer, Steve Asmussen, said her next appearance
would be in the Coaching Club American Oaks on July 24, a $350,000
stake at 1 1/2 miles and the climactic race in the Triple Crown
series. The Oaks will also be the goal for Oh What a Windfall, who
finished second, but not for Better Than Honour, who ran third
after finishing second to Three Ring in the Acorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's run two hard races in a row, and maybe they took
something out of her,'' said John Kimmel, who trains Better Than
Honour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
