<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT DECISION LEAVES MANY INNOVATORS OUTRAGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Fla.)  (mk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's Supreme Court decision granting states immunity from
patent infringement cast a pall over what might be called the
innovation community, summed up in the melancholy grumblings of a
Chicago patent lawyer, Peter Tryzna, who declared that Wednesday
was ``not a good day for innovators in America, but it's a great
day for thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the decision, he had talked to clients and
colleagues, and like many other intellectual property lawyers and
analysts, inventors and academicians across the country, he was
alternately disgusted, angry and outraged.
</P>
<P>
   At the American Intellectual Property Law Association, Joseph
Re, the chairman of the association's Amicus Committee, said his
organization was ``extremely disappointed.'' The association had
filed a friend-of-the-court brief asking that the Supreme Court
consider patents as property protected by the 14th Amendment and
that states be required to waive their immunity if they are holders
of patents, trademarks or copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``States can participate in the intellectual property system,
make lots of money and royalties, file their own patents, license
their own patents, but they don't have to be accountable in
reverse,'' Re said. ``It's a shame that states can now freely
infringe without incurring any monetary liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's ruling was one of three landmark decisions that
curbed Congress' ability to impose federal law on states, including
the statutes that grant exclusivity to holders of patents,
trademarks and copyrights. That gave the states, their universities
and agencies immunity to infringement suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means states can freely rip off citizens' patent,
trademark and copyright rights,'' Tryzna said. ``It will take a
constitutional amendment to fix this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But before that happens _ if it ever does _ inventors and their
lawyers are already talking about alternatives to suing states that
they contend infringe, including taking legal action against
private companies that do business with those states.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they are speculating as to how far states and
their agencies might go to appropriate the writing, research or
properties of others. Musing over a worst-case scenario, Peter
Roberts, who owns the patent that was at the center of the Supreme
Court ruling, said: ``Imagine a corporation wants to do research.
That corporation could go to a state university, because the
university can pilfer someone else's intellectual property with
impunity, and the corporation could hide behind the university's
shield.''
</P>
<P>
   The court declared last week that states are immune from
lawsuits over a variety of violations of federal law, and its
decisions represented a dramatic realignment of authority between
states and the federal government. Explaining the 5-4 ruling
against making federal laws like patent statutes binding on states,
Justice Anthony Kennedy wrote: ``Congress has vast power but not
all power. Although the Constitution grants broad power to
Congress, our federalism requires that Congress treat the states in
a manner consistent with their status as residuary sovereigns and
joint participants of the governance of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the three cases originated with a 1994 lawsuit brought by
the College Savings Bank of Princeton, N.J., against the state of
Florida. Roberts is the bank's chairman. In 1988, Roberts won
patent No. 4,722,055 for a computerized prepaid college tuition
plan. His patented method involves selling certificates of deposit
to parents who want to save for their children's education. In the
last decade, an increasing number of financial instruments have
been patented, a practice that was upheld in July 1998 by the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in Washington, despite
criticism by some.
</P>
<P>
   Florida created the Florida Prepaid Postsecondary Education
Expense Board and began offering a college savings plan of its own.
Roberts sued the state in 1994, contending the Florida plan
infringed on his patented method. In the intervening years, as the
case wound its way through the judicial system to the Supreme
Court, 16 more states adopted college savings plans that Roberts
contends infringe his patent. But as of last week, there seems
little left that he can do about it. When asked how he felt about
the Supreme Court ruling, Roberts was silent a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said finally, and then paused again. ``I think the
Supreme Court gave license to states to lower the Stars and Stripes
and raise the Jolly Roger. State piracy is going to spread like
wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just believe the Supreme Court has elevated political rights
over personal rights such as property rights, and that stands the
Constitution on its head,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said he thought any effort to craft a constitutional
amendment to allow patent infringement lawsuits against states was
``a pretty tall order.'' But there could be alternatives, he said.
A patent holder who feels he has been infringed might sue a state
under laws that govern the seizure of property, or via statutes
that allow one state to sue another, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a state sues another state, it goes into federal court and
immediately to the Supreme Court,'' Roberts said. ``If a patent
holder whose rights are violated can go and try to assign part of
the patent to some small state agency in another state, and then
sue the first state, the Supreme Court would have to act as a trial
court.''
</P>
<P>
   He also theorized that he could sue individual state officials,
and eventually ``enjoin them to stop them, but not recover any
money damages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
