<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-INTERNET-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIANS TAKE TO THE WEB WITH UNCOMMON SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Pierre Schuermann, one of Brazil's Internet
barons, did not know things would develop so fast.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Schuermann, 30, founded Zeek, a popular search
engine. Earlier this year, he sold Zeek to Star Media Network, a
company that was formed to seek out Internet opportunities in Latin
America, and became director of new business development in Brazil.
Then Star Media went public with a stock offering on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed of it all is amazing,'' Schuermann said in an
interview. ``I'm not sure when the 18-hour days are going to let
up.''
</P>
<P>
   They will probably continue for some time because Star Media is
facing competition from companies including Yahoo Inc., Microsoft,
America Online, Psinet and Telefonica SA _ that are jumping into
Brazil's portal war.
</P>
<P>
   The growing competition in Brazil among portals, the Web pages
people often use for information and links to other sites, may be a
preview of how large Internet companies will spread in other parts
of the non-English-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perhaps the most competitive portal market in the
world at this time,'' said Osvaldo Barbosa de Oliveira, the head of
Microsoft's online operations in Brazil. Oliveira cited the entry
this year of the three largest portals, America Online, Yahoo and
Microsoft, plus competition from companies that provide
local-language content.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, companies like Telefonica of Spain are entering the
battle, as well as the Globo organization, Brazil's largest media
group.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's MSN was the first large foreign portal to establish
operations in Brazil, reaching deals with 19 Brazilian content
providers. Yahoo quickly followed with its own Portuguese-language
portal, opening an office in Sao Paulo this month, while America
Online, whose partner in Latin America is the Cisneros Group of
Venezuela, is expected to start operations this week.
</P>
<P>
   Making Brazil a priority is easy to understand. With a single
currency, set of borders and regulatory framework for nearly 165
million people, this country is an easier target for expansion than
the many Spanish-speaking countries stretching from Mexico to
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is another animal altogether because you get a huge
market with a common culture in one swoop,'' said Laura d'Oliveira,
the president of Sky3 in Hollywood, Fla., which specializes in
making corporate Web sites more profitable through online marketing
in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people using the Internet in Brazil grew 130
percent last year, making it Latin America's most wired nation,
accounting for half of the region's 6 million people on the Web,
according to International Data Corp. And despite a weak economy,
industry experts expect the number of Internet users in Brazil to
grow 60 percent to 100 percent over the next three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those users pay rates for Internet access that are comparable to
those in the United States. The top two providers charge about $20
and $12 a month, respectively, for unlimited access. Others charge
a fee for a certain amount of time and then more for each extra
hour. For instance, IBM Brazil charges $23 a month for 30 hours of
access and $1.50 for each additional hour.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the growth in Internet use has taken place through the
efforts and innovation of local companies like Universo Online,
Brazil's largest service provider and portal, with 400,000
subscribers. Universo Online, which is owned by two large media
concerns, Grupo Folha and Grupo Abril, is known for imaginative
strategies like using live online ads to sell cars two years ago,
when such practices were rare anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Although Caio Tulio Costa, the managing director of Universo
Online, declined to comment on speculation that the company had
been in takeover talks with a large portal company starting
operations in Brazil, he acknowledged that Universo Online was
close to selling a 10 percent stake to a new partner. And the
company has begun its own buying spree, with the purchase last week
of Miner Technology, a company in central Brazil that creates Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   While newcomers learn to compete with entrenched locals, the
portal war is taking place amid two bigger transformations. The
first is the invigoration of Brazil's telecommunications system, a
change that occurred after the nation's telephone monopoly was
privatized and opened to competition in 1998. That has increased
telephone and Internet access nationwide, something that is
expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The second is the consolidation among Internet service
providers, or ISPs, a trend underlined by the recent purchase of
two leading providers by Psinet of Herndon, Va., catapulting Psinet
into the ranks of the country's five largest service providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By acquiring ISPs in Brazil, we're tapping into a market for
e-commerce that should grow by 75 to 100 percent over the next
couple of years,'' said Philippe Kuperman, head of Psinet's Latin
American activities. Though companies like Yahoo are largely in
search of advertising revenue, Psinet hopes to make money by
providing specific services to the corporate market.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar yet wider-reaching transaction, Telefonica bought a
controlling stake last week in Nutec, Brazil's second-largest
service provider and portal. Telefonica, already the biggest
telephone company in Brazil after gobbling up many parts of the
former state monopoly, bought Nutec to pursue its goal of being the
largest portal in the Portuguese- and Spanish-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
   Local news organizations speculated that Telefonica paid $500
million for Nutec, although people close to the transaction said
its value was considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is quite sure when, or how, the dust will settle as the
competition among portals gears up and Internet use continues to
climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S. it's hard to find a friend who's not on the
Internet, while in Brazil I know many people who aren't
connected,'' said Gabriel Bitran, a Brazilian who is deputy dean at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Sloan School of
Management and an expert on electronic commerce. ``I don't think
poverty should be that much of an obstacle as the price of PCs
falls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
