<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH HOPES FOR AN OLD BOOK IN A NEW COVER  
 MTV NETWORKS, STAYING FOREVER YOUNG  
 REPORT ON TELEVISION, REBUTTAL ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the shelf life for most new books only months, can a
publisher correct a marketing mistake three years after publication
by reissuing a book with a new cover, a new title and an angle
linking it to a best seller?
</P>
<P>
   Walker &AMP; Co. is gambling that the technique will work for a book
it first published in 1996. The author, a professor named Morrie
Schwartz who died of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, known as Lou
Gehrig's disease, four months before publication, shared his
thoughts about dying and living. Walker's publisher, George Gibson,
marketed them under the title ``Letting Go'' as a death and
grieving book. It sold 6,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to last week's hard-cover best-seller list. There,
with almost 1.9 million copies in print, is ``Tuesdays with
Morrie,'' published by Doubleday in 1997. Its author, Mitch Albom,
reminisces about learning life lessons from a dying professor:
Morrie Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   In April, with the permission of Dell, Doubleday's sister
company in the publishing empire of Bertelsmann AG, which did a
modest paperback reprint of ``Letting Go,'' Walker reissued the
hard cover as ``Morrie: In His Own Words.'' There are now 30,000
copies in print.
</P>
<P>
   Although publishers often jump on best-selling bandwagons, the
ploy adopted by Walker is rare. Mitchell Kaplan, owner of Books &AMP;
Books in Miami Beach and Coral Gables, Fla., cautions that it would
be taken seriously only ``if we personally trust the publisher and
what he or she does.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Morrow, co-owner of Northshire Bookstore in Manchester
Center, Vt., has not seen sales spike. But a spokeswoman for the
Borders chain said its buyer liked the new cover, made an
aggressive purchase on the book and is pleased with sales.
</P>
<P>
   _ GAYLE FELDMAN
</P>
<P>
   MTV Networks, Staying Forever Young
</P>
<P>
   Why are young people, heavy users of new media, watching more
television, one of the bastions of old media, as they surely are
these days on channels like MTV and Nickelodeon?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting more value into our brands,'' said Tom Freston,
the chairman of MTV Networks, which controls those two channels and
two others, VH-1 and TV Land. All four had ratings increases in the
second quarter of this year, most of all MTV itself, which jumped
36 percent from the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers were even stronger for young viewers, MTV's natural
constituency. One measure of the channel's potency with this group:
Its MTV Movie Awards special on June 10 reached more viewers
between the ages of 12 and 24 than NBC, ABC and Fox combined that
night.
</P>
<P>
   The value that younger viewers seem to like is coming in new
programs like ``Total Request Live,'' a daily music show that is
regularly setting ratings records, and ``The Tom Green Show,'' an
offbeat comedy show whose host has so quickly become a figure in
the youth culture that he is already pitching to the newest Pepsi
generation in a series of quirky Pepsi-Cola commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also coming in old shows like ``The Real World,'' the
series about real people trying to live together. Its season
premiere last week drew its highest rating ever _ and among viewers
between 12 and 34, it was the third-most-watched show on any
channel that night.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the event shows. When the Movie Awards show had
its highest rating ever, it continued a pattern for MTV Networks.
The ``Divas Live'' event for VH-1 hit its best rating ever this
year, as did the ``Kids Choice Awards'' on Nickelodeon. That
success contrasts with the ratings for the Oscars (down), Emmys
(down) and Grammys (down).
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reaching more people than ever,'' Freston said. ``Even
though we're competing with this horde of new cable channels as
well as the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is not complicated. ``We're just spending more
money on marketing and programming,'' Freston said. That money is
increasingly available with advertisers eager to reach teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is staying relevant and current,'' Freston said,
which is not especially easy to do when your channels are older
than most of your viewers. ``Really it's about staying cool,''
Freston said.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Report on Television, Rebuttal on the Web
</P>
<P>
   The concept of letters to the editor has new meaning on the
Internet, where e-mail reactions can fly back and forth almost
instantly. Now CBS News has added another twist, posting a lengthy
list of objections from the subject of one of its investigative
reports on cbsnews.com, the news division's World Wide Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The aggrieved party, Charter Behavioral Health Systems, the
United States' largest chain of psychiatric hospitals, was the
subject of a ``60 Minutes II'' special report, by Ed Bradley, on
abuses of children in some of the hospitals. The report ran on
April 21 and was repeated on June 16, with CBS reporting that
Charter had closed the North Carolina hospital that was prominently
featured.
</P>
<P>
   But Charter, saying the report had several unfair or inaccurate
elements, sent CBS a videotaped statement from its chief medical
officer, Dr. Gary Henschen, and a lengthy document detailing those
elements and asking CBS to correct its statements on the air.
Instead, CBS News posted Charter's lengthy complaint on its Web
site, adding its own rebuttals to each Charter point
(www.cbs.com/flat/story161689.html).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very comprehensive response to their objections,'' said
David Gelber, the producer of the investigative report on Charter.
``We didn't feel any of their objections were valid. If we felt we
had made a mistake, we would have addressed it in the broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karen Jenkins, a spokeswoman for Charter, said the Web site
had not displayed all the documentation Charter had sent to CBS,
and she noted that the Web posting would not reach the great
majority of people who saw the broadcast on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it allows the public to see there are two sides to
the story,'' she said. ``But we were disappointed that our response
did not get on as part of the broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   In closing the June 16 program, Bradley told viewers about the
Charter response and described how to find the CBS News Web site
where they could read the accusations and rebuttals ``exactly as
they appear in our correspondence with Charter.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for abcnews.com and msnbc.com said neither of those
sites had been used for such exhaustive complaint and rebuttal. But
they said that they did get plenty of e-mail and that journalists
responded to most of it _ making letters to the editor interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Brown, editor in chief of msnbc.com, said most
reporters' bylines were ``hot,'' meaning a reader can click on a
byline and send an e-mail message to that reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response rate, especially of aggrieved parties, is
incredibly fast,'' Brown said. ``We've had cases where we posted a
story at 7 p.m., and at 7:05 there's a response in my in-box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere fact of having hot bylines keeps our feet to the fire
all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
