<SLUG> BC-FBN-WORLDBOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKFURT BEATS BARCELONA, 38-24, IN WORLD BOWL FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN MAIMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany _ The Frankfurt Galaxy defeated the
Barcelona Dragons to capture World Bowl '99 Sunday by 38-24, ending
the NFL Europe season while setting the stage for Lawrence
Phillips' return to the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Andy McCullough, allocated to the NFL Europe by
the Arizona Cardinals, led the offensive onslaught with three
touchdown catches and was named the game's most valuable player as
Frankfurt avenged two regular-season losses to Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   But after the game, played before 39,643 at Rhein Stadium, all
eyes were on the Barcelona locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, the often troubled running back who was given a chance
to turn his career around with Barcelona, became the first player
in the seven-year history of the NFL Europe to rush for more than
1,000 yards in a season.
</P>
<P>
   A pulled hamstring Sunday in the second quarter sidelined
Phillips for the entire second half. He finished the game with 40
yards on seven rushes and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significant, Phillips has shown NFL teams he can
stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The problems that plagued Phillips at the University of Nebraska
and in the professional ranks after he was drafted sixth overall by
the St. Louis Rams in 1996 did not surface during his stint in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Barcelona coach, Jack Bicknell, believed in giving Phillips
a chance to prove he had learned from mistakes. Phillips had not
played for 18 months before joining Barcelona as a 10th-round pick
in the NFL Europe draft.
</P>
<P>
   He earned only $15,000 playing for the Dragons, a far cry from
the $5.6 million over three years he would have made with the Rams.
Phillips was arrested three times and spent 23 days in jail during
his 19 months with the Rams, who eventually released him.
</P>
<P>
   Bicknell is gratified that Phillips rewarded his trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawrence has shown me a lot this season,'' Bicknell said. ``He
came to play in Europe voluntarily and ended up benefiting so much
from this experience. I can't wait to see him in the NFL''
</P>
<P>
   Several NFL teams have contacted Phillips' agent, and the
Raiders and Packers are believed to have the inside track. Green
Bay general manager Ron Wolf said that he would do everything in
his power to sign Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf and other general managers can start lining up to talk to
Phillips this week. The running back has trimmed down to 210 pounds
and believes his time in Barcelona was exactly what he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely a better player than I was in St. Louis and
Miami,'' Phillips said before the game. ``I played well this season
and I had fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of a high-visibility player like Phillips along
with several strong NFL prospects helped the European league find
secure footing this season. Last season, 139 players with league
experience played in the NFL. The number is expected to rise next
season.
</P>
<P>
   One player who can enter training camp brimming with optimism is
McCullough. Frankfurt coach Dick Curl used his usual quarterback
platoon of Pat Barnes and Jake Delhomme. Both quarterbacks were
able to find McCullough free for big receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, McCullough hopes to be catching passes in
Tempe, Ariz., from another Jake _ Cardinal quarterback Jake
Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I have to do to make the Cardinals,'' McCullough
said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is guaranteed another shot at an NFL career. McCullough
can go to camp flaunting impressive numbers from the NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of players in the NFL Europe, however, have
less-certain futures. Scott Dragos, a Barcelona tight end allocated
by the Giants, heads to training camp in Albany, N.Y., knowing he
faces a hard battle.
</P>
<P>
   But like many NFL Europe players, he hopes for the best and
talks positively about the time he spent playing in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it this way,'' Dragos said before Sunday's game. ``I
played good football in Europe and had a chance to brush up on my
college Spanish at the same time. Now I have to go to camp and give
it my best shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
