</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-REVIEW-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ACCOUNT REVIEW MOVES TO CYBERREALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Mass., Calif., Ohio, N.J.)  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A French company is bringing an Internet service to the United
States intended to assist in conducting account reviews online,
helping agencies hook up with advertisers and consultants seeking
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Maydream SA is introducing a Web site named Agency Preview
(www.adforum.com), a database that will include information about
subscribing agencies like credentials, client rosters, billings,
specialty services and awards. The site will also offer samples of
creative work that can include television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have already been capitalizing on the benefits
of interactivity for agency reviews by offering Web sites,
including Business Partnering International in Richmond, Va.
(www.agencyfinder.com) and Pile &AMP; Co. in Boston
(www.agencycompile.com). The role cyberspace is beginning to play
in how agency searches are conducted is indicative of the ways the
Internet is changing the way the advertising industry operates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally bringing the agency search process in line with
the new technology,'' said Neil Kreisberg, executive vice president
and group director at Grey Advertising in New York, one of more
than 30 American and European agencies taking part in the start-up
of Agency Preview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the technological revolution in most of what we're
doing,'' he added, ``the way the process is being run now is pretty
archaic.''
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of the transformative nature of the Internet for
Madison Avenue include Web sites like www.adsgallery.com and
www.portfolios.com from Warp 10 Technologies Inc. in San Francisco,
which are meant to offer online showcases for the work of agencies,
graphic and Web designers, copywriters, photographers and other
creative talent, and online services for buying and selling
advertising space and commercial time like Adauction.com in San
Francisco and Adoutlet.com in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   One agency, Mann Bukvic Gatch Partners in Cincinnati, has even
put up a Web site (www.yourpitch.com) to compete for an account
placed in review by Screaming Media, a new media company in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advertising world is becoming more and more reliant on
global information,'' said Herve C. de Clerck, the founder and
president of Maydream, who goes by the fanciful title of dream
leader. ``Our goal is to connect advertisers, consultants and
agencies in an efficient manner, so that their new-business efforts
can be maximized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers don't want to waste time talking to agencies that
aren't right for them,'' he added, ``and agencies don't want to
waste time chasing business they will ultimately not win. And
consultants want to identify agencies they might have initially
overlooked _ or that might have conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 13 consultants, which help manage reviews,
participating in Agency Preview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe it's a plus,'' said Leslie Winthrop, managing
director at AAR/Bob Wolf Partners in New York, a consultant that is
part of the worldwide AAR consulting network.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have more information that's more easily accessible is more
cost efficient for the client,'' she added. ``And we can spend more
time with the agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Consultants will pay $9,500 a year to have full access to the
Web site. Agencies will pay $2,000 a year to subscribe; in addition
to the data they can put up, they can also provide hot links to
their own Web sites, list e-mail contact information and offer
animated presentations.
</P>
<P>
   To oversee Agency Preview, Maydream, which is based in Boulogne,
France, has opened an American unit, Maydream Inc., in Hoboken,
N.J., where Rob Drasin is vice president for United States
marketing and sales.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's something you don't read every day, ``Hoboken'' and
``France'' in the same sentence.
</P>
</TEXT>
